<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOSA-DOMINICANS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UPPER MANHATTAN, SAMMY SOSA RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mo.)  (Eds: See also ND-MARIS-HOMETOWN, BBN-CUBS-PIRATES,
BBN-CARDS-REDS) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These days, it is almost impossible to wander around
Washington Heights without hearing the name Sosa on every block, in
every store, in every apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   In front of a bodega on Thursday morning, for instance,
immigrants from the Dominican Republic grumbled that Sammy Sosa,
the Dominican-born baseball star for the Chicago Cubs, had received
far less attention than his slugging competitor, native-born Mark
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a restaurant at lunch time, two Dominican immigrants who
were sitting at different tables suddenly started arguing about
which player was more powerful. ``McGwire muy fuerte,'' one man
pitched; ``No, Sosa tiene mas!'' another replied.
</P>
<P>
   On the hot asphalt of West 170th Street near Audubon Avenue,
just before dinner time, a boy, wearing a turned-around Chicago
Cubs cap and carrying a baseball bat, bellowed: ``I'm Sosa! I'm
Sosa!''
</P>
<P>
   And Sammy Sosa didn't even play on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire and Sosa raced to eclipse Roger Maris' record of 61
home runs in a single season, Sosamania has reached a fevered pitch
in this slice of upper Manhattan, which, with perhaps 150,000
Dominicans, represents the largest cluster of Dominicans in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But the obsession is more than just a whimsical dance with
sports history. For the Dominicans, Sosa's pursuit is also a story
about a local boy who stands for all that can be good in their
beleaguered homeland, a national hero whose every home run seems to
validate an entire people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can escape the politics and the problems, because we are
all proud of Sosa,'' said Leonardo Ivan Dominguez, a dance
instructor who works for Alianza Dominicana, a social service
agency in Washington Heights. ``He's a hero, and he's going to be
the whole mirror for the kids in his country.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in true patriotic fashion, the Dominicans also wonder
why McGwire has received so much more media coverage than Sosa,
even though they both have been in hot pursuit of the home run
record. After all, some contend, Sosa is carrying a team that is
vying for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Is it just because McGwire has led the home run race all year?
It it the distances of McGwire's towering shots? Or is it something
more conspiratorial?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always McGwire, McGwire, McGwire; there's too much
McGwire,'' complained Charles Rosario, who works at an electronics
store in Washington Heights. ``I think it's because McGwire is
American, and white, and Sosa is a Dominican, and black. Americans
want to see McGwire break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sosa is not the only star in a galaxy of outstanding
Dominican players. There is Pedro Martinez, the hard-throwing
pitcher for the Boston Red Sox; Moises Alou, the Houston Astros'
slugger, and Washington Heights' own Manny Ramirez, a cog of the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, it is Sosa who has captivated his countrymen, a
people as fanatical about baseball, perhaps, as the Brazilians are
about soccer.
</P>
<P>
   At the Latin Brothers Billiard hall in Washington Heights, fans
of Sosa's painted the words ``SOSA 56'' on the window Wednesday
night, his total at that point. But by the first inning of Friday
night's game between the Cubs and the Pittsburgh Pirates, Sosa had
made history, hitting his 57th home run and breaking the team's
68-year-old single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   At Peligro Sports, more than 200 Cubs caps have been sold in the
last month, and all the Sammy Sosa jerseys are sold out, said Jose
Rivas, a store manager. This time last year, by contrast, the store
would sell 20 Cubs caps a month _ maybe _ and didn't carry Sosa
jerseys.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the Cubs are on television, people jam West Side Audio and
Electronics, on Broadway and 143rd Street. Sometimes the streets
seem to echo with applause and hoots when Sosa hits a home run,
said Anthony Rodriguez, the store's owner.
</P>
<P>
   Some Dominicans have altered their routines. Julian Reyes, 22,
who works at a brokerage firm in Queens, has concocted excuses to
skip out of work when the Cubs are on television. He also has
friends who have actually traveled to Chicago to watch Sosa in
person.
</P>
<P>
   Cira Rosa, whose 10-year-old son, Wilson, attended a baseball
camp this summer in the Dominican Republic, said that her son is so
engrossed by Sammy Sosa highlights on television and Sammy Sosa
articles in Sports Illustrated for Kids, that nothing else seems to
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To take a shower, to eat; forget it with the baseball thing,''
Mrs. Rosa said, while watching her son playing baseball in an
alley, pretending to be No. 21 of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny has intensified with each game. This weekend, the
Cubs continue their series with the Pirates, and McGwire's
Cardinals play the Cincinnati Reds in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Cubs visit the Cardinals in a much-anticipated
matchup that Dominican fans say they hope will give Sosa equal
billing with McGwire. McGwire has appeared on the cover of Sports
Illustrated three times and The New York Times Magazine once this
year, while Sosa has but one appearance on Sports Illustrated's
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are plenty of Dominicans who, when prompted,
say they respect McGwire, a Paul Bunyan type of slugger whose home
runs are threats to any windows in the stadium's ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   Some Dominicans feel that Sosa's success is an antidote to the
criticism endured by Felipe Lopez, the Dominican-American high
school basketball star from New York City who had an inconsistent
career at St. John's University. Sosa, they point out, has already
broken the record of 47 home runs by a Latin American-born player,
set by George Bell of the Toronto Blue Jays in 1987, and Juan
Gonzales of the Texas Rangers and Andres Galarraga of the Colorado
Rockies, both in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   No one can take that away from Sosa, or the community.
</P>
<P>
   But athletic prowess is not the only quality in Sosa that
Dominicans say they appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, 29, grew up poor in a sugar-mill town, San Pedro de
Macoris, selling oranges and shining shoes to make money, and using
a cardboard milk carton as a baseball glove. And while he was known
as a bit of hot dog early in his career, he has matured into one of
the best all-round players in the game. Through it all, Sosa, who
has one of the richest contracts in baseball, has been credited by
Dominicans for remaining humble, donating money to his hometown
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a simple man, he helps the poor people and he's a good
example for little kids,'' said Reyes, the occasionally truant
brokerage-firm employee.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is so popular, in fact, that many people in Washington
Heights said they would prefer to see the Cubs in the playoffs
instead of the Mets, as the two clubs fight for the National
League's wild-card spot. But there is a limit to the adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Like, who would people be rooting for if the Cubs faced the
Yankees in the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh, that's a tough one,'' said Reyes, recoiling as if someone
had asked him to choose between the cooking of his wife or his
mother. ``I got to feel for Sammy, but I'm a Yankees fan. We're
from New York, you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
