<HEADLINE>
SPIRLEA BEATS SERENA WILLIAMS AT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-USOPEN-DAY) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Irina Spirlea did Friday night what she could not do
last year at the U.S. Open: She beat a Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on the same court where she lost to, and collided with,
Venus Williams in the 1997 semifinals, Spirlea shrugged off a
ferocious second set from the younger Williams sister, Serena, and
won 6-3, 0-6, 7-5. The tall and powerful Spirlea, seeded ninth,
will face Wimbledon champion Jana Novotna in the Round of 16.
Serena Williams will have to settle for watching her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, who was playing in her first U.S. Open, will
watch with some regrets. At 5-5 in the final set, she played a
mediocre game to lose her serve, knocking a relatively routine
backhand well long at 15-40 after Spirlea's return bounced high off
the net cord. Spirlea then held her serve to finish off her first
victory against Williams, who had beaten her in their two previous
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The postmatch handshake was hardly an embrace, but there was no
repeat of last year when Spirlea and Venus Williams bumped into
each other on a changeover and Spirlea used an expletive to
describe Williams in the postmatch news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened last year, the problems we had, are all
cleaned up,'' Spirlea said.
</P>
</TEXT>
