<HEADLINE>
FUMES PROMPT EMERGENCY LANDING IN NEWFOUNDLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A Royal Airlines Boeing 757 made an emergency landing
in Newfoundland on Friday after oil warning lights came on in the
cockpit and the pilot smelled fumes, airline officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, bound for Glasgow from Toronto and reported to be
carrying more than 200 people, landed safely at the Canadian Forces
base in Goose Bay, Newfoundland, about 4:30 a.m. local time, about
30 hours after a Swissair McDonnell Douglas MD-11 jetliner plunged
into the Atlantic Ocean five miles from Peggy's Cove, Nova Scotia,
killing all 229 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   Al Graham, chief operating officer for Royal Airlines, a charter
service based in Montreal, said the pilot landed the plane because
he could smell oil fumes in the cockpit and both the ``low oil
quantity'' and ``high oil temperature'' lights were blinking.
Graham said the smoke that some on the plane had reported was
actually oil fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Airlines mechanics examined the plane and decided to send
it back to Montreal for further inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers were to continue on to Glasgow on two other planes
provided by Royal Airlines.
</P>
</TEXT>
