<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WIN NO. 100, 11-6 OVER CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Yankees have won 100 games many times in their
extraordinary history, but Babe Ruth never played on a team that
won 100 like the '98 Yankees have. Nor did Joe DiMaggio, or Mickey
Mantle, or Reggie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees came back from a two-run deficit Friday night to
earn their 100th victory of the season, 11-6, over the Chicago
White Sox. Their record improved to 100 wins and 38 losses _ the
fewest number of defeats for any team winning 100 since the 1909
Pittsburgh Pirates (36). Only four teams in the 20th century had
fewer losses when they reached 100 victories, according to the
Elias Sports Bureau. It is also the fastest calendar date for a
team to reach 100 victories _ the previous was Sept. 9 by the 1906
Cubs and the 1954 Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Every victory, it seems, pushes the '98 Yankees to another
milestone. Ten more victories and they will tie the Yankees'
single-season record, set by the 1927 Yankees (110). The Yankees'
magic number for clinching the American League East has been
reduced to five.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams slugged two home runs Friday night, including
the eighth-inning shot that propelled the Yankees into the lead.
Both Jeff Nelson and Mike Stanton, important pieces to the Yankees'
bullpen, pitched effectively. Nelson pitched two-thirds of an
inning, retiring Frank Thomas and Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago led, 4-3, in the top of the eighth inning. Chuck
Knoblauch opened the inning by chopping the ball off home plate and
toward first base; Greg Norton rushed in and gloved the grounder,
but not quickly enough to tag Knoblauch as he sped past. Knoblauch
quickly stole second, moving into scoring position. Then Derek
Jeter had enough strength to fight off an inside fastball and
dribble a roller through the middle, sending Knoblauch home with
the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   After Paul O'Neill flied out, Bill Simas relieved Chad Bradford,
and as many pitchers did early in the year, he tried blowing a
chest-high fastball past Williams. Early in the year, this worked.
On the fourth day of September, the chest-high fastball was
redirected into the right-center-field stands, Williams looking up
and watching the ball, his helmet falling off as he neared first
base.
</P>
<P>
   He rounded the bases, greeted at home plate by Tino Martinez _
and before Williams could settle into the dugout, Martinez blasted
a home run, as well, his 25th, in almost the same spot as Williams
had before him.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Lloyd, one of five relievers following Orlando Hernandez,
earned the victory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hernandez's pitching mechanics are elaborate, with all the
spinning gears and movement of a Swiss watch. With so many pieces
and parts to his motion, it's remarkable Hernandez can maintain
command of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday night, he could not. Hernandez struggled in trying to
find the proper point of release for his slider, and as a result,
he sometimes threw it far too low and outside, or he flipped it
over the plate. Thomas powered a fastball for a double with two
outs in the first inning, after falling behind in the count by one
ball and two strikes, and after Hernandez failed to finish off
Thomas with his slider. Hernandez jumped ahead on the count to
Belle, 1-2, but when Belle fought back to 3-2, Hernandez hung a
slider and Belle walloped it _ an estimated 400 feet, left-center
field, his 43rd home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked three batters in the second inning, and if not
for a quick throw from catcher Jorge Posada to cut down a potential
base-stealer, the White Sox might have added to their 2-0 lead.
Through two innings, Hernandez had thrown 47 pitches, an
exceptionally high number.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees came back to tie the game at 3-3 in the top of
the fourth, Hernandez continued to have problems with his control.
He walked Thomas in the fifth inning, again after getting ahead in
the count, 1-2. Belle popped up, but Robin Ventura walked, and
after Norton walked on five pitches, loading the bases, Hernandez
snapped at the return thrown from Posada, furious with himself,
then turned and walked off the back of the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, hustled to
conference with Hernandez, Posada translating on the mound, but
Hernandez knew what the problem was all along: The six walks El
Duque allowed were the most in any of his 17 starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Abbott's fly ball enabled Thomas to tag up and score from
third base and push the White Sox ahead, 4-3. Hernandez departed
after six innings, having allowed six hits and three strikeouts and
the four runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
