<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO, ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL, SHARPENS CRITICISM OF CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMIRA, N.Y. _ On the first day of a three-day campaign swing in
upstate New York, Geraldine Ferraro on Friday delivered her
sharpest criticism yet of President Clinton's involvement with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with editors and reporters at The Star-Gazette in
Elmira, a Gannett newspaper, Ms. Ferraro, who is in a three-way
contest for the Democratic Senate nomination, said she agreed with
the substance, though not the timing, of Sen. Joseph Lieberman's
speech on the Senate floor on Thursday, in which he called the
president's relationship with the White House intern ``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with what he said,'' Ms. Ferraro, the former
vice-presidential candidate said of Lieberman, adding later, ``I
don't think there are too many Democrats who don't agree with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's terrible, you know, what happened,'' she
said of Clinton's actions. ``I actually believed that he didn't do
anything. I had no reason not to believe him, and I was as
distressed as any, and perhaps more so, because I do know him, and
I didn't expect that he'd lie to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Ferraro was also critical of the decision by Lieberman,
D-Conn., to deliver the speech while the president was in Northern
Ireland trying to bolster a fragile peace process. ``The timing, I
think, is wrong,'' she said. ``He should have waited until he came
home. I think when the president is off doing business outside of
this country, that he should be able to do the business of the
country and not be distracted by questions and speeches like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she had given any thought to what psition she
would take on impeachment if the issue came before her as a
senator, Ms. Ferraro said, ``Sure.'' She said she would wait for
Kenneth Starr's report on his investigation of Clinton to see
whether Clinton's offenses went beyond ``a man lying about his sex
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro's stance Friday afternoon was sharper than her
position immediately after the president's speech three weeks ago,
when she described herself as ``disappointed'' by the relationship
and the fact that he had misled the American people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro's opponents for the Democratic nomination
essentially reiterated what they had said in the days after
Clinton's speech. ``I said I thought the president was wrong,''
said Rep. Charles Schumer of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer noted that he was a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, which would consider any impeachment proceedings that
might be brought against Clinton. ``In terms of specific action, I
don't think it's fair for me to say anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A third candidate, Mark Green, the New York City public
advocate, said his position had not changed since Lieberman's
speech. ``What the president did was clearly immoral, deceptive and
inexcusable,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he thought talk of impeachment was ridiculous.
``Let's get a grip here,'' Green said. ``Richard Nixon's obvious
public corruption of the justice system and the FBI, which led to
29 executive branch officials going to jail, is of a wholly
different magnitude than Bill Clinton's fundamentally private
misconduct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
