<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS SELECTED HICKS' SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Antelope Valley native Jermaine Lewis is the
Bruins' top tailback, for now. Lewis will start Sept. 12 against
Texas, but Keith Brown and rapidly improving freshman DeShaun
Foster will get their chances, as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's UCLA's most riveting competition, with the potential to
change weekly until one player establishes himself as the heir to
Karim Abdul-Jabbar and Skip Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine was a little more consistent,'' coach Bob Toledo
said. ``But Keith will play early.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's appearances, and carries, will be predetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other personnel developments Friday:
</P>
<P>
   __Michael Wiley will start at outside linebacker, with Santi
Hall playing second string.
</P>
<P>
   __At the troublesome free-safety spot, where Eric Whitfield and
Jason Stephens are competing, the coaches decided not to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might go all the way to game time'' before making a
decision, Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __Josh Webb couldn't crack the defensive-line rotation, so the
Bruins decided to put his size (6-6, 280 pounds) and athleticism to
use: he has moved to offensive tackle. The switch bolsters UCLA's
line depth, freeing tackle James Ghezzi to play guard or center if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies in red: Three true freshmen definitely will play:
Foster, linebacker Robert Thomas and nose guard Ken Kocher.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, receiver Jon Dubravac and cornerback Julius
Williams, might play. Dubravac is one of the biggest surprises,
having improved dramatically since camp began. He's pushing Hart
High alumnus Cody Joyce for the fifth receiver spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On July 1), I thought we'd redshirt Dubravac,'' Toledo said.
``We may still, but I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA needs four cornerbacks, and Williams is currently running
fifth, behind starters Marques Anderson and Jason Bell, and
reserves Damian Allen and Ryan Roques. Whitfield, one of UCLA's
best athletes, can play cornerback if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real possibility we'll still redshirt Williams,''
Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears both freshmen offensive linemen, tackle Blake
Worley and guard Mike Saffer, will redshirt. Injuries have slowed
their progress, and Webb's move could solve the depth problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ghezzi, Troy Danoff, Matt Phelan, Ed Anderson and David Wilford
are the reserve linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Walking wounded: Bumps and bruises aside, the Bruins survived
training camp in good health.
</P>
<P>
   Only two members of the two-deep are in danger of missing the
Texas game: starting fullback Craig Walendy (allergic reaction to
bug bites) has not practiced and is not expected to play.
Second-string nose guard Kocher (sprained ankle) did some light
running Friday for the first time in nine days. But if he plays, it
will be in a limited capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant surprise: Toledo canceled today's scrimmage and gave
the players the weekend off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little reward,'' he said. ``We're relatively healthy,
and I wanted to give them a little rest. I want them to get away
from football, get out of here and relax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
