<SLUG> BC-BBO-$MILLION-BID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1 MILLION BID FOR NO. 62 BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An anonymous donor has offered to pay $1 million to the fan who
catches the 62nd home run ball by Mark McGwire or Sammy Sosa to
help in the continuing search for justice in the 1980 murders of
three American nuns and a lay worker in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to raise awareness,'' the donor, a longtime baseball
fan, said Friday in a telephone interview, ``and what better way to
publicize the cause than to tie it to the home run derby? I hope
when sportscasters talk about the money, they'll also talk about
the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The donor, who says he wants to protect his identity because he
fears for his safety, will buy a $650,000 annuity that will pay the
fan $50,000 annually for 20 years. His plans are to resell the
ball, and any profits above $650,000 will go to the Lawyers
Committee for Human Rights, a New York-based organization that
represents the victims' families and promotes human rights around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no profit, the donor has guaranteed to make a
$75,000 donation. He said he would make the same donation even if
the fan declined to sell the ball and gave it to McGwire or Sosa or
donated it to the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The donor said he had followed the case and was particularly
outraged that two Salvadoran officers implicated by a U.N. Truth
Commission report for covering up the murders were never
prosecuted, and live in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, four Salvadoran National Guard members and their
immediate superior were convicted of the murders and sentenced to
30 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, three of the five were released. The Truth Commission
found that Gen. Jose Guillermo Garcia and Col. Carlos Eugenio Vides
Casanova, the two officers now living in Florida, organized and
directed the cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the four former national guardsmen said they acted
only after receiving ``orders from above.'' They made their
admissions during interviews with R. Scott Greathead and Robert
Weiner, members of the Lawyers Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``These officers _ you can't prove they ordered the murders, but
they covered it up, and now they're living comfortably,'' the donor
said. ``Everybody I talk to is outraged by all this.''
</P>
<P>
   The donor approached the Lawyers Committee on Thursday, and the
committee spent Friday investigating him and his ability to pay for
the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what he says he is,'' Greathead said. The donor's lawyer
is Elaine Wood of Kroll Associates, a private investigation and
security firm. She said the donor's background and finances checked
out ``affirmatively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
