A0700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HNS &LR;      09-05 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McGWIRE INSPIRES FANS AS HE CHASES BASEBALL HISTORY 
 
By NEIL HOHLFELD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Over the past 60 years, the St. Louis Cardinals have
been known mainly for their speed and aggressiveness on the bases.
Dating from Pepper Martin in the 1930s to Lou Brock in the 1960s to
Vince Coleman in the 1980s, the Cardinals have achieved success, by
and large, by playing small ball.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Cardinals haven't been successful, but they've
changed their mode of attack in a big way. With Mark McGwire
hitting home runs at what has been a record pace, the Cardinals
have left their personal dead-ball era and started living large.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire hit four home runs in his last two games at
Florida this week to raise his season total to 59, expectations ran
high Friday night at Busch Stadium. But in a 3-2 loss to
Cincinnati, McGwire was 0-for-3 with two strikeouts and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   He remains three home runs away from breaking the single-season
record of 61 set by Roger Maris in 1961. Sammy Sosa of the Chicago
Cubs hit No. 57 on Friday night, reinforcing that this year's
home-run chase will be a two-man contest.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire once again was stymied by a Reds pitching staff that has
hardly baffled the rest of the National League. In seven games
against Cincinnati this season, McGwire has no home runs _ the only
team against which he has not connected in 1998. The Reds have
allowed 151 home runs this year, the 10th-highest total in the
16-team National League.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Reds this season, McGwire is 2-for-16 with no RBIs
and 12 walks _ five of them intentional. Friday night, former
Houston Astros pitcher Pete Harnisch got McGwire to fly to right
field in the first inning and struck him out on a high fastball in
the third. In the fifth, McGwire walked on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that if you make your pitches, you
probably won't give up a home run,'' Harnisch said. ``That's not to
say if I miss my spot by eight inches, he won't hit it 500 feet.
Tonight, though, I hit my spots and made my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Reds reliever Scott Sullivan in the seventh inning,
McGwire struck out on three pitches. With flashbulbs popping on
every pitch to McGwire and fans literally praying in the seats for
home run No. 60, the scene at Busch Stadium was one of tension and
anxiety each time the redheaded slugger came to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's quest for the record has turned on this
baseball-crazed city in a way that hasn't been seen since 1987,
when the team made its most recent World Series appearance. A
sell-out season-high crowd of 48,076 watched Friday's contest, and
the next four games through Tuesday are sold out. The Cardinals
expect to draw 3.2 million fans this season, which will set a
franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   This year's all-out enthusiasm in St. Louis is a testament to
the power of power. Without McGwire's quest to overtake Maris, the
crowd likely would have been half of what it was Friday. The Reds
and Cardinals were a combined 43 1/2 games behind the Astros in the
NL Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   But with McGwire bearing down on the record, seemingly nothing
else matters in this city. At a hotel near the St. Louis airport, a
desk clerk said Friday a man told him he would pay up to $500 for a
seat in the left-field loge level, where the majority of McGwire's
home runs at Busch Stadium have landed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Security in that area of seats was tight. A ticket for a
front-row seat was no match for one in the left-field bleachers. In
order to enter that area, a ticket had to be produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening here this year goes beyond amazing,'' said
St. Louis manager Tony La Russa. ``He's absolutely turned on this
city with what he's done. And what's so remarkable is that from the
very first day of spring training, people have asked him, `Can you
break the record?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't sneaked up on anyone. He's just gone out and done
it. When I see the concentration and the focus he's had during all
this, it's beyond description.''
</P>
<P>
   The McGwire story is hardly a St. Louis-only affair. Major
League Baseball issued nearly 700 media credentials for Friday's
game, and that number likely will grow as McGwire gets closer to
62. A typical World Series will attract between 900 and 1,000 media
members.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Stadium security personnel are being assisted by the St.
Louis Police Department, and, according to Major League Baseball
security director Kevin Hallinan, FBI personnel.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, McGwire did not appear in an interview room and
had not come to his locker in the Cardinals' clubhouse 30 minutes
after the game. That goes against the trend McGwire has followed in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month or so, McGwire has seemed more relaxed,
despite the growing media attention. In early August, McGwire
chastised a group of reporters who questioned him about a game by
saying, ``Worry about your families, don't worry about me.''
</P>
<P>
   After three more home runs by McGwire, the fun will go into
overdrive. If McGwire breaks Maris' record before Sosa and the home
run happens in St. Louis, a postgame celebration is planned by the
Cardinals. The loyal St. Louis fans, who for years could only dream
of a long-ball attack, will revel in having the record-setter on
their team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 0031EDT &QL; 
