<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GONZALEZ-RBI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ SURPASSES OWN CLUB RBI MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ In his remarkable season of home-run smashes
and extra-base hits, Juan Gonzalez took the easy route to a club
record for runs batted in last night.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up No. 145 in the third inning of Texas' 9-3 victory
against Minnesota when, of all things, he was nicked, almost
imperceptibly, on the left forearm by a bases-loaded pitch from
struggling Twins starter Frank Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a little bit,'' he said with a sheepish grin, pretending
to look for a bruise that wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But an RBI is an RBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez added No. 146 in his standard fashion, pulling an
eighth-inning double just inside the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   He also held the previous club record of 144, set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago that 100 RBI in a season was a
milestone,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``All those things
have gone by the wayside now. He continues to amaze me with the
number of runs he can drive in.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring injury, Gonzalez is almost certain to become the first
American League player to drive in 150 runs since 1949. That year,
Boston's Vern Stephens and Ted Williams each had 159, and at his
current rate of production, Gonzalez should top that one, too. He
could even become the first major-league player in 60 years to top
160 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   And Gonzalez, who also is on a 15-game hitting streak, perhaps
is the leading candidate for the league's MVP award, which he won
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Nomar Garciaparra is among the other MVP possibilities,
as are Anaheim's Darin Erstad, and New York's tandem of Derek Jeter
and Bernie Williams, although they could split the Yankees vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez believes the Rangers might have to win the American
League West _ they did in '96 _ for him to bring home another MVP
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the division would give me more chances,'' he said.
``We've got three weeks remaining, and I'll just continue to work
hard on my numbers every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is, winning every ballgame right now is very
important to us. And we need a lot of runs every night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
