<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COP-HOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT CITY TOPS IN HOMES FOR COPS UNDER FEDERAL PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Beating metropolises like Los Angeles and
Chicago, Lancaster, in the Antelope Valley north of L.A., leads the
nation in the number of police officers buying repossessed homes at
half-price under a federal program.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Palmdale ranks third.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo
disclosed the cities' rankings Friday in announcing that the
program is being expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Cementing the Antelope Valley's reputation as an enclave for
peace officers, Cuomo said 115 have taken advantage of the Officer
Next Door program to buy homes in distressed areas of Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is far and away the largest number for any city,'' said
Stan Vosper, a HUD spokesman. ``The next largest is Chicago, with
97.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale had the third-largest number in the nation with 91
officers, while 82 officers bought homes in Los Angeles, putting it
in fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   The Officer Next Door program enables peace officers to buy
homes at half the appraised value, provided that they agree to live
there for at least three years. The program is designed to boost
homeownership while improving neighborhood values and quality of
life.
</P>
<P>
   In Lancaster, Los Angeles Police Department officers account for
more than 20 percent of participants, although more precise figures
were not immediately available. Buyers also included members of
other area police departments, sheriff's deputies and correctional
officers at California State Prison-Los Angeles County in
Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, more than 10 percent of all homes purchased nationally
in the Officer Next Door program were in the Antelope Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Antelope Valley officials said it is no surprise that their
suburban cities led the program, given their traditional popularity
with law enforcement officers from Los Angeles and other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of officers who lived here before this program,
because they like the privacy they get here,'' said Elizabeth
Brubaker, redevelopment project coordinator in Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lancaster and Palmdale may have proved too popular for
their own good. So many officers have bought there that HUD took
the unusual step of cutting off the program in those cities in
June, with more than 300 other officers still hoping to buy there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed,'' Brubaker said. ``We're not really
happy about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Brubaker said she thought federal officials might have ordered
the halt in Lancaster because they realized its neighborhoods are
not as old and distressed as communities in other parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because our houses are very nice and our area is
nice,'' she said. ``They don't consider us as a ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some are wondering if the Antelope Valley might once
again be able to participate in the program after the announcement
Friday by Cuomo and Vice President Al Gore that 2,000 homes were
sold to officers nationwide during the first year of the program
and that HUD plans to make available an additional 1,000 homes to
keep the popular project going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police officer moving onto the block is the single best
thing we can do,'' Cuomo told reporters in a telephone conference.
``A single officer next door can start a cycle of reclamation and
rebirth'' for a distressed neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   However, Vosper said Friday he could not determine whether the
extension of the program might reopen opportunities in the Antelope
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the HUD program, the city of Los Angeles has a
separate one that provides discounted mortgages and subsidizes
closing costs for LAPD officers who buy homes in the city. The goal
is to encourage officers to live in the communities where they
work.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials said last month that 145 police officers
and firefighters have bought homes in the city with the help of
both home-buying programs, with some 500 other Los Angeles public
safety employees having expressed interest in participating.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a study by the American Civil Liberties Union of
Southern California concluded that 83 percent of LAPD officers
lived outside the city, many in predominantly white suburban
enclaves far from the ethnically diverse community they police.
That was a concern to the ACLU, which feared officers would not be
able to relate those they serve.
</P>
<P>
   The study found, for instance, that 120 LAPD officers lived in
Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Although the HUD program does not require officers to buy in the
areas where they work, Cuomo said that is one of several goals of
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a police officer live in the community they serve is an
advantage in and of itself,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the HUD program may be helping LAPD officers move
out of the city -- apparently in conflict with the city's own
subsidy program -- did not cause great concern to Los Angeles
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective, what we would like to see is officers
living in the city limits,'' said Police Commissioner Dean Hansell.
``I would hope that with this extension we would see a lot more
officers buy homes in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Cmdr. Dave Kalish, a department spokesman, also had a mixed
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that our personnel are receiving help in buying
homes anywhere,'' Kalish said. ``It would be even better if the
homes were in the city limits.''
</P>
<P>
   ACLU spokeswoman Ann Bradley said her organization remains
concerned that few LAPD officers live in Los Angeles, but she
praised the HUD program for helping officers move into distressed
communities.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials also said their program still has other strong
merits, which include helping distressed communities to benefit
from the presence of law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (to benefit) the highest-crime neighborhoods, the
highest-poverty neighborhoods. That's why we have a 50 percent
discount,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
