<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-REDS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS STUMP MCGWIRE; IT'S STILL 59 AND COUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When the Cincinnati Reds saw Mark McGwire in July,
they walked him, then walked him again, walked him some more and
kept on walking him. With McGwire going into a three-game series
with the Reds only two home runs away from Roger Maris' home run
record, Jack McKeon, the Reds' manager, was asked if he planned to
have his pitchers repeat their July performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game situation will dictate it,'' McKeon said Friday night
before the Reds played the St. Louis Cardinals. ``I can't tell you
anything now.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon's pitchers, Pete Harnisch and Scott Sullivan, spoke
volumes. They pitched to McGwire and held him hitless in three
at-bats. They each struck him out once, and the only time he
reached base was when Harnisch walked him on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who entered the game with 12 home runs in the
Cardinals' previous 17 games and his previous 52 at-bats, not only
didn't become the third player in major-league history to hit 60
home runs, but he also lost a bit of his lead over Sammy Sosa
because Sosa hit his 57th home run in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was Sosa's first in six games against the Pirates
this season, but the Reds continued to confound McGwire. They are
the only National League team he has not hit a home run against
this season, and they extended his failure to seven games and 16
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire opted not to be available to the more than 600 reporters
who were at Busch Stadium, but his manager, Tony LaRussa, credited
Harnisch and Sullivan with doing a good job of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the Reds' 3-2 victory if he thought McKeon had the
Reds going at McGwire more than they had in July when they walked
him 11 times, LaRussa said, ``Yeah, I wish he hadn't done it so
much. I wish they had walked him three times. Harnisch made very
good pitches. Then Sullivan made three Hall of Fame pitches. They
were really nasty pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time McGwire walked to the plate, the sellout crowd of
48,076 cheered loudly and stood at their seats. Cameras flashed
from all points of the stadium with each pitch, fans hoping to get
lucky and get some minuscule image of the swing that produced No.
60.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, McGwire came to bat after Brian Jordan
lined a one-out single to left field and continued to second when
the ball scooted past Dmitri Young for an error. He lofted a fly
ball that the fans thought was headed for the right field fence,
but it turned out to be a routine fly ball that Reggie Sanders
caught easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that ball wasn't a home run,'' Harnisch said. ``But
when he hit it, it went so high the crowd went berserk. But I knew
he hit it straight up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third and fifth innings, McGwire didn't hit the ball at
all. He struck out swinging in the third and walked on a 3-2 pitch
in the fifth. The walk loaded the bases and preceded a sacrifice
fly by Ray Lankford for the Cardinals' second run in the inning and
the game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire got his last chance, for this night, to match Babe
Ruth's 60 home runs in 1927 in the seventh inning. But Scott
Sullivan didn't give him much of a chance. Sullivan, who relieved
Harnisch at the start of that inning, threw three pitches, and
McGwire swung at all three and missed all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGwire is at kind of a disadvantage in the sense that the
spotlight's on him,'' said Sullivan, a 27-year-old right-hander.
``The average player might elevate his game to a higher level to
get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he threw a fastball on the first pitch just to try
to get ahead of McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``That probably was the best pitch to hit,'' Sullivan said. ``I
don't know if he was going to do much with the sliders. They were
down and away. I was lucky enough to have a little bite on the
sliders and he chased them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Each time McGwire came to bat the pitchers were given new balls
to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything about it,'' Harnisch said. ``I asked
the second base umpire if these are the hard balls because they
kept switching them around.''
</P>
<P>
   The balls are the same as the others used in games, but they
specially marked with serial numbers so when McGwire does hit a
home run, officials will be able to determine which ball is
legitimate when a fan claims he caught it.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko, the Reds' scheduled starting pitcher for Sunday's
third game of the series, acknowledged that he and his teammates
have discussed the scenario in which McGwire would break the record
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have chatted about it,'' Tomko said. ``What
would they do if he hits the home run? If you're playing third,
would you high-five him? It's a monumental thing. It doesn't happen
very often that someone is going to achieve this feat so everyone
is sort of preparing how they're going to feel and how they're
going to react when this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   When he realized that he would be pitching Sunday's game, Tomko
related, he started thinking about the game and the possible
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's three days away,'' he said. ``I sat back and said well,
if he gets a couple the first couple games he's going to be sitting
on 61. You play the little games, the scenarios, and try to think
how you would feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
