A0712 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ND-MARIS-HOMETOWN-ART     09-05 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ND-MARIS-HOMETOWN-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN HAS MIXED FEELINGS ABOUT NEW BASEBALL RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: SUBS to update Sosa's homerun total in graf 5.)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. _ If this had to be the baseball season when the
home-run record was smashed, Sandy Thiel had a small request:
Please don't let it happen on her birthday, which is coming up in a
few days. That, she says, would force her ``to remember it for the
rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sid Cichy had stopped watching baseball games altogether,
figuring it would be easier to take if he did not actually see it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   And Tim Olson had bet a candy bar and a soda that the
history-making home run would not happen and, in less delusional
moments, tried to tell himself that it was not a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't felt this way about baseball since I was in fifth
grade,'' said Olson, 45. ``I can hear the baseball cards rattling
through my bike spokes again, like when I was a kid and you put
them there with clothespins to make your bike sound like a
motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pretty much resigned myself that they'll probably break
the record, and I keep reminding myself that it's not mine,'' Olson
added, referring to Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals, who
hit his 58th and 59th home runs in Florida on Wednesday night, and
Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, who hit No. 57 in Pittsburgh on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Such were the emotional calisthenics that people were putting
themselves through in the hometown of Roger Maris, whose record of
61 home runs in a season had stood for 37 years but was fast
slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the country was gripped by irrepressible
excitement as McGwire and Sosa moved ever closer to the magic
number, people in Fargo were wrestling with more complicated
feelings. They were wistful and nostalgic, grateful for the sudden
flood of recognition being paid their hero, but achingly aware that
it was more of a requiem than a coronation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Maris, who died in 1985 of lymphatic cancer,
was one of their own. It's also that people from this modest
prairie town, tundra-cold and table-flat, are moved by some of the
sadder particulars of the Maris story: that in 1961, when he played
right field for the New York Yankees, Maris felt hounded by
reporters and denigrated by those who did not want him to break the
record of 60 home runs set by another Yankee right fielder, Babe
Ruth, in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   People here are also keenly aware that Maris was never elected
to the Baseball Hall of Fame, and that the baseball commissioner
relegated his achievement to a footnote in the record books because
the regular season had been extended by eight games at that time _
a notation (since removed) that came to be known as the
``asterisk.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, people here believe that Fargo is considered to be
an asterisk, too. Although it is North Dakota's largest city, with
nearly 80,000 people, Fargo is rarely in the national spotlight.
People thought the movie ``Fargo'' made fun of them, and on top of
that, most of the film was shot in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of Fargo's record as well as Roger's,'' said Dick
Savageau, 64, a longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carney, 82, who knew Maris when he was a star all-round
high school athlete, said, ``We don't get many big heroes out of
North Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   Out here, Roger Maris is as big as they come _ bigger still,
people say, because he never forgot his friends or lost his
down-to-earth demeanor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is a Roger Maris charity golf tournament and a Roger Maris
Cancer Center. And there is his baseball-diamond-shaped gravestone
in Holy Cross Cemetery, with its inscription, ``Against All Odds.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the Roger Maris museum, a 74-foot glass case in the
West Acres shopping mall, sandwiched between a Pet Center and a
Spencer Gifts store. It was placed there, said Jim McLaughlin, the
curator, because Maris wanted his plaques, bats and home-run balls
in a place where the admission was free and lots of people would
see them.
</P>
<P>
   Maris even designated 100 autographed postcards for visitors who
``understand who Roger Maris really is,'' said McLaughlin, who
bestowed one on a couple stopping by on their honeymoon and gave
another to a devoted elderly fan.
</P>
<P>
   A whole trove of Roger Maris folklore permeates Fargo. How
Maris, whose family was originally from Minnesota, played football
for Shanley High School and ran five kickoffs back for touchdowns
in one game, causing the opposing coach to say he dreaded when his
own team scored.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and classmates remember the young Maris as a prankster,
who once put pancake batter in the overshoes of the nuns at Shanley
High. And Bob Wood, a close friend, talks of the time they got
tired of hooligans pestering them and their dates when they parked
on Lover's Lane. Wood put on his sister's kerchief and he and Maris
pretended to be a couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they started harassing us, we'd jump out and have a nice
little fight with them,'' said Wood, now 63.
</P>
<P>
   Lover's Lane has since been renamed; now it's Roger Maris Drive.
</P>
<P>
   There is even ``Maris,'' the musical, created in part by Olson
and produced by Ms. Thiel, who are hoping it might get a nibble
from a New York theater someday. It's got a Mickey Mantle-Roger
Maris song-and-dance number, and a ballad about unflinching
loyalty:
</P>
<P>
   ``Long after the cheering fades
</P>
<P>
   And after the big parades,
</P>
<P>
   And long past all the accolades
</P>
<P>
   I'll still believe in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing better expresses Fargo's feelings for Maris, exalting in
his accomplishments, commiserating over the pressure he weathered
in that 1961 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really felt sorry for the guy,'' Savageau said. ``He'd get
that same question every day: Are you going to hit a home run
today? Are you going to break Babe Ruth's record? `How do I know?'
That would be his answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it got personal,'' Savageau added. ``Do you womanize when
you're on the road? He was losing his hair, just getting so
uptight. He wanted out of the glass bowl that he was in, to go back
home and find his friends.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, some people have been worried that when someone
smacked number 62 out of the park, it would steal the recognition
from Fargo and its hero. Others hoped that this year's pursuit of
Maris' record would have the opposite effect, maybe even get Maris
into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people throughout the country know Roger now than did
before, and that might give him a better chance to finally get
in,'' said Wayne Blanchard, 63, who played high school football
with Maris and is chairman of the charity golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Fargo will probably face the post-Maris future with
the kind of affable, weatherproof fortitude that greeted Yogi Berra
in 1985. Berra, the Hall of Fame catcher and onetime teammate of
Maris, was in Fargo for the charity golf tournament, and he
reportedly remarked that he did not believe such flat land could
produce enough potatoes to fill up his front yard. A few months
later, 900 50-pound boxes of North Dakota potatoes were trucked to
Berra's home in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the record is broken and we're no longer the site of the
fellow who hit the home-run record?'' asked Cichy, who coached
Maris in all his sports at Shanley High. He paused, considering the
question, and then replied: ``We'll get our snow shovels out. It's
going to be winter before long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
