<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILL CLARK PACES RANGERS BY DRIVING IN FOUR RUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ First baseman Will Clark established his
reputation during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It remains intact a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the victim of a strength-zapping virus, arrived at The
Ballpark in Arlington yesterday ``feeling worse than he did''
Wednesday evening in Detroit, Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark took two _ make that two, two-run base hits _ and likely
will feel better this morning after the Rangers' 9-3 victory last
night against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason he's Will Clark,'' Oates said after the
victory that cut the first-place Angels' lead in the American
League West to two games, with Anaheim playing host to Kansas City
in a game played later last night.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele, who perhaps threw his best pitch during
the first inning, allowed only one earned run in his seven-inning
appearance and coasted to his 17th victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sele escaped a one-out, bases-loaded jam by inducing an
inning-ending, double-play ground ball from Twins left fielder
Marty Cordova and let Clark's swing produce more than enough
offensive support.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's two-run, third-inning single gave the Rangers a 3-0
lead, and his two-run, sixth-inning double only enhanced his
reputation as a player who can be counted on during September and
October when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was extra special,'' Oates said. ``He didn't have much
strength, but he's the type of guy who rises to the occasion. You
don't get to be that type of player without coming through again
and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark will enter tonight's game against the Twins and
right-hander Bob Tewksbury hitting .417 (5-for-12) with two
doubles, a home run and seven runs batted in during the Rangers'
first three games of September.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old first baseman entered this season with a .306
average for his career during this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``September is a fun time,'' said Clark, who Wednesday delivered
a go-ahead, run-scoring double during the sixth inning before
leaving feeling ill. ``You've worked for seven months to try to
make the playoffs, and we're down to our last 22 games now.''
</P>
<P>
   That also serves as the reason Oates plans to pitch
right-handers Sele and Rick Helling every fifth day the remainder
of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's latest performance represented his fourth victory in as
many starts. The right-hander also owns a 2.15 earned-run average
during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (17-10) escaped another bases-loaded situation and
prevented the Twins from a multiple-run frame during the fifth
inning by retiring Twins first baseman David Ortiz on strikes. The
other two runs Sele allowed were unearned after a seventh-inning
error by second baseman Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we want from our starters,'' Oates said. ``Give us
six or seven innings and give us a chance to score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Producing runs falls under Clark's department, especially in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've worked for,'' Clark said, ``to be in this
position now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
