<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS WILL START ROOKIES ONLY IF HE MUST. HE MUST. 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ While leading a New York Giants team on its
way to the Super Bowl, Bill Parcells could virtually boast to his
rookies: ``I don't need you.''
</P>
<P>
   But he needs them now.
</P>
<P>
   He needs them despite his fears that rookies are, well, rookies.
For, while his New York Jets remain in a rebuilding mode, Sunday's
season opener at San Francisco is not going to be delayed until his
first-year players learn a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   If you count punter Nick Gallery, who has never played a
National Football League game but was on the practice squad last
year, the Jets will start three rookies against the 49ers. The
others are right tackle Jason Fabini, a fourth-round draft pick out
of Cincinnati, and Kevin Williams, a third-rounder out of Oklahoma
State.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Johnson remembers the 1986 season with the Giants, when
he was one of a remarkable core of second-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuna told the team, `We had a good team in 1985, so I don't
need any rookies. Just play a role.''' So Johnson, a linebacker,
sat and watched, as did defensive tackle Erik Howard and cornerback
Mark Collins.
</P>
<P>
   In contemplating rookies, Parcells likes to refer to George
Allen's contention that for every first-year player you start, you
lose a game.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Gallery, Parcells worries not so much that he
is an untested player but that he is a kicker. Kickers seem born to
aggravate Parcells; it is the one area of football that makes him
almost want to shirk his coaching duties.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Parcells seems reasonably comfortable with Fabini.
``Normally, you equate rookies with mistakes,'' he said. ``I will
say this in Jason Fabini's case: This kid has been one of the
rarest rookies I've ever had. This kid makes zero mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 10 years since a rookie tackle started the opener
for the Jets. In 1988, the rookie was the first-round pick Dave
Cadigan of Southern California. The last time before that was 1978,
when Chris Ward of Ohio State went right into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Fabini recalls this year's rookie camp and a lecture: ``Coach
Parcells gave us four things he wanted us to do to help us make the
team. One of them was `no mental errors.' Another was `be
reliable.' The other two, I've forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Williams, he quickly demonstrated speed and agility
during training camp. When the Jets drafted him, they thought he
might be a cornerback. They also wondered about him at strong
safety, and they liked his ability to return kickoffs. They even
tried him on special-teams coverage. In the final exhibition game,
he was at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We overloaded him until we decided what to do with him,''
Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells, feeling hamstrung by having to bring three
specialists to the game _ John Hudson, just for long snapping; Nick
Gallery, for punting, and John Hall, for place-kicking _ is
contemplating designating Vinny Testaverde as his third
quarterback, or 46th man. Under that designation, Testaverde's
appearance in a game before the fourth quarter would mean that both
Glenn Foley and Ray Lucas could not play the remainder of the game.
If Testaverde entered in the fourth quarter, Foley and Lucas would
still be eligible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
