<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS CHANGE STRETCHES SARATOGA STREAK TO THREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Nothing could be sweeter for a juvenile
filly than to win at Saratoga, unless it is winning twice at
Saratoga, or three times. And that is what Things Change achieved
Friday when she won the 107th running of the Spinaway, casting the
glow of tradition and promise on a career with a three-race winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The streak began on Aug. 2 when she won in a six-furlong race,
and gathered luster on Aug. 17 when she won the Adirondack, the
middle race in the cycle of three stakes at Saratoga for 2-year-old
fillies. And it gained star quality Friday when Things Change shot
to a four-length victory in the Spinaway, one of Saratoga's oldest
and most important stakes for young horses.
</P>
<P>
   She was joined in the spotlight by her trainer, Linda Rice, a
34-year-old from Wisconsin who got her start by working as an
exercise rider and assistant to her father, Clyde, who trained
horses. The family now develops young horses and operates two
training centers near Ocala in the Florida horse country.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Rice took two years away from racing to study computer
science at Penn State, but returned to the track and went on her
own as a trainer 11 years ago. She passed a milestone Friday when
she made the winner's circle at Saratoga for the sixth time this
season, the fourth time after a graded stakes and the third time
with her striking gray filly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was especially excited with this race,'' she said, ``because
it was my first Grade I victory. But she broke a touch flat-footed,
so right away I was concerned because I wanted to see her closer to
the lead. She was pushed back at the start, and I felt that we
needed to be closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Things Change ran sixth in a seven-horse field for half a mile
while Jose Santos let her settle down. Appealing Phylly, meanwhile,
was setting a fast pace, which included the first quarter-mile in
22 1/5 seconds and the half-mile in 45 3/5. But by then, Things
Change had overcome the poor start, and she charged into the lead
as they turned for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace was quick, so for the first quarter of a mile I just
took hold of my filly,'' Santos said. ``I waited until the turn; I
just wanted to take my time and get her to the outside. When I did
that, it gave her a clear shot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, Things Change had four and a half lengths on
Extended Applause, who also ran second in the Adirondack. And
Extended Applause, in turn, had three lengths on Miss Jennifer
Lynn. The winner ran the seven furlongs in 1 minute 24 4/5, paid $6
for a $2 bet to win and added $120,000 to her growing bankroll.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES:
</P>
<P>
   Mike Smith left the Albany Medical Center on Friday wearing blue
sweat pants, a T-shirt and an Anaheim Angels baseball cap given to
him by Chris DeCarlo, a fellow jockey. ``I'm a New York Yankees
fan,'' Smith said, ``but Chris gave this cap to me because he said
I must have had an angel on my shoulder the other day.'' On Monday,
Smith's mount was trapped in traffic and flipped him into the hedge
lining the track at Saratoga. Smith was also wearing an upper-body
cast to support the two vertebrae he fractured in the spill. Dr.
Allen Carl, his orthopedic specialist, said that Smith would return
to the hospital for evaluation in three months. ... Smith was the
leading rider at Saratoga when he was injured, but was not likely
to hold his lead in the final four days of the meet. Jerry Bailey,
who was overtaking Smith in the standing, withdrew his appeal for
careless riding on July 23, and will serve a 10-day suspension
starting Monday. Also, in separate cases, Shaun Bridgmohan withdrew
his appeal and Aaron Gryder lost his appeal. So both also will
serve 10-day suspensions for careless riding.
</P>
</TEXT>
