<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-05 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ Two heroes danced among the mortals Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   They were mammoth figures. Timeless, mythic and larger than
life. One was Mark McGwire, the Cardinals slugger with arms like
cannons and a calm voice that belies the gunpowder drive that has
him chasing a legend.
</P>
<P>
   The other was Babe Ruth, who descended from wherever it is that
hard-living, hard-hitting gods spend eternity and was the legend
whom McGwire chased.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment McGwire stepped onto the Busch Stadium field
hours before Friday night's game against Cincinnati, it was clear
to those of us who once could only imagine the awe that surrounded
Ruth that we no longer had to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   This was it. This was Big Mac chasing the great Bambino on a
breezy, warm night. They were here. McGwire and Ruth. You could see
one of them. You could feel the other.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, considering the many ties that connect these
giant heroes, McGwire received a reception that few baseball greats
have earned before. Maybe only one other baseball hero has seen
what McGwire saw, felt what McGwire felt. Only Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   We know now that McGwire indeed will eclipse the single-season
home-run record belonging to former Yankees great Roger Maris.
Chicago Cubs power merchant Sammy Sosa probably will do it, too.
But outside of Chicago and a few other Cubs havens, it is McGwire
who captivates the imagination and boggles the mind.
</P>
<P>
   And it is because McGwire is baseball's Ruth, while Sosa is its
Maris. McGwire is larger than life. Sosa is having a very good
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Pete Rose thrilled us two decades ago by giving Joe
DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak a little scare. Cal Ripken Jr.
warmed the heart when he chased and caught Lou Gehrig's record of
2,130 consecutive games played. Rickey Henderson was electric when
he broke Lou Brock's mark of 938 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   But none of those feats compared to this. Those were records
grounded in reality, to say nothing of being grounded on the
ground. Those were hustling records, consistency records,
perseverance records. Those were marvelous. But they were not
majestic, monumental and high above the mortals, like the shots
that whistled off Ruth's bat and now sail off McGwire's.
</P>
<P>
   There was a collective gasp from the 48,076 fans who came hoping
to see history Friday night. There were women hanging over railings
and shouting McGwire's name, begging for a look from the handsome
hero, or maybe even a wink of the eye or a doff of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   There were men carrying children on their shoulders, pointing to
McGwire and telling their sons and daughters, ``That's him,'' as if
a godlike figure had appeared, a Ruth-like figure.
</P>
<P>
   During batting practice, McGwire did what Ruth did. He caused
everyone, including the opposing team, to stop and watch. He tugged
on the bill of his batting helmet, flexed his shoulders and began
punishing baseballs, whacking seven shots over the fences. Home
runs bounced off the facade of the upper deck, planted themselves
in the grass over center field and rattled the Plexiglas in the
luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of leather hitting wood sent shivers down the spine.
It was a remarkable display of power by McGwire and unconditional
love from his fans. It was Ruthian.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, McGwire swung mightily in the game, often too
mightily, striking out twice on an 0-for-3 night. He never managed
to hit the historic 60th. It was as if Ruth, watching and reveling
in the scene, tapped McGwire on the shoulder and said, ``Not
tonight, kid.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will happen. And when McGwire smacks his 60th to tie Ruth
_ perhaps today _ he will forevermore be connected to a legend with
whom he has more in common than Maris, Sosa or any other.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, like McGwire, was a massive man. Ruth had big, paw-like
hands and stood 6-2, with a barrel chest. Ruth, like McGwire, also
helped save the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Chicago Black Sox gambling scandal of 1919,
Ruth gave baseball a new dimension with his unfathomable power. He
gave baseball new life. McGwire today has done the same, bringing
back all those fans who vowed after the 1994-95 strike never to set
foot in another big-league ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, like McGwire, didn't just hit home runs. He shot them to
the skies like a baseball god. So does McGwire. On the way to
Friday night's encounter with Ruth's legend, McGwire's 58th home
run traveled 497 feet, his 59th 458 feet. Compare that to Sosa's
56th, which traveled about 340 feet, barely squeezing over the
basket in right field at Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, like McGwire, suffered through a poor season not long
before his record-setting campaign. In 1925, Ruth's carousing
lifestyle led to a struggle at the plate and nearly 60 games missed
with injuries. In 1991, McGwire hit just .201 with 22 homers in 154
games. People wondered about him, too.
</P>
<P>
   But now, McGwire is on a Ruthian streak. Before Friday, he had
hit 12 home runs in his previous 16 games. In 1927, on the way to
60, Ruth finished with a streak of 10 home runs in his final 17
games.
</P>
<P>
   These are legends, so different but so alike. Sometime soon,
McGwire will get No. 60. And somewhere, Ruth surely will plop a
shot of bourbon into his beer, take a long drag on a cigar and
grumble, ``Attaway, kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
