<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEECHES OK, BUT PITCHING MUST DELIVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Is it too late for the Dave Valle speech?
</P>
<P>
   You remember, the one-for-all and all-for-one inspirational
message that ignited the Rangers in their drive to the American
League West title in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Can we get Dave on the phone? Fly him in from Seattle for the
day?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe manager Johnny Oates has it all on cassette and he can
just gather the troops around and turn the volume on the tape
player up as loud as it will go.
</P>
<P>
   Valle delivered that soul-stirring speech on Aug. 9, 1996,
before a game in Toronto and the day after a devastating loss to
the Tigers in Detroit. He said exactly what needed to be said at
exactly the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Valle's words, as the Rangers began their final 23-game drive to
overtake the Anaheim Angels with a 9-3 victory against Minnesota
last night at The Ballpark in Arlington, ring as true today as they
did two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for the Rangers to rededicate and recommit
themselves. Time to spend September focused on one thing and one
thing only: winning.
</P>
<P>
   Time to put away the bows, the guns and the Big Berthas. Time to
stop the talk of postseason hunting trips and the golf vacations.
Time to concentrate on winning each and every game. Time to talk
ball and only ball.
</P>
<P>
   That was Valle's message in '96. With an intuitive sense of
timing, the veteran backup catcher understood that the loss in
Detroit and a scalding postgame lecture from Oates had left the
players open and ready for a positive push in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the entire team, Valle went around the clubhouse, to
each individual player, asking them to commit themselves to each
other for the final seven weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers responded by winning seven straight and nine of 10.
They eventually built their lead to 10 games, allowing them to
withstand a harrowing near-collapse in the season's final two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With only 22 games remaining, it would seem timely for someone
to try and find that magic again. But who?
</P>
<P>
   There is no Valle in the Rangers' clubhouse this season, more's
the pity.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark? He has the fire and the know-how, but his daily
duties as the team's ``Sheriff'' sometimes provokes teammates to
tune out his often shrill message. Besides, Clark may be more
intent on leading by example, as last night's four clutch RBI would
seem to indicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're way past speeches,'' Clark said. ``We've got a lot of
veteran guys in this room. They know what has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McLemore? Another likely choice, except he has had to focus
almost all his energy on his own sore knees, shrinking batting
average and mounting error total.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think speeches are going to do it,'' McLemore said.
``We just have to go out and do our jobs. We have to get all phases
of the game done: pitching, hitting, and defense. Not one out of
three, not two out of three, all three.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland? Ah, now you're onto something. He's articulate,
intense and he has been there. He knows what it takes. Such
speeches, however, rarely seem to come from pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the perception is that the Angels are winning the West
because they want it more, that they're a bunch of over-achievers
playing with grit and determination. Sounds like the '96 Rangers,
doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   While that may be at least partially true, the reality is that
the Angels' team earned-run average (4.44) is almost three-quarters
of a run better than the Rangers' (5.13), who rank second to last
in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we pitch decent,'' Oates said, ``we'll win this sucker. But
we can't give up eight or nine runs a game. If we can hold 'em to
four, we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so simple and yet so true. If they pitch well, the Rangers
have the better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nobody to look at but ourselves,'' McLemore said. ``I
think things will work out. I think we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to tell whether it was a declaration or a
prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
