<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX HELP KEEP TORONTO ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ If the Red Sox want to inspire hope where there is
none, this is the way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more than their most one-sided loss of the
season, a 12-1 beating at the hands of the Toronto Blue Jays under
a full moon and open SkyDome roof Friday night, to cause tremors to
be felt through the Red Sox clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sitting here like, `We got blown out. Wow. What
happened?''' said Mo Vaughn, to whom all divining rods point at the
first hint of trouble on the Olde Towne Team. ``It hasn't happened
too much to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays, who have Roger Clemens on deck this afternoon,
are a season-high nine games over .500 and within seven games of
the Red Sox in the American League wild-card chase after winning
their eighth straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, meanwhile, have lost six of their last nine and haven't
won consecutive games since Aug. 26. With 23 games left, they have
a 6 1/2-game lead over the Texas Rangers, 9-3 winners over the
Twins Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just go play tomorrow,'' Vaughn said. ``We're facing one
of the best pitchers in the game tomorrow, but we got our guy (Bret
Saberhagen) going, and he throws the ball pretty good, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not hanging on strings till the situation takes shape.
Just play the game. If it doesn't happen tomorrow, it will happen
the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly didn't happen Friday night. With Nomar
Garciaparra's 23d error of the season and seventh in the last 14
games setting the tone in the first inning, the Blue Jays won their
second in a row over the Red Sox. After exploiting more Red Sox
sloppiness afield to open a 4-1 lead, they broke the game open with
a seven-run seventh inning fueled by Jose Canseco's three-run home
run off Tim Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I stunk,'' said Wakefield, whose yield of eight
runs was one more than the season-worst seven he had given up
twice, including his last start. ``I couldn't keep us in the game
long enough. I gave up a home run to Canseco that opened up the
game a little bit. That's something I'm not accustomed to doing,
and I don't like to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Garciaparra staggered fill-in first baseman
Mike Benjamin with a hard sinker that Benjamin barely held on to.
Friday night, with plenty of time to throw out Canseco, who is not
known for overexerting himself down the line, Garciaparra bounced
one past Mo Vaughn at first, an error that led directly to the Blue
Jays' first two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green, who had singled and taken third on the error,
scored on a passed ball, Canseco advancing to third, and Canseco
scored on Carlos Delgado's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Stanley of the Red Sox and Darrin Fletcher of the
Blue Jays exchanged bases-empty home runs in the second, Toronto
went ahead, 4-1, in the third when Green's drive hit the base of
the left-field wall and caromed past Troy O'Leary. By the time
O'Leary ran the ball down, Shannon Stewart, who had been hit by a
pitch, scored, and Green took third when O'Leary overthrew two
cutoff men.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Scott Hatteberg dropped Green's foul popup with two out
in the fifth, and Green hit the next pitch for a double, but the
Blue Jays didn't make the Sox pay for that error as Canseco
grounded out to short.
</P>
<P>
   There was no getting off the hook the next time, however, in the
seventh. Craig Grebeck doubled and scored on Stewart's single to
make it 5-1. The Sox pitched out on the next play, correctly
guessing that Stewart would be stealing, but catcher Jason Varitek,
who had entered as a pinch hitter in the seventh, was unable to get
a grip on the ball and never made a throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got it out of the glove,'' Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   A clearly annoyed Wakefield snatched Varitek's toss back to the
mound, then intentionally walked Green. On his first pitch to
Canseco, he hung a knuckleball over the middle of the plate that
Canseco promptly turned into an hors d'ouevre for someone dining in
the Windows Restaurant, his 38th homer crashing off the glassed-in
restaurant located in the second deck of SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   That was all for Wakefield, though there was still more agony
for the Red Sox to endure. Lefthanded reliever David West, proving
to be no more effective for the Sox this time than he had been on
his previous go-round, gave up a single to Delgado and walked Jose
Cruz. When he went ball one on Tony Fernandez, Jimy Williams yanked
him for Carlos Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez hit Reyes's first pitch over the head of center
fielder Darren Lewis for a two-run double, and Fletcher singled
home Fernandez to make it 11-1. Green, who had four hits on the
night, hit his 30th home run in the eighth, making him the first
30-30 player in Toronto history (30 homers, 30 steals).
</P>
<P>
   At game's end, Williams stood behind his desk, still wearing his
Red Sox jacket, arms folded, as reporters filed into his office. He
got off the first question.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are ya?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the question was redirected to him, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play 162, you're going to have some like that,'' he
said. ``What are you going to do? Get ready for tomorrow's game.
That's all you can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I feel? I feel like eating.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one of Williams's strengths, Vaughn would say later,
taking the big losses and the big wins with the same pulse rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know Red Sox Nation is quick to panic,'' he said. ``But
Jimy keeps it regulated. He keeps it all together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
