<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dodgers knew they weren't seeing the real Shawn Estes. They
hope they haven't been watching the real Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   After 31 games with the Dodgers, Grudzielanek finally hit a home
run, a three-run shot Friday night that helped in an 8-5 victory
over the San Francisco Giants in front of 35,182 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It paled in distance to one Charles Johnson hit in the sixth
inning and it hardly compared to the Giants' Barry Bonds, who had
four hits and two walks to set a National League record by reaching
base in 15 consecutive plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek's home run was big for Dodgers starter Darren
Dreifort (8-12). It helped build a 6-0 lead he didn't give back
even though he allowed two-run homers to Ellis Burks and Armando
Rios.
</P>
<P>
   For Rios, who was called up Tuesday, it was his first
major-league hit. For Dreifort, who allowed eight hits and four
walks in seven innings, it was his second straight victory after
going winless in six consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, who are hoping Estes regains his 19-victory form
from 1997, Grudzielanek's homer was bigger. After missing a month
with a sore shoulder, Estes lasted just five innings and his team
dropped three games behind Chicago and New York in the National
League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   But Grudzielanek's homer was biggest for the Dodgers, who are
trying to learn about their future in the final three weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   With no guarantees where many players will wind up after the
season, Friday was was proof there is pop in Grudzielanek's bat.
Since he arrived from Montreal in a July 31 trade, Grudzielanek has
been an excellent defensive shortstop, but he only has three extra
base hits. In 1996 with the Expos, he was lousy in the field but
had 54 doubles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have a dilemma. Opening Day shortstop Jose Vizcaino
has not played since June 21 when he sprained his right ankle. He
has two years and $6 million left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman/leadoff hitter Eric Young, who has just six
stolen bases in the second half after stealing 32 in the first
half, has three years and $14 million left on his contract.
Grudzielanek is making just $300,000 but is eligible for salary
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Young also played a big part Friday night, with three hits,
including a two-run single off Estes (7-9) in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort breezed until the middle innings, allowing just a Bonds
single and two walks until the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   But Burks reached on an infield single and stole second to open
the fifth. Dreifort struck out the next two batters, forcing Giants
manager Dusty Baker to make a decision. Estes was on a pitch count
of 90 and had made just 72.
</P>
<P>
   Baker left Estes in the game and he singled to left. But Matt
Luke made a perfect throw to the plate to hold Burks. After walking
leadoff hitter Marvin Benard, Dreifort struck out Bill Mueller to
end the inning, but he no longer was dominant.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds opened the sixth with a single to center, the 13th
consecutive time he reached base. And for the second straight time
in the game, he was thrown out by Johnson trying to steal second.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeff Kent struck out, Dreifort appeared out of trouble. But
then he walked J.T. Snow and Burks crushed a 1-1 fastball deep into
the left-field stands for a 431-foot homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was Burks' 20th home run and ended a string of consecutive
scoreless innings by Dodgers starters at 232/3. That included five
by Dreifort, nine by Carlos Perez on Wednesday, seven by Ismael
Valdes on Tuesday and the final 22/3 by Chan Ho Park on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Estes left after five, but the Dodgers weren't done. The Giants'
new pitcher, Chris Brock, walked Roger Cedeno to open the sixth
then allowed Johnson's 18th homer to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the eighth, Bonds doubled to left, tying the NL
record set by Pedro Guerrero in July 1985, when he was a member of
the Dodgers. Then in the ninth, he singled off Jeff Shaw to set the
national-league record of 15, one short of the major-league record
held by Boston's Ted Williams, who made it 16 in September 1957.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
