<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS RALLY TO BEAT ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It was supposed to be the make-or-break road trip, the
one that would show if the Angels really had what it takes to win
the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   And after going 6-4 against the AL's best _ New York, Boston and
Cleveland _ the Angels returned to Edison Field on Friday night
saying they had nothing on their minds but the road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   That focus wasn't lost on the Kansas City Royals as Anaheim
clawed back from a two-run deficit, only to see the Royals score
two ninth-inning runs off closer Troy Percival for a 5-3 victory in
front of 33,832 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had their lead over the Texas Rangers in the West cut
to 1{ games. Texas defeated Minnesota, 9-3, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That road trip's over ... It's done,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``We've gotta stop talking about it. What we just did
there (back East) has no bearing on what we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   The players seemed to take that attitude to heart for most of
the night in what could easily have been a letdown situation
against a Royals team that was 11 games under .500 and 13 games
behind Cleveland in the AL Central heading into the game.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the late innings that things finally collapsed
for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals took the lead on a pinch-hit single to right by
veteran Terry Pendleton off Mike Holtz (2-2), scoring Hal Morris
for a 4-3 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   An opposite-field bouncing single to left by Johnny Damon off
the outstretched glove of third baseman Troy Glaus scored Mike
Sweeney with an insurance run.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City closer Jeff Montgomery came on in the ninth to
record his 32nd save of the season, picking up a double-play
grounder from Randy Velarde to quell a potential rally.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Tim Salmon's seventh-inning, two-out single on reliever
Chris Haney's first pitch scored Velarde to put the Angels ahead
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals tied it at 3-3 in the bottom of the seventh on Dean
Palmer's 101st RBI of the season and his third of the game when his
two-out blooper to left-center landed just past the glove of diving
center fielder Jim Edmonds, allowing Damon to score.
</P>
<P>
   Damon led off the inning with a slow tapper to second, but
reached base when Velarde charged and threw wildly to first.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up two runs in the fourth inning, Angels pitcher
Ken Hill, in only his second start since being activated from the
disabled list on Aug. 28, seemed to get stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who pitched seven innings, retired 10 of the final 14
batters he faced, allowing only one to reach second base. He walked
three and struck out six, including Jose Offerman three times.
</P>
<P>
   Hill also received some key defensive help in the seventh after
Morris led off with a single to right. Larry Sutton followed with a
deep fly to right that Garret Anderson caught a few feet from the
warning track before firing to second to double up Morris trying to
tag up from first.
</P>
<P>
   Royals starter Pat Rapp, whose 11-11 record coming into the game
is testament to what has been an inconsistent season for the
31-year-old, showed those same traits early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed only two hits through the first four innings before
letting the Angels tie the game at 2-2 in the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   After Glaus started the inning with a single to left-center,
Rapp induced flyouts from Charlie O'Brien and Gary DiSarcina,
looking as if he would put another inning away.
</P>
<P>
   But then the trouble really started. Rapp walked Edmonds and
Velarde, setting the stage for Anderson. Even then, Rapp looked
like he would escape, but Anderson's grounder to the hole at short
thrown on a bounce into the Royals dugout by Mendy Lopez, allowing
Glaus and Edmonds to score.
</P>
<P>
   On the way by, Anderson's cleat accidentally spiked first
baseman Jeff King in the right heel, forcing him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City took a 2-0 lead in the fourth inning, also using an
error to at least get things started. Damon reached on an error by
Gary DiSarcina at short and moved on to third when Jeremy Giambi
doubled off the scoreboard in right.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, the duo came home on a rocket double to
left-center by Palmer, pushing him to the 100-RBI mark for the
second time in his career. Palmer's career high is 107 RBI in 1996
with the Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
