u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-CUBS-BOS &LR;      09-05 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-CUBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA BLASTS NO. 57 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The third pitch he saw of the night was really a
ball. Well, it would have been a ball if he hadn't swung at it. But
Sammy Sosa swings bats very well. So well that Friday night he was
able to send a fastball 401 feet at Three Rivers Stadium and wipe
out a 68-year-old Cubs record in one motion.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to know the Cubs right fielder to understand the
items that go into his daily diary. You are living his diary with
him. He now has 57 home runs, one more than Hack Wilson had in 1930
_ which stood as both the club and National League record until
Sosa and Mark McGwire started playing home run derby this summer.
The only person who wasn't happy about that was a young man named
Jason Schmidt, the Pirate righthander who gave up the first-inning
solo homer during the Cubs' 5-2 win. Everyone else? Happy.
Especially Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how far you hit a home run,'' Sosa said after his
shot, ``it's still a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter what an official scorer rules, as long as
a run scores. That's a reference to the ninth inning, when Sosa
grounded to third baseman Freddy Garcia, who misplayed the ball and
allowed the tie-breaking run to score. The official ruling was that
it was an error. Sosa thought it should have been a hit. No matter.
The Cubs maintained their one-game lead over the Mets in the
wild-card race and Sosa continued to stoke home run imaginations
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: He's just as excited about this pursuit of Roger Maris
_ and McGwire _ as you are. Each time McGwire went to the plate
Friday night in St. Louis, the at-bat was shown on the stadium
scoreboard here. Sosa peeked a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking,'' Sosa said. ``I'm a Mark McGwire fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sosa was asked why he always calls McGwire
``The Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has 59 home runs,'' Sosa replied, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is now within two home runs of season leader McGwire and
five away from breaking the major league record set by Maris in
1961. With each homer, Sosa knows the crowds will grow. He knows
some of the fans will boo, as many among the 36,510 (the Pirates
drew just over 8,000 Thursday) did Friday night in the fourth
inning. Sosa's crime? He did something silly. He singled. And his
teammates were worse. They actually played a game, when they should
have known everyone was here to watch Sosa swing. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hilarious when crowds get up to leave late in the game
after Sammy has batted,'' first baseman Mark Grace said. ``I'm
like, `Hey, don't you want to see me and my 14 home runs?'''
</P>
<P>
   Long after Sosa sent Schmidt's 2-0 pitch into the right-field
stands, the Cubs lounged in their locker room and did what everyone
does these days. They watched McGwire. ``I know how you feel, Big
Mac,'' Grace said as McGwire fell behind in the count. He would
eventually strike out. The Cubs went back to their conversations.
</P>
<P>
   This has been Sosa's routine for the last eight weeks. It
usually begins with a glance at the highlight shows, a prayer, a
chat with the media, a home run or two during the game, an ovation
from a home or opposing crowd (``I feel like this is my house,'' he
said of Three Rivers Friday night), and, by nightfall, a summary of
his previous 20 hours or so. We hope you're having fun during this
season. Sosa is. You said something about pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure?'' he said. ``This isn't pressure. Pressure for me
was when I was back home, a shoeshine boy. Yeah, I was a shoeshine
boy. Trying to make money for my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in the Dominican Republic, where Sosa's bats were tree
branches or slabs of wood. Baseballs were actually socks with
rubber taped in the middle of them. Word is that the stroke was
good even then. He said he dreamed of coming to the United States
back then, and since coming here, he hasn't stopped saying, ``I
love this country.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated that phrase at least four times Friday. Someone told
him he sounded like boxing promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Sosa said, smiling again. ``I say, `God bless America.'
He says, `Only in America.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Sosa is enjoying the publicity. He knows no one
expected him to be in this race. Know how many home runs he had as
of May 24? Nine. By that time, McGwire had 24. But the next day,
Sosa hit two home runs and hasn't stopped swatting balls into the
skies of Pittsburgh, Chicago, St. Louis, Los Angeles, New York ...
</P>
<P>
   Since May 25, Sosa has outhomered McGwire, 48-35. But he doesn't
mind if more people are rooting for McGwire. He is rooting for him,
too. He expects Americans to root for the powerful redhead. Just as
many in the Dominican Republic expected Leonel Fernandez, the
president of the country, to call Sosa after he hit his 56th home
run to tie Wilson's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire is the man here, but I'm the man over there,''
Sosa said. ``If he goes there, I'll pass my _ how do you say? _ my,
uh, my crown to him for the day he's going to be there. And after
he leaves, I'll take it back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
