</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-APOLOGY (Dublin) _ President Clinton, at a news
conference in Ireland in the wake of Sen. Lieberman's critical
speech, says ``I'm sorry.'' By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LIEBERMAN (Washington) _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman, a
longtime political supporter of Bill Clinton, said Friday that it
was conversation around his family's meal tables during a beach
vacation that prompted his taking the Senate floor the day before
to denounce the president. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KIDS (New York) _ America's children, some as young as
7, are aware that President Clinton was unfaithful to his wife, but
they seem less interested in the sexual details of the White House
scandal than the moral shortcomings of a man who would deceive and
hurt his family. By Jane Gross. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-GIRLSLAIN (Chicago) _ Prosecutors in Chicago dropped
their murder case against a 7-year-old and 8-year-old boys who
police said confessed to attacking a girl riding her bicycle in
their neighborhood. A crime laboratory report issued to prosecutors
showed the presence of semen in the 11-year-old girl's underpants.
Police crime experts said it's highly unlikely that boys so young
could produce semen. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RDP (Peggy's Cove, Nova Scotia) _ As grieving families
from several countries began to converge on this tiny fishing
village on Friday, officials looking for the cause of the crash of
Swissair Flight 111 on Wednesday said that it appeared that the
crew was in control of the jet and making rational decisions about
how to land the stricken plane until it abruptly disappeared from
radar. By Randy Kennedy and Matthew L. Wald. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-VICTIMS (Undated) _ The dark waters swallowed 229 lives
when Swissair Flight 111 plunged into the Atlantic on Wednesday
night, and Friday many grieving families began the painful process
of trying to recover their dead. By Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-DITCH (Undated) _ Despite the demonstrations by flight
attendants on how to inflate a life vest, and instructional videos
on how passengers should operate the life vests, the chances of a
pilot successfully ditching a stricken aircraft in the water are
very slim. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERAL-PRIEST (Rochester, N.Y.) _ When the Rev. James B. Callan
says his last Mass at Corpus Christi Roman Catholic Church on
Sunday, he can look back on a 22-year ministry that packed the pews
on Sunday and created a battery of programs to help the poor, but
that also moved so far away from standard church practices
regarding the roles of women, gays and non-Catholics in the church
that he has been removed from his job. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   ND-MARIS-HOMETOWN (Fargo, N.D.) _ While most of the country is
gripped by irrepressible excitement as Mark McGwire of the St.
Louis Cardinals and Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs move ever closer
to the magic number, people in Fargo are wrestling with more
complicated feelings. They are grateful for the sudden flood of
recognition being paid their cherished hometown hero, Roger Maris,
but they are achingly aware it is more of a requiem than a
coronation. By Pam Belluck. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLON-YOUTH-MARCH (New York) _ Intent on preventing any
outbreaks of violence, the Police Department plans to saturate the
site of Saturday's planned rally in Harlem with as many as 250
officers along each of the six blocks set aside for the event. By
John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   HELICOPTER-CRASH (Washington) _ Two Air Force helicopters
crashed early today on a nighttime training mission over a remote
mountainous area in Nevada, killing all 12 crewmen on both craft.
By Steven Lee Myers. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CARIBBEAN-PARADE (New York) _ Caribbean New Yorkers prepare
lavish, and popular, pageant. By Somini Sengupta and Garry
Pierre-Pierre. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Hours after Russia's acting prime
minister finally laid out his program to pull the country out of
its economic crisis, Parliament Friday put off a crucial vote on
the new government until Monday, buying more time for political
negotiations. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ASSESS (Moscow) _ As Viktor Chernomyrdin has battled to
become prime minister, critics have wondered how he could placate
the Communists and still take tough steps to rescue Russia from its
deepening economic crisis. By Michael R. Gordon. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-TRIBUNAL (Arusha, Tanzania) _ A U.N. tribunal sentenced a
former prime minister of Rwanda to life in prison on Friday for his
part in the 1994 genocide there, despite his agreement to plead
guilty and to testify against other high-ranking officials. By
James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ North Korea said on Friday that the
purpose of its launching on Monday of a two-stage rocket was to
carry a satellite into orbit, not to test a missile. It denounced
Japan and other countries for jumping to the conclusion that it was
launching a new class of missile. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-CROCODILE (Massa Marittima, Italy) _ Wrestling with the
pseudo-crocodile. By John Tagliabue. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (San Francisco) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, signaled Friday that the central bank is now less
concerned about inflation as a threat to the U.S. economy but is
increasingly wary that the spreading global financial crisis could
harm the United States. By David E. Sanger with Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The labor market rebounded in August
as GM workers returned following the strikes' settlement. The
unemployment rate was unchanged at 4.5 percent. Payrolls rose by
365,000 jobs, in line with forecasts. Workers' average hourly
earnings, a gauge of business costs, rose half a percent, or 7
cents, after having increased 0.2 percent during July. By Sylvia
Nasar. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   CORPUS-CHRISTI-TOURISM (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ Corpus Christi,
a socially conservative and heavily Hispanic city, has few
spectacular natural assets or claims to fame. Instead, it has gone
about its pursuit of tourism in a methodical manner, investing
millions to try to overcome some difficult strokes of geographical
misfortune. And success is already evident in the rising number of
visitors. By Edwin McDowell. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ With Brazil's stock
market in a nosedive and the central bank spending as much as $1
billion a day to defend the currency, economists warned that Latin
America's biggest economy could pull the region into a recession.
By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market flirted with the bears
again Friday, as the Dow Jones industrial average fell below where
it closed Monday, the day of the 512-point, 6 percent plunge that
shook investors here and around the world. But in the last-half
hour, the Dow and other indexes rebounded, cutting their losses by
two-thirds and more. Still, the Dow was off 5.1 percent for the
week and gave up most of Tuesday's 288 point rally. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTELLECTUALS-LABOR (Undated) _ The labor movement and
intellectuals on the left have been attempting a reconciliation
after a long period of estrangement. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   LURIE-NOVELS (Undated) _ It has often been said Alison Lurie
writes comedies of manners. That, she admitted in a recent
interview, is more accurate than saying she writes ``tragedies of
morals.'' The truth is that her novels are comedies of manners and
morals, which explore the lives of the literati and the
relationships between the sexes in academia. By Mel Gussow. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   UNUSUAL-MUSEUMS (Undated) _ Museums built on the passion to
collect ... anything. By Michael Kimmelman. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN-DAY (New York) _ Lesser-known figures get their
moment on stage. By Christopher Clarey. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-$MILLION-BID (Undated) _ $1 million bid for No. 62 ball. By
Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   INTELLECTUALS-FOOTBALL (Undated) The tension between culture and
football. By Samuel G. Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Katzenmoyer plays; Ohio State
takes a hit. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN (St. Louis) _ Everybody celebrates the next
one. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BASEBALL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Hack Wilson's lesson remains a
valid one. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   OPINION _ COMMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `k' category)
</P>
<P>
   BAKER-COLUMN (Undated) Top of the mountain. By Russell Baker.
</P>
<P>
   OBITUARIES
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-WILLIAMS _ Crash victim Roger Williams, 54, found way to
