A0764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-600&AMP;     09-05 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IT GOES: SOSA CONNECTS FOR NO. 57 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire aren't giving Mark
Grace much time to work out his etiquette problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a hard time deciding what to do,'' said Grace, the
Chicago Cubs' veteran first baseman. ``If Sammy gets to 62 home
runs _ or let me say, when Sammy gets to 62, we would usually mob
him at home plate. That's the record. But if McGwire gets to 62
first, do I just give Sammy a handshake when he does it? It won't
be the record anymore. This is a crazy year.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace's dilemma moved closer Friday night, as Sosa hit his 57th
home run in the first inning of the red-hot Cubs' 5-2 victory over
the Pittsburgh Pirates. The Dominican hit a high, outside fastball
an estimated 401 feet into the seats in right-center field at Three
Rivers Stadium. The homer came on a 2-0 pitch from right-hander
Jason Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa received a huge ovation from the 36,510 fans in Pittsburgh,
and he replied with a tip of his cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in my house right now,'' Sosa said of the
reception.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the ninth inning, Sosa knocked in the game-winning run
when his hard-hit infield grounder was mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs _ who have won five in a row _ remained one game ahead
of the New York Mets and two games ahead of the Giants, pending San
Francisco's result at Los Angeles later Friday night, in the NL
wild-card race. If they hold on, it would be the Cubs' first
playoff appearance since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa moved back to two homers behind McGwire in the race to beat
Roger Maris' single-season record of 61 home runs set in 1961.
McGwire went 0-for-3, walking once, in the Cardinals' 3-2 loss to
Cincinnati Friday night in St. Louis, and remained at 59 home runs.
One player or the other has homered on five straight game days.
</P>
<P>
   The two sluggers are threatening to outpace the field in the
manner of Babe Ruth _ or Secretariat. Fans and reporters talk
endlessly of a player's pace for the season. But a better indicator
might be their recent performance. If they were to extend their
success of the past three weeks, McGwire and Sosa would end up with
71 and 68 home runs, respectively. McGwire has 22 games remaining,
and Sosa has 21. In their previous 22 games, each player has hit an
extraordinary 12 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's turns at bat in St. Louis were shown in Pittsburgh on
the giant video screen in center field, irking the Cubs, who
believe it encourages Sosa to swing for the fences. ``I like to
wait till after the game to know,'' Sosa said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa now rank one and two on the historical list of
home runs in a season by a National League player. They are trailed
by Hack Wilson, who held the National League and Cubs record of 56
from 1930 until Tuesday. Next on the list is Ralph Kiner, who hit
54 for the Pirates in 1949, the best post-war effort before this
year.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was expected to challenge the record. After all, last
year he hit 58 with Oakland and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa? His previous career high was 40. How does a hitter
improve his power so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing a lot more pitches this year,'' Sosa said before
Friday night's game, entertaining a gaggle of reporters before
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   His news conference was moved from his locker to the field,
because the crush of cameras is now too great.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa might have Grace, or Manager Jim Riggleman, to thank for
his jump in productivity. Last year on the last-place Cubs, Sosa
hit fourth in the lineup, in front of Ryne Sandberg (.264 batting
average) and Shawon Dunston (.284). This year he is followed by
Grace (.319) and Brant Brown (.303).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He leads the NL in runs batted in and total bases, and his
batting average of .313 is much higher than his pre-1998 career
average of .257. He has waited more patiently for pitches, hitting
more than one-fourth of his home runs to the opposite field. He has
homered in 15 straight series and at least once against every NL
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For McGwire, every at-bat is a home run, a walk or a
strikeout,'' Grace said. ``Sammy is pushing us into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Sosa went 2-for-5. Leading off the fourth inning,
Sosa hit a single to left, took third on a single by Grace and
scored. In the sixth, he struck out, and in the eighth, he reached
on an error.
</P>
<P>
   After three games here, Sosa and the Cubs fly to St. Louis to
confront McGwire and the Cardinals on Monday afternoon and Tuesday
night. The Cubs scratched their rookie star pitcher, Kerry Wood,
from Sunday's lineup because of a sore elbow on his pitching arm.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said the record might not wait until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is very, very focused right now,'' Sosa said. ``He's
going to hit some this week. He's very into breaking the record
this weekend. He's not going to wait for me. I hope that he breaks
it before I go over there. That will make it easier for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 0247EDT &QL; 
