<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0766 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-CORRIGAN-$ADV     09-05 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-CORRIGAN-$ADV06-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN OF '87 SEES LITTLE CAUSE FOR ALARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the world's stock markets wobble wildly, Asian economies sink
into recession, Russia slams the door on its creditors and U.S. and
foreign financial institutions make provisions for billions in
losses, the Treasury and the Federal Reserve are hastily dusting
off their primers on financial crisis management.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the current turmoil, few of the world's financial leaders
have much to say publicly. But some who have seen markets plunge
before believe the reaction to recent events is overwrought.
</P>
<P>
   One is E. Gerald Corrigan, who as president of the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York for a decade was the nation's financial
fireman at the time of the 1987 stock market crash.
</P>
<P>
   There is suddenly too much pessimism, Corrigan said in an
interview last week. Stressing the current capital strength of the
U.S. financial system and the absence of major credit problems, he
argued that the world was better positioned to withstand stress
than it had been in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly all news is bad news, after a period when all news is
good news,'' said Corrigan, 57, now a managing director at Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. ``The truth, as always, lies somewhere in between.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from Montana, where he was on vacation after the
Kansas City Federal Reserve's annual conference in Jackson Hole,
Wyo., Corrigan underscored that he is now a Wall Streeter, without
inside knowledge of government efforts to deal with the new round
of turbulence. It has been nearly five years since he stepped down
as president of the New York Fed after a long career.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Corrigan readily acknowledges, there is some truth to the
maxim ``Once a central banker, always a central banker.'' And he is
married to one, as well; last October, he wed Cathy Minehan, the
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston. Corrigan, the Fed
and Goldman, Sachs have all said they have established procedures
to guard against potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   While the roots of today's turmoil are structural problems in
Asia's economy _ weak banking systems, for example, and Japan's
paralysis _ the surprise is that Russia is now roiling world
markets, Corrigan said. He called the country ``kind of the wild
card.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, is ``because while its economy is nowhere near
big enough to have much effect on world markets,'' it has caused
``political anxiety, and its contagion effect has been greater than
anyone expected.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``got markets very nervous'' about Russia, he said, was the
government's declaration, effectively, of a unilateral moratorium
on paying both foreign and domestic bonds and its further
moratorium on the foreign currency liabilities of Russian
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Such steps are anathema to central bankers, Corrigan said. Debt
moratoriums ``fundamentally seem to be so in conflict with the
whole fabric of the credit system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises the question: If it could happen there, could it
happen somewhere else?'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Corrigan argued, the prospect of debt repudiation is not
as threatening as it was in the 1980s. ``If you look at the system
as a whole, we are not nearly as leveraged as we were in the mid-
to late '80s,'' he said. ``Some institutions will take some lumps
here. But none of this should be remotely life-threatening for the
system.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is a sharp contrast to the days after Black Monday in 1987,
when the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 22.8 percent in a
single trading session. ``If you go back to the stock market crash
of '87, especially the Tuesday or Wednesday, every newspaper was
laden with stories about credit problems,'' Corrigan recalled.
``That's not the question today.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the question today is how to prevent the collapse of
economies in countries ranging from Thailand to Russia. Asked what
remedies he might suggest, Corrigan referred to ``Sovereign
Financial Crises: Facing Realities and Building a More Secure
Future,'' a paper he wrote in May. It strongly suggests that
prevention is far preferable to searching for cures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a crisis strikes, the country, its creditors, its
investors and the official community are left with nothing but bad
choices,'' the paper states. Corrigan argues instead for better and
more prompt dissemination of economic information, tougher
conditions on lending, increased financial resources for the
International Monetary Fund and stronger banking systems.
</P>
<P>
   From his office at Goldman, Sachs, Corrigan has had a hand in
trying to manage some of the recent crises. He has advised South
Korea and Thailand as those countries seek to pull themselves up
from Asia's continuing woes; earlier, he consulted with the Mexican
and Argentine governments.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York Fed in the early 1990s, Corrigan also worked
with Russian leaders, forming a friendship with President Boris
Yeltsin and becoming chairman of the Russian-American bankers'
forum, which has sought to provide training and technical help to
the Russian banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the current tangle of international financial problems,
Corrigan keeps faith in the world's ability to withstand the
current buffeting. ``Financial markets are really quite
resilient,'' he said. ``They really can handle most things _ unless
there is the perception or reality of major credit problems in the
system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
