<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-VIOLENCE-     09-05 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-VIOLENCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING IN A VIOLENT WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Strahan, the Giants' Pro Bowl defensive end, was chasing
down the Washington Redskins running back Terry Allen, his eyes
locked on the target. Wide receiver Michael Westbrook, running in
the opposite direction with a full head of steam, hit Strahan with
a vicious crack-back block that knocked the nearly 285-pound
Strahan off his feet. Then Westbrook stood over Strahan and
celebrated, pointing a finger in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a cheap shot,'' Strahan said. ``He could have
killed me. But that's life in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   That life is more violent than ever. While Strahan was not
injured on that play, many doctors, team trainers and National
Football League team executives agree that the increases in the
size and speed of the players today have led to record numbers of
severe injuries, including concussions, ripped ligaments, popped
tendons, even cases of paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the violence that officials and fans do not see,
shrouded by a massive cloak of bodies weighing thousands of pounds.
Kicks in the groin, punches in the stomach, gouged eyes and bitten
fingers and arms are all common in the pileups after tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan and some 1,500 fellow players have spent the summer in
intense, almost militaristic training camps preparing for the
exhilarating but brutal ritual that is the NFL season, which begins
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Players train for a game that is more violent than any other
organized sport, one in which, to be effective, they must reach a
peak of aggressiveness at least 16 times during the season _
regardless of the effect it has on them off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, it is a strange thing that we do,''
the Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead said. ``During a game we want
to kill each other. Then we're told to shake hands and drive home
safely. Then a week later we try to kill each other again.''
</P>
<P>
   How players deal with that weekly cycle, punctuated by 60
minutes of cold-blooded fury, is an unnerving and largely unstudied
chapter of life in the NFL. But it is apparent from interviews with
dozens of players as well as team officials and psychologists that
a significant number of players are not able to leave that fury on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   The up-and-down cycle of the NFL may affect a player's long-term
mental health and cause strains in the relationships players have
with loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football can take more years off a player's life than drug
abuse,'' said Chris Shannon, a therapist who is coordinator of the
player's assistance program for the San Francisco 49ers and has
worked with dozens of NFL players since 1982. ``I find that
football players spend so much time gearing up for the violence
they have no energy left for anything else in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game ends, players are asked to become normal citizens
with girlfriends and wives and children. Many are able to make that
transition. Strahan, 26 years old and beginning his sixth season
with the Giants, plays football's most violent position, but
manages to be one of the game's most pleasant men off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the game is rough,'' he said. ``There are times when I
look at film the day after we play and I can't believe what I see:
the hits, the busted-up bodies. But at the same time, I won't let
the game change me into a maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan is able to do that, he says, by keeping football in its
proper perspective. He does become extremely focused before a game,
barely speaking to his girlfriend, Jean Muggli, on the couple's
drive from their New Jersey apartment to Giants Stadium, as he
reviews what he has to do. But after the game, Strahan is back to
his outgoing self when the two go with friends to a long dinner or
a movie. Strahan does not let football take control of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But not all players are so successful. For some, leaving the
violence of the game on the field proves harder than winning a
Super Bowl ring. A few bring it home; there have been widely
publicized cases of domestic violence involving the Seahawks
quarterback Warren Moon and the Giants safety Tito Wooten, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists who work with NFL players say that lengthy careers
in the NFL may permanently change some players emotionally. John
Hannah, the Hall of Fame guard who played for the New England
Patriots from 1973 to 1985 and is now an investment banker, still
seeks counseling occasionally to help him cope with the absence of
the adrenaline rush he would feel during his playing days, 13 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah says he sometimes speaks with Vietnam veterans seeking
advice, because football players, like war veterans, can suffer the
symptoms of post-traumatic stress disorder. ``There are cases where
the post-traumatic stress in players rivals that of men who have
come back from wars,'' Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug use in the NFL has declined drastically since the 1980s,
but it is still a problem, especially cocaine, because it gives
players the same invigorating feeling they get from playing
football, Shannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Players use a variety of means to get themselves ready for a
game. Some isolate themselves from everyone, even family and
friends. Shannon said that players will sequester themselves from
loved ones before games not because they want to focus better, but
because ``they are basically nonviolent people who have to gear up
to see a side of themselves they don't want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Millen, who played in the NFL for 10 years and is now an
analyst for Fox, said, ``It's the most unspoken but powerful part
of the game, that deep-seated desire to be better at all costs,
even if it means alienating your family or friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan does not go that far, but he does get quiet, sometimes
grouchy, because his attention is shifting from the everyday
aspects of life to having to deal with the violence on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Bailey, a 12-year veteran linebacker who is currently
unsigned, said that on the day before a game he would not answer
his telephone or the door and would spend most of the night
alternating between reading passages of the Bible and visualizing
various game scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Players are not alone in their intense efforts to prepare
themselves for games. They are coached to brutalize their
opponents, to act, as Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor once said,
``like a bunch of crazed dogs.'' Some coaches tell their players to
try and knock out opponents, to knock quarterbacks out of the game
or to take out someone's knees.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists maintain that sometimes players are so intense in
this preparation that the needs of family members become secondary.
That may be why divorce is a significant problem among players,
according to a National Football League Players Association study.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1989 survey of former players, 50 percent of those who
responded said playing in the NFL caused problems in their personal
lives; that figure was 30 percent in 1970. About 33 percent of the
respondents said that they were divorced. Some therapists who work
with NFL players believe the divorce rate in professional football
is over 60 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the high rate of separation, therapists say, is
that players want to take the same risks in their personal lives
that they do when they play. An extramarital affair may be a way to
recapture the excitement of a blocked punt or a touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would venture to say there are a lot of marital problems
right before camp starts and during the season,'' said Millen.
``There are probably a lot of arguments between players and their
wives. It happened with my marriage. You have to be selfish,
getting ready for a game that only a handful of people understand.
It's tough on the people around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen retired six years ago, after playing for the Oakland
Raiders, the San Francisco 49ers and the Redskins, but his playing
days often come flashing back into his life. Last year, Millen was
playing a game in the family's swimming pool with his then
14-year-old son. When his son started to beat him in the game,
Millen began to feel the competitive urges again. He started to
pile up points against his son. Then more points. And more.
Millen's wife suddenly yelled, ``Matt!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad,'' Millen's son told him, ``you're sick.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens on the field can affect loved ones in more innocent
ways. Once, Strahan got into a fight with a teammate during
practice. They later apologized to each other, but the wife of the
player approached Muggli afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two players get into a fight on the field, they go out over a
beer and it's over, but two years later the wives are still mad at
each other,'' said Muggli, only partly kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has always been a part of professional football. Hannah
recalled a play in his rookie season in 1973 when he ran downfield
and crashed head-on into another player. Hannah felt a ringing in
his ears. When he tried to button his chin strap, he noticed his
helmet was cracked almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the 1990s is that the players are bigger and
faster and the collisions more fierce. There are more 300-pound
players than ever. Guard David Dixon and tackle Korey Stringer, the
right side of the Minnesota Vikings' offensive line, weigh a
combined 705 pounds, making them the largest duo in NFL history.
The explosion in speed has been equally startling; it is not
unusual for 240-pound linebackers to run with sprinters' speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I don't even recognize the game
anymore,'' said the former Giants quarterback Phil Simms, a Super
Bowl most valuable player who played 14 seasons. ``It's so fast and
brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL seems to understand that more controls are needed; in
recent years several rules have been passed in an attempt to make
the game less dangerous, including more protection for quarterbacks
and a crackdown on vicious chop blocking. But despite the rules
changes, the NFL remains savage.
</P>
<P>
   Equally brutal is the routine, play-by-play battle for physical
and psychological domination. There are bites that nobody sees,
punches in the stomach that go unnoticed and illegal leg-whips that
officials miss. One player said that he urinated on an opponent
last season and that no one noticed except the other player, who
responded with a swift kick to the groin on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jets tackle Jumbo Elliott played against the Bears
linebacker Bryan Cox last year, before Cox signed with the Jets in
the off season, Elliott smashed hard into Cox on one play, sending
him toppling backward. As they both fell, with the 300-pound
Elliott on top, Cox punched Elliott in the ribs several times. When
they hit the ground Elliott grabbed Cox around the throat. Elliott,
his face inches away from Cox's, then asked a simple question. ``Do
you know who's in control of this situation?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski spit in the face
of the San Francisco wide receiver J.J. Stokes during a nationally
televised game and it caused an uproar because seldom had that
nasty part of NFL life been caught live on camera. But most players
were not surprised, because such acts are simply extensions of the
game's violence.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining such constant ferocity can be much more devastating
to the psyche than most players realize, and the effects may last
years after a player retires. Harry Carson, the linebacker who
played for the Giants from 1976-88 (and estimates he had 18
concussions during that time), said he stayed wired for two months
after the Giants won Super Bowl XXI, sleeping only two to three
hours a night.
</P>
<P>
   Another former player said he became addicted to the violence.
Four years ago, craving a physical pounding, he attacked his two
Rottweilers, both weighing more than 125 pounds, punching them,
hoping to instigate an attack. The dogs bit him on his hands and
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan, for one, has been able to remain well-adjusted in the
cold-blooded atmosphere. A second-round draft pick out of Texas
Southern University in 1993, he gained immediate respect from
teammates even as a rookie because of his combination of ferocious
play, professionalism and friendly personality. He has evolved into
a leader on a defense that is among the best in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Football has had few effects on his personal life, Strahan said,
especially since he began dating Muggli four years ago. They became
engaged March 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football hasn't overwhelmed us,'' Muggli said.
</P>
<P>
   But because football is such a demanding sport, one that during
the season requires a 16-hour workday nearly every day, it is bound
to cause stress in even the strongest relationships. Before
training camp or a big game, Strahan can become distant. Muggli
will sometimes make him dinner, serve it, then leave the room so
Strahan can be alone. Therapists say such behavior is normal;
still, it can cause strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks before camp, you can feel the tension,''
Muggli said. ``Sometimes I will tell him, `Michael, we're on the
same team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those times are rare, however, because Strahan works hard at not
bringing his frustrations home. The few times a year when Strahan
gets fed up with football, he often goes golfing to blow off steam
or to a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Some players find it difficult to relax after a game, especially
a loss, not speaking to loved ones or friends until several days
later. Others, like Strahan, go through specific routines that help
them calm down after a game; being social is part of that process.
Strahan, Muggli and friends like to go to a long dinner after a
game, and by the time they get home, usually late, Strahan is
unwound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are great,'' Strahan said, ``because for a couple of
hours you forget about all the craziness that happened on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bailey was with the Giants in 1993 and 1994, he did similar
things after home games. He would reserve a table for four at a
Manhattan restaurant, sit by himself and watch people sing on
open-microphone night. ``It was nice to be by myself and watch
someone else perform for a change,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all players have strategies for handling the football life
like Strahan and Bailey do. Some current or former players may know
they have a problem, but don't seek therapy because it is
considered a sign of weakness, despite such services being
available from the league.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the NFL is believed to have the most sophisticated and
thorough player assistance program in sports. The program, headed
by Lem Burnham, a psychologist and former player for the
Philadelphia Eagles who is vice president of player and employee
development for the NFL, can address almost any player need.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said the NFL is not violent but physical. The
difference: violence is shooting or robbing someone, he said; the
hard hitting in the NFL is physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that violent people don't enter the NFL,''
Burnham said. ``They bring violence to the game; the game doesn't
bring violence to them.''
</P>
<P>
   If players do feel the game is changing them, Burnham said, the
NFL has 150 therapists, specialists in many different fields, on
call to help. Players are promised confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   But when players come into the league, they are not thinking
about the brutality of the sport. They want to make a team, and
they will do anything to accomplish that goal, even if it means
sacrificing their own physical or mental well being.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Cindrich, an agent, conducted a survey this year of 100
highly rated NFL rookies, and 55 percent of the respondents said it
would be worth it even if doctors told them they would require a
knee or hip replacement by age 55.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I see with a lot of guys is that outside of
football, they have nothing else,'' Strahan said. ``They lose
perspective on life. That's when all of the other problems come in.
When you get ready for a season, when you play during a season, you
want to be focused, play hard, give the game everything you have.
But at the same time you want to keep your perspective on life and
stay grounded. It's hard but it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
