<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; var-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-REV     09-05 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-LITTLE LEAGUERS: THE BOYS OF SUMMER ONCE REALLY WERE BOYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pictures of the Little League champions from Toms River, N.J.,
standing proudly next to their Yankee counterparts during the
National Anthem at Yankee Stadium last Tuesday did more than give
the kids the second thrill of their lives in a week. They evoked
the fact that the big leaguers once were Little Leaguers
themselves, sporting baggy uniforms and major league dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember it like it was yesterday,'' said Paul
O'Neill, the Yankee right fielder, who played Little League in
Columbus, Ohio. ``I remember pitching when I was 12. I pitched the
championship game and struck out a kid named Darren Waugh to end
it. I remember every detail. The games then meant as much to you as
these games do now. And you got to go to Dairy Queen afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 80 percent of today's major leaguers played Little
League baseball _ including players from places outside the United
States, like Panama (Mariano Rivera of the Yankees) and even tiny
Curacao (Andruw Jones of the Atlanta Braves). Eight played in the
Little League World Series. Derek Bell of the Houston Astros and
Gary Sheffield of the Los Angeles Dodgers were on the same Tampa,
Fla., team in 1980. Only one played for a champion: Marc Pisciotta,
a right-hander for the Chicago Cubs, pitched his Marietta, Ga.,
team to the 1983 title.
</P>
<P>
   With or without any national glory, major leaguers look back on
their Little League days more nostalgically as the years pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just had fun,'' said the Yankee shortstop Derek Jeter, who
played in Kalamazoo, Mich. ``You didn't worry about making an error
or striking out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee pitcher David Wells, already beefy as an 11-year-old
in San Diego, once slammed two home runs in a game, and played
every position but one. ``Catcher,'' he said. ``I refused.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first at-bat as a 10-year-old in Southern California,
Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals hit _ what else? _ a home
run. (Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, his rival in the current
home-run chase, didn't play Little League ball in his native
Dominican Republic.)
</P>
<P>
   For Cal Ripken, the iron man of the Baltimore Orioles, the
Little League was the place to hone a boy's unabashed love for
baseball. ``I shined my shoes after every game,'' Ripken recalled,
``and sometimes wore my uniform to bed because I couldn't wait for
the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter can't imagine how the Toms River boys withstood the
pressure of playing before 41,200 spectators at the World Series
last weekend in Williamsport, Pa., with millions more watching on
national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, there were like 12 people in the stands,''
he said. ``And all of them were parents.'' Not that those folks
can't get pretty boisterous themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alomar, the catcher for the Cleveland Indians, grew up in
Puerto Rico, where baseball is a cultural passion. ``The thing I
remember the most is the competitiveness, and a lot of that has to
do with the parents,'' he said. ``The Little League parents are
even worse in Puerto Rico than they are in the States. They will
scream at the kids for whole games. They put a lot of pressure on
the kids. Every parent thinks their kid is going to play in the
major leagues someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Mack, the Hall of Fame manager for the Philadelphia
Athletics in the first half of the century, looked into the future
with a more discerning eye. In 1954, when he watched the Little
League World Series, he commented to a friend, ``I wouldn't be
surprised if some of these kids made it to the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Five players went on to become the first Little
League World Series veterans to reach the big leagues, including
the 1962 National League Rookie of the Year, Ken Hubbs, and the
Baltimore Orioles slugger Boog Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while youngsters dream of reaching The Show, most have
other, more pressing concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two teams in our area, the Lions and the Expos,''
recalled Chipper Jones, the Atlanta Braves third baseman.
``Everybody wanted to play for the Lions because they had
better-looking uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan, who struck out more batters and threw more
no-hitters than any major leaguer ever, said his fondest baseball
memories were of Little League ball in Alvin, Texas. ``We played
for the love of the game and the camaraderie,'' he said. ``Little
League was the first opportunity for children in Alvin to get
involved in any organized activity. It was one of the biggest
events in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   So even if the boys of Toms River never won the World Series,
never stood next to the Yankees at the Stadium and never make the
majors, they won't forget their Little League days. Still, it makes
you wonder who some of them might be standing next to in 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 0955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NFC-2TAKE     09-05 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NFC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS, VIKINGS AND NINERS PICKED AS NFC DIVISION WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: Teams previewed in predicted order of finish
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EASTERN DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Giants
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 10-5-1, division champion.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ It all starts and stops with the defense. Defensive
end Michael Strahan and linebacker Jessie Armstead, both Pro Bowl
players, were big reasons why the Giants had a league-high plus-25
turnover ratio, third-best in the league since the 1970 merger.
Losing cornerback Jason Sehorn (torn knee ligaments) hurts
tremendously. But the defense remains rock solid and will carry the
Giants back to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The running game. Tyrone Wheatley has the speed and
size to be productive, but still doesn't have the support of the
coaching staff. Gary Brown is solid, but he may not be the answer.
The Giants want to use fullback Charles Way as a fulltime running
back, but Way isn't crazy about the idea. Tiki Barber has had his
problems in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Like last season, the Giant defense will shut down
offenses, the offense will do enough to get by and the coaching
staff, led by Coach Jim Fassel, will find ways to help the team
again win the division.
</P>
<P>
   2. Washington
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 8-7-1
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ In Coach Norv Turner's fifth year, it is about time
he lived up to his reputation. The Redskins have had winning
seasons the last two years but have not made the playoffs. This
year they have two big guys in the middle who are each a dessert
short of 320 pounds in defensive tackles Dan Wilkinson and Dana
Stubblefield. With that kind of beef, very few teams should have
success running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The lasting impression of quarterback Gus Frerotte
is after scoring a touchdown against the Giants last season, he ran
into a wall near the end zone and banged his head into it. He needs
to be more stable, as does wideout Michael Westbrook, who has a
tendency to run undisciplined routes.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Turner will either corral all of this talent and
propel them to the playoffs or they will flounder again. They will
likely make the playoffs and could end up being one of the year's
surprise teams.
</P>
<P>
   3. Arizona
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 4-12
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ The Cardinals fired offensive coordinator Dick
Jamieson, who was unpopular with the players, and hired Marc
Trestman. The new man runs the West Coast offense, and those
three-step drops and quick passes will work well for the young
quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Offensive line play. Arizona allowed a league-high
78 sacks and was last in the conference in rushing.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK Don't jump on the Cardinals' bandwagon just yet. They
are taking the right steps to get better but they are still a few
years away.
</P>
<P>
   4. Dallas
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 6-10
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Only weeks into his tenure as Cowboys coach, Chan
Gailey had to weave his way around ``scissorgate.'' The incident,
in which wide receiver Michael Irvin cut offensive guard Everett
McIver with barber's shears, was truly a bad hair day for Gailey.
But he handled it calmly, and gained the respect of the players.
His offensive smarts and strong backbone are the Cowboys' best
assets.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ They're old. Teams picked apart the talented good
old Cowboys in free agency, and Dallas hasn't drafted as well as
the club needed to replace that talent. Only five starters are from
the drafts between 1993 and '97. By comparison, practically the
entire Giants defense is composed of players they drafted.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Going winless (0-5) for the first time in a dozen
preseasons normally means nothing; except that in the two other
years the Cowboys failed to win an exhibition game, they went on to
losing seasons. The Cowboys' first team offense scored only 3
touchdowns in 15 possessions during preseason. Look for the Cowboys
to finish 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   5. Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 6-9-1
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Offensive tackle Tre Thomas may be one of the team's
best draft picks in a decade. Wide receiver Irvin Fryar, playing
for a new contract, will probably have a stellar year. Quarterback
Bobby Hoying has shown spurts of talent.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Lots. Running back Ricky Watters is gone, and the
Eagles will rely on Charlie Garner, who has a career average of
almost five yards a carry but has also been injury prone. On
defense, Philadelphia signed Hugh Douglas to help pass rush, but
there are still too many holes.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK Ray Rhodes is a smart coach who hasn't drafted well, so
the Eagles are in a sorry state. Unless they pull one of the
biggest surprises of the last five years in the NFL, it is likely
that Rhodes will be fired at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTRAL DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 9-7, wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ The best offense in football. Brad Johnson, a smart
quarterback, is headed to the Pro Bowl. Receiver Cris Carter should
break the 800-catch barrier this season and is headed for the Hall
of Fame. Wide receiver Randy Moss has stayed out of trouble and his
explosiveness has put him on a path to stardom. Throw in running
back Robert Smith, a solid offensive line, and a great coaching
staff and Minnesota could turn the toughest division in football
upside down.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Before the Vikings make hotel reservations for the
Super Bowl, they will need far better play from the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The only thing that could keep the Vikings from the
Super Bowl are the wacky moves of the new owner Red McCombs, who
has refused to give Coach Dennis Green, in the last year of his
contract, a new deal until the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   2. Green Bay
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 13-3, division winner.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ The usual. Quarterback Brett Favre is an amazing
41-5 at Lambeau Field. Running back Dorsey Levens, despite missing
the preseason because of a contract holdout, should still get his
1,200-plus yards rushing. The Pack's offense is never a problem and
it will still be one of the most formidable in the league.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The defensive line. Last season, Green Bay finished
ranked 20th against the run, their lowest ranking since 1990. It
must have been embarrassing to be blasted off the ball in Super
Bowl XXXII when the Denver Broncos rushed for over 150 yards and 3
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ This division is so stacked that any of the top three
teams could win the Super Bowl. For the Packers, this will likely
be their last run at the Super Bowl with Coach Mike Holmgren, who
could end up in Seattle next year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   3. Tampa Bay
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 10-6, wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Perhaps one of the most unheralded free agent
signings this offseason was Tampa Bay grabbing wide receiver Bert
Emanuel from the Atlanta Falcons in a four-year, $16 million deal.
Emanuel adds some juice to a struggling passing game.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The Buccaneers will only go as far as quarterback
Trent Dilfer will take them.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Buccaneers have a great defense, a great coach in
Tony Dungy and a great chance to win the division and go beyond.
But first, they must find a way to beat Green Bay (on a 4-0 streak
against Tampa Bay) and, second, Dilfer has to take his game to the
next level.
</P>
<P>
   4. Detroit
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 9-7, wild-card team.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Running back Barry Sanders and wide receiver Herman
Moore will again be practically unstoppable. Defensive tackle
Luther Elliss, who finished second on the team last season with 8{
sacks, will only get better.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Quarterback Scott Mitchell. This offseason the
Lions drafted the Eastern Michigan quarterback Charlie Batch in the
second round. Quite simply, if Mitchell doesn't get the Lions deep
into the playoffs, this will be his last year as Detroit's starter.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Lions may get a playoff spot on talent alone. But
how far they go depends on Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   5. Chicago
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 4-12
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ A team that won only four games last season has few.
Two of them are running back Edgar Bennett, signed away from Green
Bay, and wide receiver Curtis Conway, when healthy.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Bad special teams and an average quarterback in
Erik Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Bears have bad karma. They stayed away from Randy
Moss in the draft because of his off-field troubles and selected
running back Curtis Enis because he was supposed to not have any.
Then Enis became involved with a controversial religious group, was
accused of sexual assault, and became stuck in a protracted
holdout. The Bears will likely go through another four- or
five-victory season, so expect management to clean house, beginning
with Coach Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WESTERN DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 13-3, division winner.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ The 49ers' division schedule is their biggest asset.
Not one of their division opponents finished above .500 last
season, which gives the team a near automatic 9 or 10 victories.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Possibly at fullback. Marc Edwards has talent but
it will be hard to replace the departed William Floyd, who signed
as a free agent with Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The 49ers are always good. But much of the season
depends on wide receiver Jerry Rice, who is coming back from torn
ligaments in his knee. If he can be the Rice of old, the 49ers
could find themselves in the conference title game again.
</P>
<P>
   2. St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 5-11
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Quarterback Tony Banks, in the same offensive system
for the second consecutive season, finally has stability _ and no
more excuses. During a dedicated off season, Banks attended 80
percent of his workouts (earning a $25,000 bonus). He also has a
slimmer, more athletic Orlando Pace to anchor a solid offensive
line and a healthy Isaac Bruce at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Home blues: Last year the Rams lost six of eight
games at home.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Coach Dick Vermeil ran one of 1998's toughest training
camps. Maybe the hard work will be worth it as the Rams are ready
to make a push to respectability.
</P>
<P>
   3. Carolina
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 7-9
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ The defense should get back to the top form of
Carolina's 1997 run at the Super Bowl. The front office spent big
bucks this offseason _ including $46.5 million over seven years for
defensive tackle Sean Gilbert. They also brought back linebacker
Kevin Greene and signed the former Pittsburgh Pro Bowler Greg
Lloyd, then spent $22.5 million on cornerback Doug Evans.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The Panthers still lack a big-play wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Carolina could surprise the 49ers, but only if
quarterback Kerry Collins rebounds from a disastrous season.
</P>
<P>
   4. Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 7-9
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Chris Chandler has always been a top 10 quarterback,
but he has had problems staying healthy. In games that Chandler
started and finished last year, the Falcons were 7-3. Without him,
they were 0-6.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The offense is still a conservative, predictable
mess.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Teams in the division will not be caught by surprise
by the Falcons this season. The Falcons didn't do much to improve
since last year via the draft _ because Coach Dan Reeves is a
terrible evaluator of talent _ or even through free agency. And
while the 40-something backup Steve DeBerg is a cute story, it is a
sad state of affairs that Reeves has him as his second quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   5. New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   1997 RECORD 6-10
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Punter Mark Royals led the league last year with a
45.9-yard average. The Saints will need him.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ None more obvious than quarterback Billy Joe
Hobert, whom the Buffalo Bills cut last season after he admitted he
hadn't studied his playbook. Last year the offense had a
league-leading 55 turnovers and 33 interceptions. They also allowed
51 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Linebacker Andre Royal got into a public cursing match
with Coach Mike Ditka last month, then there was a nasty hazing
incident involving numerous veterans and the team's rookies. Both
showed that Ditka has lost control; if the team wins more than five
or six games it would be a miracle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0799 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-05 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE THE MIND OF NORTH KOREA'S `DEAR LEADER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I finally got the world's attention! The United States and
Japan thought they could ignore me and _ kersplash _ I send one
missile shooting over Japan, and finally they look in my direction.
Ha! Maybe I should do this more often!
</P>
<P>
   And then they call me irrational. Can't they see that this was
the only rational thing to do? If I didn't scare them every now and
then, they would ignore me totally and I'd be like Fidel Castro, a
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Look at me! The imperialists tried to bully me back in 1994,
telling me I had to stop my nuclear program. But I was ready to go
to war with them, and so they decided to save lives and chicken
out. We reached a big agreement: I would freeze my program and the
Americans and the other countries would give me free heating oil
and build me a $4 billion light-water nuclear reactor. You've got
to be pushy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Americans tried to double-cross me. Despite their
agreement, they wouldn't lift most of their sanctions, they lagged
in building the new reactor, they delayed shipping me oil and they
didn't even think about normalizing relations.
</P>
<P>
   I was ready to get rid of my whole missile program in exchange
for the right payoff, but they wouldn't cough up the kind of dough
I was talking about. They wouldn't pay me money and they wouldn't
pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now maybe they'll pay something! If my nuclear program got
them to give me a $4 billion reactor and free oil, think what my
missile program should be worth _ especially since the CIA thinks I
still have a few nukes that I just might figure out how to attach
to a missile. The imperialists were worried about my old Nodong
missiles, which couldn't even reach Tokyo. Well, they missed a
bargain. Now they'll have to pay billions for my program, because I
can take out anything in Japan. And if my engineers can improve the
booster rocket, I'll be able to reach Alaska and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, I know the missiles are hopelessly inaccurate. But so
what if I aim for the Yankee base at Yokosuka and hit Tokyo
instead? It just makes the Japanese more nervous than ever. And
their fear is what gives me bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and think of all that free advertising I got. The Syrians
and Iranians see Secretary of State yapping puppy Albright denounce
my missiles, and they'll pay more than ever. I'll get paid off one
way or another; by the Yankees for giving up my missile program or
by the Syrians and Iranians for continuing it. These two-stage
rockets can deliver a one-ton payload more than 1,000 miles, and
Israel will be in the bombsights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, my Foreign Ministry is whining these days. The
diplomats say we may have overplayed our hand, and they're worried
now that Japan has cut off aid and flights to our country, now that
the Yankee Congress is sniveling about whether to back away from
the 1994 nuclear agreement. Huh! Wimps!
</P>
<P>
   Washington will come through because it knows that it would be
risking war if it didn't. Sure, I would lose. But I've got one
thing in my favor: 10 million people within artillery range. Seoul
will be a sea of flames. I have the guts to fight to lose, but the
Yankees don't have the stomach to fight to win.
</P>
<P>
   The imperialists don't really think I'd level Seoul, but they
can't be sure. Sometimes it pays to be perceived as irrational, and
sending a missile racing over Japan just adds to my credibility as
a maniac. (And wasn't it a nice touch when we said later that the
missile launched a scientific satellite transmitting immortal
revolutionary hymns?)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, sure, if the Yankees do cut off aid, then that will
make it tougher here. But when things get really desperate, people
will come running with aid. If people go hungry here, then the
pressure is on Washington and Tokyo, not me.
</P>
<P>
   I love to read what these foreign analysts say. They think North
Korea is falling apart. It's just like those foreigners who thought
China was falling apart in the early 1950's. But hunger doesn't
make people rebel; it just makes them die.
</P>
<P>
   In China, 30 million people died in Mao Zedong's famine of the
early 1960's; there wasn't a peep of protest. Then Deng Xiaoping
gave the Chinese people pork and rice and they tried to stage a
revolution against him at Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never make that mistake. I know that contact with
barbarians or, worse, bourgeois democracy, destabilizes a country.
I'll never open up my country the way Deng did.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrogant foreigners think they can make life hard on us
and change us. This is Korea! We're not weaklings. If we were
compromisers our nation would have been absorbed by China or Japan
a thousand years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago, King Yongjo knew his son would be a
terrible heir, so he locked the weeping young man in a box in the
courtyard and left him to die. It took 13 days. That's the
toughness that it takes to be a king of Korea, and I've got that
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean puppets have lost their strength, and we in the
North are the only real Koreans left. That's why we have restored a
dynasty, just like the ancients. My father died four years ago, and
the foreigners all puzzled about why I didn't fill the vacancy and
whether that meant I was weak. Don't they know about filial piety?
If they had read Korean history, they would have known that a good
Korean prince waits several years before succeeding his father. I'm
not a communist. I'm a Confucian.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is my turn to succeed my father as president and party
leader. I'll reform the economy and try to rely more on the market
mechanism, because that's the only thing that works. But I'll never
open up this country. I'll never risk losing control.
</P>
<P>
   I will stand up to the foreigners and my people will stand
behind me, as long as they have the strength to stand. I need
enemies more than I need friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, what a lovely missile that was. It made me a few more
enemies. They can despise me, insult me. But they'll have to
respect me.
</P>
<P>
   Poor little Castro. I should sell him a missile or two to launch
over Florida. Then he would get some respect as well, and maybe
some American foreign aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
