<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-AFC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS, JAGUARS AND BRONCOS ARE AFC DIVISION SELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: Teams previewed in order of predicted finish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EASTERN DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 10-6, division champion, lost in second round of
playoffs
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ This team still has the best defense in the
division. It starts with end Willie McGinnest, a mammoth man (6-5,
255) who has the range and power and quickness and to have a career
year. It includes linebacker Chris Slade, a Pro Bowl player last
season with nine sacks. It has a rugged linebacker in Teddy Bruschi
, a top-flight cornerback in Ty Law and a playmaking-safety in
Willie Clay.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ No Curtis Martin. Will the running game click with
rookie running back Robert Edwards from Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Patriots can throw it (Drew Bledsoe to Terry Glenn
and Ben Coates) and they can defend. Their diamonds far outshine
their flaws.
</P>
<P>
   2. MIAMI
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 9-7, lost in first round of playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Dan Marino. New offensive linemen Kevin Donnalley in
from the Tennessee Oilers. Linebacker Zach Thomas. Newcomer Brock
Marion at safety from Dallas. And a new commitment by the Dolphins
to run the ball and keep running it despite the flavor of each
game.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Pass rush _ Miami needs plenty more of it. It had
only 31 sacks last season, 23 fewer than conference leader Kansas
City. Losing receiver Yatil Green for the second straight year to a
knee injury hurts badly. His size and speed would have stretched
defenses. Does Miami have a competent burner who can catch the ball
consistently and do that? A receiver who strikes fear?
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ If rookie back John Avery from Mississippi maintains
in the regular season what he exhibited in the preseason, the
Dolphins could be on their way. It is a team that should improve
each step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   3.JETS
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 9-7
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Curtis Martin gives the Jets a proven tailback and a
tough one. He can catch the ball and convert third downs. The Jets
offense should move the ball with regularity. Fullback Jerald
Sowell packs a punch. Cornerback Aaron Glenn at the top of his game
changes games. The club's special teams have spunk.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Inexperience at quarterback. Only 29 sacks earned a
year ago. And a much better effort required in divisional play,
where the Jets last year finished 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ This team can win 11 games. It could slip. It needs
plenty of breaks.
</P>
<P>
   4. BUFFALO
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 6-10
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Defense. Ranked No. 9 overall last year in defense
despite an offense which kept putting it in terrible positions.
Antowain Smith at tailback appears ready to bust out. The Rob
Johnson/Doug Flutie quarterback duo could be a weapon if Flutie
enters for six or seven plays a game and changes the pace with his
mobility. Bruce Smith _ any team that has him has a tower in
strength.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ It is Rob Johnson's job to lose but no one knows
how this warm-weather guy will stack up in the brutal December,
Buffalo weather. No Chris Spielman at linebacker hurts.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ New coach (Wade Phillips), new quarterback, new
offense, new defense. A team in transition.
</P>
<P>
   5. INDIANAPOLIS
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 3-13
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Running backs. Marshall Faulk leads the group. He is
an exciting tailback with a tremendous burst in his running. Lamont
Warren is a versatile backup at tailback. He can dip and dive and
juke and slice. Nice player. And then fullback Zach Crockett. Great
size (6-2, 246) mixed with more than adequate speed. And the Colts
have a quarterback in Peyton Manning who excites all around him. A
franchise player.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The offensive line is a huge question mark. So is
the linebacking play.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Colts are a team that have wonderful skill players
_ a shiny exterior _ but need more nuts and bolts and strength in
the interior. Expect growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENTRAL DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. JACKSONVILLE
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 11-5, lost in first round of playoffs
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Plenty. A wonderful, agile quarterback in Mark
Brunell. A solid big back in James Stewart and a bright new one in
Fred Taylor from Florida. A dynamic receiver in Kennan McCardell
and an offensive line, led by tackle Tony Boselli, that can make it
all click. A defensive line led by end Tony Brackens that is quick
as much as it is strong. Linebacking led by newcomer Bryce Paup
from Buffalo that is efficient. And quality defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ One has to look hard to find them. Maybe the
special teams bear watching. Injuries hurt this team plenty last
season and it still won 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Super. As in Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   2. BALTIMORE
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 6-9-1
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ A new attitude. A new quarterback (Jim Harbaugh) who
is a leader and a winner. A new back in Errict Rhett who has plenty
to prove and is set on doing so. A trio of linebackers _ Ray Lewis,
Peter Boulware and Jamie Sharper _ who rank among the best in
football. The leadership of veteran cornerback Rod Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Wilting in close games. The Ravens were 3-5-1 in
games decided by 3 or fewer points.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ A surprise team. Playoff potential.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   3. PITTSBURGH
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 11-5, lost in second round of playoffs
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Experience. Success. Six consecutive playoff
appearances. Levon Kirkland and Jason Gildon at linebackers,
wonderful players in their prime, with even more talent beside and
behind them. The consummate defensive back and leader in Carnell
Lake. A bulldozing running back in Jerome Bettis. The most elusive
quarterback in the league in Kordell Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ No Yancey Thigpen at receiver and yet another year
for Pittsburgh to compensate for a huge free agency loss. Their are
several capable answers but presently they are questions.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Is this the season the rest of this division finally
begins catching up with the Steelers? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   4. TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 8-8
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ They have a young, vibrant team and a three-pronged
offense (quarterback Steve McNair, running back Eddie George and
receiver Yancey Thigpen) that will cause defenses fits. A rookie
receiver in Kevin Dyson from Utah who is a strong rookie of the
year candidate.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The defensive front is young and inexperienced. The
linebackers are not dominating.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ The Oilers look like a team that will score a lot and
give up a lot. If the defense rises, so does this team.
</P>
<P>
   5. CINCINNATI: 7-9
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Corey Dillon. He is an exciting tailback who has
only begun to maximize his abilities. Neil O'Donnell at quarterback
is a safe choice. As rocky as the Bengals have been, he will
provide stability if not spectacular play. Dick LeBeau as defensive
coordinator: a natural strength because he is one of pro football's
finest defensive minds.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ With Dan Wilkinson gone off the line, who provides
teeth on the defensive front?
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ This team led the NFL in rushing touchdowns last
season with 23. In another division, it could fight for the top.
Even now, it is not as far away as it may appear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WESTERN DIVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DENVER
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 12-4, Super Bowl champions
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Terrell Davis is the player who makes the Broncos
special and John Elway is the player who makes the franchise click.
Denver won the Super Bowl with these two at the top but with plenty
of help on both sides of the ball and from the sideline. It was the
essence of teams and big plays and players rising to new levels to
achieve greatness. If only it could be bottled.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ The offensive line, particularly the right side, is
a concern. Especially with guard Brian Habib gone, who left for
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Rosy. The Broncos have terrific leadership in head
coach Mike Shanahan. From top to bottom, he is as good as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   2. KANSAS CITY
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 13-3 lost in second round of playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ A robust defense. The talent and desire of
linebacker Derrick Thomas. Good chemistry and consistency: this
team has finished first or second in this division in each of the
past nine years.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Is the running game going to work? The Chiefs did
it by committee last season and did not have a 1,000 yard rusher.
Kimble Anders at fullback is a wonderful player. But at tailback
this team is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Strong. Super Bowl caliber.
</P>
<P>
   3. SEATTLE
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 8-8
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Warren Moon. He is 42 this season and still provides
a wonderful arm, nimble feet, strong decision making and leadership
at quarterback. His receivers are stellar: Joey Galloway, Brian
Blades and Mike Pritchard. Toss in James McNight _ he led the
league in yards per catch last year at 18.7. Ricky Watters is the
new tailback and he gives the Seahawks a path to success. Kevin
Glover, a Pro Bowl center in from Detroit, is a nifty addition. The
defensive line with Cortez Kennedy and Michael Sinclair is stout.
Linebacker Chad Brown (former Steeler) should settle in nicely in
his second season in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Special teams. They were lousy last season.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ This team has a great upside. It could soar. It could
fall flat. The Seahawks have the ability to take anything they
want.
</P>
<P>
   4. OAKLAND
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 4-12
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ Charles Woodson. Though just a rookie, he is the
kind of player who elevates teammates' play. The Raiders' defense
certainly needs that. Defensive tackle Darrell Russell is the
catalyst the Raiders would like to build around. Jeff George at
quarterback can wing it and Napoleon Kaufman at tailback can run
it. Tim Brown can catch it.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Can the Raiders defend it? They ranked dead last
last season in overall defense, rushing defense and in passing
defense.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ New coach Jon Gruden has work to do. The Raiders are
so tangled that it will take time to straighten them out.
</P>
<P>
   5. SAN DIEGO
</P>
<P>
   1997 record 4-12
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTHS _ New hope in franchise quarterback Ryan Leaf. The
return of big back Natrone Means. Receiver Tony Martin. Linebacker
Junior Seau. Kicker John Carney.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKNESSES _ Allowed the most points in the league last season
(425). Gained fewest sacks (27). Lost their last eight consecutive
games. Was penalized for the most yards (1,101). Lots of problems.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK _ Leaf will have to play way over his head to turn this
team around in one season. The defense will have play out of its
mind to accomplish the same. Maybe later. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
