<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FACES IN NEW PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Seifert was contemplating his career change, from
coaching to neophyte studio analyst on CBS' revived ``The NFL
Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you say, `God, what did I get myself into?'''
Seifert, the former 49ers coach, said last week. ``I find myself
getting nervous and needing a walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League season that begins this afternoon
will be a test for Seifert, but more importantly, for CBS. Having
committed $500 million a year through 2005 for American Football
Conference rights that were NBC's, CBS will be the focus of intense
scrutiny as it returns from a four-season hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics will await news contrary to CBS' guarantee that it will
``make a dollar'' on its $4 billion contract. NBC, which declined
to renew the AFC rights and mocked the CBS deal, will leap eagerly
on word of the first losses.
</P>
<P>
   On-screen changes begin with game times. Late Sunday afternoon
games on CBS and Fox will begin at 4:15 p.m. Eastern Time to
accommodate late-ending early games. ABC's ``Monday Night
Football'' will begin at 8 p.m. with a 20-minute pre-game show, the
first in its 29-year history.
</P>
<P>
   CBS _ In the studio, Seifert will join Marcus Allen, the former
Chiefs running back, Brent Jones, the former 49ers tight end, and
the host, Jim Nantz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize we're an expansion team,'' Nantz said. ``We won't be
perfect right away. It's going to be a slow process. In December,
we'll look back and see significant improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   A totally untested analyst threesome is risky, especially when
studio shows let networks truly differentiate themselves. CBS
should have hired Cris Collinsworth, but when he came calling, he
got no clear sense of CBS' plans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to CBS, the combination of two newly retired players and a
coach who is one year from sideline work was irresistible. ``We'll
be as fresh and contemporary as anyone,'' said Sean McManus, the
president of CBS Sports. The key, as always, will be the quality of
information from the group.
</P>
<P>
   For games, CBS imported its No. 1 team, Greg Gumbel and Phil
Simms from NBC. Randy Cross, Sam Wyche, Don Criqui and Beasley
Reece also came from NBC; Verne Lundquist and Mark May came from
TNT, Kevin Harlan from Fox and Ian Eagle from Jets broadcasts on
New York's WFAN. CBS erred in not hiring Charlie Jones, who will
not call football for the first time since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ABC _ While ``Monday Night Football'' rights stayed put (they
cost more, at $550 million a year), there is a new start time, and
the pre-game show from the ESPN Zone sports bar in Baltimore, with
two hosts _ ESPN's Chris Berman and Frank Gifford, who shifts to
the studio after 27 years in the ``M.N.F.'' booth.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McAndrews, general manager of ABC Sports, said: ``It will
not be in-depth X's and O's. It's meant as a prime-time
entertainment launching pad.''
</P>
<P>
   On games, Al Michaels and Dan Dierdorf will return, but
Gifford's successor is Boomer Esiason, the former Jets and
Cincinnati Bengals quarterback. ``My biggest problem,'' Esiason
said after three preseason games, ``is knowing so much about the
game and compacting my thoughts into small sound bites. I know
there've been times when I'm a little wordy. It's a work in
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN _ With its $600 million-a-year deal, ESPN took home to
Bristol, Conn., the entire Sunday night cable package. No more
taking over the Sunday night schedule in midseason after TNT
finished its half-season of games.
</P>
<P>
   To its Sunday morning ``NFL Countdown'' show, ESPN added 30
minutes (to two hours), Mike Tirico as Berman's co-host and Jim
Kelly as an analyst. Paul Maguire is ESPN's third game announcer,
with Mike Patrick and Joe Theismann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess people will say, `Gee, Joe will talk less,'''
Theismann said. ``But Paul offers so much, you can just sit back
and listen.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL cross-promotion between ABC and ESPN will run rampant,
reminding everyone from here to Alpha Centauri of the Sunday
night-Monday night football link. Hank Williams Jr.'s ``Are you
ready for some football?'' song, which has long opened ABC's
telecast, will also open ESPN's.
</P>
<P>
   Fox _ The network that roiled the business in 1993 with the
blockbuster deal that ousted CBS from the NFL made the fewest
changes. Collinsworth will spar with Howie Long and Terry Bradshaw
while James Brown keeps refereeing. Collinsworth will not shrink
from verbal conflict like his predecessor, Ronnie Lott, who was
shifted to game analysis beside Tim Ryan, Fox's other key hire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cris is opinionated, witty, and quick,'' Bradshaw said. ``I
may have to forget what I want to say to pull him in. If you let it
go _ let Howie do what he does and Cris do what he does, and I
follow suit _ it could be a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Long said adding Collinsworth stokes him competitively. ``It's
going to be like when I was playing,'' he said, ``and they drafted
another defensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Collinsworth: ``Face it, to say something interesting, you
have to go out on a limb and walk the edge. No matter what side of
the branch I'm on, someone will try to knock me off. And that's
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of James Brown's role? ``Being left out is a perception
because they're so strong, but my role is no less significant,''
Brown said. ``When they talk esoterica, I can't let them lose sight
of the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC/TNT _ Out of the NFL picture, they are planning a summer pro
football league starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
