<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to a
special report, End of a Ghetto, on efforts to raze some of the
nation's worst public housing projects and integrate their
residents into mainstream communities.
</P>
<P>
   The story will move in two forms: full length as published in
The New York Times and in an abridged version of 1,900 words. They
will move Saturday morning in the ``a'' news file and are for
publication beginning Sunday, Sept. 6 and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for the article follows:
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM (Chicago) _ From Hartford, Conn., and
Newark, N.J., to Denver and San Francisco, the federal government
is working with cities to clear the very slums it helped create:
public housing projects crippled by flawed policies and
mismanagement and overwhelmed by poverty and crime. Hundreds of
thousands of tenants will move to smaller developments that mix
families of different incomes or into privately owned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But success will require communities to accept as neighbors
people they have long been happy to have out of sight. And one of
the toughest questions facing housing officials is how to deal with
intensely troubled families, whose problems could cripple their
adjustment to a new home or harm their new neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the challenge greater than at Chicago's Robert Taylor
Homes, the nation's largest housing project, much of which is
``considered the worst slum area in the United States'' according
to its landlord, the Chicago Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABRIDGED VERSION SLUG: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABR-PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Photos, a map and a graphic to accompany the article are being
made available to clients of the NYT News Service graphics and
photo desk.
</P>
<P>
   Photo captions and a description of the map and graphic follow:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-1 _ Henry Sistrunk, 27,
watches the action in The Hole, the most oppressive section of
Chicago's notorious Robert Taylor Homes housing project. On the
back of Sistrunk's left shoulder is a tattoo of The Hole's three
high-rise buildings, done by his brother. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-2 _ A student at Mary B.
Terrell Elementary School, a public school near the Robert Taylor
Homes, walks through The Hole. Much of Robert Taylor, the nation's
largest housing project that is ``considered the worst slum area in
the United States,'' according to its landlord, the Chicago Housing
Authority, is being demolished. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHICAGO _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-3 _ Brenda Hunter, of the
Chicago Housing Authority relocation office, gives Katie Sistrunk a
hug in her new apartment in Rogers Park, on the Northside of
Chicago. At this ``scattered site'' apartment her landlord will
remain the federal government. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-4 _ Angela Smith, 25, was
in a frenzy to pack her belongings before the movers came to put
her things into storage. Like most people who lived in The Hole,
she didn't want another housing authority apartment: she wanted a
federal rent subsidy known as a Section 8 certificate, which will
allow her to rent her own apartment. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROSELAND, Ill. _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-5 _ Billy Kimmons,
23, looks over his neighborhood from the porch of his new apartment
as movers deliver his furnishings. Kimmons, like many others, was
forced to move out of The Hole, the most oppressive section of
Chicago's notorious Robert Taylor Homes housing project. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO _ PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-6 _ Lenzie Jones, 61, and
his daughter, Mary Bee Christian, in Jones' temporary apartment in
the Robert Taylor Homes housing project. Jones and his daughter
presented one of the toughest relocation situations for families in
The Hole. As a result, they were among the last people to leave
their building, and then they moved only to temporary housing with
about 25 other intensely troubled families. (Ozier Muhammad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAP and GRAPHIC &LR;  _ A map depicting the location of the Robert
Taylor Homes will accompany the story, as will a graphic providing
demographic information on the residents of housing project.
</P>
