<HEADLINE>
END OF A GHETTO: THE EFFORT TO RAZE A SLUM AND REHABILITATE ITS
RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map and
graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PAM BELLUCK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the final months of The Hole, anarchy was
everywhere. The Hole, the most oppressive section of Chicago's
notorious Robert Taylor Homes housing project, was coming down.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members shot at a moving van outside one of The Hole's
three high-rise buildings. Moving crews tried to hurry out each day
before drug dealers commandeered the elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Lenzie Jones packed his grandchildren's clothes for the movers
but did not know what to do with their mother's belongings. She had
fled a few days before, after the drug gang she hawked heroin for
accused her of stealing and beat her with a baseball bat and a
two-by-four.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Smith frantically swatted cockroaches and attacked stains
in her kitchen. An inspector from the building she wanted to move
into was coming to scrutinize her housekeeping. If she failed, she
would lose the new apartment she had set her heart on.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Sistrunk, who at 45 had reared 13 children in the Hole,
had no idea where she would go, days before her building was to be
emptied. Juanita Williams, 74, was so paralyzed over leaving her
apartment of 25 years that she stayed after the water and gas were
shut off, until police officers removed her.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale not seen in decades, the federal government is
helping cities clear slums again, but this time they are slums it
helped create: public housing projects crippled by flawed policies
and mismanagement and overwhelmed by poverty and crime.
</P>
<P>
   From Hartford and Newark to Denver and San Francisco, 100,000
apartments in the nation's worst public housing projects are being
razed under a federal program called Hope VI. The plan is to
replace them with smaller developments that mix families of
different incomes, while moving thousands of tenants into privately
owned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, where high-rise housing projects are corrosive
landmarks of poverty and racial segregation, the demolition will be
nothing less than seismic: the city wants to raze 11,000
apartments, nearly 40 percent of its public housing for families,
over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   And in a city whose housing projects contain 11 of the nation's
15 poorest census tracts, and where buildings in five large
projects are being demolished in whole or in part, nowhere is the
challenge greater than at Robert Taylor, the nation's largest
housing project, much of which is ``considered the worst slum area
in the United States'' according to its landlord, the Chicago
Housing Authority. The Hole, at the project's southern end, was the
first section to go, demolished in July. But the housing authority
wants to tear down all of the project's 28 high-rises, all 4,321
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is not just for the 11,000 people who will leave
Robert Taylor, a population 99 percent black, so poor that nearly
half of the adults live on less than $5,000 a year, and so isolated
that many are unfamiliar with life beyond the grim monoliths that
shadow the Dan Ryan Expressway on the South Side for nearly two
miles.
</P>
<P>
   It is a test for Chicago itself, as housing officials try to
eliminate a ghetto by placing most of Robert Taylor's tenants in
private apartments. The goal is to disperse the project's
concentrated poverty without introducing or aggravating social
problems in the tenants' new neighborhoods. Success will require
communities to accept as neighbors people they have long been happy
to have out of sight. But already a pattern is emerging of tenants
from Chicago's housing projects being moved mainly to poor black
neighborhoods, many as rundown and unsafe as the high-rises they
left.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six percent of Robert Taylor adult residents are
unemployed and little may change if they are simply moved. So a
second goal of Hope VI is to ease tenants off government
dependence. In Robert Taylor, the housing authority is spending
$1.5 million of its initial $25 million Hope VI grant on social
services, trying to place as many residents as possible in high
school equivalency courses, training programs and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Some tenants need more basic help: clothes to wear to interviews
with prospective landlords, assistance arranging electric and gas
services, classes on such housekeeping skills as cleaning carpets
and operating garbage disposals.
</P>
<P>
   The distance between Robert Taylor and the outside world is not
lost on the tenants. ``Goddamn public aid penitentiary,'' Esther
Jones, 41, said in June as she left the project after 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other complications in relocating residents reflect the extreme
conditions at Robert Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Residents who needed temporary housing could not move for weeks
because they were identified with the Mickey Cobras, the gang that
controlled The Hole, while the apartments available were in a
Robert Taylor building controlled by a rival gang, the Black
Gangster Disciples.
</P>
<P>
   Some tenants had criminal records, drug problems or erratic
rent-paying habits that had been tolerated at Robert Taylor but
could disqualify them for new housing.
</P>
<P>
   Citywide, housing officials are trying to help tenants get the
support they need, without stigmatizing them. They are also trying
not to arouse community opposition to the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really need a not-in-my-backyard backlash right now.''
said Wanda White, the housing authority official supervising the
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-to-Place Tenants Face a Difficult Move to Private Sector
</P>
<P>
   Angela Smith, 23, hauled out of her apartment anything broken or
filthy: ice cube trays, baby shoes, a radio. She asked friends who
were smoking marijuana to leave. The housekeeping inspector was
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got nowhere for people to sit,'' she fretted. She threw out
her cockroach-infested couch and chairs a year ago. She and her
children shared one bed and sat on milk crates and the hood of a
large hair dryer. But roaches persisted. They crawled over her
newborn son.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people in The Hole, Ms. Smith was desperate to leave,
but not for another housing authority apartment. Virtually all of
The Hole's residents wanted federal rent subsidies known as Section
8 certificates, which would allow them to rent their own
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Hope VI wants Section 8 subsidies and the private
market to replace 60 percent of the destroyed units, though some
advocates for the poor worry that will worsen already severe
shortages of housing. New York, for instance, has largely ignored
Hope VI because demand for its public housing is so high.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Taylor is unusual because no new public housing will be
built on the cleared site. Instead, smaller mixed-income
developments and an industrial area are planned. There are plans to
construct some public housing units nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for Section 8 housing makes relocating tenants
harder. The housing authority's success in finding enough landlords
willing to accept them in enough communities to avoid
reconcentrating them has been limited since it began moving tenants
from other housing projects in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis by The Chicago Reporter, a monthly
magazine that focuses on racial issues, the great majority of
Section 8 placements have been in poor black neighborhoods on the
South and West Sides.
</P>
<P>
   Already some Robert Taylor tenants have had to move twice
because of disputes with landlords or perilous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Aldermen have begun calling to say that their constituents are
concerned about Section 8 tenants moving in, Ms. White said.
</P>
<P>
   To find apartments for The Hole's tenants, the housing authority
contracted with a private relocation agency in February. The
agency's job included taking tenants to see apartments and helping
with things like applications, credit checks and arranging
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But tenants must satisfy landlords' expectations for cleanliness
and conduct, and the housing authority expected the agency to be a
hand holder: coaching tenants on how to dress for interviews with
landlords or making sure they were prepared for housekeeping
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White said that after several months she replaced the agency
because it showed homes in too few neighborhoods and did not give
tenants enough help.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's president, Pam Gecan, said her staff had expected
the authority to provide that help for difficult tenants. She said
gunfire in The Hole sometimes made her workers afraid to visit
clients. The tenants, she said, tended to request certain
neighborhoods, because they were familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Kimmons, for example, a 23-year-old former gang member who
now works as a school patrol officer, was rejected by several
landlords and finally moved near a church he attended in a poor
minority neighborhood on the far South Side. Ms. Smith chose
Woodlawn, a struggling neighborhood near Robert Taylor, because her
grandmother had lived there.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith was a typical Robert Taylor tenant, a young single
mother. She said she left her mother's home at 17 because of
problems with her stepfather, and had been living on her own at
Robert Taylor since. She has three children, Nathaniel, 5; Keosha,
3; and Shamari, 4 months. Her younger sister, Aderonke Akanni, who
said she left home at 13 after her stepfather abused her, also
lived with her.
</P>
<P>
   Life in The Hole was chaotic. Ms. Smith said the father of her
children beat her. She struggled on welfare, falling behind on her
$44 monthly rent. She did not permit her children to play outside
the apartment because gang violence made even hallways dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' she said. ``They shoot just to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turbulence, Ms. Smith and her sister were driven to
improve their lives. Ms. Smith, petite and spirited, is studying
for a high school equivalency diploma and plans to study nursing.
Ms. Akanni, 18, works at a Lady Footlocker store and takes classes
toward her equivalency diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Applying for a Section 8 apartment, Ms. Smith was organized and
efficient. She quickly assembled birth certificates, Social
Security cards and her son's report card to prove he attended
school.
</P>
<P>
   But the housekeeping inspector for her new landlord was
unimpressed. Ms. Smith said he complained about writing on the
walls, lack of furniture and her friends _ who had moved their
marijuana smoking to the hallway. Just weeks before her building
was to be emptied, she failed the inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Crestfallen and angry, she had to search for an apartment again,
while living with her mother. Finally, in July, she was approved
for an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weren't nobody smoking weed in my house,'' she said about
failing the inspection. ``And nobody going to be fixing up this
raggedy place when you're fixing to move. They know this is the
projects, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Decline and Fall _ Public Housing Becomes Hell Hole
</P>
<P>
   The Robert Taylor Homes, named for Chicago's first black housing
authority chairman, was among the last housing projects built in
the city. Begun in 1959, it completed a four-mile corridor of
public housing along State Street. While its new high-rises were
welcome replacements for a shantytown, they quickly became the
nation's largest government-sponsored ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Housing projects in Chicago are starkly identified with race and
poverty. From the beginning, city officials used them, along with
the expressways being built at the same time, to contain the city's
growing population of poor blacks. Of Chicago's 67,000 public
housing families, 97 percent are black.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, six years after completion of the last buildings, the
three that became known as The Hole, Congress changed the public
housing rent policy with disastrous results for projects across the
country. Instead of a fixed rent, tenants were to pay a percentage
of their income.
</P>
<P>
   At Robert Taylor, working families moved out as their rent rose
while neighbors on welfare paid almost nothing. Housing officials,
wary of discrimination suits, stopped screening tenants. Single
mothers as young as 16 were given apartments.
</P>
<P>
   As the project filled with impoverished people, rent income fell
and maintenance had to be cut. Tenants threw things off the
exterior gangways that linked apartments, so they were covered with
steel grating, like a prison. Leaks and broken windows went
unfixed. Elevators and hallways reeked of urine.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago's projects, ``everything that could have gone wrong
went wrong,'' said Joseph Shuldiner, the executive director of the
housing authority, who was brought in to fix an agency so inept the
federal government took it over in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a population that is beginning to create
problems, then you have trouble attracting people,'' he said. ``The
managers said, `They're not letting me screen _ the heck with it.'
Then your maintenance stinks. It just becomes a steamroller
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In a housing project that was home to 20,000 residents at its
peak, but few men, gangs got an early hold. Violence and drugs
devastated generations. As families moved out, vacant apartments
became havens for drug dealers. Gangs ripped out metal detectors
installed at entranceways and cut the wires of intercoms intended
to screen visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In The Hole, clusters of drug dealers brazenly hawked heroin and
cocaine, forming gantlets in the entranceways. The wind whipped
crack vials like shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   Police were frustrated by gang lookouts and the ability of
dealers to vanish into high-rise hideouts. Dealers became so cocky
that recently a gang member waved a roll of money at a group of
housing officials and offered to buy The Hole for $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's why they call it The Hole,'' said Deborah
Mardis, a resident for 20 years. ``You fall in and you never get
out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mardis managed to leave in 1994, but her son Dequan, a gang
member, kept returning. In January, visiting a girlfriend at a
rival gang's building, he was shot six times. He survived.
</P>
<P>
   After another shooting the next day, parents kept children home
from the elementry school across a parking lot from the Hole, then
formed patrols to escort them to class.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a man was killed crossing from The Hole to Disciple
territory. In March, postal workers did not deliver mail for a day
because of shooting. One April weekend, a man was killed and
another wounded. In June, a 9-year-old was shot. In August, a
police officer investigating drug dealing was critically wounded. A
16-year-old and two 17-year-olds were charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long time ago, I decided that to survive here, you had to be
crazy, chemically saturated, Christian, or some kind of
character,'' said a woman called Cat Lady, a squatter in The Hole
who rescued cats trapped in vacant apartments. ``If we could gather
the children, I'd do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Troubled Families with Stubborn Problems Hinder Relocation
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bee Christian handed her sons vanilla ice cream cones she
had bought from an ice cream truck and made a beeline for the
bedroom with what she had bought for herself: $5 worth of crack and
$20 of heroin. Using a lottery ticket to scoop the heroin and a
tube from a light fixture as a crack pipe, Ms. Christian snorted
and smoked her speedball.
</P>
<P>
   When Willie, 7, shouted that the boys had finished eating, Ms.
Christian replied, ``Then watch some cartoons.'' When her lighter
ran out of fluid, she told Willie and his brother, Jhonell, 6, to
go to their room, so they would not see her light her crack pipe at
the kitchen stove.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Lenzie Jones, at 61 stooped and leather-faced,
watched helplessly. ``Oh Mary,'' he said, ``Do you have to do that
now?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the toughest questions facing housing officials is how to
deal with intensely troubled families. Not only could their
problems cripple their adjustment to a new home, but they could
harm their new neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make it better for the people you are
relocating,'' Ms. White, the housing authority official, said,
``but you also have to make it better for the people who will be
their neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Taylor has two devoted and savvy relocation specialists
to work with families. In early 1997, they began untangling
complications for the nearly 300 families in The Hole. Now they are
doing the same in the next two buildings scheduled to come down.
</P>
<P>
   Making repeated visits, sometimes working nights and weekends,
they sort out who is on each lease _ and therefore entitled to new
housing _ tell tenants of problems such as unpaid rent, and explain
their options: Section 8 subsidies, another housing project, or
``scattered site'' apartments, which are managed by the authority
but are not in a project. They also arrange moves, pay security
deposits and visit families in their new homes.
</P>
<P>
   But the authority's relocation workers face many of the same
problems as the private relocation agencies. Tenants miss
appointments, waffle on their housing choice, misunderstand
instructions. Because few have telephones, it is difficult even to
check on them.
</P>
<P>
   Once families move, visiting them can take two months because of
the staff's workload.
</P>
<P>
   When the relocation specialists encounter problems like drug
abuse and child neglect, they can only refer families to the
housing authority's social services department, which arranges for
help from government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Responses are slow, said Ms. White, who is introducing
improvements designed to ensure that each family's problems are
monitored closely.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge is determining whether some families are so
troubled that they should be turned out of public housing entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Under a federal court order in the 1970s and 1980s, Chicago
moved 7,100 families out of segregated public housing and into
rent-subsidized apartments. Central to the highly praised program
was intensive counseling for families that was able to screen out
troubled people.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of screening is much harder when entire buildings are
being emptied. ``That was a huge criticism, that we have people not
being compassionate and it's just the get-them-out syndrome,'' Ms.
White said. ``On the flip side, you have the fear that we're just
transferring problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In The Hole, Jones and his daughter presented one of the
toughest situations. As a result, they were among the last people
to leave their building, and then they moved only to temporary
housing with about 25 other families with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to protect Jones and his grandchildren from his
drug-addicted daughter, housing officials separated the grandfather
and grandchildren from Ms. Christian in April. They knew that in
March, Ms. Christian's boyfriend had hit Jones with a crowbar to
make him give up the children's welfare money.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was given an apartment in another Robert Taylor building
for himself and the children. Ms. Christian was supposed to stay
away.
</P>
<P>
   Housing officials could have tried to evict Ms. Christian from
the project because of her drug use. But one of the relocation
specialists, Brenda Hunter, who grew up in Robert Taylor, said she
knew Ms. Christian would then impose on her father, so instead she
was given an apartment of her own _ rent-free, because she had no
legal income.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Christian's new apartment was in the same building as
her father's, and she began staying with her father and children,
planning to rent or lend her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other tenants, Jones wanted a private apartment, so
Ms. Hunter and her partner, Sonya Franklin, arranged an interview
with CHAC Inc., the agency hired by the housing authority to see
that tenants qualify financially for rent subsidies. On a late
April day, he dressed up in a white hat with a yellow feather _
picked up at a church giveaway _ but the interview did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because the apartment in The Hole had been leased in his
daughter's name, he was told, the Section 8 program could not help
him until the housing authority put his name on the lease, too. And
because his daughter owed $250 in back rent, no one living there
could get a rent subsidy until the debt was paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the government,'' the interviewer, Patrice
Halliburton, said apologetically. ``You can't bend the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones wilted, bewildered by bureaucratic red tape. He went back
to his temporary apartment, where later that day his daughter
arrived, carrying the ice cream for her boys and the drugs for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   A well-meaning but overwhelmed man who has spent most of his
life in housing projects, working at jobs like spray painting
barrels, Jones had trouble asking for help. He had no phone. When a
gang war broke out in June, even Ms. Hunter and Ms. Franklin were
afraid to visit.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jones fetched the police to stop Ms. Christian and
her boyfriend from stealing his furniture, clothes and the
children's food. The next day, he armed himself with a meat cleaver
when the couple tried to return.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost what she called her ``advertising job'' shouting out
to drug buyers ``Hurricane'' and ``Chaos,'' the names of heroin,
Ms. Christian turned to prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Christian blames herself for ravaging her family and
sometimes she resolves to stop using drugs. In June, she checked
into a short-term detoxification program, then came home and read
stories to her sons. At other times she said, ``All I know is to go
out there and do my hustle and get myself some wake-up so I can
function.''
</P>
<P>
   By late July, the family owed nearly $500 in rent and Jones'
welfare payments had been cut in half because he had missed an
appointment with a caseworker.
</P>
<P>
   In early August, housing officials met with each of the
temporarily relocated families, most of whom were behind on rent.
At least four were told they would be evicted, Ms. Hunter said. No
family is permanently moved until back rent is paid.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunter said Jones told her he would try to pay his rent so
that she could begin trying to get him a Section 8 subsidy. The
rent has not been paid, but Ms. Hunter said she is not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely don't want him to get left behind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Problems and Promise: Diverse Family Poses Dilemma
</P>
<P>
   Katie Sistrunk was packing, getting ready to move any day. Then,
in January, the letter came.
</P>
<P>
   The private agency screening people for the apartment she wanted
had rejected her. The letter cited ``many problems with this
family,'' including ``gang affiliation'' and ``poor rent-paying
habits.'' It said two of her teen-agers quit school ``to pursue a
career in crime, i.e. robbing and stalking innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the letter was wrong. In part, it confused Ms. Sistrunk
with a sister arrested on drug charges. It was just the first hitch
in her effort to maneuver her large and complicated family through
the housing bureaucracy and out of the Robert Taylor Homes.
</P>
<P>
   With gravelly voice and gap-toothed smile, Ms. Sistrunk is a
passionate advocate for herself, 13 children, 28 grandchildren and
dozens more relatives. Her family is so identified with the Hole
that one son, 27-year-old Henry, has a tattoo of the three
high-rises.
</P>
<P>
   The Sistrunks illustrate the complexities of many families in
Robert Taylor. One family may have members who have succeeded
against bleak odds and members whose criminal behavior could result
in eviction under public housing rules, or could prevent them from
getting private housing.
</P>
<P>
   Over 27 years in The Hole, the Sistrunks have made undeniable
strides. They relied little on welfare, living mostly on income
from Ms. Sistrunk's former husband. In the middle of squalor, the
children ironed their jeans and T-shirts. Three children have
attended college. One, on a basketball scholarship, expects to
graduate with a degree in architecture. But five of Ms. Sistrunk's
grown children have criminal records, some involving weapons or
drugs, court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got tons of problems,'' Ms. Hunter, the relocation
specialist, said, ``but they got a lot going for them, they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hunter does not volunteer sensitive information like arrests
to prospective landlords. And she tried to get the private agency
that rejected Ms. Sistrunk to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is toughness combined with natural mercy and
humanity,'' said Joseph Shuldiner, the housing authority's
executive director. ``We have to be realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   In moving, Ms. Sistrunk wanted dignity and choices for her
family.
</P>
<P>
   She lobbied housing officials until six of her grown children
got rent-subsidized apartments. Then her 24-year-old son, Joe, was
charged with cocaine possession and her two youngest children, 16
and 17, were charged with interfering with the police during the
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Charges against the teen-agers were dropped, but Joe was in jail
the day he was to sign his lease. The family sent his girlfriend to
sign for him.
</P>
<P>
   For herself and her two youngest children, Ms. Sistrunk wanted
one of the housing authority's new scattered-site apartments. She
rejected one. Twice, she accepted homes but was told they had been
taken. She phoned top-level housing officials. Two days before her
building was to be emptied, she rounded up other tenants and
threatened not to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me about one thing, then they switch it,'' she
thundered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while on vacation Ms. White, the housing authority
official supervising the relocation, guaranteed Ms. Sistrunk a
place that she wanted so she would not have to move to temporary
quarters. Aware of the Sistrunks' complicated history, Ms. White
decided they had great potential to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have some flexibility to look at people
individually,'' Ms. White said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Ms. Sistrunk moved out, carrying an urn with the ashes
of her former husband, who died in March; salt for good luck; and
her daughter's prom glass, a proud symbol of her high school
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   She passed a drug dealer who was yelling ``Bubble on State,''
signaling that the police were nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so sick of that `Bubble on State,' '' she whispered.
``What they should have did is torn it down many years ago and
saved a lot of mothers' sons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0819 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-RUMORS-REVIEW-NYT     09-05 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-RUMORS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTY LAUNDRY: NOW, THE SPIN CYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Everybody here is whispering about whispering about
everybody else's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   No one, of course, is recommending such talk. Heaven forbid. No
one wants the president's troubles to unleash a squinty-eyed
inquisition into the sexual mores of a publicly dull, prudish city
with a history of smeared lipstick behind closed office doors.
</P>
<P>
   But in the White House, on Capitol Hill and in political
consultancies and law firms, people say it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is going to burn,'' predicted one prominent
Democrat here, while insisting that his camp would have nothing to
do with setting the blaze. The prospect of a report to Congress by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr started the latest round of
expectant rumor-mongering.
</P>
<P>
   But predictions of a sexual Armageddon have been rife almost
since the president was first reported to have had an affair with
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. They have yet to come true.
While Ms. Lewinsky's dirty laundry _ literally _ has been aired in
press accounts, few others besides her and the president have been
seared so far.
</P>
<P>
   One exception is House Speaker Newt Gingrich, whose sexual past
was recently picked over in the online publication ``Salon.'' The
article reprised reporting in Vanity Fair three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the most prominent exception is Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who
admitted Friday that he had had an extramarital relationship years
ago that produced a son. Earlier in the week, Burton had told
constituents of unspecified past troubles in his 38-year marriage,
saying he was motivated by the fear that Vanity Fair (again) was
about to publish scandalous details.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Burton's disclosure, jittery politicians were
admitting mistakes or declaring their virtue right and left.
Obliquely asked by reporters if marital faithfulness was properly
an issue in presidential contests, some have pre-emptively declared
themselves true to their wives. Texas Gov. George W. Bush has done
so, as has former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   ``To run in 2000, as a prospective presidential candidate in
particular, you're going to have to be Mr. or Mrs. Clean,'' said
Greg Mueller, a Republican political strategist.
</P>
<P>
   The other approach _ admitting mistakes _ was on display last
week. In criticizing Clinton, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut
and several other Democratic senators practically stumbled over
each other in conceding, vaguely, transgressions (though not
necessarily sexual ones) in their personal lives. That technique
blunted not only any appearance of censoriousness, but also the
news hook that an accusation of hypocrisy might provide reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In admitting his mistakes, Burton blamed the White House for
putting Vanity Fair onto the story, an accusation dismissed by the
administration and the magazine. ``When it comes to anybody's
personal life, that's just off limits as far as we are concerned,''
said a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials say that it would be stupid for them to
risk spreading sexual rumors, though they say they worry that rogue
aides might be freelancing.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists' willingness to poke into bedrooms is often traced _
wrongly _ to a challenge in 1987 by Gary Hart, then a Democratic
candidate for president, to a reporter from this newspaper.
``Follow me around,'' he said. ``I don't care. I'm serious. If
anybody wants to put a tail on me, go ahead. They'd be very
bored.'' In fact, by the time those words were published, people
already were tailing him. They weren't bored.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent rumors of Hart's womanizing appear to have piqued
reporters' interest, and let the genie out of the bottle. Then, in
1991, the face-off between Anita Hill and Supreme Court nominee
Clarence Thomas helped turn sexual behavior in the workplace into a
national issue. That set the stage for Sen. Bob Packwood's
resignation in 1995, after years of criticism and investigation of
his relations with women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, presidential candidate Bill Clinton was beset by rumors
similar to those that dogged Hart. This time, a woman, Gennifer
Flowers, stepped forward to describe an affair. The accusation came
as Clinton was under fire for his honesty on issues like the
Vietnam draft. Reporters rolled such matters together under the
portentous-sounding heading of the ``character issue.''
</P>
<P>
   That journalistic approach seemed vindicated last week when
Lieberman delivered his speech. ``I know that the president is far
from alone in the wrongdoing he has admitted,'' he said. ``But the
president, by virtue of the office he sought and was elected to,
has traditionally been held to a higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last presidential campaign, the sex life of
Republican nominee Bob Dole came under scrutiny, but not only
potential presidents have been held to the higher standard. Dick
Morris, a Clinton political adviser, was accused in print of seeing
a prostitute. The story was deemed newsworthy in part because
Morris had devised a campaign emphasizing ``values.'' He was forced
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   After Morris, two Republican political consultants, Arthur
Finkelstein and Don Sipple, found their private lives explored in
magazines. (Last week, in Salon, Democratic consultant James
Carville argued that consultants should be exempted from such
prying. ``Isn't there a danger here that we might be going too
far?'' he wrote, with admitted self-interest.)
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and their advisers blame the news media in part for
legitimating and aiding attacks over private behavior, treating
people in politics more like Hollywood celebrities in a quest for
ratings and readers. Sensational stories like the O.J. Simpson
murder trial, according to this argument, addicted reporters and
editors even at once-staid organizations to sensational stories
that run for weeks like soap operas, but may have little policy
significance.
</P>
<P>
   In the view at least of Democrats here, Starr's inquiry into
Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky burned down any remaining
fences around politicians' _ and maybe prominent journalists' _
private lives.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic political consultant Carter Eskew argued that the
Lewinsky matter demonstrated that while voters are disgusted by
adultery, they are also angered by people who dredge it up. Most
political candidates, he said, would not risk airing opponents'
sexual secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it's mutual assured destruction,'' he said. ``So it
won't happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0820 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKING-BOOKS-REVIEW-     09-05 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKING-BOOKS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A HIKE! CAN'T YOU SEE I'M READING? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent with `L' code) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(editors: bold-faced words should be italicized) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walking seems simple: You take your right foot and place it
ahead of your left. Then you take your left foot and place it ahead
of your right. Locomotion ensues. You may wish to vary the starting
foot. Left, right _ It's up to you.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, walking is a lot less complicated than the
hokey-pokey, but you don't see a lot of books written about the
hokey-pokey, even though pretty much everybody has to dance it at
weddings, sometimes drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Walking, on the other hand, has inspired dozens of books as well
as a glossy magazine in recent years _ a response to an
increasingly aging, sedentary and obese population that recognizes
the need to get off its collective keister but also says, ``Hey,
let's not overdo it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, as walking has assumed a lucrative, baby-boomerish niche
in the consumer economy, this simple activity, in typically
American fashion, has become rocket science, brain surgery,
quasi-religious ritual and organizing principle of life all rolled
into one.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the impression you come away with after
perusing volumes like those excerpted below, lugged back to the
office after a recent foray into one of Manhattan's book
superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Before trying this or any other strenuous activity, consult your
physician.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TOM KUNTZ
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 1: ``The 90-Day Fitness Walking Program''
by Mark Fenton and Seth Bauer (Perigee, 1995, 188 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Sample Workout: Day 1 . . . Walk out of your door and walk for
five minutes in any direction at any speed. Then turn around and
come home. That's it. You're done.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 2: ``Walking: A Complete Guide to the
Complete Exercise'' by Casey Meyers (Random House, 1992, 313 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: I have worked with thousands of people in walking clinics
coast to coast. During this time two things have struck me as
funny. First, everybody drove to the clinic to learn how to walk,
and second, almost all knew more about how their cars functioned
than about how their bodies did.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 3: ``Walk Yourself Well'' by Sherry
Brourman, P.T., with Randy Rodman (Hyperion, 1998, 292 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Every step we take has two phases: a stance phase and a
swing phase. The stance phase is the part of walking when the foot
is touching the ground. The three parts to the stance phase are:
(1)  &UR; heel strike, &LR;  when only the heel is on the ground; (2)
 &UR; mid-stance, &LR;  when the foot and toes come to the ground; and (3)
 &UR; pushoff, &LR;  when the foot lifts onto the toe, which bend, squeeze
down, and propel us forward, mostly with the big and middle toe.
</P>
<P>
   The swing phase is everything that happens between the time that
the toes go airborne until the heel of the same foot strikes the
ground again. Both stance and swing phases play a primary role in
propelling us forward with optimal balance.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 4: ``Walking Fast: Techniques and Workouts
for High-Level Fitness and Performance'' by Therese Iknoian (Human
Kinetics, 1998, 183 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Walking is walking. That's it. You might go faster, or
you might go slower, but if you're putting one foot in front of the
other for your health, fitness or performance, you're walking.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 5: ``Walking'' by Ruth Rudner (Human
Kinetics, 1996, 120 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: One bright autumn Sunday afternoon, I left the village of
Igls, a couple of miles from and a thousand feet above Innsbruck in
the Austrian Tyrol, to go for a walk. The air was crisp, the world
shimmering with the gold of larch trees and birches. The pretty
forest path was well-trod by about 200 years of walkers. I was
headed for a mountain hut a few miles distant for an afternoon of
coffee and cake. On the way, I came upon an old woman walking up
the path, holding the hand of a tiny girl. The girl was little
enough that walking must have been a new activity for her. The two
kept pace with one another, their footsteps matching. It struck me,
in that moment, that I was seeing the ending and the beginning of
life; that the rhythm of age and childhood were in accord; and that
all of this was happening on foot.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 6: ``JayWalking: the Ultimate Fitness
Journey'' by Jay Ciniglio (Berkley, 1998, 137 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: The beauty of JayWalking is that it is a state of mind,
as well as a philosophy, and can be done anytime and anywhere, in
any footwear.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 7: ``The Spirited Walker: Fitness Walking
for Clarity, Balance and Spiritual Connection'' by Carolyn Scott
Kortge (HarperSanFrancisco, 1998, 253 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: When you've had a day filled with activity and what you
need most is to quiet your mind so that you can reconnect with
nature _ and with your own divine nature _ experiment with
contemplative walking meditation. Pick a location where you can
focus fully on your steps. It might be a hallway or your living
room. Perhaps you know a quiet path outdoors. Lower your eyes and
turn your attention to your steps. Walk slowly, counting each step
in a pattern of one to four. When your attention strays, simply
begin the count again. Or focus on your breathing, blocking out
mental chatter by thinking ``in'' as you inhale and ``out'' as you
release each breath.
</P>
<P>
   Thich Nhat Hanh, Vietnamese Buddhist monk and peace activist,
teaches meditation students to plant peace and happiness on the
earth with each step. . . . Be aware of your foot touching the
ground and consciously imprint peace with each step. Think about
leaving footprints that heal the earth.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 8: ``The Rugged Walker: Great Workouts for
the Great Outdoors'' by Patricia Kirk (Human Kinetics, 1998, 201
pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: Walking the rugged path has led me on a journey that
travels deep into the unfolding of who I am.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Groucho-Based Exercises:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Groucho Walk  &LR; . . . Start walking, then bend your knees so you
are in a deep lunge position. Make sure your knees stay over your
heels (forming a 90-degree or wider angle at the knee) as you step
forward. Walk quickly in this squat position while pumping your
arms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Groucho Lay-Ups  &LR; . . . Take three Groucho steps beginning with
your right foot, then hop on the third step (on your right foot),
bringing your left knee up and landing on your foot again. When you
land, be sure to bend your knees to help absorb the impact. Take
three Groucho steps beginning with your left foot, hop on your
third step (on your left foot). Pump the arms as you Groucho-walk
and then swing them wider or shoot them overhead, as in basketball,
when you hop. Continue to step-step-step-shoot (on the count of 1,
2, 3, 4).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Backward Groucho Walking Uphill  &LR; . . . Be sure the way is clear
of debris. Crouch low into the knees (however, avoid bending too
low and putting stress on the knee) and Groucho-walk up the hill
backward.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 9: ``Walk It Off! 20 Minutes a Day to
Health and Fitness'' by Suzanne Levine, D.p.m. (Plume/Penguin,
1990, 257 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Sample Walking Type: The Sensual Stroller . . . For this one,
think Marilyn Monroe or Elvis Presley. Your whole body is alive
with pleasure as you walk. You feel your lithe limbs moving under
your clothes. You step forward with a slinky roll, leading with
your hips, your arms gracefully flowing forward and back with each
sensuous unfolding of your thighs.
</P>
<P>
   You move like a graceful tiger, leisurely but calculating. . . .
You're beautiful and desirable, and you know it. You're humming
something provocative, like ``Mama Said There'd Be Days Like This''
or ``The Girl From Ipanema.'' You know you look marvelous. You're
in the mood for love.
</P>
<P>
   How-to-Walk Book No. 10: ``Walk Yourself Thin'' by David A.
Rives (Moon River, 1998, 149 pages)
</P>
<P>
   Quote: First of all, it really is a fact of life: If you're
going to get thin, you're going to have to control  &UR; something! &LR;  If
you don't want to control the amount you eat, then you're going to
have to control the amount you exercise. There's no getting around
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, poop!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Postscript: Perhaps walking isn't for you. In that case, you might
consider books like ``The Art of Breathing'' by Nancy Zi (Vivi,
1997), or even ``The Art of Doing Nothing'' by Veronique Vienne
(Clarkson Potter, 1998), which includes chapters on lounging,
napping and yawning.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0822 &Cx1f; var-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKING-BOOKS-REVIEW-     09-05 1063
