<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-AIKMAN-80     09-05 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-AIKMAN-800&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MID-CAREER CRISIS: AIKMAN AND COWBOYS STARTING OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It could have been first down or third down, a
critical call or simply the continuation of an exacting drive
toward the end zone. Troy Aikman, the Dallas Cowboys quarterback,
would walk to the sideline last season and talk it over. Run or
pass? Hit the middle or attack the outside? Remain in the pocket or
try something on the run?
</P>
<P>
   Aikman would seek answers with the Dallas coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the answers would not come directly from Barry Switzer, then
the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never spoke to Barry,'' Aikman said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never say never. But Aikman does.
</P>
<P>
   He says a lot by saying little about Switzer. The two did not
click. Maybe it was a lack of respect or resentment or different
personalties. Whatever it was, it was the backdrop for Dallas'
winning Super Bowl XXX in 1996. It was the stage on which the
Cowboys dropped dead, to a 6-10 record last season, missing the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   There was trouble in Dallas last season with players that were
viewed as hooligans-in-chaos, there was trouble in the offense
(gone stale), with the defense (too leaky), and with the personnel
(no longer Pro-Bowl laden). There was frustration and shoddy
execution and injury. Seemingly, suddenly, Dallas looked a lot as
it did when Aikman first arrived in 1989 from UCLA as the National
Football League's No. 1 draft pick. It was a 1-15 team that first
Aikman season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discouraging thing is that we allowed this franchise to
fall to 6-10,'' Aikman said, with a fidgeting hand and a twisted
face. ``For those of us who were here in '89 and knew how hard we
had to work to get to be a Super Bowl team, it was awfully hard. I
never thought we would ever get back to where we would be a
rebuilding team, and I use that word loosely. I expect to win now.
But to win Super Bowls again, yes, that might take some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't a real talented group in '89 and it was implied
that I was going to be the guy that we were going to build around.
We already had Michael Irvin in place. That second year we drafted
Emmitt Smith. The third year Norv Turner arrived as offensive
coordinator. It all fell into place. This is the most change in
this organization right now since '89. Now, you can look at change
in many different ways. Stability was missing. But I see Chan
Gailey as a coach who can be here for a long time. I'm not the
first one to go down this chute.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not. Because he has been there before. Right in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Starting over.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes it an exciting yet harried time for Troy Aikman,
31, a three-time Super Bowl champion quarterback, the Cowboys'
career leading passer who holds or is tied for 42 Dallas passing
records, a man with an 11-2 record in post-season play. A player
viewed as the conscience in the Dallas locker room and one with
clout. Enough to help force Switzer's departure. Enough for the new
Dallas coach, Gailey, to replace Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   As the NFL season opens Sunday, quarterbacks around the league
face enormous and persistent pressure. Quarterbacks color the
personalities of their teams. They get too much credit and they get
too much blame, but it has always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman takes a peek around the league and sees Kordell Stewart
in Pittsburgh routinely expected, in only his second year as a
starter, to keep the Steelers at the top of the Super Bowl chase.
He sees Gus Frerotte in Washington under monumental pressure. He
says that Elvis Grbac in Kansas City is in a tough spot with a team
that soared in the regular season, but crashed in the playoffs last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He need only look in the mirror, however, to find that he is the
quarterback who faces the toughest scrutiny this fall. He is the
National Football League's highest-paid quarterback, with a
contract that averages $6.2 million a year. His team is the one
that America loves and hates. His team is down and he has to pick
it up. He asked for a new head coach, and he got one.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people feel I am the cause for lots of changes here but
that is not entirely true,'' Aikman said. ``I have been vocal the
last couple of years, but changes would have been made whether I
was vocal or not. I feel very fortunate that I have an owner in
Jerry Jones who is committed to winning. I am fortunate that I have
an owner who takes into consideration my opinions. I am not above
enough to think that I am always right or that what I say goes. And
when you have a voice like that, you have to be able to handle it.
I have never gotten caught up in it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aikman wanted Turner, currently the Washington Redskins' head
coach, to replace Switzer. Aikman and Turner are special friends.
``We talk weekly,'' Aikman said. ``We had a special relationship
from Day 1. We are similar in our approach. We are not afraid to be
honest or optimistic. Winning counts for us. He was here for three
years, and I credit Norv for a large part of any success I've had.
He came as a first-time offensive coordinator and I came as a young
quarterback seeking success. I needed him and he needed me.
Together, we flourished.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas could not work a deal to get Turner. But in Gailey,
Aikman has a head coach who, for the first time, will personally
call Aikman's plays. He has a coach he can talk to. He likes that.
</P>
<P>
   He has a new offense for the first time in seven years. Before,
the Dallas passing game under Aikman featured mostly strict pocket
passing and holding on to the ball longer. Then an addition was
made with five-to-seven-step drops and quick releases. Now Gailey
will employ Aikman in those ways and more: the shotgun, moving the
pocket, rollout passes and more throws downfield. Aikman likes
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a quarterback with the physical skills and intellect
of Troy and not even make the playoffs,'' Jones said, ``to not give
him a chance to get to the Super Bowl while he is in the prime of
his career was tough to take last year. I just never thought that
would happen. Some of it was my fault. I did not get him the
offensive line he needed and that will never happen again. But I
say with no question that we believe in Troy on and off the field.
You can see why he is our Rembrandt.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has become an ambassador for pro football well beyond
Dallas. Last year he was named the National Football League Man of
the Year, the most prestigious honor a player can receive for
off-the-field service and charity. Aikman has four seasons left on
his Dallas contract. He knows he is lucky that during the off
season he was treated successfully for a cancerous tumor that was
detected on his back. He has sustained enough concussions in his
nine pro seasons to provide a scare, but not to prevent him from
continuing to play. His dream is to one day play again for Turner.
But he has bigger dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment I have made here is for the long haul,'' Aikman
said. ``I have tried to become numb and desensitized to all of the
attention. I don't know if you ever really master that. I have
never gotten comfortable with my role as the quarterback of this
franchise. My role in the scheme of all things is very short-lived.
This is a fleeting experience in the course of my lifetime. I will
attempt to enjoy it for whatever it brings.''
</P>
<P>
   This season for Aikman could be one of pure frustration. Or
wonderful surprise. It will be packed with pressure because he is
starting over again. Going down that chute again.
</P>
<P>
   He eagerly awaits the ride. ``But if you had asked me that
question a year ago,'' he said, ``I might have had a different
answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
