<HEADER>
A0826 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEHOUSE-CAMPAIGNS-     09-05 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATEHOUSE-CAMPAIGNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE LEGISLATURE CAMPAIGNS BECOME SOPHISTICATED AND EXPENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Mich., Wis., Fla., Va., S.C., Texas, Neb.,
Ark.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Not so long ago, state Sen. Edward Warren ran
for re-election every two years by handing out combs. Thousands of
combs. Thousands of green combs (because Warren is from Greenville)
with his name embossed in white type.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go out to the restaurants where the farmers go for
breakfast, like Tom's in Greenville and Bum's in Ayden, and I'd
pass out my combs,'' said Warren, a 68-year-old former high school
principal who has served in North Carolina's Legislature for 18
years. ``I'd always just tell people that I don't have any hair, so
I have no need for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, a Democrat, still hands out combs. But in the past four
years, he has also become conversant in the modern politics of
television advertising buys, polling cross-tabulations and targeted
direct mail. While he once spent no more than $30,000 to hold on to
his state Senate seat, his 1996 campaign cost $210,000. This year,
he may have to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just out of control,'' Warren said. ``I never thought I'd
see it in my career, but that's the real world in North Carolina
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it has become the real world for lawmakers in virtually
every statehouse in the 1990s. With partisan control of
legislatures at risk in a remarkable number of states, and with
states inheriting vast new responsibilities from Washington, the
once-quaint business of legislative politics has become intensely
competitive, sophisticated and costly.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of hidebound, one-party domination, nearly a third
of all legislative chambers are now within theoretical striking
distance of a switch in partisan control. In several chambers, like
the Michigan House of Representatives, the California Assembly and
the Wisconsin Senate, control has changed multiple times in the
last six years.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some states have long had closely contested and
relatively expensive legislative elections, but now even the
once-solid South, where the state legislatures were the last
bastion of Democratic control, is in play.
</P>
<P>
   This new competitiveness, driven largely by Republican inroads
in this decade, has led to a sea change in the tactics of
legislative campaigning, said dozens of lawmakers, political
consultants and authorities on state government interviewed last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Television advertising was once considered absurdly inefficient
in legislative races because media markets are typically far larger
than districts. But it is now commonplace, and not just on cable.
Legislative leaders make extensive use of polling to determine how
to allocate their party caucuses' financial resources. Partisan
messages and policy positions are crafted with the help of focus
groups.
</P>
<P>
   With states playing a crucial role in welfare, education,
taxation and criminal justice, the national political parties are
placing renewed emphasis on legislative campaigns, and so are
various interest groups. And the political stakes are only rising,
since the elections in 1998 and 2000 will determine which parties
control the redistricting process after the next census.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has led to skyrocketing costs _ and a need for
ever-greater fund-raising. ``Targeted races are running two to
three times what they cost in the early '90s,'' said Kevin Mack,
director of the Democratic Legislative Campaign Committee. ``It's
almost a congressionalization of state legislative campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   In California two years ago, two assemblymen, Rusty Areias and
Bruce McPherson, spent a combined $3.49 million in trying to move
up to the state Senate, a race won by McPherson, a Republican.
Total spending on legislative races in that state increased to $105
million in 1995-96 from $15 million in 1975-76, the secretary of
state reported.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's recent experience demonstrates that campaign
inflation is not limited to large states with high advertising
rates. As the General Assembly here has become a partisan
battleground, with the Republicans gaining a slim majority in the
House of Representatives in 1994, the cost of campaigning has
soared.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, candidates from the two major parties in North Carolina
spent a total of $13.6 million on their campaigns, according to a
study by Thad Beyle, a political scientist at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill. After accounting for inflation, that
was an increase of 81 percent over the amount spent in 1994, and an
increase of 172 percent over 1992, Beyle reported.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the increase in spending is that legislative
politics have destabilized in the 1990s after decades of calm.
</P>
<P>
   From 1972 to 1994, Democrats were as prevalent in state
legislatures as plaid sportcoats. They controlled the majority of
statehouses and exerted little effort in maintaining their power.
They were particularly dominant in the South in those years, a
period when Democrats controlled every legislative chamber and
never held fewer than 71 percent of the region's legislative seats,
according to the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the Democratic campaign strategy consisted of
little more than ``hearing at the grocery store that Senator Joe
was in trouble and sending him $500,'' said Sen. Roy Cooper, the
Democratic majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1994, as Republicans took control of Congress, they also
asserted themselves on the state level. Republicans entered that
election with control of 8 legislatures and emerged with 19, while
the Democrats were left with 18. Twelve legislatures were divided
with each party controlling one chamber. (Nebraska has a unicameral
Legislature whose members run in nonpartisan elections.)
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the Democrats rebounded a bit, taking control
in 20 states to the Republicans' 18, with 11 states divided. In the
South, Democrats hold only 62 percent of all seats, and Republicans
control both chambers in Florida and Virginia, as well as the House
of Representatives in North Carolina and South Carolina and the
state Senate in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This year, in the 46 states with elections in at least one
house, the parties are separated by six seats or fewer in 23
chambers, a staggering level of competitiveness. Adding to the
instability is the onset of term limits, which will dislodge large
numbers of incumbents in several states. In Michigan, for instance,
where Democrats hold a six-seat majority in the House, term limits
will open 67 of 110 seats this year. In the Arkansas House, 49 of
100 seats will be open because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the new spending in legislative campaigns is fattening
the wallets of pollsters and consultants who have nudged
legislative candidates into the modern age. Democratic pollster
Alan Secrest said that close to a third of his firm's revenues now
come from legislative candidates, as against less than 1 percent
only four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these legislators think that their 65 million years
aren't up yet and that another campaign of flatbed trucks and
pocket combs will carry the day,'' Secrest said. ``But incumbents
don't take these races for granted in Congress anymore and they
better not do it in legislatures either or they'll wind up as
dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they consult pollsters and cut television ads, many
lawmakers lament that the new professionalism of legislative
politics has transformed their political culture.
</P>
<P>
   Like their congressional counterparts, they complain that fund
raising monopolizes their time. The reliance on big money has given
new power to legislative leaders and their centralized fund-raising
committees, which collect contributions for their party caucuses
and then distribute cash to the most vulnerable members. It has
heightened the influence of lobbyists, interest groups and
political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   Here in North Carolina, Sen. John Kerr, a Democrat from
Goldsboro, used to shun contributions from political action
committees on principle. This year, he said, he can no longer
afford to be pure. ``When your opponent is running 30-second
commercials and dropping all these mailings,'' Kerr said, ``you've
got to be able to combat that, to do background research, to
poll.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Daniel Blue Jr., a Democrat from Raleigh and a former
speaker of the House, said the cost of campaigning had made public
service ``unachievable for ordinary folk.'' The influence of
check-bearing lobbyists, he said, ``just pervades everything that
goes on here.''
</P>
<P>
   All too often, he added, policy proposals seem to be crafted by
out-of-state pollsters with an eye on November. Compromise is often
sacrificed in the name of political positioning. Last week, for
instance, the General Assembly here was deadlocked over a proposal
by House Republicans to eliminate the state's inheritance tax.
State Senate Democrats agreed to a partial repeal, but Republicans
did not budge. ``Apparently it polls very well,'' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse in Raleigh has contributed to the longest
legislative session in the state's history. And legislative leaders
worry that the demands on lawmakers' time will make it difficult to
recruit candidates for an increasingly full-time job that pays
$13,951 a year and $104 a day in expenses. Sen. Leslie J. Winner, a
respected Democrat from Charlotte, is quitting this year after
three terms because the job now keeps her apart too often from her
9-year-old daughter, Lily. One of Lily's poems, which Ms. Winner
has posted in her office, is ``dedicated to my mother, who's always
in Raleigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rosenthal, a political scientist at Rutgers University,
said it was important to remember that two-party politics is often
a good thing. But, he said, ``like anything else, it's got a down
side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
