<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-KIM-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA DESIGNATES KIM `GREAT LEADER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea became the first Communist country to
transfer government power within a family dynasty on Saturday, as
it anointed Marshal Kim Jong Il as its ``Great Leader'' and head of
an expanded National Defense Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Kim, the eldest son of former ``Great Leader'' Kim Il
Sung, who died four years ago, will govern in much the style of an
ancient Korean king, ruling absolutely and inheriting legitimacy
not from institutions but from the bloodline of the previous ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's announcement did not specify what would happen to the
presidency, but there have been reports that it will be abolished
and the position held forever by Kim's late father. While many
countries have had presidents for life, North Korea apparently
would become the first nation to extend the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, and the consolidation of power by Kim Jong Il,
ends the four-year interregnum left by the death of Kim Il Sung.
The younger Kim had already assumed the top positions in the ruling
party and the army, and now he effectively adds a job as head of
the state itself.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts expect few immediate changes because Kim has been
running North Korea since his father's death. But some say that the
coronation of a new king permits the country to experiment
carefully with new policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's less ideological than his father and he represents a
different generation,'' said Han Park, a political scientist at the
University of Georgia who regularly visits North Korea. ``He's much
more pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea now refers to Kim as ``Great Leader,'' instead of
the ``Dear Leader'' title he carried while his father was alive.
</P>
<P>
   But the Korean expressions used are still different from the one
that was reserved for his father, although the younger Kim is
hailed in terms that could scarcely be grander.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an outstanding thinker and theoretician, a distinguished
statesman and a peerlessly brilliant commander who has ushered in a
heyday of the era of the Workers Party, an era of great prosperity
of socialist Korea,'' the official Korean Central News Agency
declared Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   If North Korea is one of the most perplexing of nations, Kim
Jong Il is among the most mysterious of leaders. Intelligence
experts believe that he may have several nuclear weapons, making
him the least understood of any leader with a finger on a nuclear
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, 56, has traveled outside his country only once, to China in
1983, and has never met a non-Communist. Although he is hailed in
North Korea as a virtual deity, his voice has been broadcast only
once, when a television clip showed him addressing a military
parade with a brief slogan: ``Glory be to the heroic officers and
men of the Korean People's Army!''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see him as a maniac, noting that he has been
accused of kidnapping a South Korean actor-and-actress couple whose
work he admired, of planning the bombing of the South Korean
Cabinet in 1983, and of plotting the bombing of a civilian South
Korean airliner in 1987. The woman who planted the bomb, Kim Hyon
Hee, said that Kim Jong Il ordered the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that he lacks his father's charisma but appears to be
intelligent and relatively open-minded. Tape-recordings of private
conversations in which he frankly acknowledges the economic
inefficiency of socialism were smuggled out of North Korea several
years ago, and a defector who claims to have lived in his house
says that Kim worked hard, had a computer on his desk and watched
CNN and other foreign television networks.
</P>
<P>
   That defector, Lee Nam Ok, who is now living in hiding in
Europe, told a Japanese magazine that she never saw any sign that
Kim was a temperamental playboy _ as he is sometimes described. She
recounted Kim's life in his compound as luxurious, with air
conditioning and a huge playroom full of slot machines and other
toys for his son to play with, and she said that he sent his son to
a boarding school in Switzerland to gain exposure to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual and remarkably moderate essay last year Kim called
for improved relations with South Korea and the United States. But
then Kim presumably was also behind a series of commando missions
in which submarines dropped off armed troops on the South Korean
shores, and he has resisted calls for a summit meeting by South
Korea's president, Kim Dae Jung.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea remains the most mobilized and rigidly controlled
society in the world, comparable with the Soviet Union under
Stalin. But in recent years, there have been signs of change in
North Korea, including the emergence of small-scale free markets in
some towns, and the country has also sought foreign investment,
particularly in a special investment zone in the far northeast.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of change at the edges, North Koreans outside
the country seem increasingly casual in what they say, sometimes
even urging that one not pay too much attention to their country's
official statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please forget the North Korean rhetoric,'' said Kim Myong
Chol, an unofficial spokesman for North Korea based in Tokyo.
``North Korea is headed for North Korea's version of a free-market
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Myong Chol, who previously edited a North Korean-backed
newspaper in Japan and still regularly visits North Korea to confer
with officials, said that he expected that Kim Jong Il's ascension
would over time lead to more flexible policies.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the effective abolition of the presidency
complicates an already muddy picture at what seems to be a crucial
time in North Korean history. Millions of North Koreans are widely
believed to be on the edge of starvation and the economy has
largely collapsed because of energy shortages, mismanagement and
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   There are widely diverging estimates of the seriousness of the
food shortages. By all accounts, hunger is widespread and is
causing some death, but some estimates are that the death toll is
modest while others range up to the millions.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea refuses visits by most foreigners, so it is
difficult to gauge the true level of suffering.
</P>
<P>
   A landmark agreement reached in 1994, under which North Korea
agreed to give up its nuclear program in exchange for energy from
the West, now appears to be in jeopardy because of recriminations
and ill feeling on both sides. If that agreement is completely
breached, North Korea may revive its nuclear program, leading to a
renewed confrontation between North Korea and Western powers.
</P>
<P>
   Many diplomats and scholars now say that the last such showdown,
in 1994, came much closer to war than was generally known at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions were underscored in the last week when North Korea
launched a multi-stage rocket that sailed over Japan, prompting a
furious reaction from the Japanese government. Western officials
say that the rocket was a test of a new class of North Korean
ballistic missile capable of carrying chemical weapons or a nuclear
warhead, while North Korea says it was simply a launch of a
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Western scholars say that Kim was born in a camp in the Soviet
Union, where his father was based as a guerrilla fighting the
Japanese forces then occupying Korea. But North Korea says that Kim
was born on Mount Paektu, a sacred mountain in Korean history.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has often claimed magical associations with Kim.
Last fall, when he was named leader of the ruling Workers Party,
the official news media announced that flowers suddenly bloomed and
that a magical white sea cucumber entered a fisherman's net ``to
hail the auspicious event'' of Kim's rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the mysterious natural phenomena, Koreans say Comrade
Kim Jong Il is indeed the greatest of great men produced by heaven
and that flowers come into bloom to mark the great event,'' the
official news agency declared at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
