<HEADER>
A0842 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABR-PUBLIC-HOUSING-RE     09-05 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABR-PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF A GHETTO : THE EFFORT TO RAZE A SLUM AND REHABILITATE ITS
RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (Eds: This is an abridged version of PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM, which
moved earlier Saturday.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. A map showing
the location of the Robert Taylor Homes and a graphic providing
demographic information on Robert Taylor residents are being sent
to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-602-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the final months of The Hole, anarchy was
everywhere. The Hole, the most oppressive section of Chicago's
notorious Robert Taylor Homes housing project, was coming down.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members shot at a moving van outside one of the project's
three high-rise buildings. Moving crews tried to hurry out each day
before drug dealers commandeered the elevators.
</P>
<P>
   Lenzie Jones packed his grandchildren's clothes but did not know
what to do with their mother's belongings. She had fled a few days
before, after the drug gang she hawked heroin for accused her of
stealing and beat her with a baseball bat and a two-by-four.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Smith frantically swatted cockroaches and attacked stains
in her kitchen. An inspector from the building she wanted to move
into was coming to scrutinize her housekeeping. If she failed, she
would lose the new apartment she had set her heart on.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Sistrunk still had no idea where she would go, days before
her building was to be emptied.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale not seen in decades, the federal government is
helping cities clear slums again, but this time they are slums it
helped create: public housing projects crippled by flawed policies
and mismanagement and overwhelmed by poverty and crime.
</P>
<P>
   From Hartford and Newark to Denver and San Francisco, 100,000
apartments in the nation's worst public housing projects are being
razed under a federal program called Hope VI. The plan is to
replace them with smaller developments that mix families of
different incomes, while moving thousands of tenants into privately
owned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Hole was torn down in July, and the Chicago Housing
Authority will eventually tear down all of Robert Taylor's 28
high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, where high-rise housing projects are corrosive
landmarks of poverty and racial segregation, the demolition will be
nothing less than seismic: The city wants to raze 11,000
apartments, nearly 40 percent of its public housing for families,
over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the challenge greater than at Robert Taylor, much of
which is ``considered the worst slum area in the United States''
according to the Chicago Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is not just for the 11,000 people who will leave
Robert Taylor, a population that is 99 percent black, so poor that
nearly half of the adults live on less than $5,000 a year, and so
isolated that many are unfamiliar with life beyond the grim
monoliths that shadow the Dan Ryan Expressway on the South Side for
nearly two miles.
</P>
<P>
   Hope VI is a test for Chicago itself, as housing officials try
to eliminate a ghetto by placing most of Robert Taylor's tenants in
private apartments. Success will require communities to accept as
neighbors people they have long been happy to have out of sight.
But already a pattern is emerging of housing project tenants being
moved mainly to poor black neighborhoods, many as rundown and
unsafe as the high-rises they left.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-six percent of Robert Taylor adult residents are
unemployed and some need assistance with basic, non-job-related
skills, such as arranging for utility services and selecting
clothes to wear to interviews with prospective landlords.
</P>
<P>
   The distance between Robert Taylor and the outside world is not
lost on the tenants. ``I guess that's why they call it The Hole,''
said Deborah Mardis, a resident for 20 years. ``You fall in and you
never get out.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to simply relocating tenants, Hope VI plans to ease
tenants off government dependence. While relocating Robert Taylor
tenants, the housing authority is spending $1.5 million of its
initial $25 million Hope VI grant on social services, trying to
place as many residents as possible in high school equivalency
courses, training programs and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to disperse the housing project's concentrated
poverty without introducing or aggravating social problems in the
tenants' new neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really need a not-in-my-back-yard backlash right
now.'' said Wanda White, the housing authority official supervising
the relocation.
</P>
<P>
   The housing authority has contracted a private relocation agency
to help find apartments for tenants, some of whom have criminal
records, drug problems or erratic rent-paying habits that could
disqualify them for new housing. The agency's employees not only
show tenants homes in a variety of neighborhoods, but also help
with things like applications, coaching for landlord interviews and
ensuring that tenants are prepared for housekeeping inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such help, making the move to private-sector housing
is difficult for many tenants. Ms. Smith, 23, was desperate to get
out. She was in many ways a typical Robert Taylor tenant: a young,
single mother with three young children. She struggled on welfare,
falling behind on her $44 monthly rent.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who lived in The Hole, she didn't want another
housing authority apartment: She wanted a federal rent subsidy
known as a Section 8 certificate, which would allow her to rent her
own apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Hope VI officials want Section 8 subsidies and the
private market to replace 60 percent of the destroyed units.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who is studying for a high school equivalency
diploma, was organized and efficient in applying for a Section 8
apartment. She assembled birth certificates, Social Security cards
and her son's report card to prove he attended school.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the housekeeping inspector who assessed her as a potential
tenant was unimpressed. The inspector complained about writing on
the walls, said Ms. Smith, and about her friends, who smoked
marijuana in the hallway. Just weeks before her building was to be
emptied, she failed the inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Crestfallen and angry, she moved in with her mother. Finally, in
July, she was approved for a Section 8 apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody going to be fixing up this raggedy place when you're
fixing to move,'' she said, commenting on the initial housekeeping
inspection. ``They know this is the projects, right?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1959, the Robert Taylor Homes quickly became the
nation's largest government-sponsored ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 Congress changed the public housing rent policy: Instead
of a fixed rent, tenants were to pay a percentage of their income.
</P>
<P>
   At Robert Taylor, that caused working families to move out as
their rents rose while neighbors on welfare paid almost nothing.
Housing officials, wary of discrimination suits, stopped screening
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   As the project filled with impoverished people, rent income fell
and maintenance had to be cut. As families moved out, vacant
apartments became havens for drug dealers. Violence and drugs
devastated generations.
</P>
<P>
   The legacies of that devastation have spawned one of the
toughest questions faced by housing officials: how to deal with
intensely troubled families.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Taylor has two relocation specialists to work with
families. They sort out whose name is on each lease, and therefore
who is entitled to new housing; tell tenants about problems such as
unpaid rent, and explain their options: Section 8 subsidies,
another housing project, or ``scattered site'' apartments, which
are managed by the authority but are not in a project. They also
arrange moves, pay security deposits and visit families in their
new homes.
</P>
<P>
   Lenzie Jones, 61, and his daughter, Mary Bee Christian,
presented one of the toughest situations. They were among the last
people to leave their building before it was razed, and even then
they moved to temporary housing with about 25 other families with
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and his grandchildren had been living with his
drug-addicted daughter even though housing officials had separated
Ms. Christian from them in April, a month after her boyfriend hit
Jones with a crowbar to make him give up the children's welfare
money.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to qualify for a Section 8 subsidy, Jones was interviewed
by the agency that assessed tenants for the subsidies. But the
interview, on a late April day, did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   Because the apartment in The Hole had been leased in his
daughter's name, the Section 8 program could not help him until the
housing authority put his name on the lease, too. And because Ms.
Christian owed $250 in back rent, no one living there could get a
rent subsidy until the debt was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Jones left the interview bewildered by bureaucratic red tape.
</P>
<P>
   By late July, the family owed nearly $500 in rent and Jones'
welfare payments had been cut in half because he had missed an
appointment with a caseworker.
</P>
<P>
   But a housing caseworker, Brenda Hunter, said she is not giving
up on Jones, who said he would try to pay the back rent and apply
again for a Section 8 subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely don't want him to get left behind,'' Hunter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Sistrunk, 45, determined that she would not be one of
those left behind. Like many Robert Taylor families, the Sistrunk
family _ Katie, her 13 children and 28 grandchildren _ has some
members who have succeeded against bleak odds and others whose
criminal behavior could result in eviction under public housing
rules, or could prevent them from getting private housing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sistrunk became a passionate advocate for herself and her
extended family when the private agency screening people for the
apartment she wanted rejected her, in part because they had
confused her with a sister who had been arrested on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   During 27 years in The Hole, the Sistrunks have made undeniable
strides. They relied little on welfare, living mostly on income
from Ms. Sistrunk's former husband. In the middle of squalor, the
children ironed their jeans and T-shirts. Three children have
attended college. But five of Ms. Sistrunk's grown children have
criminal records, court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ms. Sistrunk lobbied housing officials until six of her
grown children got rent-subsidized apartments. For herself and her
two youngest children, she wanted one of the housing authority's
new scattered-site apartments. She rejected one. Twice she accepted
homes but was told they had been taken.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ms. Sistrunk was guaranteed a place that she wanted,
saving her from moving to temporary quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In June, she moved out, carrying an urn with the ashes of her
former husband, who died in March; salt for good luck; and her
daughter's prom glass, a proud symbol of her high school
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   She passed a drug dealer who was yelling ``Bubble on State,''
signaling that the police were nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so sick of that `Bubble on State,''' she whispered.
``What they should have did is torn it down many years ago and
saved a lot of mothers' sons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
