<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-540&AMP;ADD-     09-05 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS RUMMAGE FOR THEIR SAVINGS IN CHAOS OF BANKING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With a bitter wind biting at his cheeks on this
unusually cold but clear Saturday morning, Yevgeny Ushakov arrived
at his local bank branch to find the doors closed.
</P>
<P>
   While a city holiday was the official reason the bank was not
open, Ushakov and others unable to enter believed that was merely
an excuse for banks to avoid long lines of anxious depositors that
have been snaking in front of branches all over the city during the
last week.
</P>
<P>
   As the ruble continues to crumble and increasing numbers of
insolvent banks are brought under state control, untold numbers of
Russians are left with the unenviable choice of leaving their
savings in barren banks or allowing the accounts to be transferred
to a state-owned bank at a fraction of their value.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawing the money is almost impossible, but people still
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put my money in three different banks because I thought it
might at least be safe in two of the three,'' said Ushakov, a
66-year-old who had lived on the interest from $4,000 in savings
and a monthly pension now worth a third of the $150 it was worth a
month ago. ``They say don't put all of your eggs in one basket. I
didn't think all three would fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Depositors were given some hope late in the week when the
government, its own future still unclear, promised that it would
salvage citizens' savings from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, Russians learned that the government
guarantee carried a stiff price. If depositors choose to have their
savings transferred to Sberbank, the state-owned savings bank, they
cannot withdraw money until mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting so long is likely to eat even further into the value of
the average Russian's savings because the ruble, which was valued
at about 6 to the dollar in mid-August, has now fallen to between
16 and 21 to the dollar, depending on where it is exchanged. And
the ruble is likely to fall even further if the government remains
paralyzed and the economy continues its downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the misery, the government told Russians with savings
denominated in dollars that the value of their accounts will be
pegged at 9.3 rubles to the dollar, far below what dollars attract
on the street. Depositors have until Sept. 26 to decide if they
want their accounts transferred to Sberbank.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the government's savings bailout drew angry reactions
in Moscow and St. Petersburg on Thursday and Friday, as throngs of
Russians clogged the doorways of six banks that are candidates for
savings transfers: Inkombank, Menatep, Mosbiznesbank, MOST-Bank,
Promstroibank and SBS-Agro.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in response to the outcry, Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said in a television interview Thursday that ``losses
are inevitable'' on the savings accounts but ``if the gap is too
big, we will have to solve this problem as well. We have no other
way out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Chernomyrdin defended a broader plan of pumping
fresh funds into the economy before the government launches a
stricter austerity program. A Russian Central Bank spokesman said
Friday that it considered the terms of the savings transfer to be
fair and that depositors who did not participate would have to fend
for themselves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``That's their problem,'' said the spokesman, Leonid Nitko.
``They have to settle with their banks directly. If they don't want
to transfer, they forfeit their rights immediately to transfer to
Sberbank later.''
</P>
<P>
   Ushakov had a different view of the government's transfer plan.
``How can they say they're treating us fairly?'' he asked. ``I
deposited money to get interest. Now I can't have my money or my
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the anger in the last week has been directed at
the government, the state is hardly the only institution
responsible for the banking mess. Russian banks were central
players in a speculative whirlwind that spread over recent years as
the free market was touted as the newest solution to centuries of
economic hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Many banks, such as Most-Bank, where Ushakov keeps his savings,
took the deposits of Russians completely unfamiliar with uninsured
retail banking and funneled the money into risky securities or used
it to help finance the takeover of sagging industrial companies.
When the securities market crashed and the economy collapsed, those
investments took the banks, and the savings of average Russians,
down with them.
</P>
<P>
   Few Russians seem to hold bank management responsible for their
losses. They are used to identifying the state rather than a
private sector as the author of their woes. And the Central Bank,
which has never been a strict regulator of the banks, said it had
no intention of holding management accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Although the loss of savings only compounds other hardships,
including rapidly escalating prices and dwindling supplies of food,
there is some relief in that most Russians have never put much
faith in banks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Russia's 147 million people keep their savings at home,
or ship money abroad if they can. About 80 percent of the $21
billion that is kept in banks is already tucked away in Sberbank
accounts. Even so, that means that $4.2 billion in Russian savings
is now up for grabs, and those depositors are not happy.
</P>
<P>
   Many were well aware that the banks were troubled, there were
stiff penalties for withdrawing deposits slated to stay in banks
for at least one year _ interest rates of two percent rather than
17 percent, for example. And a year ago, the outlook for banks did
not look as bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Yevgenia Serebryakova, a 61 year-old pensioner, said she was not
aware of how horribly the banking system had crashed until she
returned on August 14 from a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I was shocked, because I had put all of my money in
there,'' she said, gesturing toward her Most-Bank branch. ``I asked
them if they were a strong bank and they said, `Yeah, no
problems.'''
</P>
<P>
   The banking system's meltdown may cause an entire generation of
younger Russians to distrust any bank. Alexander German, a
39-year-old information technology manager for a Western
corporation, said the outlook for his job and his faith in Russia's
banking system is uncertain, although he has hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic but it depends on the political situation and
doesn't depend on the economy anymore,'' he said. ``There could be
a civil war or stabilization. No one knows.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ushakov said he is too old to wait and see if the
banking system can be reformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister always got money on her birthday and put the money
in her sock,'' he said. ``Now she's the richest one of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   So will he be transferring his money to Sberbank?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Into my sock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
