<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR AARON, THERE WAS A DREADED DIFFERENCE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He had 713 homers and Henry Aaron's season was over, but his
worry wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   While chasing Babe Ruth's record of 714 homers, the Atlanta
Braves' slugger had been haunted by racist threats in some of the
hundreds of letters he received daily. Now, with six months to wait
before he could tie and break the record in 1974, he was asked
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go into hibernation now,'' he said. ``I can't hide.
I've said that all I have to do to break Babe Ruth's record is to
stay alive, but I've got to live my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Stay alive. For a healthy slugger who would be 40 years old on
Feb. 5, 1974, that wouldn't seem to be a problem. But he remembered
the anonymous hateful racist letters that threatened his life when
he approached or broke the Babe's record.
</P>
<P>
   Those threatening letters, which were turned over to the FBI,
prompted Aaron to hire a bodyguard, an Atlanta policeman who
carried a loaded .38 revolver.
</P>
<P>
   And in Aaron's home-run chase, those threatening letters created
a dreaded difference from the concerns that confront Mark McGwire
and Sammy Sosa now and that affected Roger Maris in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and Sosa have had to contend only with each other and
the swarming news media, although the Cardinal slugger is also
surrounded by the daily debate over his use of androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Maris had to contend only with Babe Ruth's ghost and the
asterisk that was attached to his eventual total of 61 homers.
</P>
<P>
   But less than six years after Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., had
been assassinated, Aaron had to worry about a faceless somebody out
there who didn't like the idea of a black man breaking a white
man's record.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's countdown had begun after his 712th homer in Houston on
a Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the Braves returned to Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium for
the season's final week, about 15 out-of-town sportswriters
arrived. Before a game Aaron talked to them for about an hour at
his locker in more of a casual conversation than an interrogation.
Finally he grabbed two or three bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me go hit,'' he would say, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   After a game he conducted a formal interview in a separate room
to accommodate another dozen cameras and microphones. But when two
midweek games with the Los Angeles Dodgers attracted only 10,211
and 5,711 customers, he professed not to be insulted by Atlanta's
indifference to him and to history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a job to do,'' he said. ``It doesn't make any
difference to me if there are 750 people watching or 75,000.''
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend, Atlanta awakened. Saturday night 17,836 showed
up and he responded with his 713th homer, off Jerry Reuss, a
Houston Astros left-hander. His ovation lasted so long, he hopped
out of the dugout for a rare curtain call. In Sunday's finale,
before 40,517, he smacked three singles, raising his average to
.301, and when he trotted to left field in the ninth inning, he got
a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ovation was tremendous,'' he said. ``That ovation was
really great.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew now that Atlanta appreciated him, but he knew there were
others out there who didn't. He also knew that he had to ``stay
alive,'' that he had ``to live his life'' until the Braves opened
the 1974 season with three games in Cincinnati before returning to
Atlanta where the Braves hoped to assure that he would tie and
break the record.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Braves' owner, Bill Bartholomay, announced that
Aaron ``will be available as a pinch-hitter for the games in
Cincinnati and for part-time play if required.'' Stirred by news
media protests over the Braves' disregard for the integrity of
their lineup, Commissioner Bowie Kuhn expected Aaron to start at
least two of the three games.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season opener in Cincinnati on April 4, the sixth
anniversary of King's assassination, Aaron asked the Reds to
observe a moment of silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, they found that their schedule wouldn't
permit it,'' he said later. ``They already had the program all set.
But it would've been appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   On his first swing against right-hander Jack Billingham in the
first inning, Aaron hit his 714th homer over the left-center field
wall in Riverfront Stadium, tying the Babe's record. Friday was an
off day, but on Saturday the Braves' manager, Eddie Mathews, didn't
write Aaron's name into the lineup. The Braves lost, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night Kuhn phoned Mathews with a ``direct order'' to
start Aaron in Sunday's game or face ``serious penalties.'' Aaron
struck out twice and grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the possibility of the 715th homer, the Braves' home
opener on Monday night drew 53,775, a record. After walking in his
first at-bat, Aaron, on his first swing against left-hander Al
Downing, smashed a fastball over the left-centerfield fence near
the 385-foot sign. It was caught in the Braves bullpen by pitcher
Tom House.
</P>
<P>
   As the number ``715'' flashed on the scoreboard, fireworks
exploded and two young men raced onto the field to accompany Aaron
around the bases. In the stands, Aaron's bodyguard, as he would say
later, clutched his revolver but didn't draw it.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the Braves, having rushed out of their dugout, were
around home plate as House and the others in the bullpen hurried
there to join in the celebration that would last 11 minutes. From
the Aaron family's special section, his father, Herbert Sr., hopped
onto the field. So did his mother, Estella, who embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew,'' the man who broke Babe Ruth's record would say
later, ``my mother could hug so tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, who finished his career with the Milwaukee Brewers,
would hit a total of 755 homers. And some of those homers were hit
with a dreaded difference from what now hangs over Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa in their chase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
