<HEADER>
A0851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-KING-ART-2TAKE     09-05 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDANIAN KING'S ILLNESS SHIFTS SPOTLIGHT TO PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KERAK, Jordan _ King Hussein has reigned for 45 years, more than
twice as long as Ahmed Thneibat has been alive. But now the king is
undergoing cancer treatment for the second time in six years, and
Thneibat and other Jordanians are apprehensive about what is to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rest assured, I am not over and done with yet,'' said the
king, 62, in a televised address to his people from the Mayo Clinic
in Minnesota in July. But he also left the impression that he is
determined to prepare the country for the prospect that he might
not return, saying in the same speech, ``There is life and there is
an end to life, and that is the way with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Few in Jordan doubt that power would pass to Crown Prince
Hassan, the king's younger brother and closest adviser, who has
been the designated heir to the throne for more than three decades.
He has been regent in the king's absence, which is expected to last
at least until November.
</P>
<P>
   But many Jordanians and foreign observers say they wonder
whether a King Hassan could prove as successful as King Hussein in
guiding Jordan through the kinds of storms that have been a main
feature of the country's recent history.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are worried; they think there could be trouble,'' said
Thneibat, 18, who like all but a minority in this close-knit
country of 4 million has known no king but Hussein, who took power
in 1953 at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   Kerak, a southern city crowned by a Crusader fortress, has long
been a base of support for Jordan's monarchy. But riots broke out
here two years ago over an increase in the price of bread, a
reminder that loyalty has limits. Now the public mood is again
turning volatile, a result of a crippling water crisis, severe
economic problems and rising disillusionment over peace with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Over tea and hummus in a simple cafe adorned with
black-and-white portraits of the country's current and former
kings, Thneibat spoke for many in saying he hoped that a King
Hassan might prove more vigorous than his brother in addressing the
economy. But as he and other Jordanians try to conceive of a new
era, a bigger question may be whether a King Hassan would inherit
his brother's capacity to chart his own course, even when it means
forging ahead of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a minefield, and he doesn't have what it takes to cross
it safely,'' Labib Kamhawi, a prominent human rights campaigner,
said, spelling out one view. ``He doesn't have the charisma the
king had. He doesn't have the broad base of support. And he would
take power at a time when the power of the Hashemite dynasty is at
a very low ebb.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Hassan say he shares Hussein's deep commitment
to Jordan's peace with Israel, though it has borne little fruit and
has little domestic support. That assessment is shared by most
foreign analysts, who say they are confident that the departure of
King Hussein would not cause Jordan to back away from promoting a
broader settlement of Arab-Israeli disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats do say that Hassan, as king, may have less
latitude to promote the peace than his brother, in part because
hostility toward Israel has deepened among Jordanians, and in part
because the crown prince has rarely displayed his brother's
magnanimous style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a great deal of uncertainty about the crown
prince,'' a Western diplomat said. ``He's not his brother. He
doesn't have a common touch, and he gets his information from
briefing papers whereas the king gets his information from the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The prince has declined interview requests during the king's
illness and has played the role of caretaker, not addressing the
doubts about him. But in what may have been an attempt to defuse
some criticism, he did convene an unusual meeting in late August
that included leaders from all of Jordan's political parties,
including Islamists who form the main opposition bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a Jordanian leader with untested domestic
prestige is particularly worrying to Israelis, who are nervous
about Yasser Arafat's pledge to declare an independent Palestinian
state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip next May, when the Middle
East peace plan begun by the Oslo accords is supposed to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   At 51, Prince Hassan is nearly 12 years younger than the king,
who will turn 63 on Nov. 14. Hassan was 6 when Hussein took power
on May 2, 1953, succeeding his grandfather, King Abdullah _ who had
been assassinated in Jerusalem in 1951 as Hussein stood at his side
_ and his father, King Talal, who stepped down in favor of his son
after less than a year in power.
</P>
<P>
   Since his 18th birthday in 1965, Prince Hassan has been the
country's designated No. 2, and he is described in an official
biography as having ``constantly served as King Hussein's closest
political adviser, deputy and confidant, as well as regent in his
absence.''
</P>
<P>
   He earned a degree in Oriental studies from Christ Church
College, Oxford University, and has worked tirelessly within Jordan
to promote scientific study and better integration of the region's
economy. He took part in the negotiations that led to Jordan's
peace agreement with Israel, met with Benjamin Netanyahu even
before Netanyahu was elected Israel's prime minister, and has close
ties to most Arab leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has always seemed in many ways the king's alter ego,
more comfortable in a tie and blue blazer than an Arab headdress,
and more disposed toward academic-style oratory than toward the
emotional eloquence of his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his admirers say that he could not have been expected to
show more color as crown prince; his mission, they say, has been to
stay in the background. ``He's been in the shadow of a very
important historic figure, so it will be prudent to judge him only
after he takes center stage,'' said Mustafa Hamarneh, director of
the Center for Strategic Studies at the University of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But in listing the qualities that have made the king such a
dominant figure, most other analysts give prominence to some that
are not readily transferable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Jordanians would side with the king even if
they think he is wrong,'' said Fahed Fanek, an economist who is one
of Jordan's most popular newspaper columnists. ``Ninety percent of
the population of Jordan was born after the king took power. They
know that he was indispensable in leading the country to safety. So
even if they think he was wrong, they give him the benefit of the
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   After renal cancer in 1992 and a prostate operation in 1997, the
king was found to have lymphoma this summer after nearly a year in
which he had been suffering from inexplicable fevers. A statement
issued by the Mayo Clinic said that the disease is ``highly
treatable with chemotherapy,'' which the king began in July, but it
also mentioned a need for plenty of rest.
</P>
<P>
   So far the king has displayed a vigorous public face, even
flying his own jet to Washington after completing the first and
second of six scheduled rounds of chemotherapy. On the first of
those trips, he and his wife, Queen Noor, dined privately on a
White House balcony with the Clintons, and even now, two months
into what is expected to be at least four months of treatment,
Jordanian officials say that he consults by telephone with Prince
Hassan at least once a day.
</P>
<P>
   It was the king, Jordanian officials say, who assumed the
leading role in orchestrating a change of government in August,
replacing a team tarred by evidence that its mismanagement was to
blame for a water crisis so severe that Saudi Arabia and Syria sent
emergency stocks to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   And even while recuperating at his private home in Washington,
he has met with the new government, led by Fayez Tarawneh, a former
ambassador to the United States and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   In the months ahead, Jordanian officials expect the country's
affairs to be administered along a kind of triangle between Amman,
Washington, and the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn. But people
familiar with the king's health say that his resistance to disease
has been weakened by the chemotherapy and that it is likely to
diminish further as the treatment progresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
