<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-05 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PROTECTING BALL SPECULATORS FROM THEMSELVES  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ On this long and steamy Labor Day Weekend, Major
League Baseball is on a double mission, protecting the world from
two separate rampaging hordes.
</P>
<P>
   The first horde consists of reporters in soggy t-shirts and
baggy shorts, with Mark McGwire quote lust on their faces. The
second horde consists of beer-ingesting fans, eager to grapple in
the violent scrum for the ball that could make all the difference
in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But first, they must live to tell the tale. That is why dozens
of baseball's special agents are poised for duty, just waiting for
the sacred clout.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went into Saturday's game _ in brutal heading-for-97
weather _ seeking the home run that would tie Babe Ruth's old
record of 60. Then he would take dead aim at Roger Maris' record of
61 and then the record-breaking blast.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us were hoping the big basher would hit three on Friday
night and get us out of here, but he let us down, going 0-for-3.
</P>
<P>
   Now it became a vigil, not only for McGwire but also for the
fans who have procured seats in McGwire's home-run alley,
particularly from the left-field foul pole toward right-center.
These fans have a ticket for a wonderful souvenir or a big pay day
_ or personal injury.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the No. 62 home run has been estimated at $100,000,
although one anonymous voice claims he will pay 10 times that. We
shall see. The value of the ball could fluctuate like some
electronics stock in legalized gambling, that is to say, the stock
market. What happens to the 62nd ball if McGwire and Sammy Sosa
both go on to 63, 64, 65 homers?
</P>
<P>
   Fans might ask if they want to risk death or disfigurement for
the 62nd home-run ball, particularly if its value should ``correct
itself,'' as they say on Wall Street. (``Correction'' sounds like
``You just lost a bundle, my man,'' at least to my unsophisticated
ear.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, fans will see dollar signs on the 62nd home-run
ball as it soars into some distant grandstand, but the fans must be
protected from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Security comes in many forms. The baseball home office in New
York and the Cardinals' management have put up metal barricades
around the field during batting practice, to keep the assembled
news media in its place. Baseball distributed 700 credentials for
this weekend, surely a record for a regular-season game between two
teams under .500, and only 300 credentials behind the annual
October infestation of sportswriters for the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The press was lured off guard by promises of a McGwire press
conference before Friday night's game. In docile swarms, we herded
into a sweltering and gloomy cave under the stadium, sat through
four other conferences, only to be told _ oh, by the way _ McGwire
was not coming, after all. This was not Major League Baseball's
fault. The big boy had put one over on us. Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious security note involves the fans in the outfield
seats. This is, rather literally, a matter of life and death. There
are thousands of fans in McGwire territory, many of them children,
all of them in jeopardy of the home-run-ball-from-hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw in some games that a lot of big men who had been
drinking heavily were running after the ball,'' said a baseball
official.
</P>
<P>
   This is considered normal behavior in my part of the world, that
is to say, Noo Yawk, Noo Yawk. But in nice parts of the world like
St. Louis, the average innocent fan may be unprepared for a couple
of hundred alcohol-fueled louts, willing to dive headfirst into the
pile, like linebackers on 'roid rage (or is that redundant?)
</P>
<P>
   To keep the McGwire chase from becoming Lord of the Flies Meets
World's Toughest Man Bar Fight, baseball has organized a tactical
response. The first step is to bar everybody from home-run country
unless they have a ticket. Reporters, with our special 59-62
credentials, are not allowed to infiltrate the hallowed sections.
</P>
<P>
   While fans will be protected from the mobs in foul territory and
other alien sites, it could still come down to father vs. son,
brother vs. brother, truck driver vs. little old lady. It could get
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal management has beefed up the security guards and ushers
in the outfield _ no numbers given _ and Major League Baseball has
imported approximately 20 so-called agents, security people on the
payroll around the country, along with approximately 30 local
special hires, all in plainclothes, but with identifying badges.
</P>
<P>
   As the big home run heads toward the stands, these officers,
guards, ushers and agents will rush to the scene, presumably to
pull bodies off the top of the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is happening underneath the pile is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to allow somebody to take the ball from
somebody else,'' the baseball official said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds nice, in theory. Eventually, they will pry off
enough bodies to uncover the lucky fan. If he or she is still
breathing, the assorted officers, guards, ushers and agents will
escort that fan either to the nearest hospital or to a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Internal Revenue Service agents will also be on hand,
taking down Social Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This being the litigious '90s, one can only assume that a mighty
phalanx of personal-injury lawyers will be screeching into downtown
St. Louis from their suburban palaces.
</P>
<P>
   The safest scenario for all concerned would be for the ultimate
home run to hit the foul-pole or clang off a distant facade and
come bouncing back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe McGwire would hit an inside-the-park home run for No.
62, a 265-pound moose lumbering around the bases in pursuit of
immortality, or possibly heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the opposing fielder does not get to keep the ball
or barter it for a few McGwire mementos. In fact, the ball belongs
to Major League Baseball. The home-run-ball market would then
suffer a major ``correction,'' but at least nobody would die from a
home run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
