<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PREVIEW-GIANTS-NY     09-05 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S KANELL'S TEAM NOW AS GIANTS DEFEND CONFERENCE TITLE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let it be known that Danny Kanell, the 24-year-old son of a
Florida physician, the easy-smiling, Bible-school attending
quarterback who still lives at home with his parents, is not to be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   When he played checkers with his grandmother as a kid, he would
cheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Kanell said of his grandma-distracting,
checker-stealing shenanigans. ``I wanted to win that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Let it be known that Kanell, whom no Giant has ever admitted to
seeing angry, who takes a nap almost every day, whose favorite
movie is ``Hoosiers'' and whose favorite ice cream is rainbow
sherbet, is a trash-talker on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I like that,'' he said. ``I was coming through the
tunnel at halftime during a preseason game last month and a guy on
the other team said: `That one ball you threw near me, I should
have intercepted it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell responded: ``Like you can catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Let it be known that Kanell, who when thrown into his first
professional huddle as an emergency replacement two years ago
entered with a goofy smile and a joke _ ``Why's it so quiet in
here, guys?'' _ and who has never lost consecutive games as a
starter, not in high school, college or the pros, isn't the least
bit worried about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my team,'' he said recently. ``I have all the
confidence in the world in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   What then, does he say to people who want to know if Danny
Kanell _ the grinning, innocent-acting, third-year pro _ is indeed
the answer to the Giants quarterback miseries?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll show you the answer on the field,'' he said. ``That's my
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   And he smiled quickly, in case that sounded too confrontational.
But don't be disarmed. Ask grandma. Kanell isn't to be trusted in
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants will tell you that Kanell, who in relief of the
woebegone Dave Brown last season was 7-2-1 as a starter, never
curses, never berates his linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys who play with him don't hear him scream and holler
but they know when he feels the game is turning, when the level of
intensity has to go up,'' coach Jim Fassel said of Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   Center Lance Scott calls Kanell ``an encourager not a yeller.''
But Scott said: ``I saw him get dinged once. He got to his feet all
fired up. He was saying: `Yeah, let's go.' That's a football
player's response.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. It could just be a Kanell family response.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad taught me a long time ago to never show my emotions,''
Kanell said. ``I think he's right. The people on your team will
believe you're still thinking, still focused, still in control. The
people on the other team won't know what to think. And that's what
you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell, in fact, didn't play football until he was 16. He was a
baseball player first, his father the orthopedic surgeon not
thinking it wise to subject his only son _ even if he was a big,
athletic son _ to the collisions of midget or junior high school
football.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell was good enough in baseball to be drafted by the
Milwaukee Brewers in 1992 and the Yankees in 1995. But as a junior
at Westminster Academy in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., when Kanell led
Westminster to a state title in his first season, he started to
emerge as the quarterback who played baseball, not the baseball
player who was a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like talking about myself,'' Kanell said last week.
``But all my life, I've been someone who leads in sports, whatever
the team. I'm very comfortable in that role.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning kept coming at Florida State, so much so that Kanell
thought seriously for the first time of a career as a pro
quarterback. He was disappointed when he wasn't drafted until the
fourth round in 1996, but realized he'd have to wait to prove
people wrong.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie with the Giants, he made friends with Brown quickly,
staying in the background as he learned the game. During his second
season, it was comical to see the look of mystification on Kanell's
face when reporters would ask him if he was bridging the gap in
ability or skill between himself and Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my job then,'' he said last week, looking back on
the 1997 season. ``But I felt sure I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the sixth game of the 1997 season, Brown left the lineup
with a strained chest muscle. Kanell led the Giants to a 20-17
upset of the Cowboys and then seven more victories and the team's
first National Football Conference East title in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   There was one hiccup along the way. After two subpar games,
Fassel publicly questioned some of Kanell's work habits. The coach
said he wanted Kanell to study more film, to practice with more
concentration, to exhibit a commitment that would give the team
confidence in him, and ultimately in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that to get a question answered about Danny,'' Fassel
said Friday. ``Under that kind of pressure, would he point the
finger at other people? Would he wilt? I wanted that question
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel got his answer when he came to Giants Stadium the next
day _ a day off for players _ and found Kanell alone in the meeting
room watching film.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, who has a 24-year-old son, understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to do right,'' Fassel said. ``Most of us do.
Sometimes you have to be challenged to see it. He knew the right
response when he was challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all questions about Kanell, whose new $9.5 million,
three-year contract makes him the quarterback of the immediate
future, have been answered. There is still talk that his arm isn't
strong enough _ talk that his receivers and Fassel dispute. He
hasn't proved his durability. Last season, Kanell completed only
53.1 percent of his passes, ranking 23d among starters. And he had
an uneven preseason this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not satisfied,'' he said. ``All my goals are set high.
When I'm done playing, I'd like people in this community to think
of me the way people in Denver think of John Elway or people in
south Florida think of Dan Marino. Those guys mean a lot to their
towns. The people there are proud of them. Who knows if that's even
possible here. But I'm shooting high.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Kanell, if asked, would also tell you not to bet against
him. Remember, he cheats. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
