<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF TRUST CREATES A GREAT DIVIDE IN NORTHWEST STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.) (js) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines says that the only issue in the week-old
strike by its 6,200 pilots is pay. The pilots counter that job
security and money are the two big hurdles standing in the way of a
settlement. But the real issue that has divided the two sides _
leading to the longest airline strike since maintenance workers
shut down Eastern Airlines in 1989 _ seems to be trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there are some significant issues between them,''
said Kit Darby, a longtime United Airlines pilot who is also
president of Air Inc., a company that helps place commercial pilots
in jobs, ``they are not significant enough to cause a strike. The
two sides really don't trust each other. And in an atmosphere of
total distrust, you really can't sell anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to break the deadlock, a federal mediator brought
Northwest and representatives of the Airline Pilots Association
together for a meeting Saturday in Chicago to explore whether there
was enough movement on either side to make returning to the
bargaining table worthwhile. Neither side appeared to give any
ground before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots walked out last Saturday after two years of
negotiations with the airline. Even before the strike, the two
sides were trading barbs in a nasty public relations battle that
has since intensified.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict dates back to 1993, when Northwest was near ruin.
Four years earlier, Alfred Checchi and Gary Wilson, former
executives at Marriott Corp., bought the airline in one of the last
leveraged buyouts of the 1980s. They each invested $10 million and
borrowed $3.1 billion more to buy the airline, which was founded in
1926 and had become a venerable Minnesota institution. They were
soon swamped by one of the worst downturns in commercial airline
history, making it difficult for Northwest to pay off its huge
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Minnesota pitched in with some loans in 1991, but
Northwest only averted bankruptcy in 1993 after its three biggest
unions, led by the pilots, agreed to nearly $900 million in wage
concessions in return for stock and three seats on the company's
board.
</P>
<P>
   Both Northwest and the unions say the concessions ushered in a
new era of comity at the carrier. Airline traffic began to pick up
the next year, and Northwest turned around, posting record profits
in 1994 and 1995. The carrier also became top-rated for service and
on-time arrivals, a measure of the high morale of its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1996, the three-year wage concessions ended. The unions
thought they were owed a 3 percent raise, according to a clause in
the 1993 agreement that linked the raise to comparable pay at four
Northwest competitors. But the company disagreed. The dispute went
to arbitration, dragging on for nine months before the unions
finally won. Still, the employees felt betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That broke the partnership bond,'' said Paul Omodt, a
spokesman for the pilots. ``You can track the decline in morale and
service back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hirst, Northwest's chief labor negotiator, said the
clause was meant to ensure that the wages of Northwest workers were
at parity with their peers at other airlines. But the way it was
written only counted increases at rival carriers, not decreases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a legitimate issue,'' he added. ``We weren't playing
games with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirst thinks the breakdown in relations with the pilots began in
early 1996 _ before the raise became an issue _ when a new group of
union leaders took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have been following a strike strategy all
along,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As negotiations dragged on for two years, the boom in the
airline industry only became bigger. Northwest had record years in
1996 and 1997 and earned nearly $600 million last year. At the same
time, pilots at other airlines negotiated substantial raises.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the anger of the pilots and of other unions at
Northwest, who are also negotiating new contracts, have been the
giant profits made by Northwest executives and directors.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Wilson, who is chairman, sold 300,000 shares
worth $15.2 million. John Dasburg, the carrier's chief executive,
cashed in stock options worth $19 million. Checchi, who resigned as
co-chairman of the airline last year to run for governor of
California, and Wilson each still own 11.4 million Northwest
shares, which are worth $302 million at the company's current share
price, which is down 60 percent from its high in March.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots are seeking a 14 percent raise over three years, a
lump-sum payment of $86 million and the elimination of a two-tier
wage scale that pays younger pilots a lower salary until the end of
their fifth year.
</P>
<P>
   The union also wants to limit the number of smaller, regional
jets the company can buy to 66 because it fears that Northwest will
transfer more flying time to the pilots of those planes, who earn
less. Northwest's 6,200 pilots make an average of $120,000 a year,
according to the union, but the company puts the number at
$133,000.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has offered a 9 percent raise over four years, a
lump-sum payment of $57 million, profit sharing and a reduction of
the two-tier wage scale to three years. It would like to be able to
buy 84 regional jets, and then link every subsequent one to the
addition of one narrow-body jet.
</P>
<P>
   The deep resentment of management has helped line up the support
of Northwest's other unions behind the pilots. But it has also tied
the hands of union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the International Association of Machinists,
which represents 27,000 Northwest employees, including maintenance
workers, customer service agents and baggage handlers, reached a
tentative contract with the company. But the rank and file rejected
it in July.
</P>
<P>
   The union has asked the National Mediation Board, which oversees
labor issues in the airline and rail industries, to declare an
impasse, starting a 30-day cooling-off period after which the union
could strike. The board has not yet made a decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company is reluctant to give in to the
pilots because it knows that the other unions will then demand an
equally generous settlement. Hirst said that Northwest would end up
with higher costs than its larger competitors. But that does not
win the sympathy of Joe Scarcella, a Northwest flight attendant for
the last 15 years and member of the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what we deserve and I know what this company makes,''
he said as he demonstrated in support of the pilots in New York on
Friday. ``There is plenty to go around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
