<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BARTER (Novgorod, Russia) _ Russia's currency may be
tumbling. Its stock market may lie in ruins. But Yevgeny Shulman is
used to operating without money. Shulman's factory churns out
valves for nuclear power plants and heavy industry. What his
company receives in return is clear from a stroll around
headquarters: Newly minted cars and trucks are lined up near small
mountains of railroad-car brake pads and raw metal. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKS (Moscow) _ As the ruble continues to crumble and
increasing numbers of insolvent banks are brought under state
control, untold numbers of Russians are left with the unenviable
choice of leaving their savings in barren banks or allowing the
accounts to be transferred to a state-owned bank at a fraction of
their value. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-KIM (Tokyo) _ North Korea on Saturday became the first
Communist country to transfer government power within a family
dynasty, as it anointed Marshal Kim Jong Il as its ``Great Leader''
and head of an expanded National Defense Commission. By Nicholas D.
Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-JAPAN-SPLIT (San Francisco) _ The economic policy leaders
of the world's two largest economies, the United States and Japan,
spent hours here Friday night talking about the heightened risk of
global recession and a further spread of the turmoil that has
engulfed Asia, Russia and now Latin America. But they left Saturday
morning with no new plans, and an uneasy sense that Japan and the
United States remain on different wavelengths about how quickly
countries must act. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Limerick, Ireland) _ It has been a question from
the start of President Clinton's five-day trip to Russia, Ireland
and Northern Ireland this week: will his domestic troubles affect
his ability to function abroad as the nation's leader? By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-BINLADEN (Washington) _ A look at U.S. thinking on Osama
Bin Laden, who has been linked to a terror campaign against the
United States. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-CHINESE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Though they make up
little more than 3 percent of Indonesia's population of more than
200 million, ethnic Chinese are the nation's trading class, from
shopkeepers to billionaire managers of multinational conglomerates,
and they control as much as 70 percent of the Indonesia's private
economy. They are also often the target of scapegoatism for the
nation's ills. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-KING (Kerak, Jordan) _ King Hussein has reigned for 45
years, more than twice as long as Ahmed Thneibat has been alive.
But now the king is undergoing cancer treatment for the second time
in six years, and Thneibat and other Jordanians are apprehensive
about what is to come. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-KOHL-HEIR (Bonn, Germany) _ In dire straits, a political
party taps its most popular figure to lead the campaign to cling to
power. Right? Wrong, at least in Germany. As this country heads for
a national election on Sept. 27 that will chart its course into the
21st century, the focus for many people is on whether Chancellor
Helmut Kohl will survive. Behind him, though, there is a figure far
less known outside Germany, but just as familiar to Germans,
Wolfgang Schaeuble. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM (Chicago) _ From Hartford, Conn., and
Newark, N.J., to Denver and San Francisco, the federal government
is working with cities to clear the very slums it helped create:
public housing projects crippled by flawed policies and
mismanagement. Nowhere is the challenge greater than at Chicago's
Robert Taylor Homes, the nation's largest housing project, much of
which is ``considered the worst slum area in the United States,''
according to its landlord, the Chicago Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: The story has moved in two forms. The full-length version
_ 4,440 words as published in The New York Times, and an abridged
version of 1,900 words, slugged ABR-PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM. Photos
to illustrate are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STATEHOUSE-CAMPAIGNS (Raleigh, N.C.) _ With partisan control of
legislatures at risk in a remarkable number of states, and with
states inheriting vast new responsibilities from Washington, the
once-quaint business of legislative politics has become intensely
competitive, sophisticated and costly. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-RDP (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ As busloads of grieving
relatives made their way onto the rocky spit of land closest to the
wreckage of Swissair Flight 111, investigators said Saturhat they
had made little progress in learning what caused the plane to crash
into the sea on Wednesday night minutes after its pilot reported
smoke in the cockpit. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ANTITERROR-U.S. _ At a time of growing fear of terrorism within
America's borders, senior state and local officials say the federal
government still has no coherent system for deterring or responding
to it. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-STRIKE _ Northwest Airlines says that the only issue
in the week-old strike by its 6,200 pilots is pay. The pilots
counter that job security as well as money are the two big hurdles
standing in the way of a settlement. But the real issue that has
divided the two sides _ leading to the longest airline strike since
maintenance workers shut down Eastern Airlines in 1989 _ seems to
be trust. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CUBA-EXCHANGE (Miami Beach) _ For Carlos Varela, who sings
of present-day Cuba, warts and all, playing Miami meant the first
few baby steps into a market virtually closed to him because he
lives in Cuba. In cultural exchanges allowed in recent years under
the American economic embargo of the island, Cuba-based artists
have toured all over the United States, but they have generally
skipped Miami, where many Cuban-Americans shun them as envoys of
the Cuban government and take offense at their presence in exile
territory. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-DEPT (Los Angeles) _ A look at the LAPD in light of
a recent corruption case.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On landing your very own president. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
