<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-600(2TA     09-05 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES ARRIVE AT CRASH SITE AS SALVAGE EFFORTS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-0136 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ As busloads of grieving relatives made
their way onto the rocky spit of land closest to the wreckage of
Swissair Flight 111, investigators said Saturday that they had made
little progress in learning what caused the plane to crash into the
sea on Wednesday night minutes after its pilot reported smoke in
the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The first bus of relatives drove up the narrow, winding road to
Peggy's Cove, a fishing village and tourist attraction about 20
miles southwest of here, at 8:45 a.m. Around 20 people filed off
the bus, some holding hands, some arm-in-arm, and were met in
olive-drab tents by clergy members, Red Cross officials and other
counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Then they made their way down the jetty, past the white
lighthouse with its red top, and laid wreaths at the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to get down to the rocks, and they want to say their
last words at the rocks quietly and peacefully,'' said Murielle
Provost, who is directing the Red Cross operation.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m., more than 100 relatives had walked down the narrow
pathway past the lighthouse and toward the sea, nearly all of them
carrying bouquets of roses and carnations tethered to pieces of
wood to help them float to sea in memory of the crash's 229
victims. Some carried teddy bears. One woman dabbed her eyes
beneath her sunglasses. They were followed by Red Cross workers
carrying boxes of tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making the sad pilgrimage was Tim Larson, 39, from
East Hartford, Conn., whose wife's uncle, Victor Rizza, 58, died in
the crash with his son Antonino, 15. ``This is such a pretty
town,'' he said, looking off at the rocky jetties, the lighthouse
and the churning sea as his voice cracked. ``You read about this
stuff and you see it, and it's never supposed to happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The fog, rain, and high seas that hampered the early search and
salvage efforts lifted Saturday, and Canadian officials said that
although a brisk north wind was still blowing, they were hopeful
that search teams would be able to make progress as they scoured
the seas for more victims and clues.
</P>
<P>
   But, much to the frustration of investigators, the most
important pieces of evidence that would help them piece together
the last moments of the flight _ the so-called black boxes
containing the flight data recorder and the cockpit voice recorder
_ have yet to be found.
</P>
<P>
   The boxes are equipped with audio beacons, or ``pingers,'' that
emit signals for the purpose of helping searchers find them, but no
trace of them has been picked up by sonar or by a Canadian
submarine that combed the area on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, remote-controlled submersibles equipped with video
cameras, which are a kind of underwater robot, were flown here from
British Columbia. Salvagers sent the submersibles, known as Flying
Fish, to the ocean floor, about 120 feet below the surface, in
several spots where sonar detected what might be pieces of the
wrecked airplane. As the weather improved, the first divers went
into the water Saturday morning shortly after 8 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   The searchers continued to scan the ocean floor with sonar,
comparing the results with existing charts and looking for any
anomalies. But no large pieces of wreckage have been identified,
Lt. Cmdr. Michael Considine of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police
said. ``To date, we have not located any large pieces of
fuselage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The search-and-salvage mission, involving a flotilla of more
than 40 ships and boats and 1,000 workers, was dubbed Operation
Persistence by the rescuers. Officials set up a Web site for
information about the search:
www.marlant.hlfx.dnd.ca/marlant/swissair.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Canadian Transportation Safety Board
pored over the technological evidence that was left behind,
studying the transcripts of tape-recorded conversations between the
pilot and the control tower and scrutinizing radar tapes to chart
the plane's final, erratic movements before it went down into the
ocean, about five miles off the shore of Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of the Preserver, a Canadian supply ship, directed
smaller boats as they picked up debris from a crash site that was
growing ever wider from wind and tides.
</P>
<P>
   Cpl. Frank Skidmore of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said
that the search area had grown to a 70-square-mile swath of ocean,
and that the Canadian authorities have placed the entire area off
limits to boats and planes for nearly 50 miles of coastline, from
Mahone Bay to the mouth of Halifax Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   On land, 250 Canadian soldiers and 300 volunteers fanned out to
scour the rocky coastline to gather the debris and wreckage
buffeted ashore by the tides.
</P>
<P>
   They preserved everything: the blue sleeping mask with the
Swissair logo, a turtleneck sweater found peeping out from beneath
the sand and twisted pieces of metal and foam that were difficult
to place. It all went into clear plastic evidence bags.
</P>
<P>
   On board the Preserver, all the human remains that were
recovered were carefully labeled as to where they were found and
then flown off the ship by Sea King helicopters and taken to a
makeshift morgue in an airplane hangar at a nearby air base, where
a team of pathologists began the long and painstaking task of
trying to identify them through dental records, X-rays and DNA
samples.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Saturday that the first victim had been
identified. Dr. John Butt, the chief medical examiner of Nova
Scotia, said Friday that in addition to trying to identify the
victims, his team would see whether the bodies yielded clues to
what happened in the last minutes before the crash. Butt said that
investigators have asked the pathologist to conduct toxicology
tests, to try to determine whether the victims inhaled smoke before
they died.
</P>
<P>
   Butt said that a significant number of bags containing human
remains had been brought ashore in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of operation that Nova Scotia has come to be
familiar with in the four centuries since the first shipwreck was
reported off the treacherous coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous instance was in 1911 when the Titanic went down
700 miles east of here. The Cunard Liner Carpathia took the
survivors to New York; the dead were brought here.
</P>
<P>
   Don Flynn, whose family has run Cruikshank's Halifax Funeral
Home here for generations, said that he was called the night of the
crash and told to begin making preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be our biggest job since my grandfather handled the
Halifax explosion,'' he said, referring to the worst disaster in
Halifax history, when a munitions ship exploded in Halifax harbor
in 1917, killing more than 1,700 and leveling whole neighborhoods
here.
</P>
<P>
   Out at Peggy's Cove, Skidmore said that it was difficult to
watch the family members grieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're devastated by the tragedy,'' he said. ``Though they
don't expect to find loved ones alive, they're hopeful that we will
at least find identifiable remains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
