<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-CUBA-CULTURE-ART-     09-05 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CUBA-CULTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN PERFORMERS GETTING KINDER RECEPTION IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Carlos Varela is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ At a recent nightclub concert before a
word-of-mouth audience of fewer than 200 people, the Cuban
singer-songwriter Carlos Varela surveyed the room from the stage
and said, ``This looks like a concert in Havana.''
</P>
<P>
   But between the standing ovations, the shouted requests for
songs and the tears, it was obvious on which side of the Florida
Straits he found himself. ``I came in '80!'' one woman yelled. ``I
came in '98!'' a man piped in. ``I was born here!'' another man
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Varela, who sings of present-day Cuba, warts and all,
playing Miami meant the first few baby steps into a market
virtually closed to him because he lives in Cuba. In cultural
exchanges allowed in recent years under the American economic
embargo of the island, Cuba-based artists have toured all over the
United States, but they have generally skipped Miami, where many
Cuban-Americans shun them as envoys of the Cuban government and
take offense at their presence in exile territory.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, performers from Cuba took Miami by storm. Varela
put on his show here before leaving last week for appearances in
Chicago and Madison, Wis., while a powerhouse group of Cuban
musicians, including the virtuoso pianist Chucho Valdes and his
group Irakere, headlined the annual music industry conference known
as Midem Latin America and Caribbean Music Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're giving me the happiest moment of my life,'' Francisco
Repilado, a 91-year-old traditional guitarist who is featured on
the 1998 Grammy-winning album ``Buena Vista Social Club'' and who
is better-known as Compay Segundo, told his audience at the
conference. ``I've traveled throughout Europe: London, Madrid,
Switzerland, Germany. And why not here?''
</P>
<P>
   Many outside South Florida may ask the same question, wondering
how people who promote the cause of democracy in Cuba can turn
around and censor artists from the island. Only two years ago,
protesters hurled insults and spat at concertgoers attending a show
by a Cuban jazz pianist, Gonzalo Rubalcaba, who did not even live
on the island but had not publicly repudiated its government.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, a Little Havana restaurant planning to
showcase a Cuban actress-singer, Rosita Fornes, was firebombed. And
last year, Midem failed in its effort to showcase Cuban artists
because of an ordinance that prohibits Miami-Dade County from doing
business with Cuba or anyone who does business with Cuba. (This
year, the problem was solved when the fund raising to coordinate
the music conference locally became strictly a private effort.)
</P>
<P>
   A more auspicious climate has greeted Cuban performers this
year. Isaac Delgado, a salsa singer; Vocal Sampling, an a cappella
group; Gema 4, another a cappella group; the band La Charanga
Habanera and Varela, who first performed here last March, have
played here at different times with no major incidents. Longtime
residents speculate that a confluence of factors may be at work,
including the impact of the death last November of Jorge Mas
Canosa, the most powerful exile leader advocating a hard line
toward Cuba, and Pope John Paul II's call for reconciliation in his
visit to Cuba in January.
</P>
<P>
   But a look at the audiences that come to see the Cubans offers
the best explanation: Generally black Cuban-Americans turn out for
Delgado; Cuban, Latin American and young people for Varela; a mixed
bag of music lovers for Valdes. It is a sample of changing
demographics, and generations, in Hispanic Miami that by now
includes the tens of thousands of Cubans who migrated over the last
two decades and had grown up with much of the music that has been
banned in this corner of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know the artists, they know the songs, they know the
words,'' said Maria Romeu, whose marketing company, Luna Media, has
promoted and co-produced several of the concerts. ``Miami has a new
portion of the population that hears that music and it is
infectious.''
</P>
<P>
   But new and old Miami still coexist, and the appearance of an
artist from Cuba sets off contrasting raw emotions. On the evening
of Compay Segundo's performance at the Miami Beach Convention
Center last week, a group of about 400 demonstrators waved little
Cuban flags, chanted ``Liberty! Liberty!'' and held up signs that
read: ``Castro's rats'' and ``Stop using Uncle Sam's money to
promote your Cuban hell.'' The group included former political
prisoners in Cuba, Cuban-American musicians and older exiles for
whom culture equates with politics if Fidel Castro's government is
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This intransigence of ours is a just intransigence,'' said
Miriam Sifontes, 51, a medical clinic owner. ``Castro is an
assassin.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention hall, meanwhile, the scene was almost
reverential. Interspersed among Midem's international delegates
were Cuban-Americans, including one man who sat with a cellular
phone perched on his shoulder. He said his grandfather in New York
was listening.
</P>
<P>
   Varela's concert at Starfish nightclub here three nights later
was even more jarring. Some women cried openly during some songs,
and two men left the room at one point, overcome by emotion.
Varela, 35, who played accompanied only by acoustic guitar, is
often described by music critics as the voice of Cuba's disgruntled
youth, a writer in the tradition of Bob Dylan and Bruce Springsteen
who writes verses like ``Freedom only exists when it belongs to no
one'' and ``What are windmills for, if there are no Quixotes
left?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets as real as anyone gets to describe Cuba,'' said Carlos
Betancourt, a 32-year-old Cuban-American painter who visited Cuba
for the first time this year out of curiosity. ``It was a very sad
concert and that's my definition of Cuba: a very sad country.''
</P>
<P>
   Varela's inspiration is not criticism, however, but ``the
Cuban's illusion of transforming things,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although he tours internationally and plays concert halls in
Havana, Cuba has banned some of his music from the radio. So has
Miami, as it does with other Cuba-based artists.
</P>
<P>
   Varela said he had received nothing but love and respect in
Miami and that his shows here had been unusually intense because
the public ``wants to condense all their longings in a two-hour
concert.'' But noting the commercial radio ban of his music, and
the fact that he and other Cuban performers so far have mostly
played concerts for select audiences or in small venues with little
advance publicity, Varela said he hoped for the day he could ``fill
stadiums and sell records.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make no mistake,'' said Varela, always the realist, ``I
have not sung in Miami.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
