<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REVIVING RANGERS
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez hit 10 home runs in the Texas Rangers' first 47
games. The Rangers then played 78 games without their catcher
hitting his 11th home run. But once Rodriguez found the range
again, he slugged six home runs in the space of 14 Texas games.
</P>
<P>
   And how about Rodriguez's prolific run-producing teammate? Juan
Gonzalez has batted eight times in his career against Bryce Florie
of Detroit and has eight hits, none of them cheap. He has ripped
five doubles, a triple and two home runs, giving him a 2.625
slugging percentage for his troubles. Gonzalez battered Florie for
half of those hits in one game last week and drove in seven runs
against him.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO'S SLUGGERS
</P>
<P>
   Three days apart, the two Chicago teams had their home run
records broken. There was just a little difference in the number of
years the records had lasted.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday Albert Belle hit his 42d home run, surpassing the
41 Frank Thomas hit for the White Sox in 1993. Last Friday Sammy
Sosa socked his 57th, slipping past Hack Wilson, who hit 56 for the
Cubs in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   POWER DOESN'T EQUAL VICTORY
</P>
<P>
   In this season of the celebration of the home run, look no
further than the Seattle Mariners to see how overrated home runs
are. The Mariners lead the major leagues in home runs with 207 but
haven't had a winning record since May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Readily acknowledging the need for a more diversified offense,
Manager Lou Piniella said: ``I've talked about that for a couple
years. It's great to have power, but when the power isn't there,
you have to be able to manufacture. And in that area we've
struggled. We have to be able to win games without hitting the ball
out of the ball park. For a couple of years we outslugged people
and hid our deficiencies, but this year we haven't been able to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners discovered, too, that their minor league system is
in need of help before it can provide aid.
</P>
<P>
   The season, Piniella said, ``shows you the importance of a farm
system that's ready to produce,'' adding: ``Ours has been dry. We
didn't have anywhere to go unless we wanted to throw money at the
problem and we haven't thrown any at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the season been his most disappointing as a manager?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting better,'' he said. ``We felt when the season
started that we would be competitive. We came off of a 90-win
season, the first in franchise history. We had basically the same
people back. So when you look at it in that respect, to be under
.500 and out of the race, yes, it's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with all of the other elements of a poor season was the
Randy Johnson mess. The Mariners announced last November they would
not sign their No.1 pitcher to a contract extension, and he asked
to be traded, but they did not trade him. He was a festering sore
at the heart of the team until he was traded July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put everything in perspective,'' Piniella said, ``if
it was going to come to that, it should've been done early on, last
winter. We could've gotten some players back and had money to go
out in the free-agent market and fill in other holes. We didn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was a positive for us,'' he continued.
``That started in the spring and basically stayed with us the whole
summer. It drains you somewhat. When you have somebody that's not
happy, you're better off moving that individual than trying to make
it work. I think this organization has learned that lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   BLAME IT ON SELIG?
</P>
<P>
   When the owners elected Bud Selig commissioner July 9, his
Milwaukee Brewers had a winning record, 43-42, and were only nine
games out of first. Since Selig's election, for which he had to
place his ownership in the team in a trust and relinquish operation
of the club to his daughter, Wendy Selig-Prieb, the Brewers have
staggered to a 23-33 record and have plummeted 22 games from the
top.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes indication that the team's general manager is in inner
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after saying that Phil Garner would return as
manager next season even if the Brewers didn't fix themselves, Sal
Bando apparently thinks he might have spoken too soon. In the
interim, the Brewers lost three consecutive games to the expansion
Arizona Diamondbacks _ right in Selig's warm-weather backyard _ and
Bando didn't like the way they looked doing it.
</P>
<P>
   His latest pronouncement: He will re-evaluate Garner's status
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA'S COMEBACK
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of expansion teams, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
catapulted well ahead of the Diamondbacks in the early weeks of the
season, winning 16 of their first 37 games while their fellow
neophytes won 8 of their first 39, a difference of 9 games in the
standings. Those records took the new teams to May 14. As recently
as the end of July, the Devil Rays held a four-and-a-half-game
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, in the midst of a seven-game winning streak that
they took into their game Saturday. the Diamondbacks edged in front
of the Devil Rays for the first time in the teams' first season, by
a percentage point. They remain in front. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
