<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-05 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MIXED VIEWS ON WHETHER CLINTON IS LOSING CLOUT ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ It has been a question from the start of
President Clinton's five-day trip to Russia, Ireland and Northern
Ireland last week: Will his domestic troubles affect his ability to
function abroad as the United States' leader?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, from the president's aides, has been a resounding
and unanimous no.
</P>
<P>
   But others are not so certain, and a strong piece of evidence
came from Moscow on Friday, when Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin announced measures to try to pull Russia out of its
economic tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a day after Clinton left Moscow, where he delivered a
series of stern lectures on fiscal and monetary responsibility,
Chernomyrdin proposed an ``economic dictatorship'' that would
include a huge infusion of new rubles to prop up failing banks,
almost certainly a prescription for a burst of inflation and a step
that Clinton specifically warned against.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Chernomyrdin is in a tough battle for confirmation
and Russia's internal politics are little influenced by outside
forces. But it was clear that Russia's leaders either were not
listening to Clinton's lectures or did not fear the effects of
defying him.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence came on the front pages of American newspapers
all week, which were dominated by stories not of Clinton's
diplomacy but of the slow progress of his penitence over his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took questions twice from reporters, during a news
conference Wednesday with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and a
Friday meeting with Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   Both appearances were overshadowed by questions about Ms.
Lewinsky, and the coverage in the United States focused almost
exclusively on the president's calibrated regrets over the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say it is impossible to separate a president's domestic
fortunes from his prestige abroad. Although Clinton remains popular
overseas _ particularly in Ireland, where he is given credit for
supporting efforts that led to the Northern Ireland peace accord
this year _ leaders recognize that even without the Lewinsky
scandal, Clinton is a lame duck with a little more than two years
remaining in his term, if he completes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to be damaged goods at home and to be
effective abroad,'' said Dmitri Simes, director of the Nixon Center
research organization in Washington and a longtime foreign-policy
aide to former President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Simes said that many Russians have written Clinton off, not only
because he is crippled by domestic difficulties but also because
the Russian people perceive him as being too close to Yeltsin, who
is widely reviled by his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton today lacks the moral authority to be ``a lasting
partner for the Russians, particularly during the post-Yeltsin
era,'' Simes asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides insisted that the president was not hampered in
his ability to do his job by the low cloud of scandal hanging over
him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's press secretary, Mike McCurry, said Friday that
Clinton operated in ``parallel universes'' _ battling scandal at
home while conducting high policy abroad _ and declared that the
two did not intersect.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton's authority had been diminished by the
Lewinsky matter, McCurry replied: ``It clearly has not been, and I
think the president takes some satisfaction in that. He dealt with
world leaders on this trip and is confident that he continues to do
good work in the interest of the American people as he fulfills his
constitutional responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a less guarded moment, McCurry conceded that the Lewinsky
matter had ``detracted'' from the main missions of the trip _
encouraging Russian leaders to stick to the course of economic
reform and urging Catholics and Protestants in Northern Ireland to
press ahead on the road to reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry and other aides blamed the press for an unhealthy
obsession with the Lewinsky matter and for drowning out the
president's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so circular,'' said one of Clinton's top foreign
policy aides, his voice tinged with bitterness. ``You ask the
questions and then you write that Clinton was forced once again to
deal with Lewinsky. It hasn't come up in one meeting that we've had
on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Lewinsky matter did not arise in meetings, neither
did foreign leaders rally to the president's defense, at least not
in public. McCurry assured reporters that Clinton had received many
messages of encouragement from leaders around the world, but
declined to name any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Yeltsin nor Ahern spoke on the president's behalf as he
took questions about the scandal. Nor did British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, with whom Clinton spent the day in Northern Ireland on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Blair offered Clinton private solace and public support during a
visit to Washington last January, shortly after the president's
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was first revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The trip has taken Clinton from meetings in a Moscow gripped by
political and economic crisis to a meeting with families of the
victims of the car bomb in Omagh, Northern Ireland, to a festive
rally in the streets of Limerick on Saturday morning. Clinton's
mood has shifted as dramatically as the settings: somber in Moscow,
mournful in Omagh, upbeat in Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was hailed as a peacemaker in his appearances in
Northern Ireland and Ireland during the last three days, and he
clearly reveled in the warmth of his reception here.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere his message to the Irish was the same: Though terror
will surely return, the determination to have peace will overcome
those who seek to destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over a sea of waving U.S. and Irish flags among the
crowd packed onto O'Connell Street in downtown Limerick on Saturday
morning, Clinton said, ``As we mourn the losses in Omagh and the
three little boys who were killed and taken from their parents'
arms, remember there will still be efforts by the enemies of peace
to break your will, to get you to turn back, to get you to lose
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't do it,'' the president implored the enthusiastic throng
of thousands. ``Don't do it. This is you at your best. Do not let
them break your will.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to spend the afternoon pursuing the real reason he
came to southwest Ireland on Saturday, playing golf at the historic
course at Ballybunion before returning to Washington on Saturday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
