<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-DELL-0906-COX     09-05 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DELL-0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DELL ANNOUNCES $90 MILLION EXPANSION IN IRELAND
 &HT;    With IRELAND-CLINTON-0906.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ Prompted by its stunning success in Europe,
Dell Computer Corp. plans to open a third manufacturing plant in
Ireland, a $90 million development expected to create 1,700 jobs,
the company said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement timed to coincide with President Clinton's
visit here, Jan Gesmar-Larsen, Dell's president for Europe, the
Middle East and Africa, said the expansion would make the company
the largest information technology employer in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction of the third manufacturing facility will take
the scale of Dell's operations in Ireland to a new level,''
Gesmar-Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a rally in the city center, Clinton personally
expressed his gratitude to the Austin, Texas-based company for its
contribution to the Irish economy, which he has described as ``the
Celtic tiger.'' During his three-day visit here, the president has
said that economic development in the Irish Republic has been key
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud that an American company, Dell Computers, has
been able to play such a strong role in this progress,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell already employs more than 1,500 workers here and expects to
raise that total to more than 3,000 over the next year. The new
plant is expected to open in late 1999, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company decided to expand in Limerick because of the quality
of the Irish workforce, Gesmar-Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Dell purchased a 340,000-square-foot manufacturing
site nearby. The company opened its first plant in 1990, and a
second manufacturing site has been operational since April. The
company also has a sales and support call center in suburban
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Dell founder Michael Dell recently called Ireland ``the backbone
of Dell's infrastructure in Europe'' -- which provides nearly 25
percent of Dell's annual revenues, and is crucial to its ambitions
to become the world's No. 1 computer maker.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the decision to make the expansion was supported by
increased demand from business customers in Europe, the Middle East
and Africa, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of 1998. the Dell unit here reported a
year-on-year growth of 87 percent -- a rate that outpaced the rest
of the European market by almost five times. Dell is the No. 2
personal computer company in Europe in terms of revenue and units
shipped. The firm is the No. 1 personal computer company in
Ireland, with a 26 percent share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, Dell said it would contribute 100 computers to
the community of Omagh, Northern Ireland, where a car bomb
detonated on a busy market street last month killed 29 people and
injured 500 more. The company said it would work with local
authorities to distribute the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-DELL-0906-COX     09-05 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DELL-0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DELL ANNOUNCES $90 MILLION EXPANSION IN IRELAND
 &HT;    With IRELAND-CLINTON-0906.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
