<P>
   In January, Dell purchased a 340,000-square-foot manufacturing
site nearby. The company opened its first plant in 1990, and a
second manufacturing site has been operational since April. The
company also has a sales and support call center in suburban
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Dell founder Michael Dell recently called Ireland ``the backbone
of Dell's infrastructure in Europe'' -- which provides nearly 25
percent of Dell's annual revenues, and is crucial to its ambitions
to become the world's No. 1 computer maker.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the decision to make the expansion was supported by
increased demand from business customers in Europe, the Middle East
and Africa, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of 1998. the Dell unit here reported a
year-on-year growth of 87 percent -- a rate that outpaced the rest
of the European market by almost five times. Dell is the No. 2
personal computer company in Europe in terms of revenue and units
shipped. The firm is the No. 1 personal computer company in
Ireland, with a 26 percent share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, Dell said it would contribute 100 computers to
the community of Omagh, Northern Ireland, where a car bomb
detonated on a busy market street last month killed 29 people and
injured 500 more. The company said it would work with local
authorities to distribute the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
