<HEADER>
A0927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-05 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S PAULA JONES, GOP FUND-RAISER 
DEMOCRATS' WORRY: GREEN, GREEN, GONE 
CALIFORNIA PONDERS QUESTION OF THE MONTH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Steve Arnold, a Republican from High Point, N.C., saw
it, his campaign to win another term on the Guilford County Board
of Commissioners needed a lift.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit him.
</P>
<P>
   He would ask Paula Jones to be the featured attraction at an
October fund-raiser. What Republican fat cat, or thin cat, could
resist a chance to chat up President Clinton's accuser?
</P>
<P>
   ``Paula Jones,'' Arnold said the other day, ``is an
all-American, middle-class wife and mother whose only crime was to
be seen and approached by Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones makes few, if any, political appearances, although to
hear Clinton's defenders tell it, her whole life in recent years
has been one big political appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But in any event, when Arnold, the Republican nominee for
lieutenant governor of North Carolina in 1996, proffered an
invitation, she accepted _ for a fee (which was not made public),
travel expenses and an all-expenses-paid vacation in the North
Carolina mountains for her, her husband, Steve, and their two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can use the money and the break, because neither Paula
nor Steve has a job right now,'' said Nisha Mohammed of the
Rutherford Institute, the conservative advocacy group in
Charlottesville, Va., that has helped Mrs. Jones with her sexual
harassment suit against the president and manages her public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   How does all this strike Arnold's Democratic opponent, Mary Anne
Busch?
</P>
<P>
   She says she'll stick with local issues and local money-raisers
and leave the political hoopla to Arnold and Mrs. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats' Worry: Green, Green, Gone
</P>
<P>
   With their appeal to hard-core environmentalists,
counterculturists and other hard-left voters, Green Party
candidates sometimes find themselves in position to swing elections
or otherwise make political mischief. So while they seldom win
office, they more than once have kept others from winning, or have
come close to keeping others from winning _ mainly Democrats who
strayed too far to the right to hold the Green vote.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Bob Anderson, the Green candidate for Congress in
New Mexico's 1st District, got a call the other night from House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, who had a favor to ask.
</P>
<P>
   But first some political history.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st is one of the Republican-held districts that Democrats
have been closely eyeing this year as a prime takeover target.
Covering mainly the city of Albuquerque, it has a good number of
Democratic voters, and the incumbent representative, Heather
Wilson, has been in office only since June, when she narrowly won a
special election.
</P>
<P>
   Her Democratic opponent in June, as in this fall's race, was
state Sen. Phil Maloof. He would have won the June contest, many
political pros say, had not a third-party candidate siphoned off a
large number of Democratic votes, perhaps 10 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   That candidate: Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt asked Anderson to consider withdrawing from the fall
race, lest the political scenario of the June race be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, an instructor at the University of New Mexico,
refused. ``We're committed,'' he told Gephardt, adding that a few
days earlier he had also turned down a direct appeal from Maloof to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Why, the minority leader wanted to know?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson explained that the ``fundamental'' reason he was
running was that Maloof and the Democratic Party had drifted ``too
far to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt countered that the Greens would get far more out of a
district and a House controlled by Democrats than a district and a
House controlled by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was still not moved.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens, he told Gephardt, were ``a movement to empower
people'' and return ``some sanity'' to politics.
</P>
<P>
   California Ponders Question of the Month
</P>
<P>
   If Gov. Pete Wilson signs a bill sent to him by the California
Legislature, the 2000 presidential primary in the nation's most
populous state will be held on March 7 instead of in early June, as
in most years past. And if that happens, March 7, 2000, could turn
out to be one dilly of a day in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   By advancing its primary date, California, with its
biggest-of-all trove of convention delegates, almost certainly
could add to its influence in the candidate-picking process. That
influence has waned in recent years because the state, with one
exception, has stuck with its June voting date while many other
states have hastened to hold their primaries in early March _ the
result being that nominees are now often known well before June and
all remaining primaries are moot.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, candidates and voters are complaining that they
feel rushed and shortchanged by the primary front-loading. Some
election officials and national party leaders agree and are pushing
for a series of spread-out regional Super Tuesday primaries, to go
into effect after the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, as California demonstrates, the
front-loading rush continues.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says he has some doubts about advancing the primary date,
because not only would California then be contributing to the rush
but, worse, such a move might set off a wild, willy-nilly stampede
to hold early regional primaries in 2000, with most regions going
for the March 7 date, lest their influence be marginalized.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of uncoordinated, every-region-for-itself scramble
conceivably could see both presidential nominees chosen in a single
day _ history in the making, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all his concerns about the wisdom of an early
California primary, Wilson might be tempted to sign the bill before
him. He's thinking about running again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There is another political catch in all of this.
</P>
<P>
   California has a new law that says all primaries are to be
``open,'' meaning Republicans can vote for Democrats, Democrats for
independents, and so forth. But under national party rules, only
``closed'' primaries, in which Democrats vote for Democrats, etc.,
may be used to choose presidential delegates.
</P>
<P>
   So whatever the date of the next California primary, the state
has a problem. It must return to its old closed system of electing
delegates or it risks having them not seated.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal to do that will be on the fall ballot. But early
polls indicate that the measure's proponents will have to work
extra hard to get it passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
