<HEADLINE>
HOMETOWN APPLAUDS SENATOR'S SCOLDING OF CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman's hometown reacted with relief
to his extraordinary rebuke of President Clinton on the floor of
the Senate on Thursday, with both Democrats and Republicans saying
that he spoke for them, and that it was about time someone did.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Charleston, 53, a bus driver for Connecticut Transit who
voted for Clinton twice, said he watched the speech live on CNN,
flipped the channels to catch clips Friday morning, then listened
to talk shows discuss it as he drove to the start of his route.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that a Democrat gave that speech, because
everybody's going to try to use what Clinton did to hold the
Democrats down,'' Charleston said. ``I was wondering when Lieberman
was going to speak up. He spoke for Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   From a working-class diner to the gabled grandeur of Yale
University, most people interviewed here Friday said that for all
the talk about Clinton's admission of an inappropriate relationship
with Monica Lewinsky, Lieberman's measured condemnation of the
president was about the most sensible thing they had heard on the
topic. In his 24-minute speech, Lieberman, a centrist Democrat and
longtime ally of the president, called Clinton's actions
``disgraceful,'' ``immoral,'' and `` harmful, for it sends a
message of what is acceptable behavior to the larger American
family _ particularly to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton said he ``basically'' agreed with Lieberman
and said he was ``very sorry'' about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Several longtime Connecticut residents said Lieberman's speech
reminded them of the repudiation of President Richard Nixon by
another senator from Connecticut, Lowell Weicker Jr., during the
Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Weicker, who was then a Republican, was defeated by Lieberman in
1988 and later, as an independent, became Connecticut's governor.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Geisler, 55, a lawyer who was headed to his broker Friday
to pick up a check from stocks he had just sold, recalled the
string of Republican leaders who had urged Nixon to resign ``when
the evidence became too overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it's beginning to head in the same direction,''
said Geisler, who said he had voted for Clinton in 1992 and Ralph
Nader in 1996. ``This is so serious that it transcends party.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the speech was especially keen at Yale, where
Lieberman earned his undergraduate degree in 1964 and graduated
from the law school in 1967, six years ahead of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Harris, a sophomore from New Rochelle, N.Y., who is
majoring in film studies, said the speech made her feel better
about being a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes it from being a party issue and makes it an
individual issue,'' she said. ``Democrats can disagree with what
Clinton did and still be Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   What was most clear from random conversations in this city of
124,000 is that, regardless of what people tell pollsters, they
love to talk about all matters related to Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In several cases, people were so eager to vent that they rushed
up and interrupted total strangers. Some pantomimed the president's
famous finger-wagging denial in January, and lively disputes
erupted over gift ties and stained dresses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Cody's 24-hour diner on Water Street, several customers said
that the speech by Lieberman portends peril for the president. ``He
just got the ball rolling,'' said Joseph Balzano, 36, a truck
driver and stagehand who said he is a registered Democrat but votes
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   A waitress, Mary Ann Severino, 60, chipped in with her view that
Lieberman's speech was one more betrayal in a drama that has
featured way too many. ``He was a hypocrite to Clinton,'' she said.
``If he was a good friend, he wouldn't have done that. He just
wants the public _ what's the word? _ on his side.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides, who had implored Lieberman to cancel or
postpone his planned remarks, would perhaps be surprised to hear
the view of John Burnham, a retired curator of Yale's numismatics
collection, that the address was ``an easy shot'' that could have
been orchestrated by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you strip away all the ornateness, there's not much
there,'' said Burnham, a Republican. ``In the end, it probably
helps you-know-who to bounce back. It's going to be worked on a
sympathy basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Among some, there was surprise that the speech was treated as
such a momentous occasion in Washington. Here, many people know the
senator as ``Joe,'' someone they see at the Little League field,
and they felt that his words were obvious at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't say anything that anybody else didn't say, but he
came right out and said it,'' said David Munsill, 59, an
electrician.
</P>
<P>
   Where most saw courage, a few saw sanctimony. Marcus Little, a
telephone repairman who was walking a picket line at a Southern New
England Telecommunications Corp. garage here, scoffed at ``the
righteous Joe Lieberman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't mind telling you what your opinion should be,''
said Little, 28, a Democrat. ``He had appointed himself the savior
of all Connecticut. Now he's working on the whole country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
