<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   During the past several days, record heat has scorched the
southern Plains and northern Texas with many locations exceeding
100 degrees. On Sunday, the clockwise circulation around high
pressure centered over Kentucky will push the unseasonable warmth
toward the Ohio Valley and Middle Atlantic States. Indeed, beneath
abundant sunshine, afternoon readings will reach the 90s from
southern Indiana to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the southwest will also direct dry and very warm
air into southern New England. Farther north and west, a cool front
sliding south from Canada will bring a few clouds and isolated
thundershowers to the southern Great Lakes and interior sections of
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will erupt along the central Gulf
coast and Florida on Sunday as a steady flow of tropical moisture
is drawn north from the Gulf of Mexico. Local rainfall tallies will
exceed an inch in many locations, which could cause minor flooding.
Farther west, sunny skies will once again promote torrid conditions
from Texas to Kansas. Meanwhile, spotty thundershowers will
accompany a cold front moving southward through the upper Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Residual moisture from former Hurricane Isis will ignite
numerous showers and thunderstorms over the interior West on
Sunday. Storms will be most numerous in the late afternoon as
uneven heating of the irregular terrain by the sun induces
fast-moving currents of ascending air. Elsewhere, onshore winds
will drive low clouds to coastal Washington and Oregon while the
interior Northwest stays mainly sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RIP CURRENTS
</P>
<P>
   A steady onshore wind Saturday prompted warnings of rip currents
to swimmers along Florida's east coast. Because a wind-generated
wave rarely is of uniform height along its entire length, water
piles up near the shore where incoming waves are tallest. Water
sliding down both sides of the piles creates flows that move
parallel to the shore. Where these flows converge, water is
diverted seaward, creating a dangerous rip current that can push
swimmers into deep water. If caught in a rip current, it is wise to
swim parallel to the beach until out of the current and then swim
back to shore. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
