<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-VIKINGS-GREEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS GREEN'S DEAL A SIGN OF THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only several days ago, the acrimony between Minnesota Vikings
coach Dennis Green and the team's new owner, Red McCombs, seemed
thicker than cement. McCombs had rejected two contract proposals
from Green's agent, Ray Anderson, with the latest rejection coming
just last week. It increasingly looked like Green was going to
leave the Vikings at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Then Anderson received a shocking call from representatives of
McCombs on Wednesday _ they wanted to make a deal. For the next 48
hours the two sides hammered out an agreement and now Green has
what he wanted and what many around the National Football League
say he deserved: a long-term contract and security.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, Green signed a multiyear extension that makes
him one of the richest coaches in the league. While exact figures
were unavailable, it is believed Green will earn at least $1.5
million a year. Despite one of the best track records of any active
coach, Green had been severely underpaid. He is 57-45 as coach of
the Vikings, has made the playoffs five of the past six years, won
two division titles, and last year led the Vikings over the Giants
in one of the biggest playoff comebacks in NFL history, yet his
$900,000 salary made him among the 10 lowest-paid coaches in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Green is the only coach in the National Football Conference
Central with a winning record against the Green Bay Packers in the
1990s, and he was still the lowest paid coach in the division,
earning even less than Chicago's Dave Wannstedt, who is scheduled
to make $1 million this season despite his 37-45 record.
</P>
<P>
   Green's huge salary bump is yet another indication that head
coaches are becoming wealthier and more powerful. One owner
estimates that coaching salaries have quadrupled in the past 10
years. Kansas City coach Marty Schottenheimer, who made less than
$400,000 as coach of the Cleveland Browns in 1988, now makes more
than $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches have become more powerful because they are required to
do more as free agency has changed football. Now, like never
before, players move from team to team in conveyor belt-like
fashion. For a team to have cohesion, a good coach must make all
that talent gel.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams recognize this. Denver Broncos coach Mike Shanahan
recently signed the richest head coaching contract in NFL history;
a deal that will pay him more than $2.4 million a season. According
to coaching salary information obtained from various sources,
Shanahan is among a growing number of coaches who will make at
least $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Bill Parcells of the Jets ($2.4 million a
season), Mike Ditka of New Orleans ($2 million), and Jimmy Johnson
of Miami ($2 million).
</P>
<P>
   And those are just base salaries. In addition to receiving
bonuses for getting to a playoff or Super Bowl, coaches have
lucrative deals for local television and radio shows. Wannstedt and
Bill Cowher of Pittsburgh each receive $250,000 a year for media
rights and expenses; Johnson $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The only coach in the NFL who is effectively working on a
one-year deal is Baltimore's Ted Marchibroda. Owner Art Modell said
he is open to giving Marchibroda an extension and since the Ravens
will probably have a good season, look for Marchibroda to sign a
long-term extension maybe sometime in October.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
