<SLUG> BC-FBN-PREVIEW-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSON TESTS THE RULES  
 GIANTS' ACCORSI MAKES TWO GOOD MOVES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSON TESTS THE RULES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Rod Woodson of the Baltimore Ravens violated the league's
substance abuse policy by refusing to take a second drug test, it
set off an intense debate between officials with the NFL and the
players association.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Woodson passed a routine drug test for illegal
substances such as cocaine and marijuana. Then, as part of the
league's program of random testing for performance enhancing drugs
like steroids or androstenedione, Woodson was again requested to
give a sample of his urine. According to several team executives,
Woodson was upset that he had given a sample only one day earlier
and refused to give another.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Woodson eventually did give the second sample, his
initial refusal counts as a positive test.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Woodson, who team executives said has never tested
positive for any illegal or banned substances, is in Stage 1 of the
league's substance abuse policy. It calls for an evaluation by a
psychiatrist, as well as an increase in random drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   The league and union are in negotiations about what to do. The
union believes that since Woodson, a future Hall of Famer who is a
member of the league's 75th anniversary team, eventually took the
second test, he should be given a break. The league thinks that if
it bends the rules for Woodson, it would set a bad precedent for
other players.
</P>
<P>
   If the league sticks to the rules, Woodson could appeal to an
arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   GIANTS' ACCORSI MAKES TWO GOOD MOVES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi has quietly made
two key moves in recent months that show why he has been such a
highly regarded executive.
</P>
<P>
   First, he drafted UCLA defensive back Shaun Williams. At the
time, the pick was questioned because the Giants already had a
number of players at the position, but Accorsi now looks like a
genius because cornerback Jason Sehorn is lost for the season and
Williams gives them depth at Sehorn's position.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Accorsi is following the practice of his predecessor,
George Young, by continuing to lock up young players to long-term
contracts. Last week both quarterback Danny Kanell and tackle Scott
Gragg agreed to long-term contract extensions.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _ Kansas City has changed its offense and that could be the
difference between simply making the playoffs and finally getting
to a Super Bowl. The plan is to throw deep more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Contract extension talks between Detroit and wide receiver
Herman Moore continue. Moore paid close attention to the recent
extension signed by Jerry Rice, making him the highest paid wide
receiver in the league.
</P>
<P>
   _ After watching hours of film on him, some members of San
Francisco's defensive coaching staff think Jets wide receiver
Keyshawn Johnson has cut down on the many fundamental mistakes he
made in his first two seasons in the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
