<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SALTA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)   
 ROMEO SALTA, 93, PIONEERING ITALIAN RESTAURATEUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Romeo Salta, one of the first Manhattan restaurateurs
to introduce fine Italian cuisine, died Aug. 31 at his home in
Manhattan. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Salta's namesake restaurant, Romeo Salta, on West 56th Street,
opened in 1953 and was one of the first in Manhattan to offer
elegant Northern Italian cooking, although Salta was equally proud
of the many Southern Italian dishes on his menu. Pasta was prepared
at the table and served fresh and hot, and dishes such as gnocchi,
scampi and risotto were introduced, accompanied by fine Italian
wines.
</P>
<P>
   The northern origin of much of the food aside, patrons were
greeted in an expansive Southern Italian manner and the decor was
elaborate. At the time that Salta operated the restaurant, there
were only two establishments favored by serious Italian food
lovers, Romeo Salta and San Marino, and each had its loyal
devotees.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has never had an Italian restaurant as good as Romeo
Salta was in its heyday,'' Mimi Sheraton, a former restaurant
critic for The New York Times, said upon hearing about Salta's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Salta was born Romeo Saltalamacchia in Taranto, Italy, on Sept.
27, 1904, and raised in a state-run institution in Florence after
his father's death in an Italian naval submarine in 1910. As soon
as he was able, he, too, joined the submarine service. After his
discharge, he became a cabin steward and kitchen boy on several
Italian liners, where he learned to cook.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the United States as a penniless and illegal
immigrant in 1929, jumping ship in New York. A business card given
to him by a passenger, whom he had cared for during a bout of sea
sickness, was his passport into the restaurant world. The
passenger, who ran the Central Park Casino, hired him as a waiter,
and Salta eventually moved on to work in various capacities at the
Pierre Hotel, the Waldorf Astoria and the St. Moritz.
</P>
<P>
   He later took several jobs in the Midwest, before settling in
Los Angeles in 1933. There he was employed in nightclubs, including
the Coconut Grove and the Trocadero.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, he and a partner transformed a rundown
drugstore and soda shop into a restaurant they named Chianti. After
a slow start, a visit by Ed Sullivan and a subsequent mention in
his newspaper column, ``Little Old New York,'' the restaurant
blossomed and soon boasted such regular patrons as Bing Crosby,
Errol Flynn and Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Salta returned to New York in the early 1950s, and in 1951, with
a partner, he opened Mercurio in midtown Manhattan. It was one of
the most popular hangouts for the top models of the day, including
the young Grace Kelly. He and his partner eventually dissolved
their business arrangement, and Salta opened Romeo Salta on West
56th Street, where it was particularly favored by theater and music
personalities and executives in the cosmetics industry.
</P>
<P>
   Salta was the author of ``The Pleasure of Italian Cooking,''
published by Macmillan in 1962. He also developed a line of frozen
foods that was sold under his name for a short time.
</P>
<P>
   After Salta gave up the daily operation of the business in 1976,
Romeo Salta was taken over by his son, Salvatore, and Salta's
second wife, Rosita. The restaurant closed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Salta was divorced from his first wife in the 1940s and married
Rosita in 1949. They were divorced in 1970. He married his third
wife, Antoinette, in 1978. His second and third wives survive him,
as do the three sons of his second marriage, Salvatore of Queens,
Romeo Jr. of Manhattan and Remo of Ridgewood, N.J., and five
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
