<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-FAREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A COLUMNIST'S FAREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since this is my last column for ``Our Towns,'' a few answers to
often-asked questions are in order.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly five years, people have asked, ``Where do you find
stories?'' Well, sometimes, it was the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Take Herb Sherry. Herb Sherry of Brooklyn (and summers working
the Jersey Shore) started calling every once in a while, then
nearly every week, then every Friday. He had this ``human
interest'' story: his own. He billed himself as ``king of the bar
mitzvahs,'' a veteran of 40,000 parties whose Herb Sherry Orchestra
was responsible for keeping scores of musicians employed.
</P>
<P>
   At times, he'd call the day an ``Our Towns'' column ran. ``You
know,'' he'd say, ``my story is more interesting than that.'' I
must admit, after interviewing him many months later, that he was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Calls from readers led to two columns about New Jersey's
campaign to audit liquor stores and bars for back taxes. The
supposed bad guys _ tax-cheat bar owners _ turned out, in many
cases, to be the victims. The auditors, hired from civil service
lists, were coming up with some outrageous five-year bills, based
on one-year audits, that were putting little, unsophisticated bars
out of business. At least one accounting firm, in Elizabeth, found
huge errors in nearly every audit it reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   People have often asked what determines the subject of a column.
More often than not, it was news, or the stories behind news. A
visit to the Tawana Brawley defamation trial found Bill and Vera
Jones of Flatbush, Brooklyn, who drove to the Poughkeepsie
courthouse every day. They thought they'd spend a few weeks in a
courtroom, see the justice system at work. They spent eight months
there and got a mini O.J. circus.
</P>
<P>
   A news story about a murder in Hartford, Conn., led to the story
of Jay Boland, one of those rare people in a big city who look
after their neighbors. It was after one of his nightly block
watches that he was shot in a botched robbery attempt in front of
his house. His neighbors promised to stick together in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite stories? The ones about people who go their own way.
These are often people who hold on to their principles in the face
of outside pressure, like Maria Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney teaches fourth grade at Hawes Elementary School in
Ridgewood, N.J. She manages to get her students to read newspapers
and put on a play each year on a social justice issue of their
choice. Last year, after her students wrote a play on Nike's and
Disney's low-wage factories, the school refused to let them perform
it. Ms. Sweeney told her students they did nothing wrong. And
eventually, they did perform the play, on Broadway at the
Roundabout, which donated a stage for a night.
</P>
<P>
   I liked Mario Costa, owner of the White Mana Diner in Jersey
City, who had agreed to sell the place to a Dunkin' Donuts
franchisee. After realizing that the 1939 World's Fair-era diner, a
neighborhood fixture, would be effectively destroyed, he changed
his mind about selling and had to pay the buyers quite a bit of
money to go elsewhere. (They went across the street.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Bones, a homeless man who used to haunt the
fringes of Weehawken. His sad, gray face begged for a handout, but
he refused to ask for one. Instead, he would sell what he could
find, accept donations if offered or work for food. I'm sorry to
say I don't know what has happened to him.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many stories in Atlantic City, one that stands out is
Lillian Bryant's. She tried every which way to save the street
named after her father, New Jersey's first black Cabinet member,
from being torn up for a $330 million tunnel to a casino planned
for the city's marina district. It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, she and two other homeowners on Horace J. Bryant
Jr. Drive won a small concession from the state: They got an
independent overseer to watch this tunnel project like a hawk.
``Remember,'' Ms. Bryant said, ``the story isn't over.''
</P>
<P>
   As I pack for a new job as the San Francisco bureau chief, I'll
remember that those are some of the truest words a reporter can
know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
