<SLUG> BC-NY-ROSS-WEALTH-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHDRAWAL OF FINANCING RENEWS QUESTIONS ABOUT CANDIDATE'S
HUSBAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross' announcement that her
husband, Wilbur Ross Jr., was withdrawing $2.25 million he had
donated to her campaign for governor has raised a question that
prominent Democrats have been asking all year: just how wealthy is
Ross?
</P>
<P>
   No one outside Ross' immediate circle has a precise idea,
because so far he has escaped an almost obligatory ritual in modern
U.S. politics: the annual release of tax returns by candidates and
their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, politicians like Geraldine Ferraro and
Christine Todd Whitman have been pressured into revealing not only
their own tax information, but that of their wealthy husbands. If
anything, the question of a spouse's finances may be of greater
import in Ms. McCaughey Ross' case because _ until last week _ Ross
was providing most of the money for her campaign, and helping to
run it.
</P>
<P>
   Ross has revealed nothing about his finances, and he and Ms.
McCaughey Ross have faced little pressure to do so. The lieutenant
governor, who is competing in the Sept. 15 Democratic primary, made
her own tax returns available for reporters to review in April, but
she and her husband file separately.
</P>
<P>
   The other three Democrats in the race have made public their
joint filings with their spouses, as has Gov. George Pataki, the
Republican who was once Ms. McCaughey Ross' mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the lieutenant governor declined to discuss her
husband's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who is traveling on business in Asia, has not returned
calls to his office in recent days. He is senior managing director
of Rothschild Inc., the investment bank, and owns a controlling
interest in News Communications, which owns 23 weekly newspapers in
New York as well as The Hill, a weekly that covers Congress. He is
also a director of Syms, the clothing store; Mego Financial Corp.,
a developer of time-share vacation properties, and KTI, a waste
management company.
</P>
<P>
   All year, prominent Democrats have questioned whether Ross is
truly wealthy enough to bankroll a credible statewide race. Among
those voicing doubt were campaign aides to Ms. McCaughey Ross'
chief rival, Peter Vallone, the New York City council speaker. The
other Democratic candidates are Brooklyn District Attorney Charles
Hynes and former state Transportation Commissioner James Larocca.
</P>
<P>
   But the other candidates have not made an issue of Ross' refusal
to release his tax returns. Officials in the rival camps said they
were reluctant to draw attention to Ms. McCaughey Ross, who they
said has always received a disproportionate share of the news
coverage of the campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Larocca, whose effort has been hampered by a lack of money, also
argued that the lieutenant governor, as the only woman in the race,
might have accused anyone who demanded to see her husband's tax
returns of sexism. ``She has played the victim throughout her brief
public career, and is very good at it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross announced on Thursday that the campaign had
returned to Ross $2.25 million, leaving the campaign virtually
without funds. Earlier in the year, she and her aides said Ross
would spend $10 million or more, conferring instant credibility on
a candidate who had been a Democrat for just a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Some wealthy Democratic fund-raisers who know Ross, including
some who are also in investment banking, have said all year that he
could ill afford to part with even $5 million, estimating his net
worth at $10 million to $20 million. The recent downturn in the
stock market and a financial dispute between Ross and his former
wife have raised more questions about the extent of his wealth.
</P>
<P>
   While Ross has not made his tax returns public, statements filed
by the lieutenant governor with the State Ethics Commission give
glimpses into his finances.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure forms list 37 entities, many of them ventures of
Rothschild, in which he holds an ownership interest, and 26 sources
of income, including the sale of stock in such major companies as
Texaco and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   But while the filing lists broad categories of value for each of
those holdings and sources of income _ the lowest is under $5,000,
and the highest is above $250,000 _ that portion of the report, as
a matter of policy, is not available for public review.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
