u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-McGWIRE-650&AMP;ADD-N     09-05 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McGWIRE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McGWIRE HITS No. 60, JOINING RUTH AND MARIS  
(See also BBO-McGWIRE-RUTH, BBO-MCGWIRE-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ First there was Babe Ruth. Then there was Roger
Maris. Now there is Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   With one of his patented uppercut swings, McGwire lofted another
majestic fly ball into the left field stands at Busch Stadium in
the first inning Saturday, becoming the third player in major
league baseball history to hit 60 home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Just ahead: No. 61, which will tie the record Maris set in 1961
when he broke Ruth's fabled mark, and No. 62, which will break
Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire reached the rarefied plateau considerably sooner than
Ruth or Maris. Ruth hit his record-setting 60th in the Yankees'
154th game in 1927; Maris tied the record in the Yankees' 159th
game in 1961. This was the Cardinals' 142d game of this season.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire walked to the plate in the first inning to the
cheers of a sold out stadium, he carried with him a remarkably poor
record against Cincinnati pitchers. In seven previous games, he had
managed only two hits in 16 at-bats, neither of the hits a home
run, making the Reds the only National League team against whom
McGwire had not hit a home run this season.
</P>
<P>
   He would face Dennis Reyes, a 21-year-old left-handed pitcher
from Mexico, who had said Friday night he would not be afraid to
pitch to McGwire, that is, give him pitches to hit rather than walk
him, a tactic the Reds had followed 12 times this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Reyes' first pitch was inside and low for a ball, and the
fans booed. His second pitch was also low, and the fans booed more
lustily. The third pitch produced instant cheers.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:30 p.m. New York time, McGwire swung and drove the ball to
left field. He and everyone else in the park knew instantly this
was No. 60.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire rounded the bases euphorically, high-fiving Rene
Lachemann, the Cardinals' coach, when he reached third, then
exchanging fist salutes with his teammates after he crossed the
plate and reached the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The fans, who had already been standing during his time at bat,
stood even taller as they roared with ecstasy, their red shirts and
red hats brightening the park as if it could get any brighter on
this 93-degree day. They kept cheering until McGwire re-emerged
from the dugout, waved to them and thrust his left fist joyously
into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 60 for McGwire,'' said a press box announcement that is
made routinely when a player hits a home run. But there was nothing
routine about the announcement or the home run. ``No. 60'' carried
a strange sound because how many people had ever heard it announced
during a game?
</P>
<P>
   Only once in their pre1998 history had the Cardinals even had
two players hit a combined 60 home runs. That was in 1925 when
Rogers Hornsby and Jim Bottomley did it. Here was McGwire reaching
that number all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   But his achievements this season have been even more impressive.
Having slugged 52 and 58 home runs the previous two seasons,
McGwire became the first player to hit 50 or more in three
successive seasons. Not even Ruth did that.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire also surpassed Ruth's record for most home runs in two
successive seasons. The one he hit in the first inning Saturday was
his 118th in 1997-98. Ruth hit 114 in 1927-28.
</P>
<P>
   When he hit his 57th last Tuesday night in Florida, the Paul
Bunyan-like slugger broke Hack Wilson's 68-year-old National League
record. And when he deposited No. 59 into the Marlins' stands
Wednesday night, the first baseman became the most prolific
right-handed home run hitter of all time, surpassing Jimmie Foxx
(1932) and Hank Greenberg (1938). Ruth and Maris, the only ones
remaining for McGwire to pass, were left-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Another right-handed hitter, Sammy Sosa, is chasing McGwire as
well as Ruth and Maris. Sosa socked his 57th home run in the
Chicago Cubs' game in Pittsburgh on Friday night. The Cubs and the
Pirates were scheduled to play Saturday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McGwire had failed to hit a home run against the Reds Friday
night after collecting 12 home runs in the Cardinals' previous 17
games, including four in the space of five at-bats over two games
against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   In his next three at-bats Saturday, McGwire struck out.
</P>
<P>
   When he batted in the second inning, 25 minutes after he
connected for No. 60, it marked only the second time in 71 years
that a batter stood at the plate with a chance to hit his 61st home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Reyes threw the first pitch low for a ball, and once
again the fans booed. But then Reyes threw two pitches down that
McGwire took for strikes. His next pitch was up, and McGwire swung
at it but missed, prompting a sound of disappointment from the
people in civilian red.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger, also left-handed, was the pitcher when McGwire
took his second crack at 61. McGwire took his first pitch for a
strike, then swung at the next two pitches and missed both.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, with runners on second and third, McGwire struck
out swinging against John Hudek.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
