u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHEAST-BEACHES-NYT     09-05 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHEAST-BEACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEACH TOWNS GIVE SUMMER OF '98 A FAVORABLE REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Conn.)   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEASIDE HEIGHTS, N.J. _ Bobby Dee, a k a Robert DiPeso, counted
out the quarters for the players at the Gift Wheel at Bobby Dee's
Casino (``Nobody leaves without a TV!'') on the Wildwood boardwalk
and pronounced the summer of 1998 a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was excellent, the water was clean, the families
showed up,'' he said. ``That equals a good summer for us.''
</P>
<P>
   DiPeso's contented appraisal found plenty of echoes up and down
the region's shoreline as the last week of unofficial summer drew
toward its Labor Day finale.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, dramatic reporting about Hurricane Bonnie scared some
visitors away toward the end of August, and rain in June kept Jones
Beach in New York from matching last year's turnout. But for a part
of the country that equates summer with sand and salt water, with
quiet family seafood cookouts and the raucous honky-tonk of the
boardwalk, the season just ending was clearly a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have disposable cash and they're roaming around looking
for entertainment,'' said David Shotwell, senior administrator of
the Ocean Grove Camp Meeting Association, the annual Christian
jamboree on the Jersey Shore. ``You can just tell by the number of
people who don't know where the bathrooms are that we're getting a
lot of new people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have stumbled in here by accident,'' Shotwell
continued, ``but we sure try to make sure they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Masher and her daughter Jill were among DiPeso's
contestants at the Gift Wheel _ no TV yet _ which is like a wheel
of fortune game in a real casino, but stays legal by offering
prizes instead of cash. Fourteen members of Mrs. Masher's extended
family had come down for a week from Troy, N.Y., fourteen years
after their last visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been here before and wanted to come back with the
kids,'' said Mrs. Masher, a homemaker. ``It's been fun because
there's a lot to do, and the kids like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism agencies are still far from knowing the final count of
hotel taxes, beach tag sales, parking lot receipts and all the
other measures of the summer's financial impact.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some fragments of early data to suggest that it
was a good season: the Connecticut Office of Tourism reported that
tourist stops at highway information centers were up 5.7 percent
and that the $6.8 billion in hotel and motel taxes collected in
June was well above last year's $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   On the southern Jersey Shore, a collection of a similar tourism
tax to build a new convention center in Wildwood was 34 percent
ahead of last year's level through June.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City's hotels topped last year's extraordinary 94
percent occupancy rate with a 97 percent filled rate through
August, according to Linda Conlin, executive director of the Office
of Travel and Tourism in New Jersey's Department of Commerce and
Economic Development. And Ms. Conlin said an informal survey of
shore businesses also produced an upbeat bottom line: ``Equal to
last year's good summer season, if not surpassing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism spending amounted to $25.5 billion in New Jersey last
year and accounted for 623,000 jobs, according to the department.
Spending totaled $14 billion on the Jersey Shore, which supported
267,000 tourism-related jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Shore tourism officials said that water quality across the
region was not the problem it had been several years ago, when
algae blooms, pollution and medical debris washing ashore made
frequent headlines. In New York, Hurricane Bonnie actually scoured
an outlying sandbar and deposited more beach sand on the Fire
Island shoreline, said Gerard Stoddard, president of the Fire
Island Association.
</P>
<P>
   Good beach weather during July and August took crowds to the
South Shore of Long Island, N.Y., as well, but summer visits to
Jones Beach State Park decreased to 3.9 million this year from 4.4
million last year because of rainy weekends in June, said the
superintendent, Joseph F. Lescinski.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a problem, it was that because Labor Day came a
week after the end of August, the traditional finish line, many
young ride operators, ticket takers and pizza waiters were gone for
the final week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our workers come from the Toms River School District,
which, without any thought or consideration for the tourist
industry, reopened its doors on Sept. 1,'' said Bill Irwin, general
manager of the Casino Pier and Waterworks arcade and amusement
park, which employs 700 seasonal workers in Seaside Heights. ``That
left us a bit short-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin and other natives of the Jersey Shore know that, for all
the year-to-year sameness the summer seasons seem to share, a lot
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the dual-career family has meant that few visitors
take a house for the summer the way they used to, said Vicki Clark,
director of marketing for the Cape May Chamber of Commerce, so
rentals tend to be for shorter periods, and are more often arranged
on the spur of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never change, though. J.R. and Terri Bale and their
two boys, from New Providence, have a three-week rental with Mrs.
Bale's mother and her sister's family in Seaside Heights this
summer, just the way Mrs. Bale's extended family, the Azzolinas,
the Giaimos and the Valentis, shared summer rentals when she was
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always had a house when I was a kid,'' Mrs. Bale said.
``Then we grew up into teen-agers and we didn't want to do that
with everyone's parents, and it ended. But now maybe we're starting
it all over again with our own kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Dolan, a food broker from Kearny, bought a house with
his wife, Jo-Ann, on the bay side at Chadwicks, a few miles up the
barrier island from Seaside Heights, partly to give their seven
grandchildren a taste of what the shore was like in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up as a kid, we'd leave the day after school ended and
stay for two months,'' he said. ``We made new friends every
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the beach behind Dolan, Robert Gluck had reached page 239
of ``Buddenbrooks,'' which is less than halfway through Thomas
Mann's masterpiece. ``A couple of days,'' he said, when asked how
long it had taken him to get as far as that in his heavy seaside
reading. ``Three months,'' his wife, Cindy, corrected him.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter _ Mann was on his face in the sand, and Gluck was
content just to be there, with the sound of the surf thumping a few
hundred feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you grew up coming to the shore, you get to a point where
if you don't smell the brine and feel the sand between toes, you're
missing something,'' said Gluck, a freelance writer. ``You wait for
summer to come, and then it comes, and then it goes by fast,
because you're having fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
