<HEADER>
A0998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REUTERS-REAL-2TAKE     09-05 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REUTERS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUTERS CORPORATE HEADQUARTERS NEXT TO BUGS AND MICKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the next addition to the revival of Times Square,
the Reuters building on the blockfront between 42nd and 43rd
streets on Seventh Avenue faces an unusual design challenge. It is
intended to blend the dignity of a major corporate headquarters
with a location that has Bugs Bunny and Mickey Mouse as its
immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The project is a joint venture of Reuters, the international
news and financial services company, and the Rudin family, builders
and owners of residential and commercial properties in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Various Reuters operations, including a securities trading floor
and television studios, will occupy 506,000 square feet of the
855,000-square-foot building, which will have the address 3 Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try to satisfy a lot of constituencies in this
area,'' said William Rudin, president of Rudin Management Co., the
family's leasing and property management subsidiary. He said the
building would have the brightly lighted signs that are required by
the zoning in the area, but said the approach can't be ``too
glitzy,'' because of the presence of the Reuters headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with a Warner Bros. Studio Store across Seventh
Avenue and a Disney store across 42nd Street, the neighborhood is
not going to be confused with Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin said that the recent gyrations of the stock market would
have no impact on the project. ``We have our financing in place and
the interest rate is locked in,'' he said. Prudential Insurance
Co., the previous owner of the site, is providing both the
construction loan and the 20-year long-term financing and has
retained the right to place some signs on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 30 percent of the office space and 80,000 square feet
of retail space that still need to be leased, Rudin said the Times
Square market was strong enough to resist stock market
fluctuations. ``We don't see the New York market being affected,''
he said. ``There is no speculative building in the Times square
area. If you build a good product, there will be demand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   With demolition of existing buildings at the site just getting
under way, Reuters does not expect to move in until the spring of
2001, although some of the retail space may be occupied as much as
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The building is being presented as the latest in high-tech,
``green'' development, although it will apparently not go as far in
using environmentally sensitive techniques as the partially erected
Conde Nast building at 42nd Street and Broadway, which has a 4
Times Square address.
</P>
<P>
   The Conde Nast building has photovoltaic cells, which convert
sunlight into electricity without generating pollution,
incorporated in the outer wall of the building. The structure,
which is being developed by the Durst Organization, also includes
two 400-kilowatt fuel cells to provide larger amounts of low
pollution power and as a backup in case of a power failure.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin executives say they will not put photovoltaic cells in the
building wall but are still studying the economics and
environmental consequences of fuel cells. ``On photovoltaics, we
just don't think the science is there yet,'' said Rudin Management
chief operating officer John Gilbert. He said the base building had
been designed to incorporate fuel cells if studies show them to be
cost effective and environmentally benign. ``We are looking at
everything they did across the street,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Those evaluations are made easier because they are using the
same firm, Fox &AMP; Fowle Architects, that designed the Conde Nast
building as well as the same construction manager, Tishman
Construction.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fox, a principal of the architectural firm, said energy
conserving technologies, such as a facade that lets in natural
light while blocking most heat energy, were being emphasized. He
said the walls are so efficient _ and the amount of heat generated
by people and machines so great _ that the building will not have
to be heated, even on cold winter days.
</P>
<P>
   He said both electric and gas-driven cooling units would be
installed in the building, with the option of operating each based
on electrical rates, which typically peak on weekday afternoons,
but fall off at night.
</P>
<P>
   The building was designed with its core structure _ which
contains the elevator shafts, stairways and other common elements _
at the center, so that offices can ring the core for greater access
to natural sunlight. Fox said the developers were considering
interior lighting that dims as sunlight increases to conserve power
usage.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected from the Rudins, who took an aging, empty
office building at 55 Broad St. and transformed it into a high-tech
center by installing advanced communications equipment, the Reuters
Building will be heavily wired. In addition to electrical power,
the building will have optical fiber and advanced copper
communications gear plus antennas and satellite dishes on the roof
for wireless communication.
</P>
<P>
   There is also provision for future developments. ``The amount of
riser space in the building is well above the norm,'' said Glenn
Elliott, senior vice president at Reuters for real estate,
referring to the vertical passages that house the wiring. ``We
tried to figure out everything we could possibly need, then added
50 percent for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuters will have five 750-kilowatt diesel-powered generators on
the roof so that it can maintain operations in case of a power
failure. Another will be installed to sustain operations of the
building itself, with a pad provided for an additional one if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin said one reason that Reuters decided to participate in the
development of a new building, rather than rent space in an
existing structure, is the freedom it gave the company to customize
the design to its needs. For example, the floor that will house the
Reuters Instinet subsidiary's trading floor will be 16 feet slab to
slab, compared with just under 9 feet for other floors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The trading floor will be the eighth, which will place it above
the brightly lighted signs that will adorn the building.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert said Reuters also had other reasons for choosing a new
building. ``Most importantly, it was a cost-saving alternative to a
traditional lease position in a rising market,'' he said. He said
being an owner also gave the company ``an opportunity to create a
brand image for the Reuters name.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the image-creating will be done on a fourth-floor
television studio that will be visible from the outside. With the
lower part of 1500 Broadway, across Times Square at the northeast
corner of 43rd Street, being converted to broadcast ABC's ``Good
Morning America'' show, the two studios could easily each end up in
the other's backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   The original design for the building called for several news
zippers, similar to the one across Seventh Avenue at One Times
Square. But Gilbert said the zippers were now out of the picture in
favor of full video displays.
</P>
<P>
   The retail space will be multilevel, including the lower
concourse level and the first, second and third floors. Because the
building will include an entrance to the Times Square subway
station _ relocating it about 75 feet to the west, to where it was
in the 1930s _ and a lobby for the office building, there will be
less ground-floor retail space available than before demolition.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the developers say they have decided to try to
attract three relatively large retail tenants, so that each will
have adequate exposure at street level, rather than replace the
gaggle of small stores that were previously there. (These stores
operated on leases with six-month cancellation clauses that were
invoked in March. All were closed by mid-August.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult footprint to work with, because of the
subway, the loading docks and so forth,'' Rudin said. To enlarge
the site, the partnership bought a small building and driveway
facing on 43rd Street. But because the building housed offices for
the New Victory Theater and the driveway allowed back-door
deliveries to the theater, one of the loading docks in the new
building will be for the New Victory. In addition, a new lobby for
the theater will be provided at the concourse level on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   With construction under way on both sides of Times Square and to
the west along 42nd Street, Rudin said the area is clearly
re-established as an office location and retail destination. But he
noted that the process of renewal had taken a long time. ``My
father was involved in an effort to redevelop Times Square 25 years
ago,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-VECSEY-CO     09-05 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HISTORY IS MADE, AND FAN SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-MCGWIRE-RUTH, BBO-MCGWIRE) 
(th) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The ball soared into the steamy ozone of the
Mississippi River Valley, and eventually it came down. Mark McGwire
has been so hot, so consistent, so productive, that it seemed _
dare one say it? _ almost anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   The big man had tied Babe Ruth, and the day was young. In his
first at-bat Saturday, McGwire hit his 60th home run of this
season, but his excellence made the blast seem inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The left fielder did not move. McGwire jogged around the bases.
He and a few teammates performed a little elbows-and-chest bumping
ritual at home plate. And then the Cardinals swarmed around him,
but professionally.
</P>
<P>
   They would save their real emotions for the 61st home that would
tie Roger Maris, and then the 62nd that would send McGwire and his
new best friend, Sammy Sosa, toward new territory, the middle 60s,
in the last two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire's shot went soaring into the lower deck, 381 feet
away, above the BJC Health System advertisement, another
competition was just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   There was the fans' challenge to catch and keep the baseball
McGwire had propelled, a ball that could make somebody rich, or at
least solvent. Then there was the task of helping the fan live to
tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   The odd couple of Major League Baseball and the Cardinals
management had been planning the response to the epic homers that
might happen on this home stand.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, a young journalism graduate from the
University of Missouri foiled the assorted special agents, guards,
ushers, security officers and his fellow fans to come up with the
ball. And here is the upset: he doesn't want money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give it back to Mark,'' said 22-year-old Deni
Allen. ``It's his ball. I think that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't Allen want something for the ball? ``I want to take
batting practice,'' Allen said. ``And I'd like a few season tickets
for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the speculation about the value of McGwire's and Sosa's
baseballs, this seems extremely high-minded. But what if the
Cardinals _ an organization not known for its sense of fun _ refuse
to allow him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, they'll let me,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen works for the St. Louis Rams, a team that plays a bizarre
sport involving a ball that is not round. He came by his tickets
honestly _ his grandparents from Ozark, Mo., bought them _ and he
was in Section 286, plotting his move to McGwire's home run alley,
the left-field stands, where fans have a ticket for a wonderful
souvenir or a big payday _ or personal injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Mabry got his hit,'' Allen said at a news conference
later, ``I figured I'd better get hustling. I jumped a few aisles,
went around a couple of guards, thought I'd get stopped, and a guy
doing his job stopped me, and I respect that, but I hung out and I
made my move.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in perfect position for the high fly but somebody else
touched it first. ``You see it every time,'' Allen said. ``The
first guy never catches it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball skimmed off other fingers and ``I took a few punches''
but Allen secured the ball, and then the task force secured him,
without much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' said Kevin Hallinan, the executive director
of security and facility management for baseball. ``These are good
fans, nice people. We don't expect a lot of rough stuff, but we
have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In most parts of the world, the average innocent fan may be
unprepared for a couple of hundred alcohol-fueled louts, willing to
dive headfirst into the pile, like linebackers on 'roid rage. (Or
is that redundant?)
</P>
<P>
   To keep the McGwire chase from becoming Lord of the Flies Meets
World's Toughest Man in Bar Fight, baseball barred everybody from
home run country unless they had a ticket. Reporters, with our
special 59-62 credentials, are not allowed to infiltrate the
hallowed sections.
</P>
<P>
   While fans are protected from the mobs in foul territory and
other alien sites, it could have come down to father vs. son,
brother vs. brother, truck driver vs. little old lady. It could get
ugly. But it was not ugly for Deni Allen, who had already made up
his mind what he would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more excited about meeting Mark,'' he said while the game
was still going on.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the No. 62 home run has been estimated at $100,000,
although one anonymous voice claims he will pay 10 times that, and
there is talk of major corporations taking an interest in that
ball, which would only drive the price higher.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the ball could fluctuate like some electronics
stock in legalized gambling, that is to say, the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to the No. 62 ball if McGwire and Sosa both go on
to 63, 64, 65 homers?
</P>
<P>
   Fans might ask if they want to risk death or disfigurement for
the 62nd home run ball, particularly if its value should ``correct
itself,'' as they say on Wall Street. (``Correction'' sounds like,
``You just lost a bundle, my man,'' at least to my unsophisticated
ear.)
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, fans will see dollar signs on the 62nd home run
ball as it soars into some distant grandstand, but the fans must be
protected from themselves. The fun is only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   For the next homer, no doubt, Internal Revenue Service agents
will also be on hand, taking down Social Security numbers. This
being the litigious 1990s, one can only assume that a mighty
phalanx of personal-injury lawyers will be screeching into downtown
St. Louis from their suburban palaces.
</P>
<P>
   The safest scenario for all concerned would be for the ultimate
home run to hit the foul pole or clang off a distant facade and
come bouncing back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe McGwire would hit an inside-the-park home run for No.
62, a 265-pound moose lumbering around the bases in pursuit of
immortality, or possibly heat stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the opposing fielder does not get to keep the
ball or barter it for a few McGwire mementos. In fact, the ball
belongs to Major League Baseball. The alternative is the next
couple of home run balls flying into humankind. Not everybody will
settle for modest rewards.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals are wise, the kid's in the batting cage
immediately, before he answers all the phone calls from lawyers and
investment advisers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1001 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-BINLADEN-500-2TA     09-05 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-BINLADEN-500-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIN LADEN WAS TARGET OF U.S. RAID PLANS SINCE SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Repeating for all needing.)  (bl) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. intelligence officials drew up secret plans
last spring for a covert raid to capture Osama bin Laden in
Afghanistan, according to senior U.S. government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the planning began after U.S. military,
intelligence and law-enforcement officials concluded they had ample
evidence linking bin Laden to a series of anti-American terrorist
attacks in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, developed by the CIA and U.S. special forces months
before the August bombings of two U.S. embassies, called for U.S.
forces to extricate the Saudi millionaire from his hideout in
Afghanistan and bring him to justice in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were aware of the mission, which was
ultimately shelved by the director of Central Intelligence, George
Tenet, and other senior officials because of the high risks
involved. Those included the potential for many casualties among
Americans and innocent Afghans.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials said they were still
working to develop a broad range of other options aimed at bin
Laden or to dismantle his terrorist network when bombs exploded
Aug. 7 at two East African embassies, killing 263 people, among
them 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The officials' accounts of the covert planning add a new
dimension to President Clinton's decision to launch a cruise
missile attack against bin Laden's training camps in Afghanistan
and a pharmaceutical factory in Sudan with suspected links to bin
Laden's efforts to obtain chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has presented the cruise missile attack as an
instance of Clinton's decisiveness in the face of terrorism. Swift
retaliation was ordered, an administration spokesman said, because
the evidence linking bin Laden to the bombings had come together
quickly and unequivocally and because the United States had
received information that he might strike again.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, a Saudi exile who lives in Afghanistan, has publicly
announced his plans to attack Americans, and U.S. authorities
believe he directed the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, officials now acknowledge, intelligence and
military officials were convinced long before the bombings that an
attack against bin Laden was justified. The bombings in Africa and
the speed with which investigators linked them to operatives
working for the Saudi exile, officials say, gave crucial political
impetus to those already advocating a counterstrike.
</P>
<P>
   The precise timing and motivation of the cruise missile attack
has raised questions, with some of Clinton's critics suggesting
that he might have acted quickly to distract attention from his
personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials point to the fact that long-term planning against
bin Laden was under way at the time of the embassy bombings as
evidence that the cruise missile attack was not hastily improvised
by the White House because of domestic political calculations.
``These things take a long time to plan and work out,'' an official
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet Clinton and his top aides have generally been cautious about
the use of military force and have turned down other proposed
covert raids to capture suspects overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, in fact, the CIA and special forces abandoned a plan to
arrest Radovan Karadzic, the former Bosnian Serb leader charged
with war crimes, after failing to win high-level approval for the
covert operation.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missile strikes against Afghanistan and the Sudan
were a much lower risk operation than the proposed raid against bin
Laden and did not result in any American casualties. But it also
did not bring bin Laden to heel. Administration officials said that
while some other terrorists were killed in the Afghan strike, bin
Laden escaped unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Planning of the cruise missile operation was handled by a small
circle of Clinton's closest national security aides and remains
shrouded in secrecy. But several administration officials agreed to
describe how _ in their view _ bin Laden has become, over the last
several years, the international terrorist viewed as the most
serious threat facing American interests.
</P>
<P>
   Now said to be in his early 40s, bin Laden, an Islamic radical
and exiled scion of an influential and enormously wealthy Saudi
family, was an ally of the United States in the 1980s as a
supporter of the CIA-backed Afghan rebels battling the Soviet
occupying forces.
</P>
<P>
   He used his wealth to contribute millions of dollars to the
rebels' ultimate triumph and is said to have helped recruit and
support thousands of other Arab volunteers who joined the Afghan
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, we thought of him as that nice Saudi businessman
who was supporting the rebels,'' said a former CIA official
involved in the agency's Afghan program.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan, bin Laden
returned to Saudi Arabia and began to support militant Islamic
groups that opposed moderate Arab regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he turned completely against the United States with the
onset of the Persian Gulf crisis after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990. He saw the presence of hundreds of thousands of U.S. and
other foreign troops on Saudi soil as a deep religious affront _
the return of barbarian Crusaders to defile Islam's holy places.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to wage war against the U.S. presence in Saudi Arabia
and the Saudi leaders who had brought them into the country.
American officials now say they believe that it was not a
coincidence that the two embassy bombings in Africa occurred Aug.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years earlier on that date, the first U.S. forces landed
in Saudi Arabia as part of the effort to protect Saudi Arabia from
Iraq, which had invaded Kuwait on Aug. 2, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials now believe that bin Laden began his
anti-American terror campaign soon after the end of the Persian
Gulf war, ultimately emerging as the leading individual sponsor of
anti-American terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After being forced out of Saudi Arabia, bin Laden moved to
Sudan, where he invested in a wide array of businesses and became a
close ally of Hassan Turabi, leader of the Sudan's governing party,
who provided state support for bin Laden's terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   With an inherited fortune estimated in the hundreds of millions
of dollars, bin Laden created a series of front organizations that
provided the financing and the cover for networks of terrorist
operatives. He supported terrorists in Egypt, Algeria, Yemen, the
Sudan, Lebanon and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   American analysts say they have linked bin Laden and his network
to a wide array of successful terrorist acts as well as aborted
plots, ranging from plans to kill Pope John Paul II and Clinton
during visits to Manila to the botched bombing in December 1992 of
a hotel in Yemen where U.S. soldiers bound for Somalia were
staying, a 1995 attempt to kill Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and a 1995 car bombing in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, that killed five
U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, as other terrorist groups began to fade away
and American experts began to understand bin Laden's significance,
the United States made his group a major focus of its
counterterrorism efforts.
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1993, in fact, federal officials say, bin Laden had
become the subject of FBI scrutiny after the New York World Trade
Center bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a back-channel meeting was held between U.S. and
Sudanese officials in Europe, during which the U.S. officials
warned the Sudanese that evicting bin Laden was one of several
preconditions their government would have to meet before gaining
international legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, bin Laden left the Sudan for Afghanistan, but U.S.
officials insist that Sudanese leaders never severed their ties to
him.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, bin Laden had emerged as the leading target of the
CIA's Counterterrorism Center, the government's central
clearinghouse for intelligence on terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   He was named in a secret presidential covert action order on
terrorism signed by Clinton that authorized intelligence agencies
to plan and carry out covert operations that might lead to some
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials are barred by executive order from planning an
assassination. But a ``lethal'' presidential order, or finding, is
a recognition that the action contemplated could lead to some of
those involved being killed. Such a finding would permit bin
Laden's inadvertent death in a military operation against his
network.
</P>
<P>
   To track his activities, the National Security Agency's
eavesdropping satellites were used to listen in on conversations of
his operatives throughout the world, while spy satellites that take
photographs from space allowed CIA analysts to monitor his training
camps.
</P>
<P>
   With so many intelligence resources targeted against bin Laden,
CIA analysts were able to determine that in January, he held a
meeting with leading members of his network to prepare for a new
wave of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   He soon publicly announced his intentions when he issued a
``fatwa'' or edict, calling on Muslims to kill Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were reams of intel documenting bin Laden before,'' the
embassy bombings in East Africa, a U.S. official said. Another
official said, ``We've had the book on this guy for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point in this period _ officials declined to specify
precisely when _ federal prosecutors in New York obtained a sealed
indictment that charged him with terrorism crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the chief U.S. delegate to the United Nations, Bill
Richardson, traveled to Afghanistan and called on the Taliban, the
fundamentalist movement that controls most of the country, to
extradite him. The Taliban refused, and U.S. officials apparently
abandoned diplomatic efforts to negotiate the handover of bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Richardson's talks with the Taliban, criminal
charges had not yet been formally issued against bin Laden in the
United States, but federal prosecutors in New York were already
working on a criminal case against him, officials said. Federal
prosecutors later did obtain a sealed indictment against bin Laden
from a New York grand jury charging him with terrorist crimes. The
indictment, returned in the months before the Aug. 7 embassy
bombings in Africa, would have provided the legal basis for bin
Laden's capture and arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Also in this period, military and intelligence officials began
drawing up plans either to capture bin Laden or to deal a blow to
his network through other options under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   While those plans received high-level attention, officials
caution that it is not clear that any of them were ready to be
carried out before the terrorist attacks in Africa. As a result,
officials stressed that there is no sense of regret among
policy-makers that they waited too long to go after bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials familiar with the planning for the covert raid
to capture bin Laden inside Afghanistan also emphasized that the
risky nature of the mission, rather than any political calculation
in Washington, was behind its ultimate rejection. Some officials
said the planning needed much more work before it could have gone
forward.
</P>
<P>
   To be successful, a covert raid into Afghanistan would almost
certainly have required the assistance or acquiescence of
neighboring Pakistan, which could have provided the staging area
for launching the mission.
</P>
<P>
   But over the centuries, Afghanistan has been the deathbed of
invading armies, and the bid to extract the well-defended bin Laden
from his haven in the lawless Afghan wilds could have ended badly
for U.S. forces even with Pakistani support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
