A1003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRONX-POLITICS-NYT     09-05 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD FEUD DOMINATES CAMPAIGN SEASON IN BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the bustle of rush hour one recent afternoon, the
Espada brothers took their political campaigns to the busy
intersection of Westchester and Morrison avenues in the Bronx,
accompanied by a small army of supporters with bullhorns, bright
red campaign placards and white T-shirts bearing the images of the
brothers, Pedro Espada Jr. and Jose Espada.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, the Espada campaign had been outmaneuvered by a
convoy of sound trucks blaring the name of Ruben Diaz Jr., the
state assemblyman whom Jose Espada is trying to unseat. Suddenly,
Diaz himself appeared at the very corner where the Espadas were
busy campaigning. To this political duel, Diaz brought his own
campaign shirts and posters along with his vans, offering the
pounding rhythms of salsa.
</P>
<P>
   While this year's primary season offers a number of highly
competitive races in New York City, it would be difficult to find
any as boisterous, turbulent or bitter as the ones being waged by
the Espada brothers against Diaz and David Rosado, the state
senator who is Pedro Espada's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The two races in the Sept. 15 primary are linked by a tangled
history of political revenge that serves as the backdrop to
campaigns that pit one family against the Bronx Democratic
organization in a blood feud. The Espadas, who contend that the
Democratic organization has tried to lock them out of politics in
the borough, are looking for a political grand slam by having two
more family members elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   The party organization is seeking to use its muscle to hold the
Espadas at bay, and its candidates in these races are seen as being
especially strong. Rosado, 56, who was an assemblyman and city
councilman before going to the Senate, is well known in the 32nd
Senate District. Diaz, 25, was a Democratic district leader before
he was elected to the Assembly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bronx produces few challengers as formidable as Pedro
Espada Jr. Espada, 44, was a state senator for four years. But a
dispute between him and Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx
Democratic chairman, resulted in a break with the organization.
Espada was challenged and removed from the Democratic ballot in
1996, and Rosado was elected to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   In that same election year, Espada's son _ Pedro Gautier Espada,
then a freshman assemblyman _ was also removed from the Democratic
ballot and Diaz was elected to the Assembly seat.
</P>
<P>
   But the Espada family got its first taste of revenge last year,
when Pedro Gautier Espada, 25, was elected to the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Espada Jr., who continues to be called ``senator'' by his
associates, operates a large health clinic in the Soundview section
of the Bronx and employs hundreds of workers. He has indicated that
he will spend up to $150,000 in the primary and that Jose Espada's
Assembly contest will probably cost $75,000 _ both large amounts
for such local races.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue in the race is the indictment in June of Pedro
Espada Jr., who was arraigned with two employees on charges that
they illegally diverted $221,000 in Medicaid money to his failed
1996 re-election campaign and that of his son, Pedro Gautier
Espada.
</P>
<P>
   Espada has maintained that he is innocent and that the
indictment is politically motivated, accusing the Democratic Party
organization in the Bronx of seeking retribution for his decision
to challenge Rosado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the voters in this district don't know who David
Rosado is,'' Espada said in an interview while campaigning with his
brother and his 67-year-old father. ``He hasn't been an articulate
or viable representative of our community. Many people still think
that I'm still their senator. And there is no question in my mind
that I will be victorious, I guarantee that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Espada, 42, who owns an ambulette company, criticized
Diaz's term in the Assembly, saying his opponent had not
sufficiently tackled problems in the district's public schools. On
his own platform, Jose Espada said, ``We should start increasing
the standards in education.'' He added, ``If there is funding we
can bring into these public schools, we should do that.''
</P>
<P>
   To add to the campaign frenzy, Jose Espada is running for a
Democratic district leader position in one Assembly district
against Luis Sepulveda, a lawyer supported by the Democratic
organization, while in another district Councilman Pedro Gautier
Espada is running against Rosado for a party leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz is running what Bronx politicians, even the Espadas,
recognize is a vigorous campaign in the 75th Assembly District. His
image has become a fixture in the district, with blue posters
bearing his picture seemingly at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Although Diaz is spending less than his opponent _ about $40,000
by his own account _ he, too, has a network of family support. He
is often joined on the campaign trail by his wife, his brother, his
mother and his father, the Rev. Ruben Diaz, a Pentecostal minister
who runs three nonprofit centers for the elderly and is the leader
of an association of Hispanic ministers. In addition, Diaz is
receiving strong assistance from the Bronx Democratic organization,
with Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president, as his campaign
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz said he was proud of his two years in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our office has dealt with the concerns of close to 9,000
constituents since I've been in office,'' Diaz said. In his
campaign speeches, he discusses what he calls the nitty-gritty of
elective politics, from getting a natural-gas boiler in Public
School 107 to adding speed bumps in the quiet, Harding Park section
of the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have accomplished tangible things that affect the daily
lives of the residents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado has run a somewhat less visible campaign, in part, he
said, because of weeks he took off to recuperate from surgery.
Since then, he said, he has campaigned daily at subway stops and
mailed more than 200,000 pieces of campaign literature to residents
of the Senate district, which includes the neighborhoods of Mott
Haven, Hunts Point, Soundview, Castle Hill and Parkchester.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado counters his opponent's criticism by contending that
Espada, while in his last year in office, missed roughly half the
votes. ``He was a no-show in the Senate,'' Rosado said. ``As for my
own performance, I have been dealing with the many concerns of my
constituents. As a Democrat, I'm in the minority in the Senate. So,
under the circumstances, you do as much as you can. I give myself a
B-plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosado said that by primary day he will likely have spent up to
$80,000 on his re-election campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
