<HEADLINE>
TENNIS COLUMN: WORKING WITH YOUTH IN THE ASHE TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rodney Harmon grew up in Richmond, Va., three houses
away from tennis courts that, like the main court at the U.S. Open,
are now named for Arthur Ashe. A life in tennis, though not likely,
was at least a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived on the same side of town as Arthur; my grandmother
knew his mother, and everyone there knew tennis because of him,''
Harmon said Saturday. ``So even though I wasn't from a wealthy
family and it wasn't like anyone said, `Oh, you should take tennis
lessons,' it wasn't like I had to go very far to play some
tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked into the park one day, into an Ashe-inspired urban
grass-roots program, and didn't come out until he was good enough
to receive a scholarship to a rich kids' tennis school, the
Bollettieri Academy. Then it was on to Southern Methodist
University and the men's pro tour for a half-dozen years, until
1986.
</P>
<P>
   He never set the world on fire, but he did make it, with
assistance, which is the only way for an African-American kid from
a poor or lower-middle-class family, whose father isn't one in a
million.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't, in other words, Richard Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``An aberration,'' Harmon said of the man who raised two tennis
players in an area of Los Angeles, Compton, not exactly known for
serve and volley. ``You're not going to find many minority parents
who will step in and take over the development. It's a daunting
task.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was a week old for everyone else, but the Open
was just getting started Saturday for Harmon, the 37-year-old
director of multicultural development for the U.S. Tennis
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the minority juniors he has been watching over the past
13 months _ like Levar Harper-Griffith out of Brooklyn _ were
checking in, preparing to go to work Sunday on the outer regions of
the National Tennis Center, dreaming of the show courts, where
Williams, almost miraculously, has steered two daughters, all by
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams failed to survive the third round, bumped from
her first Open by, of all people, Irina Spirlea on Friday night.
But her big sister Venus sauntered into Ashe Stadium on Saturday
and toyed with Larisa Neiland for a few games before the veteran
Latvian's back began to hurt and she retired.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams was wearing the third of seven sleeveless outfits
_ blue top, yellow skirt _ that she brought to New York, a message
that she likes her chances of making her second straight final. In
three rounds here, she has lost a grand total of five games. She
could lose before the semis, especially in the quarters, to Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario or Anna Kournikova, but that's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   When she showed up here for the first time last year, you could
feel the country-clubbers just waiting for Venus Williams to fail.
She had snubbed the juniors, their rankings, their lifestyle. The
fact that Venus Williams, one year later, is now taken for granted
as a late-round fixture is remarkable in itself, though it doesn't
exactly foretell a generation of inner-city kids about to be
home-schooled for a career in tennis by Dad.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it has been years since Richard Williams and his
daughters actually lived in anything close to a city. Their
official residence in the Women's Tennis Association player guide
is listed as Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., heart of American tennis
country, an important context to some bizarre commentary by the
Williamses during the first week of the Open.
</P>
<P>
   First, Serena volleyed contentiously with reporters over the
origin of the word ``ghetto.'' Then her father told a New York Post
reporter that he thought the Open should be moved to Compton.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Richard Williams should roll down the window of the car
shuttling him in and out of the National Tennis Center, which
happens to be in the heart of an area rich in minority culture. The
problem with the Open is not where it is; it is how to bring into
the sport working-class people who don't have an advocate as
skilled and single-minded as he is.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of Harmon's job, despite some recent criticism that
the USTA was more interested in a ceremonial position and had not
provided the necessary money and staffing.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would have a budget of about $500,000, but conceded
that he could spend a whole lot more than that. For the serious
junior player, he said, it costs about $30,000 a year for the
lessons, the coaching, the travel. His goal is to spread his wealth
around as much as he can, but then most players operate on budgets
that are too tight. And since the boys tend to develop late, it's
difficult to pinpoint the best prospects when they are 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at all the great players, someone _ a parent or
coach _ took over their development when they were still very
young,'' Harmon said. ``We're trying to be that for the minority
community. But it's not easy. In fact, it's exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Ashe never gave up, though. Harmon can trace his job, and
his tennis life, to that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
