<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVANISEVIC AND RAFTER SET FOR SMASHING MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eager to get down to what for him has historically
been the risky business of surviving the first week of the U.S.
Open, Goran Ivanisevic clocked in early enough at the National
Tennis Center before Saturday morning's straight-set dismissal of
Paul Haarhuis to check his mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Inside it, the game's most erratic shotmaster found a most
unusual gift: an early birthday present from a female fan. His
admirer wanted him to have something different when he celebrated
his 27th birthday on Sept. 13, which also happens to be the date
that this 1998 Open will appoint its men's champion.
</P>
<P>
   Given a choice of birthday presents, Ivanisevic, who is not
quite resigned to sidekick status in the game's record books as the
best player never to win a Grand Slam tournament, would select the
men's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the question I've been hearing for the last six
or seven years, always the same question, and always the same
stupid answer,'' the 14th-seeded Ivanisevic said after firing 21
aces in the 7-6 (7-5), 6-3, 6-4 victory that left him four rounds
short of collecting this Grand Slam event's highest honor. ``I know
I'm maybe the best player never to win a Grand Slam, but I'm
trying. There's a chance I can win this one.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ivanisevic said the odds of his proudly displaying the
Open's trophy back home for show-and-tell in Split, Croatia, were
much better than his flashing around the shiny new handcuffs that
drew a big crowd, including his next opponent, the Open's defending
champion, Patrick Rafter, when he unveiled them in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty weird stuff,'' Ivanisevic said about the first
pair of handcuffs he had ever seen, much less owned. ``In Croatia,
things like that you hide.''
</P>
<P>
   But invisible handcuffs like the ones that have clamped down and
prevented him from winning any of the three Wimbledon finales he
has reached, including this year's loss to Pete Sampras, have
wrought a kind of mental bondage Ivanisevic has been only too
familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when I have to play against both me and the other
guy,'' Ivanisevic said of his history of self-destructive behavior
at Grand Slam events, particularly here at the Open, where he had
taken a first-round dive in three of his last four appearances.
``But lately I'm playing most of the time against the other guy,
not against myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After putting an end to a five-match losing streak against the
32-year-old Haarhuis, Ivanisevic contended that he is playing so
superbly at the Open that he intends to use serves, volleys and
passing shots to handcuff his pal Rafter in their Round of 16
clash. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe the best I've ever played at the U.S. Open,'' he
said of his form through three rounds, ``but it doesn't mean
anything. He's confident, I'm confident, but somebody has to win,
so it's going to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanisevic defeated Rafter in the fourth round at Wimbledon in
1996 in their only previous meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident in my head,'' Ivanisevic said, ``but
sometimes I get a little bit messed up there. I have to bang it,
then everything comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, after receiving a fright when he opened his title
defense of his first Grand Slam crown by scrambling out of a
five-set trap laid by Hicham Arazi, has conscientiously cruised
through the subsequent rounds in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 66-minute demolition of David Nainkin, the
188th-ranked qualifier who knocked out Gustavo Kuerten, the 1997
French Open champion, was representative of Rafter's Open game
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never feel badly about winning,'' the third-seeded Rafter
said. ``You want to get on and get off the court as quick as you
possibly can, conserve your energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter did just that in Saturday's 6-1, 6-1, 6-1 victory, his
quickest ever at a Grand Slam event, which moved him into the Round
of 16 opposite Ivanisevic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After sharing a laugh at Ivanisevic's mailbox before their
respective third-round victories, Rafter promised that he and the
iconoclastic Croat would be all business in the fourth round.
``When we get on, there will be no love lost,'' Rafter said.
``We'll be doing our business, and when we get off, we'll be good
mates. He's crazy, likes to have fun, and that sort of suits in
well with my personality.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Rafter, Ivanisevic wasn't kidding when he predicted
that this Grand Slam tournament could be the one where he finally
breaks through the barrier that has kept him from capturing a major
championship. ``He's knuckled down this year,'' Rafter said, ``he's
got his mind on the job in the last three or four months.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter has done much the same thing this summer after an
indifferent start to the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a dangerous man,'' Rafter added about Ivanisevic. ``He
can do anything and nothing on a given day; when he's on, he's on.
There's not too many better players running around than Goran when
he's on.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded Venus Williams, last year's runner-up, defeated
Larisa Neiland, after the 32-year-old Latvian retired from their
match after just five games. The 85th-ranked Neiland has been
bothered by chronic back trouble, and it flared up Saturday just 13
minutes into the match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
