<HEADLINE>
MOYA WIN OVER CHANG TAKES TOLL ON BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-USOPEN) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first thing Carlos Moya did after Michael Chang's
final backhand return flew long was to drop to his knees, which is
a reaction more commonly associated with winning a Grand Slam
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   All Moya had done was win a second-round match, but there were
good reasons for his temporary loss of balance. He had saved three
match points; he had erased a two-set deficit for the first time in
his career, and he had beaten a tenacious American whose record at
the U.S. Open takes a lot longer to examine than his own.
</P>
<P>
   Chang first played here in 1987 and has reached two
quarterfinals, two semifinals and a final. Moya first played in
1996 and had never reached the third round until Friday night, or,
more accurately, Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Moya did not finish off his 3-6, 1-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-3
victory at the National Tennis Center in Flushing Meadows, N.Y.,
until 1:33 a.m. The match had lasted 3 hours 51 minutes, longer
than any match yet this year at the Open, and it had exacted a toll
on both men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am probably going to dream about missed chances,'' said
Chang, who was relentless in the first two sets but failed to
convert any of his three match points on Moya's serve in the 10th
game of the third set.
</P>
<P>
   Moya had to wait some time to get the chance to dream. After
donning a T-shirt on which he had scrawled a birthday message to
his mother, he slumped into his courtside chair and draped a towel
over his head. He was beginning to cramp in his left thigh and
lower back, and by the time he reached the locker room, he was
stretched out with the physical therapists working overtime. At
2:15 a.m., he was still flat on his back on a training table,
wincing occasionally as a masseur kneaded his leg. ``My head felt
fine, which is not always the case in matches like this for me,''
Moya said, ``but my body was having some trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya had a memorable spring, winning one of the most lucrative
events on the tour in Monte Carlo and then winning his first Grand
Slam event at the French Open in Paris six weeks later. But with
the change of seasons and the change of surface from European clay
to North American cement, he has struggled: losing in the first
round in Cincinnati to Jerome Golmard, a Frenchman who is no
household name even in France, and losing in the first round in
Indianapolis to Thomas Johansson, who would have trouble drawing a
crowd in his native Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Moya does draw in Spain, but though he spends the bulk of his
time training on clay in Barcelona with Alex Corretja, Felix
Mantilla, Albert Costa and the other members of Spain's predictably
nicknamed ``Armada,'' he is no clay-court specialist. His first
Grand Slam success came at the Australian Open in 1997, where he
defeated Chang in the semifinals in straight sets on the Rebound
Ace hardcourt in Melbourne before losing to Pete Sampras in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, shortly before the U.S. Open, he won the warm-up
tournament in Long Island, defeating the eventual Open champion
Patrick Rafter in the final. But an arm injury, aggravated in that
match, contributed to his first-round loss to Guillaume Raoux in
the main event.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Moya is healthy. ``This was not Carlos' greatest
match,'' said his coach, Josep Perlas, of the Chang comeback. ``But
I think in the situation he was in, where he hasn't played many
matches lately, he showed lots of patience and lots of poise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
