<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-DEVELOP-REAL-885(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHICAGO RESIDENTIAL DISTRICT IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JILL SCHACHNER CHANEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A handful of developers are creating a new residential
neighborhood in a former industrial area of this city, just blocks
away from the Loop central business district.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Fulton River District, the area embraces about 10
square blocks. Within the next three years it will have as many as
3,000 units of newly constructed town houses and apartments in low-
and high-rise buildings as well as loft conversions, according to
current plans.
</P>
<P>
   The area is bounded by the north branch of the Chicago River on
the east side and the city's wholesale meat and produce market on
the southwest side.
</P>
<P>
   Developers are attracted to it because of the availability of
relatively large tracts of vacant land so close to the Loop, said
Tracy Cross of Tracy Cross &AMP; Associates, real-estate market
analysts in Schaumburg, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Because developers do not have to raze existing structures for
their new projects, prices for newly constructed town houses and
apartments are approximately $40 to $50 per square foot less than
comparable properties being built in established city neighborhoods
like Lincoln Park or Lakeview, Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never have been able to afford our place in Lincoln
Park,'' said Beth Wexler, 28, a real estate agent with Jameson
Realty Group in Chicago who, with her husband, Michael, bought a
2,200-square-foot town house in Fulton Station, one of the
district's new developments. ``We paid approximately $150 per
square foot. In Lincoln Park we could not have touched this same
place for under $200 per square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The construction of the first phase of Fulton Station, which
will consist of 24 town houses and 80 apartments in two seven-story
buildings, is two-thirds finished, said David Ruttenberg, a
developer with the Belgravia Group.
</P>
<P>
   Closings on two of the town houses have occurred and more will
take place at a rate of one a week. The two apartment buildings
also are nearly completed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruttenberg said he offered all the town houses when he began
sales in the spring of 1997, and all of them now are sold. Only 104
of the 174 apartments planned in the total project have been
offered for sale so far. Of those, 42 are under sales contract.
</P>
<P>
   The town houses range in price from $300,000 to $350,000, while
the apartments are priced from $142,000 for a one-bedroom unit to
$450,000 for three-bedroom duplex units on the top floors of the
mid-rise apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the development, which will be the
completion of two additional apartment buildings with a total of 96
units, is financed. Construction is slated to begin on the third
building this month, with completion scheduled for the fall of
1999. The fourth building should be completed by the winter of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ruttenberg does not intend to expand the development beyond the
current plans, in part because of the need to heavily landscape the
three-acre parcel of vacant industrial property he is developing,
including the creation of two parks to help change the feel of the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary to attract the buyers that we want to come
here sooner or later,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton River District still has a distinctly gritty,
industrial feel from the presence of working train tracks bisecting
the area, numerous abandoned industrial sites and a few remaining
working factories, including Blommer Chocolate Co., which permeates
the area each day with the scent of its product.
</P>
<P>
   At Kinzie Park, a new $120 million development that borders the
Chicago River on one side and commuter-train tracks on the other,
developers plan to build 350 units on a six-acre parcel to create a
``garden in the city'' effect to attract buyers to their gated
community of luxury town houses and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The development will have brick-paved streets, fountains and a
landscaped walkway along parts of the property that border the
river, said Ronald Shipka Sr., president of Enterprise Development
Co., which is developing the property in a joint venture with
Habitat Co. of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for Kinzie Park call for 90 town houses, a 39-story
apartment building with 186 units and a seven-story apartment
building with 54 units. Sales prices range from $155,000 for a
one-bedroom apartment in the high-rise to nearly $1 million for a
4,000-square-foot town house bordering the river.
</P>
<P>
   Shipka and his development partners say they believe that living
on or near the Chicago River will soon be considered an amenity for
which buyers will be willing to pay more, much as they do for
proximity to Lake Michigan. The prices for the riverfront town
houses have increased by $150,000 since they began selling last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 172 of Kinzie Park's units, including 45 town houses and
46 apartments in the mid-rise building, have been sold. Buyers
include young families, professionals who work in the Loop and
older married couples moving back to the city after their children
have moved out of their suburban homes.
</P>
<P>
   Because the entire project has been financed, according to
Shipka, the entire project is already under construction. The
mid-rise apartment building and 45 of the town houses will be
completed first, with the closings scheduled for spring. The
high-rise building will be completed in the year 2000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   u fxxnt06 nt17 nt22 nt26 nt10 nt32 &QL; 
ufxx nypt &QL; 
 &UR; BC-CHICAGO-DEVELOP-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHICAGO: year 2000. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These gated, luxury developments are a far cry from the first
projects in the area, said Michael Lerner, president of MCZ
Development Corp., who is credited with starting the development
trend in the Fulton River District.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner began converting timber lofts out of vacant warehouses
and other storage buildings in the district three years ago on a
hunch. He had seen loft buyers stretch to move to other undeveloped
areas. ``This area was remote, but it did have the proximity to
downtown Chicago,'' he said. ``But the building just stood out
there alone. There were no neighborhood amenities or conversions.''
</P>
<P>
   His success in selling out the first two projects in the area _
the 112-unit China Club Lofts and the 180-unit Clinton Street Lofts
_ convinced him and other developers that the Fulton River District
was ripe for more expensive development.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner is now completing the conversion of Randolph Place, the
former headquarters of Chicago and Northwestern Railroad, into a
$100 million development of 350 apartments and a mix of commercial
uses including a restaurant, spa and convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   All but 10 of the units are sold, he reported.
</P>
<P>
   As buyers continue to flock to the Fulton River District, other
developers are investing in more expensive residential projects.
The Levy Organization recently sold almost a third of its vacant
3.3-acre parcel of riverfront property, where the Chicago River
branches north, to Bejco Development Corp., which will build a
38-story apartment building and four riverfront town houses that
may be as large as 6,000 square feet each.
</P>
<P>
   Bejco's project will be linked to the Levy Organization's
planned commercial development of two office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Spathies, president of Bejco, said the high-rise would
house 140 to 160 apartments, to be sold at an average of $250 per
square foot when they go on the market this fall. All the units
will face the river, with unobstructed views of downtown Chicago,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spathies says she believes the growth of the area can
support the prices she plans to charge. ``It is a vibrant area,''
she said. ``A lot of funky things are happening there. It also is
an alternative to the congestion of Michigan Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some buyers also see nothing but a rosy future for the Fulton
River District.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Good, an insurance agent who is single, said he bought a
two-bedroom apartment at Fulton Station because he believed it
would be a good investment. Three years ago, Good, 34, bought a
loft apartment on the east side of the Chicago River in a
then-developing neighborhood called River North and ``watched the
area go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in two years this area will be more residential than
River North.'' he said. ``It will be totally different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
