<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-1STLD-W     09-05 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES ARRIVE AT CRASH SITE AS SALVAGE EFFORTS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds comments from victims' relatives; polishing and tightening
throughout.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-0136 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Busloads of grieving relatives made their
way Saturday morning to the rocky spit of land closest to the
sunken wreckage of Swissair Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   The first buses began driving up the narrow, winding road to
Peggy's Cove, a fishing village and tourist attraction about 20
miles southwest of here, early Saturday. The somber passengers,
nearly all clutching flowers, walked past the white light house
with its red top and made their way onto a jetty, where the surf
pounded against the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Some were followed by chaplains, others by Red Cross volunteers
carrying boxes of tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making the trip was Tim Larson, 39, of East
Hartford, Conn., whose wife's uncle, Victor Rizza, 58, a Sicilian
chemistry professor, died in the crash with her cousin Antonino,
15. They were returning home after a five-week visit to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out on the seascape, which is a popular subject on
picture postcards here, Larson suppressed a sob. ``This is such a
pretty place,'' he said, his voice cracking. ``You read about this
stuff and you see it, and it's never supposed to happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he prepared to go down to the water's edge. ``We're going
to say a prayer and just try to take it in,'' he said. ``It's just
something to hold onto.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early afternoon an elderly man collapsed on the rocky
jetty and was carried off on a stretcher and taken to a local
hospital. Officials said it was unclear whether he had slipped on
the rocks or suffered a seizure or heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   As the families struggled to come to terms with their loss,
Canadian officials stepped up their efforts to recover the bodies
of the victims and pieces of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The fog, rain, and high seas that hampered the early search and
salvage efforts finally subsided Saturday, and although a brisk
north wind continued to blue, officials said they were hopeful that
search teams would make more progress as they scoured the seas.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, teams of police and military divers were
sent down at the crash site, about five miles off the coast of
Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   And two remote-controlled submersibles equipped with video
cameras were sent to the ocean floor, about 120 feet below the
surface, in several spots where sonar had detected what may be
pieces of the wrecked airplane.
</P>
<P>
   But, much to the frustration of investigators, the single most
important pieces of evidence that would help them piece together
the last moments of the flight _ the so-called black boxes
containing the flight data recorder and the cockpit voice recorder
_ have yet to be found.
</P>
<P>
   The boxes are equipped with audio beacons, or ``pingers,'' that
emit signals for the purpose of helping searchers find them, but no
trace of them has been picked up by sonar or by a Canadian
submarine that combed the area for a second straight day.
</P>
<P>
   Without those pieces of evidence, investigators said, it would
be very difficult to learn what caused the jet, a McDonnell Douglas
MD-11 carrying 229 people from New York to Geneva, to crash into
the water as it tried to make an emergency landing here.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Canadian Transportation Safety Board
continued to pore over the little evidence they had, studying the
transcripts of tape-recorded conversations between the pilot and
the control tower and scrutinizing radar tapes to chart the plane's
final, erratic movements before it went down into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 300 friends and family members who arrived here
Friday on specially chartered flights from New York and Switzerland
longed to learn what had caused the disaster, peppering Canadian
officials with questions at special briefings about the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But others said that it made little difference to them, that the
most important thing was that they had lost the people they loved
and must try to cope with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people who are here, finding out the cause is the
burning issue for them,'' said Claire Mortimer, 45, whose father,
John Mortimer, a former senior vice president of The New York
Times, and stepmother, Hilda Mortimer, died in the crash. ``To me,
it doesn't make a lot of difference, because they're gone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mortimer walked down to the cove holding two pink roses and
a stem of freesia.
</P>
<P>
   About five miles off shore, the crew of the Preserver, a
Canadian naval supply ship, directed a flotilla of more than 30
smaller boats as they picked up debris and body parts from a crash
site that was growing ever wider from wind and tides.
</P>
<P>
   Cpl. Frank Skidmore of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said
that the search area had grown to a 70-square-mile swath of ocean,
and that the Canadian authorities had placed the entire area off
limits to boats and planes for nearly 50 miles of coastline, from
Mahone Bay to the mouth of Halifax Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   On land, 250 Canadian soldiers and 300 volunteers fanned out to
scour the rocky coastline and cobbled beaches to gather the debris
and wreckage that washed ashore.
</P>
<P>
   They preserved everything: the blue sleeping mask with the
Swissair logo, a turtleneck sweater found peeping out from beneath
the sand and twisted pieces of metal and foam that were difficult
to place. It all went into clear plastic evidence bags.
</P>
<P>
   On board the Preserver, all the human remains that were
recovered were carefully labeled according to where they were found
and then flown off the ship by Sea King helicopters. The remains
were taken to a makeshift morgue that was set up in an airplane
hangar at a nearby air base, where a team of pathologists began
trying to identify them through dental records, X-rays and DNA
samples.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the first identification was made. Dr. John Butt,
the chief medical examiner of Nova Scotia, said Friday that in
addition to trying to identify the victims, his team would see
whether the bodies yielded clues to what happened in the last
minutes before the crash. Butt said that investigators have asked
the pathologist to conduct toxicology tests, to try to determine
whether the victims inhaled smoke before they died.
</P>
<P>
   Butt said that a significant number of bags containing human
remains had been brought ashore in the past three days. But family
members were told the unsettling news that almost none of the
bodies that had been found were intact, making visual
identifications impossible in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Many family members have been asked to give small blood samples
to the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, who will use them to compare
DNA samples with the remains.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of operation that Nova Scotia has come to be
familiar with in the four centuries since the first shipwreck was
reported off the treacherous coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous instance was in 1911 when the Titanic went down
700 miles east of here. The Cunard Liner Carpathia took the
survivors to New York; the dead were brought here.
</P>
<P>
   Don Flynn, whose family has run Cruikshank's Halifax Funeral
Home here for generations, said that he was called the night of the
crash and told to begin making preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be our biggest job since my grandfather handled the
Halifax explosion,'' he said, referring to the worst disaster in
Halifax history, when a munitions ship exploded in Halifax harbor
in 1917, killing more than 1,700 and leveling whole neighborhoods
here.
</P>
<P>
   Out at Peggy's Cove, Skidmore said that it was difficult to
watch the family members grieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're devastated by the tragedy, as anyone would be,'' he
said. ``Though they don't expect to find loved ones alive, they're
hopeful that we will at least find identifiable remains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
