<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 AT HOME: SHELTER FROM THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First, the good news: The 1998 hurricane season is
nearly half over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the not-so-good news: We still have the worst half to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hurricane season begins on June 1 and lasts until Nov.
30,'' said Shelly Auster, a spokeswoman for the American Red Cross
of Greater New York. ``But the peak of the season is traditionally
September.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Auster said, while the southern coastal states
typically get the brunt of most Atlantic hurricanes, residents of
the New York City area are not immune from risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to live way out on Long Island to be affected
by a storm,'' she said. ``There are many areas of the city that
experience flooding from relatively small amounts of rain. And even
tropical storms have winds that are strong enough to break windows,
topple trees and knock down power lines.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Auster said, because it is relatively rare for the
New York City area to be hit with the full force of a major
hurricane, people who live here frequently fail to take the
precautions necessary to withstand such a storm when one finally
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In communities where hurricanes are common, people prepare in
advance for the worst,'' she said. ``Here, though, people usually
end up trying to prepare at the last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners in areas of high risk for hurricanes, for example,
often have storm shutters installed on their homes to protect
windows from high winds and flying debris. And while suburban
residents are hardly likely to retrofit their homes with functional
shutters, it might be worth the time and effort, particularly if
the home is near the water, to precut sheets of plywood to fit over
windows and patio doors, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dead tree branch can become an airborne dagger in high
winds,'' Ms. Auster said, adding that if a storm is expected, it is
also critical to take into the house or garage anything that might
turn into a flying object in high winds. That includes lawn
furniture, toys, loose pieces of wood, lightweight tables and
chairs and patio umbrellas. For homeowners with double-width doors
on two-car garages, she said, it is prudent to precut wood beams to
act as a brace for the door to keep it from buckling in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Yagerman, a spokeswoman for the Federal Emergency
Management Agency in Washington, said that homeowners with garages
should make sure to put their cars inside them, particularly in
suburban areas with lots of big, old trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was living in Salem, Massachusetts, I watched a
windstorm knock over a huge tree onto two cars parked in a
neighbor's driveway right in front of an empty garage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Yagerman said, homeowners with double-door
front entrances should install heavy-duty bolts at the top and
bottom of the stationary door to keep it from flying open in a
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bolts or pins on most doors are not strong enough,'' Ms.
Yagerman said, adding that high-strength bolts cost $10 to $40 and
can usually be installed by the homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   In areas that are susceptible to flooding, particularly near the
coast, Ms. Yagerman said added precautions are needed when a
hurricane is predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen flooding move houses off their foundations,'' she
said, pointing out that any house that has had even minor flooding
in the past is a good candidate for more serious flooding during a
serious hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to leave valuable things on lower floors,''
Ms. Yagerman said. ``And if local officials tell you to evacuate
the area, take your important papers and easy-to-carry valuables
with you.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another precaution, she said, is to remove all chemicals and
cleaning products from storage areas in basements and in
first-floor kitchens and bathrooms, to prevent the chemicals from
getting into standing water and injuring residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can get very sick from walking around in chemicals
mixed in standing water in their own basements,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yagerman also said that people with pets should call their
local branch of the American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty
to Animals for information on how to find housing for their pets if
it appears that the home will have to be evacuated in a storm. Most
temporary shelters for evacuees do not allow pets, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mackoul, president of Mackoul &AMP; Associates, an insurance
brokerage company in Lynbrook, said that one thing that every
homeowner should do _ whether or not a storm is imminent or they
have flood insurance _ is to make a room-by-room documentary
videotape of everything in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about jewelry, fine arts, paintings, rugs,
everything,'' Mackoul said. ``If you have all that stuff on tape,
and you have a running commentary about what it is and what it's
worth, you're going to have a baseline for what's in your house in
the event you someday have to file a claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who remain inside their homes during a storm, experts say,
should follow some basic survival rules like stocking up on
provisions _ water, canned food, a manual can opener and batteries
for flashlights and radios _ and should stay away from windows and
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Marian Perkowski, a spokeswoman for the Lightning Protection
Institute, a trade organization of protection contractors in
Arlington Heights, Ill., added that during a severe storm
accompanied by lightning, it is wise to unplug all sensitive
electrical appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a lightning protection system in the house, or
a master surge protector where the electrical service originates,
it's best to unplug the computer, the television and the stereo,''
Ms. Perkowski said. ``Lightning can strike a power line a quarter
of a mile away from your house and still fry your equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, it is wise to stay off the telephone during
a lightning storm _ lightning has been known to travel through
telephone lines _ and to avoid touching other electrical
appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some parents let their kids play video games during a storm,''
Ms. Perkowski said. ``But that's sure not something I would be
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, though it might seem a remote possibility to
be injured by a storm while inside the home, such injuries do
occur. And when they do, there is generally one common denominator,
Ms. Perkowski said: ``Nobody believes something like that could
possibly happen to them _ until it happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
