<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LONG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANIA LONG, 85, WAR CORRESPONDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Canada, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tania Long, a pioneering female war correspondent for The New
York Herald Tribune and The New York Times who covered the London
blitz and the Nuremburg trials, died Friday morning at her home in
Ottawa. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering from a series of illnesses, Ms. Long committed
suicide, said Dr. Guy Genier, a coroner in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a woman of strong character, strong principles,
dedicated to her work,'' said Joan Gordon, a friend of Ms. Long in
Ottawa. ``Her life had become painful to her because of illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Berlin on April 29, 1913, Ms. Long was the daughter of
the Russian-born Tatiana Mouraviev and Robert Crozier Long, a
British journalist. Educated in Germany, France and England, Ms.
Long studied economics, Russian literature and European history at
the Sorbonne in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   She became an American citizen in 1935 and began her
journalistic career a year later as a reporter for The Newark
Ledger in New Jersey. She returned to Berlin in 1938 to work for
The New York Herald Tribune and joined The Tribune's London bureau
in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   In London, she wrote of the city's poor during the blitz and of
the bombing of the Hotel Savoy while she was living there. ``I was
sitting in my third-floor room ready to get into bed when I heard
the bombs coming,'' she wrote. ``Only a split second later the next
bomb hit the cornice of the hotel and went off, and almost
immediately after that the other one hit the rear of the building.
When one hears bombs coming that close, there is not time to do
anything. One hasn't time to be afraid; that comes later.''
</P>
<P>
   During the war, Ms. Long married Raymond Daniell, the London
bureau chief for The New York Times, and she joined The Times as a
reporter in February 1942. When Allied troops invaded Europe, Ms.
Long, who continued to write under her maiden name, followed their
advance, writing stories from liberated towns in France. She
followed the Allied troops in Berlin, apparently the first female
correspondent to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Long and Daniell became a prominent husband-wife
journalistic team, covering the Nuremberg trials and postwar
Germany. Ms. Long spoke the languages of all four occupying powers
_ English, French and Russian _ as well as German.
</P>
<P>
   From 1952 until 1964, she and her husband ran The Times' bureau
in Ottawa, where they became prominent figures in the country's
political and journalistic circles. Honored upon their departure
with a gala attended by the Canadian prime minister, the couple
were hailed in The Ottawa Journal. They returned to Ottawa upon
Daniell's retirement from The Times in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Long's 1932 marriage to Merwin Mallory Gray in Paris ended
in divorce six years later. A son from that marriage, Robert Gray,
died of cancer, said Sarah Jennings, a Canadian arts journalist and
a family friend. Daniell also died of cancer, in 1969. In the
1970s, Ms. Long became the first publicist for the National Arts
Center of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of the breed of women that came out of the wartime
era,'' said Ms. Jennings, ``most of whom were happily married and
supportive of their husbands but in and of themselves were very
strong-willed and independent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      09-05 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: JAPAN'S VERY TIMID PRESCRIPTION FOR CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The frantic U.S. efforts to get Japan to act boldly to cure its
financial crisis remind me of the time my mother got sick in Japan
and was rushed to the hospital, where the Japanese doctors' best
attempts to reassure her went awry.
</P>
<P>
   As the doctors called for a battery of sophisticated tests, my
mother mistakenly assumed they were following the U.S. practice of
testing only when something worrisome is suspected. Visibly
anxious, she asked what was wrong. The doctors thought she was
doubting their thoroughness, so they ordered even more tests. The
more the doctors tried to reassure my mother, the worse she felt.
</P>
<P>
   The same wide cultural gap afflicts the anguished dialogue
between U.S. and Japanese financial officials. The United States is
demanding root canal surgery on Japanese banks as the best way to
instill confidence in the system. The more banks shut down, the
more bad loans disclosed and written off, the better. Japan
counters that these steps will lead to panic, bank withdrawals and
declining confidence in the nation's economic future _ the opposite
of what is intended.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Wall Street worry that Japan's anemic financial
policies are likely to keep its economy moribund and prevent
recovery throughout Asia, possibly leading to a financial collapse
that will make the recent turmoil in world markets look like a
warm-up. Indeed, as Kenneth Courtis of Deutsche Bank has noted,
Japan is more internationally isolated today than at any time since
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's problems are summed up in the career of Kiichi Miyazawa,
the 78-year-old former prime minister brought in by the new prime
minister, Keizo Obuchi, to oversee the economy. Sharp, charming and
unflappable _ as anyone who watched him cradle a sick President
George Bush in his arms in 1991 will long remember _ Miyazawa began
his career as a young Finance Ministry bureaucrat after the war who
resented being lectured by Gen. Douglas MacArthur. In his memoirs
he wrote that ``it may be hard for young people today to understand
how unpleasant it was to live under the occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   Any such person is unlikely to listen to American lectures, even
during a crisis. But because Miyazawa is considered a giant who
helped nurture the Japanese postwar miracle of state-supported
capitalism, with all its coziness and impenetrability, he is
especially unlikely to walk away today from a system that he feels
brought Japan back from the rubble and defeat of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   People who know him say he embraces the ``soft landing'' school
of Japanese finance, in that he feels a little more stimulus, and a
little more openness in its banking system, will pull Japan out of
its slump without causing undue panic.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to U.S. officials, is that the most
recent Japanese program is barely enough to reverse the negative
effects of Japan's ill-timed tax hike last year. Moreover, Japanese
officials are still debating the criteria for auditing the nation's
ailing banks, a bit late considering that this is the seventh year
of the Japanese slump. Tokyo has acknowledged bad debts of $550
billion, but U.S. officials and private experts say they actually
approach $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese inaction goes beyond the cultural to the political.
Those in power in Japan have a strong vested interest in the status
quo. The all-powerful Finance Ministry has no desire to shed
control over the economy. Like Miyazawa, Finance Ministry alumni
who have gone on to wield power in business and politics tend
instinctively to look out for the ministry's interests.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazawa superintends these interests at the Liberal Democratic
Party, which has dominated Japan for nearly all of the last 45
years. Like the old saying about the Holy Roman Empire being
neither holy nor Roman nor an empire, the ruling party is not
liberal or democratic.
</P>
<P>
   It is less a party than a collection of special interests, from
farmers to small businesses, giant corporations and organized
crime, who supply money and resources to the party in return for
its protection. That circle of self-interest serves as a powerful
shield against demands for change.
</P>
<P>
   Add to all these factors the traditional Japanese belief in the
importance of consensus, and it is easy to see why radical reform
is difficult. I have seen schoolchildren spending so much time
trying to choose sides fairly for a baseball game that there is no
time left for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The world economy, of course, is not a game right now. But if
Russia is a one-time superpower flailing about for solutions, the
Japanese spectacle is one of deep-rooted inertia in the face of
genuine crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-0906-     09-05 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLINTON-0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ENDS 'FEEL GOOD' TOUR OF IRELAND, RETURNING TO BAD
FEELINGS AT HOME
 &HT;    (EDs: Optional add after 700 words.)
 &HT;    With IRELAND-DELL-0906.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ A cold rain from the Atlantic paused just
long enough Saturday to provide President Bill Clinton one final
taste of Irish sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of this ancient city, Clinton took the stage to a
flurry of American and Irish flags and more of the welcoming cheers
that have greeted him at every stop on this storied island. An
estimated 20,000 people filled the narrow streets lined with pubs
and shops that lead into Connell Street.
</P>
<P>
   When the president rose to speak on a temporary stage, someone
in the crowd shouted, ``Welcome Mr. Clinton,'' to which the
president replied happily, ``I feel welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential visit provided a welcome spark for the peace
process, which had seemed stalled. A series of important
breakthroughs occurred before and during the trip, with the biggest
coming Saturday before Clinton's departure. David Trimble, the
leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, agreed to meet for the first
time with Gerry Adams, the head of Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which would be symbolically potent, could take
place as early as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had urged direct discussions on Thursday when he was in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another positive development,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   His white shirt gleaming in the late morning sun, the president
bid his farewell to the Irish people, praising them for finding the
road to peace and urging them not to lose their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the leaders in the world, all the speeches in the world
would not amount to a hill of beans if you hadn't gone out and
voted 'yes,' and meant it with every fiber of your being,'' Clinton
said, referring to the Good Friday peace accord and its subsequent
overwhelming support in referendums held in the Irish Republic and
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demons of the past are losing their power to divide you,
and a new and better and more prosperous history is unfolding for
you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also mourned the 29th victim of the Omagh bombing. Sean
McGrath, a 61-year-old baker, died from his wounds Saturday. The
father of four grown children had made the mistake of going to
Omagh's Market Street for a haircut on Aug. 15 and was cut down in
the explosion of a 500-pound car bomb. Thirty victims remain in
hospitals, three of whom are in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton admonished the crowd not to let such acts break their
will for peace. ``Don't do it, Don't do it,'' he said. ``Remember
what it was like when you were here on this day. This is you at
your best. Do not let them break your will.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's problems at home regarding his ``inappropriate
relationship'' with a former White House intern and what is likely
to be an unpleasant return, he remains very popular here -- perhaps
even more popular because of his difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Laffey, a 62-year-old railroad worker, waited more than an
hour behind a metal barricade in the rain just to get a peek at the
president as his black Cadillac whisked by Henry Street. ``I've
come because I want to see him, because of who he is, one of the
greatest presidents in America's history,'' Laffey said. ``Look
what he's done for Ireland. Look what he's done for America, and
he's going to be forced out over what? That thing with that girl?
There but by the grace of God goes just about everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so quick to forgive. ``He's a liar,'' said
Sheila Quilligan, a 28-year-old retail manager standing a few feet
from Laffey. ``He lied to the American people in January and he's
been lying since. I don't hold with liars.''
</P>
<P>
   Quilligan came only at the insistence of her boyfriend, Philip
Ryan, who said too much was being made of Clinton's relationship
with Monica Lewinsky and its messy aftermath. ``Why can't everyone
just let it alone,'' Ryan said. ``It's a private affair.''
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was also welcomed warmly
wherever she went, with each move and expression subjected to
analysis. The Clintons were far from cuddly during the trip, but
there was no obvious sign of of hostility. The first lady bought
the president a bright green Irish wool sweater, which he wore on
Air Force One. She also whispered in his ear on a number of
occasions; they often smiled at each other and he guided her up the
steps to the plane by gently holding her arm.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The president's problems even translated to a business boon for
a shop owner in Ballybunion, the town near the fabled golf course
where Clinton played in the afternoon before heading back to
Washington. The shop, ``Monica's Hair Styles'' was renamed ``The
President's Shop'' for the trip and did a brisk business in
commemorative coffee mugs and T-shirts. Catherine Fitzgerald, the
shop's owner, denied rumors that she'd been paid to make the
change.
</P>
<P>
   In Limerick, Clinton was granted an honorary citizenship, the
``Freedom of the City'' award given 35 years ago to President John
F. Kennedy. Clinton referred to his childhood hero, saying that
Kennedy pledged then to return to Limerick but was assassinated in
Dallas a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not able to fulfill that promise, but I appreciate the
opportunity to renew it, and to thank you for the springtime of
hope the Irish people have given the entire world in 1998,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his speech, Clinton reached over a metal barricade
to shake the hands of people who were pressed against the stage.
Secret Service agents held on by his belt. Some women appeared to
be try to kiss him, others just reached up to touch him.
</P>
<P>
   As he finished a relaxed 18-hole round of golf, Clinton took his
time leaving the course, stopping for photos, chatting easily with
people outside the clubhouse and signing autographs. With a
borrowed pen -- and looking very much the celebrity -- he scribbled
his name on golf caps, scorecards, gloves, whatever was handed to
him.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set over the Atlantic to the west, the direction Air
Force One was poised to return, it seemed as if Clinton, who is not
expected to return here as president, wanted to savor every minute.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
