   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH _ Chapel Hill think tank MDC's latest State of the South
report concludes that old problems and new pressures in
immigration, education, the work force and families threaten the
South's dynamic growth. We visit Hickory, N.C., to talk with people
at Catawba Valley Community College who are caught up in these
changes. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHBOX _ Chart showing that while the percentage of white men
in the labor force in the South has declined in the past 21 years,
the percentage of Hispanic men and women has doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-GAMBLING _ EUPORA, Miss._She's from a two-stoplight town
west of Starkville and east of nowhere. She wears demure church
dresses, plays the piano, and works for a state legislator when
she's not taking care of her two children. And this summer,
Elizabeth Stoner has become a household name in Mississippi. She
filed an initiative in June that would put the issue of riverboat
casinos to a statewide vote, giving Mississippians a chance to kick
the casinos out. If they vote to ban gambling, the 30 riverboats
docked in eight counties along the Mississippi River and the Gulf
Coast would have two years to shut down. (Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BINGO _ ROCK HILL, S.C. - The Indian tribe that didn't really
want to open a bingo parlor because of religious beliefs is now
raking in about $2 million a month at the largest bingo operation
on the Eastern Seaboard. Located in a former Sears Roebuck store on
the edge of this college town, Catawba Bingo offers games every day
except Sunday, luring thousands of folks from all over the
Southeast. On Big Games days, twice each month, the payout is
$200,000 with one game worth $50,000. Folks arrive as early as 10
a.m. for the start of the 1 p.m. games. ``We're doing quite well,''
said Wanda George Warren, the Catawba Indian Nation's executive
director. (Riddle, AJC freelancer; not for use by NYT clients).
</P>
