<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LATE FLAG HELPS VOLS OVERCOME McNABB  
(lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ They don't do things the easy way here at
Syracuse. Right out of the gate, coach Paul Pasqualoni wanted to
see just what he had. No messing around. So he invited Tennessee,
which is ranked 10th in the country, to the Carrier Dome to test
his Orangemen, who are ranked 17th, in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   If Pasqualoni was looking for resiliency and toughness from his
team, he found it. Unfortunately, he had no remedy for fate and an
official's flag late in the game. Benefiting from a late defensive
pass interference call, Tennessee marched down the field in the
last 1 minute 43 seconds, and Jeff Hall kicked a 27-yard field goal
that gave the Volunteers a 34-33 victory over Syracuse before a
raucous crowd of 49,550.
</P>
<P>
   The kick ended a wild back-and-forth game that saw four lead
changes in the fourth quarter. It also spoiled an otherwise
terrific game for quarterback Donovan McNabb, who helped Syracuse
overcome an 11-point third-quarter deficit and score 20 points in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, a Heisman Trophy candidate, did nothing to hinder his
chances. He completed 21 of 27 passes for 298 yards and two
touchdowns, and he rushed for a touchdown. The Volunteers got a
magnificent performance from the sophomore running back Jamal
Lewis, who rushed for 141 yards and one touchdown on 20 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Things do not get any easier this week, because the Orangemen
travel to Ann Arbor to play the University of Michigan. But they
have a great game to build on.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Syracuse might have a victory after a pass by
Tennessee's new quarterback, Tamaurice ``Tee'' Martin, to receiver
Cedrick Wilson on fourth-and-7 at the Vols' 35-yard line fell
incomplete. But the officials called pass interference on
cornerback Will Allen, who was making his first start.
</P>
<P>
   Allen came over the back of Wilson, and two officials waved it
an incomplete pass, but the back judge threw his flag. That gave
the Vols a fresh set of downs at the Syracuse 46, and after they
moved down the field, Hall kicked his game-winner with four seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right call,'' Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer said of the
pass interference.
</P>
<P>
   Said George DeLeone, Syracuse's defensive coordinator: ``I'm not
going to say it was a bad call. I just question why the guy right
on the play calls it an incomplete pass and the guy comes running
in from behind with a late flag.''
</P>
<P>
   The call overshadowed a fantastic fourth quarter in which the
teams dueled on offense and swapped leads as if they were trading
baseball cards. Martin, replacing Peyton Manning, completed just
nine of 26 passes for 143 yards, but he threw two for touchdowns
and finished with 80 yards rushing on nine carries. Martin
benefited greatly from the presence of Lewis, who rushed for 1,364
yards last year as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The first time he touched the ball Saturday afternoon, Lewis
ripped through the Syracuse defense for 30 yards. Martin completed
a 32-yard pass to receiver Jermaine Copeland that moved his team
from the 50 to the Syracuse 16. A couple of plays later, he rolled
out to his right and hit receiver Peerless Price in the flat on a
12-yard touchdown pass. The Vols were up by 7-0 and looked
unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orangemen clamped down after that drive and made
Tennessee earn everything it got in the first half. Syracuse, which
trailed by 14-10 at the half, pulled to within 14-13 early in the
third quarter, but Tennessee put its offense into gear and scored
10 consecutive points on a 1-yard touchdown run by Lewis and a
17-yard field goal by Hall that gave them a 24-13 lead with 3:15
left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orangemen would not go away. They scored 14 points _ on
a 17-yard pass from McNabb to receiver Kevin Johnson and a 7-yard
run by McNabb, plus a 2-point conversion run by Ian McIntosh _ in
under three minutes to take their first lead, 27-24.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee came back on a 55-yard run by Martin and a penalty
for a late hit out of bounds following the run. That set up an
8-yard touchdown pass from Martin to Price on a third-and-5 at the
8, which helped give Tennessee a 31-27 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse pulled within 31-30 with 6:39 to play on a 41-yard
field goal by Nate Trout that was set up by a 75-yard kickoff
return by McIntosh. Trout added a 19-yard field goal at 2:38 to
give the Orangemen a 33-31 lead, setting up the wild finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this showed that we can go toe-to-toe with a big-time
program,'' DeLeone said. ``Now we can go to Michigan and see what
we can do there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
