<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IRELAND-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON ENDS FOREIGN TOUR DOMINATED BY DOMESTIC ISSUES
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ Even as President Clinton stood in the glow
of a shining foreign policy success the shadow of scandal crept
across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Irish filled this industrial city's streets
Saturday to glimpse Clinton, cheered for his role in the Good
Friday peace accord, as the morning Limerick papers trumpeted the
president's first apology for the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended a six-day tour of Russia, Northern Ireland and
Ireland with the domestic scandal dominating every stop on the
foreign itinerary and aides denying that it was affecting his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's successfully doing the work of our nation here
on the trip and doing what he set out to do on this trip, and he's
not surprised that matters from back home arise. That's not
infrequently the case when this president or any president travels
abroad,'' said Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry spoke of the ``parallel universes we live in'' as
Clinton received warm embraces bordering on adulation from the
Irish while in the United States key Democrats denounced Clinton's
affair with Lewinsky and called for some reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said the president ``takes some satisfaction'' in
his ability to function with world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dealt with world leaders on this trip and (is) confident
that he continues to do good work in the interest of the American
people as he fulfills his constitutional responsibilities,''
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all agree.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, Clinton held a two-day summit in a gray, drizzling
Moscow with President Boris Yeltsin, but produced little progress.
Yeltsin remained unable to form a new government to combat the
financial crisis in his country that threatens its new democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How weak President Clinton is and the extent to which it
limits his international influence is still an open question,''
said Paul Saunders, director of the Nixon Center in Washington.
``It is clearly unconstructive for the president of the United
States to be mocked publicly in a foreign country.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy may have fallen through the basement but street
vendors in Moscow were doing a brisk business selling Clinton
``nesting dolls.'' Most sold out quickly. The dolls, one stacked
within another, features Clinton followed by Lewinsky and other
women inside.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Clinton delivered flat, emotionless speeches about
the need for Russia to stay on the path of market reform. But,
Saunders said Clinton's remarks could anger many Russians who have
lived through years of promises by Yeltsin for reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations for the summit were low going in on both sides
for obvious reasons _ neither president is in a position
domestically to deliver much to the other,'' Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Bush, with the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, called Clinton ``a very effective and articulate
communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said judging from the response of the Russian media and
his Moscow contacts, ``I would venture to suggest that the summit
was virtually irrelevant in the eyes of the Russian public. They
are undergoing a political, economic and financial meltdown, with
no light at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance with Yeltsin at a news conference at
Catherine Hall, an ornate domed rotunda within the Kremlin took on
a surreal air as the president, looking weary and distracted, knew
Americans reporters would be asking questions about Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first meeting with the media since his Aug. 17
national address admitting an inappropriate relationship,
expressing regret for misleading Americans and his family and
attacking Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr for his prolonged
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again turned aside an opportunity to apologize to the
nation and defended his national address as saying what he wanted
to say. The president's reluctance to apologize or display more
contrition apparently helped spark Democrats reaction later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., a Clinton ally, ignored pleas
from the White House to await Clinton's return from overseas to
launch a devastating broadside. Lieberman denounced Clinton's
behavior with Lewinsky as ``immoral'' and not just a private matter
as the president had contended.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received word of Lieberman's address on the Senate floor
as he was making what should have been a triumphant return to
Northern Ireland. The United States helped broker the Good Friday
peace pact which both Protestant and Catholics hope will end
decades of sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   Even the supportive Irish News, with its headline ``Clinton
flies in with a brave message of hope,'' couldn't resist a dig at
the president. Its front page had a small cartoon of the
president's limousine traveling down the road with the song Wild
Thing playing.
</P>
<P>
   In Dublin on Friday morning, with Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern at his side, Clinton issued his first direct apology for the
Lewinsky affair and for misleading America. He said he agreed with
Lieberman's comments about his own behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In Limerick, Clinton, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, drew a huge supportive crowd. Clinton noted that in June
1963, President Kennedy visited Limerick promising to return in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not able to fulfill that promise. But I appreciate the
opportunity to renew it and to thank you for the springtime of hope
the Irish people have given the entire world in 1998,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-based Dell Computers used Clinton's visit to announce an
expansion of its plant in Limerick to create 1,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later played golf in Ballybunion Golf Club, one of the
world's premier courses, before flying back to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   END END
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      09-05 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS OUTCLUB BRAVES, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tony Phillips flew out to end the sixth inning
Saturday, leaving the bases loaded and the Mets trailing the
Atlanta Braves by two runs. But the fiery veteran did not seethe or
sulk; instead, he waited for his next chance.
</P>
<P>
   It came in the eighth inning, with two out, a man on base and
the Mets still trailing, by a run. And Phillips made the most of
it, rocketing a two-run homer over the 396-foot mark in
right-center field. As he made his way around the bases, Phillips
remained calm. But when he crossed home plate, he found the Mets
streaming up onto the steps of the dugout to greet him.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Atlanta in a pitching duel on Friday night, the
Mets won Saturday, 5-4, by outclubbing the Braves at Shea Stadium.
The Mets have maintained in recent days that victories over the
Braves carry no special significance, that they mean no more than
any other victory as the race for the National League's wild-card
berth enters the final stretch. But for the second day in a row,
the emotion they displayed on the field seemed to say otherwise.
The victory left the Mets a half game behind the Chicago Cubs in
the wild-card race, pending the outcome of the Cubs' game Saturday
night in Pittsburgh. It also lifted the Mets 16 games above .500
for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The cheers that rained down on Mike Piazza on Friday, when his
two-run homer off Tom Glavine won the game for the Mets, were
spread among the entire team Saturday by a crowd of 43,573. It put
the Mets' attendance at 2,022,792 for the season, the first time
since 1991 that the team surpassed the 2 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' home run capped a day of comebacks for the Mets, who
erased a 1-0 deficit early and then trailed by 4-2 before coming
back in their final two at-bats. Turk Wendell earned the victory
with a 1-2-3 eighth inning and John Franco earned his 32nd save by
holding off the Braves in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza continued to be in the middle of Mets rallies. He singled
in the seventh inning to send John Olerud to third base with one
out. When Brian McRae grounded to second, Ozzie Guillen's relay
throw tipped off the fingers of the sliding Piazza. McRae was safe
as the ball skipped in the dirt and Olerud scored on the play to
cut the Braves' lead to 4-3. Piazza received treatment on his hand
and remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets threatened in the fourth inning against the Braves'
starter, Kevin Millwood, loading the bases with two out, but could
not score. Brian McRae fouled back the first pitch to him and
Millwood walked off the mound, while the Braves trainer and manager
Bobby Cox came out to investigate. After a moment, Millwood resumed
pitching and McRae drilled his first pitch into left field for a
single. After a passed ball moved McRae to second, Millwood walked
Lenny Harris and Carlos Baerga. But Rey Ordonez flew out to center.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones then put the Braves on top, driving Bobby Jones'
first pitch in the top of the fifth inning over the bleachers in
left-center field for a 457-foot home run, his 26th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones avoided further damage when McRae made a spectacular
grab in center field. Following the home run, Greg Colbrunn reached
base when he was hit in the arm by an off-speed pitch. Then, with
one out, Millwood failed to bunt Colbrunn to second and on a 1-1
count, he swung away and delivered a long drive to straightaway
center. McRae hesitated for a moment and then raced back to the
warning track, reaching out over his left shoulder to snatch the
ball out of the air.
</P>
<P>
   But no one could save Jones in the sixth inning. After Olerud
had briefly given him a 2-1 lead with a two-run homer, his 19th,
Jones could not protect it. Chipper Jones drilled a one-out single
through the box and after a walk to Ryan Klesko, Javy Lopez ripped
Bobby Jones' next pitch up the middle for a run-scoring single.
After Andruw Jones loaded the bases on a roller that stayed just
fair, Colbrunn delivered a drive to the wall in left field.
Phillips raced back, appearing to zero in on it, but the ball
skimmed just past his glove as he collided with the wall and
Colbrunn cruised into second with a two-run double, for the Braves'
4-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
