<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 9/5/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MIAMI -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- FLA-CUBA-CULTURE, 9-5 --
Carlos Varela, 35, a Cuban singer-songwriter, has been described by
music critics as the voice of Cuba's disgruntled youth. A
songwriter in the tradition of Bob Dylan and Bruce Springsteen, his
music is banned from Miami radio. In Miami, many Cuban-Americans
shun Cuba-based artists as envoys of the Cuban government and take
offense at their presence in exile territory. (Andrew Itkoff/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- CRASH-RDP,
9-5 -- A mourner for the victims of Swissair Flight 111, on the
seascape of Peggy's Cove, the rocky spit of land closest to the
sunken wreckage. On Saturday, as the families struggled to come to
terms with their loss, Canadian officials stepped up their efforts
to recover the bodies of the victims and pieces of the plane.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- NY-YOUTH-MARCH, 9-5 -- With
a turnout far smaller than organizers had hoped, and with police
officers lining every block, Harlem served as host Saturday to a
black youth rally, which earlier this month, was expected to draw
hundreds of thousands of balck youth from around the United States.
The rally which galvanized some with its calls for unity, alienated
others with the anti-white, anti-Semitic message of its chief
organizer, Khallid Abdul Muhammad. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) GREENVILLE, N.C. -- Sept. 5, 1998 --
STATEHOUSE-CAMPAIGNS, 9-5 -- State Senator Edward Warren of North
Carolina, 68, left, handing out combs embossed with his name at
Tom's Restaurant, to Coye Lewis, second from left, Joe McLawhorn
and Maggie Hugens. In recent years, Warren, a Democrat, has had to
spend more and use more sophisticated tactics while campaigning.
While he once spent no more than $30,000 to hold on to his state
Senate seat, his 1996 campaign cost $210,000. This year, he may
have to spend more. (Jennifer Warburg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NOVGOROD, Russia -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- RUSSIA-BARTER-2, 9-5
-- Workers at the Splav manufacturing company playing dominoes. The
current financial crisis has been hard on the company, which relies
on complex barter deals rather than on cash for its high-tech
valves, often used in the nuclear power industry. It lost $2
million when the government abruptly devalued the ruble and
rescheduled its short-term debt repayments. Splav has frozen
hiring, cut costs and forsworn exorbitant bank credits. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NOVGOROD, Russia -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- RUSSIA-BARTER-1, 9-5
-- Yevgeny Shulman, general director of the Splav manufacturing
company, with charts tracing barter deals. The Splav factory,
relies on complex barter deals rather than on cash for its
high-tech valves, which are used in the nuclear power industry.
``This is the way everybody in Russia does business these days,''
says Shulman. ``Of course, we'd prefer to receive cash. But it is
barter that has saved us.'' (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-6, 9-5
-- Lenzie Jones, 61, and his daughter, Mary Bee Christian, in
Jones's temporary apartment in the Robert Taylor Homes housing
project. Jones and his daughter presented one of the toughest
relocation situations for families in The Hole. As a result, they
were among the last people to leave their building, and then they
moved only to temporary housing with about 25 other intensely
troubled families. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ROSELAND, Ill. -- Sept. 5, 1998 --
PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-5, 9-5 -- Billy Kimmons, 23, looks over his
neighborhood from the porch of his new apartment in as movers
deliver his furnishings. Kimmons, like many others, was forced to
move out of The Hole, the most oppressive section of Chicago's
notorious Robert Taylor Homes housing project. (Ozier Muhammad/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-4, 9-5
-- Angela Smith, 25, was in a frenzy to pack her belongings before
the movers came to put her things into storage. Like most people
who lived in The Hole, she didn't want another housing authority
apartment: she wants a federal rent subsidy known as a Section 8
certificate, which will allow her to rent her own apartment. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-3, 9-5
-- Brenda Hunter, of the Chicago Housing Authority relocation
office, gives Katie Sistrunk a hug in her new apartment in Rogers
Park, on the Northside of Chicago. By moving to this ``scattered
site,'' apartment her landlord will remain the federal government.
(Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-2, 9-5
-- A student at Mary B. Terrell Elementary, a public school near
the Robert Taylor Homes, walks through the area known as ``The
Hole.'' Robert Taylor, the nation's largest housing project, much
of which is ``considered the worst slum area in the United
States,'' according to its landlord, the Chicago Housing Authority,
is being demolished. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1998 -- PUBLIC-HOUSING-REFORM-1, 9-5
-- Henry Sistrunk, 27, watches the action in ``The Hole,'' the most
oppressive section of Chicago's notorious Robert Taylor Homes
housing project. On the back of Sistrunk's left shoulder is a tatoo
of The Hole's three high-rise buildings, done by his brother.(Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
