<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS &LR;      09-05 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUT AFFAIR DIM CLINTON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN McGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ It was supposed to be a day of joy and
triumph, the long-awaited return to a land where he helped engineer
an unlikely peace.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday night, after President Clinton spoke to every
crowd, shook every last hand, basked in all that praise from
leaders on both sides of the sectarian divide, he arrived at the US
ambassador's residence in Dublin to receive the bad news from
aides. Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, an influential
Democratic moderate, had delivered a scathing speech in Washington
saying Clinton had ``compromised his moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, what was supposed to be one of the best days of
his presidency was unceremoniously tossed atop the pile of the
typically bad.
</P>
<P>
   There is a loosely held adage in modern American politics that
for a president to seem truly presidential, he must travel abroad _
away from the cynics, the constant barrage of negative television
news coverage, the political rivals who attack with increasing
bite. This was exactly what White House advisers had hoped and
expected when they planned this trip in the late spring.
</P>
<P>
   What they learned instead is that wherever on earth Clinton
travels, the controversy surrounding his affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky will follow close behind _ from his arrival in Russia on
Tuesday morning to his departure from Ireland last night.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow on Wednesday, Clinton's face flushed red at a joint
press conference with President Boris N. Yeltsin when he was asked
about his refusal to apologize. On Thursday, he was reported to be
incensed that Lieberman had clouded his victory tour of Northern
Ireland with the stinging indictment back home. On Friday, when he
apologized during a photo opportunity in the Irish prime minister's
office, his awkward, uncomfortable smile failed to mask his deep
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a reminder of the parallel universes we live in,''
White House press secretary Michael D. McCurry said of the
adulation in the streets of Ireland, contrasted with the criticisms
coming from home.
</P>
<P>
   When aides first planned the summit with Yeltsin, Clinton was
meant to push Russian officials to ratify a nuclear arms treaty and
begin negotiating another historic arms reduction pact that would
bring arsenals to one-fifth of the levels at the height of the Cold
War. Instead, he arrived in Moscow in the throes of the worst
economic crisis in Russia's seven-year history with a free-market
system.
</P>
<P>
   Banks shut their doors. The Russian financial instrument, the
ruble, plunged in value. The financial system seemed to be
crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts summoned unflattering comparisons between a
Clinton-Yeltsin summit and the meetings of powerful United States
and Soviet presidents during the Cold War. Time and again, the
conversation was of two leaders weakened by controversy staggering
through an ineffectual exercise of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, Clinton's visit to Moscow seemed to have a
nominal impact. The ruble continued to plummet; the Duma, the lower
house of Parliament, refused to confirm Viktor Chernomyrdin as
prime minister on the eve of Clinton's arrival; and as soon as
Clinton left, Chernomyrdin announced he would like to create an
economic dictatorship early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the week, Clinton, normally a vibrant speaker who
prides himself in making a connection with his audience, appeared
unusually subdued and detached at almsot every stop. At a speech at
Moscow State University, he repeated himself again and again and
barely garnered applause. At an elaborate dinner with Yeltsin that
night, he left a full hour ahead of schedule to retire for the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Northern Ireland on Thursday morning, his keynote
speech before an adoring audience of Protestant and Catholic
leaders was so dry that one of Clinton's aides retired to a back
room of the auditorium and promptly fell asleep. In that speech,
Clinton began describing the Good Friday peace agreement, saying,
``This has been a magic ...'' He paused for a moment, searching for
the right word, before adding, ``thing.''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, in the city of Armagh, he appeared more at ease,
inspiring a crowd of about 10,000 to a steady stream of applause.
Even there, however, a massive loudspeaker sat alone on a cricket
field far away from the audience, in an indication that the White
House advance team had anticipated a much larger gathering.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Hillary Rodham Clinton appeared from a
distance to be one of aloofness. Getting on and off airplanes
together, they barely touched. In Omagh, Northern Ireland, as
British Prime Minister Tony Blair worked a ropeline side by side
with his wife, Mrs. Clinton drifted about 30 yards ahead, shaking
hands alone, and Clinton lagged even further behind.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, aides said Clinton functioned well abroad, but even
their support seemed tempered by the moment. ``He dealt with world
leaders on this trip and is confident that he continues to do good
work in the interest of the American people as he fulfills his
constitutional responsibilities,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides privately pointed to a furious travel schedule and a
series of unexpected developments for Clinton's mood, and said that
he remained neither as upbeat as his advisers like to portray him
or as melancholy as reporters like to describe.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it was not all bad. In Limerick, an estimated 10,000
residents greeted his motorcade on the route to his hotel Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Saturday, he declared to a boisterous crowd here,
``This peace is yours, yours and no one else's. All the leaders in
the world, all the speeches in the world, wouldn't amount to a hill
of beans if you hadn't gone out and voted yes and made it loud and
clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
