<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLION-MARCH-BOS &LR;      09-05 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE, ORGANIZERS CLASH AT END OF RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For days they had promised peace. And after nearly
four hours Saturday, that promise seemed all but delivered, as a
volatile mix of militant speakers, thousands of marchers, and
scores of police avoided confrontation at the Million Youth March
in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   But at the stroke of 4 p.m. _ the time when a federal court
order said the event must disperse _ the tense peace suddenly
unraveled, and the fears of a community unfolded in a violent,
on-stage clash between police and the fiery organizer of the event,
Khalid Abdul Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   About 4:01 p.m., when witnesses said Muhammad was making his
closing remarks, police rushed the podium at the corner of 118th
Street and Malcolm X Boulevard in an attempt to reach the
electricity generator that controlled the sound from the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But a corps of Muhammad supporters had surrounded the generator,
and by 4:03 p.m. violence erupted as organizers threw glass bottles
and metal chairs at police dressed in riot gear, and as police in
turn sprayed mace and dragged organizers from the stage in order to
get to the generator.
</P>
<P>
   Panic and confusion seized the crowd, as marchers who had held
their breath through four hours of relative calm suddenly felt
police helicopters hovering about 100 yards above their heads and
police officers four and five lines deep moved in from different
directions to try to disperse the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Lower down on Malcolm X Boulevard, a phalanx of police officers
waited on motorcycles and mounted horseback, poised for the
possibility of a full-fledged riot.
</P>
<P>
   As police vehicles escorted a white Mercedes believed to belong
to Muhammad south on Malcolm X Boulevard and away from the site of
the march, organizers pleaded with the gathered audience to go
home, shouting into bullhorns as police took over the stage and
began dismantling it.
</P>
<P>
   By 4:30 p.m., the crowd had been moved out of the area, but the
side streets were jammed with people.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani said that one person had been arrested
and that more arrests were expected.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 people suffered minor injuries, according to emergency
service personnel. Police said 15 officers had been injured.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before Muhammad took to the stage in the final minutes
before 4 p.m., the crowd had responded with cheers and wild
applause as one of his lieutenants shouted from the stage, ``We're
supposed to lose this permit at 4 o'clock, but to hell with them!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beat the hell out of them with the railing if they so much as
touch you!'' Muhammad had said to the crowd. ``Look the bastards in
the eye. Take their guns and use it on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The tumult ended a day that was promoted as a followup to the
Million Man March in Washington in 1995 and the Million Woman March
in Philadelphia last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's event drew only several thousand, and attracted
most of its attention from Giuliani's efforts to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani called the event ``a march of hate,'' and the city
denied a permit to the organizers. But they won a challenge in US
District Court last month on the grounds that the city's refusal
was unconstitutional and arbitrary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a panel of three federal appeals judges narrowed the
length of the march from 29 blocks to six and cut the schedule from
12 to 4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 police officers were sent to the area in a show
of force that had some residents complaining the scene was more a
police state than a youth rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is overkill,'' said state Senator David Paterson,
who represents Harlem. Paterson, who organized a force of 500
volunteers as ``peacekeepers,'' said there was ``a strong, visible
artillery in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just antagonizing the crowd,'' said Paterson,
adding that he opposed the march but was on hand to ensure
participants' safety.
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of the overwhelming presence of police officers on
Malcolm X Boulevard, on rooftops, and in helicopters that
occasionally passed over the crowd, and in spite of the scorching
speeches that focused mostly on the city's attempts to stop the
march, some young people said they were inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see our black brothers and sisters getting
together,'' said Terrell Cliett, 11, who had come by bus from West
Philadelphia with his mother and 30 other parents and youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what they're saying,'' the boy said of the speakers.
``They're trying to get black people to remember that they're like
everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamar Williams helped advertise the march in his hometown of
Baltimore and said he was glad he came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is very positive. The kids need something like
this,'' said Williams, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell's mother, Charlynn Cliett, had one criticism of the
event. She said she wanted her son to experience the march because
she felt she had gained a lot from the Million Woman March. But she
was disappointed that the program focused heavily on adult issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little over the children's head,'' Cliett said.
``I don't really think it's geared to the children too much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1940EDT &QL; 
