r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-05 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME WORLD WAR I VETERANS ARE STILL WITH US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How many soldiers are still alive from the First World War?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.R.K., Harvard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Out of 4.73 million Americans who served during World War I,
an estimated 3,200 are alive today. They range in age from 94 to
116.
</P>
<P>
   These figures come from Muriel Sue Parkhurst, who
single-handedly runs Veterans of World War I of the USA Inc. from
her Alexandria, Va., home. When she began working for the
organization in 1975, it had 21 full-time employees working for
750,000 surviving veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Parkhurst said that most of these vets never received pensions
or other benefits, and many retired before Social Security. They
sometimes seek help with eyeglasses, hearing aids, discharge papers
and the return of stolen medals. To contact the group, write to Box
8027, Alexandria, VA 22306-8027, or call (703) 780-5660.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for these men and women to realize they're not
alone,'' Parkhurst said. Subscriptions to the group's newsletter
are sent for donations of $5 or more, which fund its bimonthly
publication.
</P>
<P>
   World War I survivors are the nation's oldest group of veterans.
The last Spanish-American War veteran died in 1992 at age 106, and
the last Civil War veteran died in 1956 at 112, according to
Veterans Administration records.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the red-haired actress Anita Morris? I
thought she died, but what's her story? She was so talented.
</P>
<P>
   _ T.S.N, Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Morris died of cancer at age 50 on March 3, 1994, in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 years on Broadway, the actress was a Drama Desk Award
winner and Tony Award nominee for her role in the 1982 Broadway
musical ``Nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Her movie projects included ``The Hotel New Hampshire,''
``Ruthless People'' and ``Radioland Murders,'' which was released
posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine called her best role that of ``Danny DeVito's
scheming, Dustbuster-addicted mistress in `Ruthless People.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
