<HEADLINE>
SMOKE IN THE COCKPIT: PILOTS ARE OFTEN UNPREPARED  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ The only problem that the crew of
Swissair Flight 111 reported to air controllers before the crash on
Wednesday night was smoke in the cockpit, but smoke alone can bring
a plane down, even if the fire that produced it does not disable
crucial mechanical or electrical parts.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows yet what made the Swissair plane, an MD-11, crash
into the sea. But in recent years the National Transportation
Safety Board has studied several in-flight fires, some that caused
disasters and some in which crashes were only narrowly averted, and
found that pilots are sometimes not adequately prepared to try to
fly a plane from a smoky cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Cockpits in airliners are stocked with goggles that cover the
eyes and oxygen masks that cover the nose and mouth. Using them is
``absolutely critical for the survival of the aircraft, and the
people on it,'' said an aviation fire safety expert who testified
at a safety board hearing into the crash of a Valujet DC-9 in the
Florida Everglades. That crash, which occurred in May 1996, was
caused by a fire in the cargo hold. The expert, Robert P. Massi,
who himself narrowly escaped death in a cockpit fire in a small
plane, said: ``If you can't see, and you can't breathe, you can't
fly. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the sound of his voice, the Swissair pilot who was
speaking to air controllers before the crash apparently put on his
mask in the last minutes of the flight, investigators said on
Saturday. They are hoping to recover the cockpit voice recorder,
and hope that it will shed more light on the amount of smoke in the
cockpit and its effect on the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say pilots are usually reluctant to put on their masks
and goggles. One problem is that the goggles are like a horse's
blinders, limiting peripheral vision, making it hard to scan the
instruments and the view outside. Turning the head to scan back and
forth can cause vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that pilots who wear glasses generally cannot
fit them under the goggles. One expert said at the Valujet hearing
that in some cases pilots had taken off their glasses to put on
goggles, only to find that they could not read the emergency
checklists.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have a dilemma,'' said Gregory Feith, a safety board
investigator in the Valujet case. ``Either you breathe or you see,
but possibly you can't do both,'' he said. The safety board called
for the development of protective equipment, either masks and
goggles or one-piece units, that could be put on more quickly, and
were more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Also, pilots are generally reluctant to put on goggles or masks,
figuring that they will wait until the smoke gets heavier. But
according to experts who testified at the Valujet hearing, smoke
can increase so rapidly that by the time the masks are really
needed, it is too late.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they put on the masks, if the smoke is too thick the
pilots will be unable to read the instrument panels. Without being
able to see the airspeed indicator or the artificial horizon, which
indicates the wings' angle relative to the ground, pilots would
find the plane very hard to fly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some planes do not carry enough oxygen to last more
than 15 minutes, and often it takes longer than that to land a
plane flying at high altitude. Flight 111 crashed 16 minutes after
the pilots first radioed for help.
</P>
<P>
   Fires have other ways to make planes crash. In the case of older
planes like DC-9s, fires can destroy the mechanical cables that
connect the cockpit controls with the flaps, ailerons, and rudder.
Newer designs, like the MD-11, use electrical cables, but fires can
cut those, too. The flight data recorder, if it continued to
function, might indicate the loss of various pieces of equipment as
a fire progressed; failure of the flight data recorder itself would
be a clue.
</P>
</TEXT>
