<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTHOUSE BECOMES A MARKER FOR MOURNERS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ For as long as anyone here can
remember, the red-and-white lighthouse that stands sentinel on the
craggy shoreline has been a kind of landmark, because it was the
first in Canada to double as a post office, used by the 60
residents of this tiny fishing village.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, as hundreds of distraught relatives of the
victims of Swissair Flight 111 poured in, the picture-postcard
tower became another sort of landmark, an impromptu grave marker to
mourners who may never recover their loved ones' bodies and who
have no other point on a map to call a resting place for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The families began arriving hourly just after 8 on Saturday
morning, and streamed slowly up a jagged hill to the lighthouse,
leaving daisies and irises and pink roses in the rocky crevices
along the way. Some gathered pebbles or rocks to carry back with
them. Others crouched down, as if trying to get closer to the
roaring surf below. Still others simply separated from family
members and walked along the shore alone. They stared out at the
horizon, where Canadian Coast Guard and Navy ships in the recovery
effort were dimly visible.
</P>
<P>
   One man left a sky-blue card in which he had written: ``Words
cannot express what I'm feeling for all of you right now. May God
be with you, my friends. Maurice.''
</P>
<P>
   All the mourners seemed to be searching for something. But
several said that despite the sense of indefiniteness that has
engulfed them over the last three days, it helped to go to the
landpoint nearest to where the jet went into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just something to hold on to,'' said Tim Larson, 39, of
East Hartford, Conn., whose wife's uncle, Victor Rizza, 58, and Mr.
Rizza's son, Antonino, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   As Larson began to talk to reporters near the lighthouse, he
looked around him at the picturesque town nestled around the cove
and started to say something about it. But he was only able to say,
``This is such a pretty town,'' before his voice cracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read about this stuff,'' he said, ``and you see it, and
it's never supposed to happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends of the victims tended to speak on Saturday of
things that should have happened. Larson said his wife's family had
planned a reunion for 2000 in Sicily, where Rizza owned a chemical
company and was a college professor.
</P>
<P>
   Rizza and his son were flying to Geneva on their way to
Stuttgart, where Rizza's son, known as Nino, lived with his mother.
The two had been in Hartford visiting their American relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot of Flight 111, Urs Zimmermann, would have celebrated
his 50th birthday Saturday night in Switzerland, said Capt. Werner
Naef, a Swissair pilot. Naef flew victims' families to Halifax from
Switzerland on Friday and visited the shore here on Saturday with
10 other Swissair crewmen who had worked with the Flight 111 crew.
</P>
<P>
   Naef added that one of the flight attendants aboard Flight 111
was on her first journey as a Swissair crewman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to express to all the victims' families,'' he said,
first in English and then in German, ``that our hearts and our love
are with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotions of the mourners veered wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Just after noon, one woman could be seen walking very quickly
across the rocks near the lighthouse toward wooden police barriers
that were erected to prevent mourners from venturing too close to
the dangerous waves. A counselor restrained the woman after she
passed the barriers and began to walk toward the water.
</P>
<P>
   Some family members were dressed in funereal black, and wept,
visibly shaking, as they walked toward the water. Others were
dressed like tourists _ khaki pants and fanny packs and tennis
shoes _ and they held hands or they put their arms around one
another's shoulders. Red Cross and Salvation Army workers shuttled
between the lighthouse and large green military tents with boxes of
tissues and, after the wind picked up, stacks of gray wool
blankets.
</P>
<P>
   As one elderly man made his way up the stairs to the lighthouse,
his shoulders shaking, he collapsed. Officials said they did not
know whether he fell or suffered some type of seizure. He was
carried off the hill on a stretcher and taken to a hospital in
Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   In the background throughout the day were the uncertainties that
linger for the families: What made the jet's cockpit fill with
smoke? How quickly did their loved ones die? When will their family
members' bodies be identified so they can go home and grieve
outside the glare of floodlights?
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to know what happened as quickly as possible,''
Naef said. For others, those answers were less important.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it doesn't make a lot of difference, because they're
gone,'' said Claire Mortimer, whose father, John H. Mortimer, 75,
and stepmother, Hilda B. Mortimer, 69, were on the flight en route
to a vacation in France.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mortimer said that what has been most important to her so
far are the assurances of crash investigators, who told families on
Friday that it appears the jet hit the water with unbelievable
impact. That means, she said, her voice calm and even, that ``they
died fast'' and did not suffer.
</P>
<P>
   She added that she perhaps drew more comfort than some of the
families who went to the cove, because her father, her stepmother
and her mother, who died many years ago, all loved the Atlantic
Coast. At the end of June, the family celebrated Mortimer's 75th
birthday at the family's summer home in Ogunquit, on the Maine
coast, with clams and lobsters and a soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have loved this place,'' she said, and added later:
``In some ways, this feels like a very logical completion.''
</P>
<P>
   As the line of family members wound up and down the hill all
day, somber village residents looked on, and many cried with the
mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy and Art Gilbert, from White's Lake, just a few miles down
the road, drove in with 130 loads of bread donated by a bakery in
Halifax. After they delivered the bread and other food, the couple
stood talking quietly in sight of the lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come to see it now,'' Mrs. Gilbert said, ``I guess
it will mean something a little different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
