<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-2NDLD-WRITE     09-05 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH INQUIRY FINDS A SILENCE FROM THE CREW  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update throughout; some info in previous CRASH-RDP now
filed as new story CRASH-FAMILIES)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ The crew of the Swissair jet that crashed
near here on Wednesday night had stopped responding to air traffic
controllers about six minutes before the plane, an MD-11 with 229
people on board, hit the water, investigators said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also said that on Friday they had detected the
homing device from one of the plane's ``black boxes,'' either the
cockpit voice recorder or the flight data recorder. Divers spent
Saturday morning trying to find the recorder, they said, but had to
be called back because of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigator, Vic Gerden, said that shortly after the
plane's last radio transmission, in which a crewman told a
controller at the Moncton Area Control Center, ``We have to land
immediately,'' the plane's transponder also stopped working. That
piece of equipment transmits the plane's identity and altitude to
controllers, and when its signal stopped, radar data from the plane
became much less reliable, Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, with 215 passengers and a crew of 14, plunged into
the sea at 10:30 local time on Wednesday night, about 40 miles from
Halifax Airport, killing everyone aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Even the brief excerpts of the conversations between a
controller in Moncton and the crew _ released here Saturday night _
show flashes of drama and tension. Someone on the plane _ whether
the captain or the first officer _ tells the controller: ``We are
declaring an emergency at time zero one two four ... we are
starting vent now. We have to land immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said he was consulting with Swissair pilots and MD-11
experts about what ``starting vent'' means. It could have meant
depressurizing the airplane to allow the cockpit windows to be
opened, or dumping fuel, which the crew had said it would have to
do, Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would not characterize the tone of the exchanges or say
what had been going on in the cockpit in the final minutes. Asked
why the transponder stopped working, he said that the failure might
be ``indicating some electrical issue, potentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the crew's tone of voice, Gerden said that it had
changed in the course of the 10 minutes, probably indicating that
they had put on oxygen masks. ``I really don't have enough
information to determine their condition inside the cockpit, I'm
afraid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cites smoke, but we really don't know what density of
smoke, what amount,'' Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing that lasted more than an hour, Gerden gave a
limited chronology of the last few minutes of the flight, beginning
at a point about 70 nautical miles from here.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, under the control of the Moncton Center, radioed in:
``Swissair 111 heavy is declaring pan-pan-pan. We have smoke in the
cockpit, request deviate immediate right turn to a convenient
place, I guess Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Advised that the plane was 300 nautical miles from Boston, the
crew readily agreed to go to Halifax, but when told that the
airport was just 30 miles away, the pilot said, ``We need more than
30 miles.'' The controller told the plane to turn left to lose
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said he would have experts analyze whether it was
possible to drop from the 33,000-foot cruising altitude to the
runway, which is not far above sea level, in the 30 miles
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, he said, was weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft at that point, about that time, had a weight of
about 230 metric tons,'' he said. But it cannot land weighing more
than 200 metric tons, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have taken probably in the vicinity of 12 minutes of
flying to dump that amount of fuel,'' he said. ``If one attempts to
land an aircraft at a weight that is greater than the maximum
landing weight, depending on many conditions _ length of runway,
surface condition of runway, is it wet, many other factors _ there
is a risk having landed the aircraft it would go off the other end
of the runway at some unknown rate of speed and cause damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether, in hindsight, the crew might have done better
risking that than falling into the sea, he said, ``The crew had a
difficult situation to contend with, starting with a high altitude
and having to descend quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles, he said, was very short if the crew wanted to
``descend into an airport that you weren't expecting to descend
into.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew would have had to make a very quick decision, he said,
about risking a landing above the maximum landing weight ``and at
the same time, contending with some problem, unknown at this
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
