u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-COX     09-05 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors will get key signals in the coming weeks
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors will find little to feel festive about this Labor Day,
the last holiday of a dismal summer in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepared for the weekend, many knew they were suddenly
less wealthy by ... 5 percent? 10 percent? More?
</P>
<P>
   Now, with an extra day to think about it, investors want to know
what comes next. No one knows for sure, but there are signposts
they can look for in coming weeks that offer clues to where the
market is going:
</P>
<P>
   Earnings pre-announcements: Often bad news released early by a
company, they offer a tip-off to which way profits will go in the
latest quarter, especially for big companies. Third quarter
pre-announcements will occur this month and in early October.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings announcements: These are the official company reports,
mostly in the month after the quarter ends. Just as important as
the earnings are comments and forecasts by management about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates: Second only to earnings, interest rate trends
provide clues to the future. They have trended lower for most of
the 1990s. In a period of earnings weakness, stocks become more
dependent on an environment of steady or declining interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve: The nation's central bank is under pressure
to cut short-term interest rates as a signal of support to the
stock market, much as it did after the October 1987 crash. Analysts
say a rate cut would almost certainly boost the market. Watch for
Fed action _ or inaction _ when it meets three more times this
year: Sept. 29, Nov. 17 and Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The economy: Typically, bear markets do not occur during an
economic boom, which means the continued strength of the economy is
important. Look especially at government reports on job growth and
unemployment, usually in the first week of each month, and on
inflation _ the Producer Price Index for wholesale prices, the
Consumer Price Index for retail prices.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign crises: The slowest, most difficult changes affecting
the market almost certainly will occur overseas, where foreign
governments may or may not do the right thing from the U.S.
perspective. By all accounts, the U.S. is less dependent on foreign
trade than most nations, but the world's problems clearly have a
psychological impact on investors, especially those of Asia and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic crises. Analysts aren't sure what impact President
Clinton's embarrassment will have, or how it will end. For the most
part, it shouldn't affect the market unless Clinton is impeached or
resigns. His successor, and which party controls Congress, are more
likely to impact the market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
