<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAIRCLOTH-SIERRA-COX     09-05 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCLOTH-SIERRA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sierra Club's anti-Faircloth ad gets mixed results
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The Sierra Club this weekend concluded
$600,000 worth of unregulated issue advertising in nearly two dozen
states that both hammered and praised members of Congress for their
votes on the environ- ment.
</P>
<P>
   This college town in eastern Carolina was ground zero in the
club's North Carolina campaign against Sen. Lauch Faircloth
(R-N.C.), who faces a tough re-election fight against John Edwards,
a millionaire attorney who has the endorsement of the Sierra Club's
political action committee. The Sierra Club spent $45,000 here and
in Raleigh to convince viewers that Faircloth, among the Senate's
most conservative members, has a poor record on the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club organizers in Washington declared the campaign a
success at a news conference in the nation's Capital last week. But
here in the small towns of eastern Carolina, around local lunch
counters and in main street shops, the reviews were decidedly
mixed. Some voters said they simply hadn't seen the ad. Others said
they tuned it out as soon as they saw it was ``political.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Hickman, a homemaker from Kinston, N.C., thought it was a
``pretty ad,'' but wasn't quite sure who paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a political ad,'' said Larry Economos, an
attorney from Greenville who is supporting Edwards. ``When you see
it, you wonder what connection it has to Edwards' campaign. It's a
good ad for Edwards.''
</P>
<P>
   The views of Economos and other voters across eastern Carolina
suggest that voters are far more skeptical of issue ads than the
ads' sponsors might wish to believe. Message is one thing. How it
is received is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me want to vote for Faircloth,'' said Joe Burchette
over a plate of fried chicken at Christopher's on the main street
in Kinston, N.C. ``Because I don't like liberals and the way they
want me to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Issue ads such as ``Fish Kill,'' the spot that aired here,
increasingly are becoming the political tool of choice for
tax-exempt organizations like the Sierra Club. Without telling
voters to vote for or against a candidate, the organizations escape
federal limitations on how they must raise their money and disclose
where it comes from.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation pending in Congress would require organizations to
abide by the same fund-raising limitations candidates face if they
air issue ads featuring the name or likeness of a candidate 60 days
before an election. The Sierra Club supports the legislation. But
Dan Weiss, the club's political director, noted that the club's ads
in North Carolina and elsewhere wouldn't have been subject to the
law anyway because they ran more than 60 days before the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Kittrell, a commercial real estate agent in Greenville,
said he thought it was wrong for the Sierra Club to air the ad
without disclosing who paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair for any group, whether an environmental group or
any other group to spend money like that,'' Kittrell said. ``I'm
supportive of the rivers, but I don't like that veiled type of
advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Contents of the ad
</P>
<P>
   The ad against Faircloth, a 70-year-old farmer from Clinton,
N.C., highlighted the senator's support of a clean water bill that
would have drastically rewritten the nation's wetlands laws,
exempting more than 50 percent of wetlands now under federal
protection. The bill also would have exempted some farmlands,
including those owned by hog farmers such as Faircloth, and the
Sierra Club's ad pointed that out.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also featured the serious pollution problems of North
Carolina's rivers, many of which have been temporarily closed
during the past several years because of outbreaks of the
mysterious fish-killing organism known as pfiesteria. Some
environmentalists think the excessive nitrates released into the
environment from hog farms is to blame for the rivers' woes.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Ocorr, a retired school teacher from New Bern, N.C., the
scene of some of the state's worst fish kills, said over coffee at
a local coffee shop here that voters need to know Faircloth owns
hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they know his involvement in the hog industry,''
she said. ``He's got all his money to put up slick advertising, and
I think people should know he has another record. People need to
see a balanced picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club's decision to feature local rivers in the ad _
it was actually shot on the Neuse River, which runs through New
Bern _ reflected the belief that voters don't connect to issues
unless they are in their back yard. They targeted eastern North
Carolina because they believe the message about clean water would
resonate most here.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the voters interviewed here said the environment was
an important issue, and they frequently mentioned their concern
over the local hog industry's impact on the environment. But they
weren't necessarily willing to adopt the Sierra Club's argument
that Faircloth was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't blame him for the hogs, because he don't own them
all,'' said Jimmy Faircloth (no relation to the senator), who lives
in Clinton. ``It's a large industry. It's made up of more than one
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all care about the environment,'' said Kevin Davis,
a youth minister from New Bern. ``I just think no matter who you
vote for, that's not going to change the Neuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Cannon, a 30-year-old ``die-hard Republican,'' said the ad
made him want to call Faircloth's office and tell the senator to
support pro-environment legislation. He still plans to vote for
Faircloth in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him on a lot of other issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cannon's father, Carlos Cannon, said the ad raised questions
in his mind about Faircloth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't vote the way he should vote, maybe we need a
change,'' said the elder Cannon from behind his music store counter
in Kinston. ``I'd love to hear from (Faircloth). The wait-and-see
attitude ain't going to work for him, because that ad is pretty
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Fuller, Faircloth's campaign manager, defended Faircloth's
record, but he said the campaign has no plans to respond to the
Sierra Club's ad. ``If we thought it was doing us some harm, we
would have responded to it,'' Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
