<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-COX     09-05 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women help change face of the South
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HICKORY, N.C. _ Buffeted by crosscurrents of ethnic, educational
and economic change, the South, like Elvis, is ``all shook up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of the second annual State of the South
report, released today by an economic think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The report says the South's leaders face daunting challenges on
top of the centuries-old problems of racism, poverty and
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges: The rapidly rising population of
Hispanics, Asians and other ethnic groups in the South could
increasingly become a source of tension in communities and in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the most significant trends: In both education and
jobs, men are losing ground to women.
</P>
<P>
   More women than men now attend college in the South.
</P>
<P>
   And in percentage terms, the participation of women in the work
force is growing steadily, while men's participation is going down.
Armed with better educations, women gradually are closing the pay
gap with men.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of men from the work force is especially
evident in Appalachia, northeast Mississippi and other areas where
traditional factory jobs are fading and new jobs are slow to fill
the void, said George Autry, president of MDC Inc., which published
the report. It was funded by the Ford Foundation, the Z. Smith
Reynolds Foundation, the Wachovia Foundation and the U.S.
Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``More often, (unemployed men) are winding up in jail or in the
underground economy,'' Autry said. ``They could be hustling,
running drugs, doing occasional day labor or living off their
girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a reversal of the African-American exodus from the
South in the three decades after World War II, migration of black
people to the region reached record levels in the 1990s. Most were
lured by jobs in cities _ including the No. 1 destination, Atlanta
_ rather than by nostalgic longings for their old family homes,
according to the report. The newcomers are better educated than the
black adults who have spent their lives in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The black migration pattern is part of a larger story of the
reversal of the brain drain,'' noted MDC, a Chapel Hill, N.C., firm
that tracks economic and work force trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South is now attracting, rather than losing, the most
highly educated.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Hackett can vouch for the new report.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Hackett moved to Hickory, N.C., a working-class
community east of Asheville in the southern fringes of Appalachia.
Then she got an education and landed a job.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old mother of four went from living in a shelter for
battered women in nearby Lenoir to renting a four-bedroom home
outside of Hickory. Her knack for mechanics led her to an
associate's degree in automotive repair at Catawba Valley Community
College and then to a technician's job at the local Volvo
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   She even holds down a second job on weekends fixing broken
bowling machines at Colonial Lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hackett landed a job working the service counter at
Armstrong Ford, and now she's earning the best money of her life:
as much as $400 a week.
</P>
<P>
   She enjoys the work, but occasionally, she said, the phone rings
and the caller ``wants to talk to a man. They think I am the
secretary to the service manager.''
</P>
<P>
   MDC noted a sharp increase in the number of Southern families
with both parents working and in families headed by a single
working parent.
</P>
<P>
   That has resulted in a big gap between the median income of
two-earner families ($56,000 in 1996) and female-headed families
($18,000 in 1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, single mothers are thrice cursed,'' the report
states, noting that women typically earn less than men, often lack
higher educations, and support families on a single income.
</P>
<P>
   The report warns that the gap between the haves and the
have-nots ``is widening, even as the South becomes more prosperous
than ever. A more economically powerful South now faces a test: Can
it give more families the capacity to improve their prospects in
life, especially the millions of Southern families headed by single
parents and families of newly arrived immigrants?''
</P>
<P>
   In Hickory, N.C., educators at Catawba Valley Community College
are grappling with many of the challenges posed by the report.
Established in 1960, its mission has expanded broadly with economic
and social changes.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of one of America's most industrialized corridors,
the community college still teams up with local furniture and
hosiery factories to train employees on the latest technology. The
college also provides basic education to adults who dropped out of
high school years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to find workers in a robust economy with an
unemployment rate below 3 percent, manufacturers are hiring
increasing numbers of immigrants. They are calling on the college
to teach them to speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Catawba Valley's Hosiery Technology Center recently created a
CD-ROM that uses photos, audio clips and animation to teach English
vocabulary related to hosiery manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But some manufacturers are reluctant to teach English to
immigrants, including a growing population of Hmongs from Laos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies fear that if they teach people how to speak
English better, they will go someplace else,'' said Debbie Saine, a
basic skills recruiter for the college.
</P>
<P>
   Catawba Valley offers a program for single parents and displaced
homemakers who need encouragement and guidance to return to school.
Most of the 200 students enrolled last year were women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common theme is that they cannot support themselves or
their families without further training,'' said Wanda Horvath, the
college's special programs coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a federal grant, Catawba Valley offers a program that
encourages women like Hackett to pursue traditionally male jobs.
Men also are encouraged to consider careers such as nursing.
</P>
<P>
   For Hackett, who studied automotive systems technology, pursuing
a male-dominated career hasn't been easy. She has run into slights
because she's a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her new job at Armstrong Ford has brought stability to
her family. She's no longer working under the hood, which allows
her to fix dinner at night without grease under her nails. She's
able to spend more time with her two sons and two daughters,
including 18-year-old Christina, who ran away a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett blamed herself for that, saying she was away too much
while working two jobs
</P>
<P>
   Now Christina is holding down a job as shift leader at McDon-
ald's. Her mother hopes she eventually will enroll in college, but
for now, Hackett said, ``She makes $7 an hour, and I'm real proud
of her.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
