<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICTIMS-COX     09-05 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tapes: Crew calm until jet vanished
 &HT;    By Randy Kennedy and Matthew L. Wald
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEGGY'S COVE, Nova Scotia _ As grieving families from several
countries began to converge on this tiny fishing village on Friday,
officials looking for the cause of the crash of Swissair Flight 111
on Wednesday said that it appeared that the crew was in control of
the jet and making rational decisions about how to land the
stricken plane until it abruptly disappeared from radar.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Canadian investigator said that aside from the smoky
condition the pilots reported in seeking permission for an
emergency landing, the crew reported no specific problems with the
operation of the jumbo jet, an MD-11 built by McDonnell Douglas in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Vic Gerden, from the Canadian National Safety
Board, said that contrary to earlier reports, the jetliner changed
course only once, when the pilot was told that he should attempt to
land in Halifax rather than in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the plane, carrying 215 passengers and a crew of
14, was about 58 nautical miles from the runway in Halifax. Gerden
said the pilot began to make wide circles to both reduce altitude
and dump fuel as he descended in preparation for a landing.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden added that the crews' communication with Canadian air
traffic controllers was ``professional throughout.'' He said that
the crew twice indicated that they had a serious problem with the
plane, which was only described as smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators analyzed the tapes, several relatives of the
victims made solemn journeys to the rocky Nova Scotia coastline.
Peter Gerety, the brother of Pierce Gerety, a U.N. official who was
aboard Flight 111, picked up two rocks there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like having a memento,'' said Gerety. ``It's such
a beautiful place; that's the irony of it.'' Gerety said he would
keep one of the stones and deliver the other to his brother's
widow.
</P>
<P>
   On several fronts Friday, the recovery and investigation
frustrated both officials and grieving families eager for answers.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise and frustration of many investigators, a
submarine equipped with sophisticated sonar and other underwater
listening devices caught no whisper from the ``pingers'' attached
to the jet's black boxes _ the flight data recorder and cockpit
voice recorder. As a result, investigators had little to go on
beyond radar tapes and the tapes of the conversations between the
crew and the ground. Investigators were still poring over this
information Friday and said they would release a transcript of the
conversations and a radar map on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact searchers have so far found no large pieces of wreckage,
although what has turned up has shown no signs of fire or other
obvious clues. Sgt. Andre Guertin of the Royal Canadian Mounted
Police said the most significant discovery Friday was about 100
mostly intact pieces of luggage.
</P>
<P>
   But other aspects of the investigation began to move forward. In
New York, the FBI joined the Federal Aviation Administration in
examining cargo manifests for the flight to determine whether any
hazardous materials were on board, either declared or undeclared.
The flight did not carry any materials owned by the airline,
investigators said Friday; that is significant, officials said,
because in the crash of a Valuejet DC9 in Florida two years ago,
the cause of a fire on board turned out to be hazardous oxygen
generators in boxes labeled ``comat,'' meaning company materials.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials also said they were looking closely at six
directives they had issued since 1994 regarding flaws that might
cause smoke or fire on MD-11s. Those are among several orders
issued by the agency for planes under U.S. jurisdiction after
scattered instances of fire or smoke on that type of jet. The
Swissair jet was registered in Switzerland and was not subject to
U.S. orders, but officials said that most European airlines
routinely adopt the FAA directives.
</P>
<P>
   At a military base several miles to the northeast, medical
examiners also joined the investigation, performing toxicology
tests on the victims' remains that may indicate whether passengers
had inhaled smoke or other fumes before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiners, working in a makeshift morgue in an
airplane hangar, began a second painstaking day of identifying the
bodies, which are stored in five refrigerated trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But they said late Friday afternoon that they had not been able
to positively identify a single body yet. The examiners also said
they were working to try to identify the bodies primarily using
dental records and other medical information so that they could
spare the families from having to view the bodies, most of which
are not intact.
</P>
<P>
   As searchers and investigators settled in for what they said
would likely be weeks of work, the families of the victims began to
arrive to be nearer to the place where the jet went down. Officials
said they expected as many as 800 relatives and friends, many of
which arrived in Halifax Friday afternoon on Swissair flights from
New York and Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Several relatives made their way to Peggy's Cove, a fishing
village and tourist haven that is nearest point of land to the
crash site. One man, who did not give his name, arrived in the late
afternoon as the fog grew so thick that the lighthouse at the edge
of the cove became invisible. He slowly made his way around a rocky
inlet near where searchers were loading debris and human remains
into a truck. Before leaving a van, he bent down quickly to the
water, wet his hands and touched them to his lips.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
