<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS &LR;      09-05 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSCRIPTS SHOW JET PREPARED FOR EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Transcripts released yesterday of the
final communications between the pilots of doomed Swissair 111 and
Canadian air traffic controllers show calm preparations for an
emergency landing dissolving into calls, apparently from behind
oxygen masks in a smoky cabin, for an immediate touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swissair 111 heavy is declaring `Pan Pan Pan','' or distress,
one of the pilots told controllers Wednesday night about 70 miles
southwest of Halifax. ``We have smoke in the cockpit, request
deviate immediate right turn to a convenient place, I guess
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The controller responded: ``Would you prefer to go into
Halifax?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirmative for Swissair 111 ... prefer Halifax from our
position,'' the pilot said.
</P>
<P>
   But about 30 miles from Halifax International Airport, the pilot
told controllers in Moncton, New Brunswick, that he needed more
distance and that he also needed to dump excessive fuel that would
have made a landing at Halifax very risky.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Swissair 111 was given clearance to make a left
turn and is believed to have begun dumping fuel over the ocean at
10,000 feet. The pilots never responded to two authorizations to
dispose of their fuel, and their MD-11 aircraft with 229 passengers
and crew soon began turning in a tight circle that ended with a
plunge into the cold Atlantic on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes after the distress call came the last transmission
from the aircraft, as it began heading over St. Margaret's Bay:
``We are declaring an emergency at time zero-one-two-four ... We
are starting to vent now. We have to land immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes later, the aircraft struck the water off Peggy's
Cove. Everybody aboard was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the jet came within 25 miles of the airport before
turning in a broad arc toward the ocean, chief crash investigator
Vic Gerden said the aircraft would have been 30 tons overweight if
it had attempted to touch down while carrying the bulk of the fuel
needed to take it across the Atlantic and on to Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   ``You risk that it would have gone off the end of the runway at
an unknown rate of speed,'' said Gerden, of the Canadian
Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Any such landing would have risked the plane's landing gear
crashing through its wings or the fuselage breaking up into a
fireball, said a high-ranking official of the US National
Transportation Safety Board, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   As Gerden briefed reporters on the day's events, relatives of
the victims were receiving another briefing from the disaster team.
</P>
<P>
   By late Saturday, one body _ of a French national _ had been
identified at the chapel on a military base near Halifax that is
serving as a collection point for both human remains and aircraft
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, only small pieces of the jet had been recovered,
although search teams believe they are zeroing in on the aircraft's
transponder, which should bring them closer to the main fuselage
and the flight-data recorder that could hold the key to this crash.
</P>
<P>
   So far, five semi-trailer trucks have been used to store the
personal belongings that are washing up on the beaches and have
been retrieved from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Family members will be allowed today to begin viewing and
identifying personal items, such as wallets, passports, and
personal papers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 6-foot rolling seas and 25 m.p.h. winds, the salvage
effort continued Saturday in a 50-mile-long area along the rocky
coast of southeastern Nova Scotia. More than 600 military and
civilian personnel patrolled broad sections of the shore in an
expanding search for remains of the passengers and of Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
   Below the surface of the Atlantic, about 75 Canadian military
divers plunged as deep as 190 feet near the estimated point of
impact to scour the ocean floor for large portions of the MD-11
jet. They were aided by a Canadian submarine, whose sonar was used
to detect any anomalies in the charted ocean bottom that might be
broken pieces of the airliner. Remote-control submersible cameras
also were being used.
</P>
<P>
   Assistance has been offered by the United States, as well as
from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Andre Guertin of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police said
the search had been concentrated on a 15-square-kilometer area near
where the aircraft's fuel slick was first discovered.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the largest remnant of the jet to be recovered has been
a 3-by-3-foot fragment. Many of the bodies of the 229 passengers
and crew may still be in the fuselage of the Swissair jet, which
was delivered to the airline by McDonnell-Douglas in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Guertin said that treacherous tides, currents, and winds off
Peggy's Cove have complicated the search, but that ``we will only
stop searching when the possibility of finding every body has been
exhausted.'' Formal identification of human remains had not begun
Saturday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian investigators plan to reassemble the aircraft at
Shearwater military base near Halifax to find clues into the cause
of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian military and police boats were used Saturday to deliver
wreaths from victims' relatives to the crash site. Because of the
rough seas, the families were not brought out on the open water.
They were, however, allowed to collect samples of water from the
ocean near picturesque Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial services are planned today at a church near the village
and also at a cathedral in Halifax. An estimated 800 relatives and
friends of the victims had arrived in Nova Scotia by Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
