<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKERS-GOODBAD-COX     09-05 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-GOODBAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These days, with steady pay comes malaise
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   American workers have never had it so good. So why do so many
feel so bad?
</P>
<P>
   Despite being materially better off, many working Americans are
disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers University and the University of Connecticut weighed in
Friday, the eve of Labor Day weekend, with the latest word from the
work-force front. An overwhelming majority of the 1,001 U.S.
workers surveyed said they are worried about job security and their
children's future in the workplace. They're also pessimistic about
job prospects, anxious about their companies' commitment to them
and looking for better ways to balance their work and personal
life. The survey was conducted during the first two weeks of
August, as Wall Street continued its descent.
</P>
<P>
   Workers everywhere seem uneasy and even combative.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's strike at General Motors Corp. led off a
high-profile series of recent worker-management confrontations at
companies such as AirTran Airlines, Anheuser-Busch, BellSouth and
Bell Atlantic. Just last weekend, pilots at Northwest Airlines
joined the fray by walking out and grounding the nation's No. 4
airline. Even Mickey, Goofy and the Seven Dwarfs are fed up.
Disney's cast of costumed characters at its theme parks, along with
ticket takers, janitors and bus drivers, may strike this fall over
pay and job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a deep resentment running in America right now among
the average worker,'' says Gerald Celente of The Trend Research
Institute in New York. Many workers feel locked out of this
feel-good economy _ just as it may be coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making less money now than I was in 1982. I can't pay my
utility. One car's been repossessed. The other is two weeks past
due,'' said Decatur resident Bill Bowman, a 54-year-old machinist
who makes about $12 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman responded to an Atlanta Journal-Constitution call-in
asking readers whether they feel they are sharing in the nation's
prosperity. While some said they are enjoying economic good times,
other said prosperity has eluded them.
</P>
<P>
   Many white-collar workers, including Anne Marie Sikorski, a
15-year veteran of the advertising marketing field, are rethinking
their jobs, careers and lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel unappreciated at the job,'' Sikorski said. ``It's not
just my current job. It's every job I've ever had.'' Sikorski
recently attended a Saturday morning career conference at Mount
Vernon Baptist Church in North Atlanta. The Crossroads Career
conference drew more than 400 people, mostly middle class and white
collar, underscoring the prevailing angst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anxiety is higher,'' said Brian Ray, an executive headhunter
and one of the organizers of the conference. ``Ten years ago, there
was a little more of the feeling that 'the company will take care
of me' as opposed to, 'Now I need to take care of myself,' and
they're not sure how.'' Jobs and entire industries that don't fit
in the new so-called ``knowledge economy'' _ where people are paid
for their mind more than their muscle _ are being squeezed out.
That has many workers scared and wondering whether they'll be next.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who felt they were immune to being made obsolete in the
workplace _ particularly college graduates _ now realize they're
not immune,'' said Kenneth Deavers, chief economist of the
Employment Policy Foundation, a research group. But the changes
haven't been all bad.
</P>
<P>
   More Americans than ever are working. Even the poorest working
American today is faring better materially than the average
middle-class family of 30 years ago, according to the EPF. ``Take
all the economic numbers and set them aside and look at ownership
of boats, homes, TV sets, cars, and the real standard of living is
higher than it's ever been,'' Deavers said.
</P>
<P>
   This economic prosperity is filled with paradoxes.
</P>
<P>
   Wages: Despite wage improvements in the past few years,
paychecks for most American families are no better than they were
in the 1980s. Median family income was $1,000 less in 1996 than in
1989 for all workers, according to John Schmitt, labor economist
for the Economic Policy Institute, another research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's true the economy is bigger than it's ever been and
we are wealthier than we've ever been as a country, it's not
necessarily the case for the typical family,'' Schmitt said.
``That's because we have a very unequal distribution of wealth and
income in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Wealth: The average chief executive makes more than 130 times
what the average worker earns, according to William M. Mercer Inc.,
a New York-based expert on executive compensation. A Mercer study
of 350 large U.S. firms found that the compensation for the average
chief executive in 1997 totaled nearly $2.4 million, compared with
$21,200 for the average worker.
</P>
<P>
   Work: Jobs are plentiful, but at the same time, more people are
losing their jobs as companies downsize and merge. Those workers
often end up in lower-paying jobs. That's the case for Richard
Wilson of west Cobb County. Wilson has lost two jobs in 10 years
because of reorganizations and is now doing part-time accounting
work, making about a third of what he used to earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to believe a lot of what I read and hear
about the economy. I'm particularly concerned about the fact I hear
the crying need for experienced, mature workers,'' said Wilson, a
former top-level finance executive. ``I understand (the prosperity)
is (good) for a lot of people, but somehow I'm missing that boat.''
</P>
<P>
   The winnowing of workers isn't likely to let up. Nor is the
workload. Seven of the 10 biggest mergers in history took place in
the second quarter of this year. Job cuts this year are 37 percent
ahead of 1997, according to Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas. The
321,217 job cuts announced through July eclipse all of the layoffs
announced in 1990. At the same time, nearly 11 million new jobs
have been created in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Even as jobs seem to be plentiful, the workload is unrelenting.
Workers are putting in more hours for less money, just to keep up.
The typical married couple with children works 247 more hours _ the
equivalent of six workweeks _ a year than they did nine years ago,
according to the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street: The stock market in the past two decades has
created lots of millionaires and even a few billionaires. But six
out of every 10 working families don't own stock, according to EPI.
The richest 10 percent of households in the United States have
reaped 85.5 percent of the growth in the market since 1989.
Conversely, the typical middle-class family had nearly 3 percent
less wealth in 1997 than in 1989. Perhaps One of the more puzzling
pieces of this prosperity is our behavior. Despite misgivings about
jobs, we are spending as if this run will never end. We are maxed
out on our credit cards. Personal bankruptcies are at historic
highs. Personal savings are at the lowest level since the middle of
the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't behave as if they were truly anxious about their
future,'' said Deavers at the Economic Policy Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And that may speak volumes about the devil-may-care attitude
some workers are taking.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers are job-hopping, bailing out or bypassing corporate
America. Career strategists see that as a positive outgrowth in all
of the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers are realizing they have to be responsible for their
own career and development, and organizations are pushing that more
and more on them,'' said Bob McDonald, who with business partner
Don Hutcheson founded the Highlands Program, an Atlanta-based
national training and development company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much more freedom for those people who want to chart
their own career,'' said career adviser Marilyn Moats Kennedy.
``This is all shaping up to give self-employment a big boost.
...The best and the brightest will end up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner covers workplace issues for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
