A1113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-MICHIGA     09-05 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-MICHIGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME BEATS MICHIGAN, 36-20  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ There were only two things that could have
soothed the Notre Dame faithful after the most difficult off season
in the school's history: the return to the option offense and an
upset victory against Michigan. One led to another Saturday as
quarterback Jarious Jackson went back in time to dart and pitch
Notre Dame to a 36-20 victory over the fifth-ranked Wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it an upset, the capacity crowd of 80,225 watched
the Irish put up the most points a Notre Dame team had ever scored
on a Michigan team in 28 meetings. They saw a defense that had
bent, most of the first half, break the will of the Wolverines with
goal-line stands, blocked field goals and timely sacks.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a Lloyd Carr-coached team was beaten in
September in 12 tries, and it was the good old option offense that
drove the beating. Autrey Denson, who is closing in on Notre Dame's
career rushing record, carried 23 times for 154 yards, and Jackson
turned the ball upfield 15 times for 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of recovered fumbles in the third quarter turned Notre
Dame from a bullied team _ cowed by a defensive unit that returned
nine starters from a national championship team that gave up only
9.5 points a game _ into a nimble unit looking for the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by 13-6 at halftime, the Irish mounted a 62-yard
drive that ended with Jim Sanson's third field goal of the
afternoon. On the ensuing kickoff, the sophomore cornerback Brock
Williams separated the ball from the Wolverine tailback Clarence
Williams with a vicious hit that sent the ball bouncing into the
hands of Tony Driver on the Michigan 34-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   It took Jackson, who has waited patiently for three years behind
Ron Powlus, only seven plays to demonstrate why he has been hailed
as the second coming of Tony Rice, the option maestro who last led
the Irish to a national title in 1988. He kept twice, scampering
for gains of 4 and 11 yards. Then on third-and-2, from the 2-yard
line, he executed a perfect play-action fake that froze the
Michigan line, and tossed to tight end Dan O'Leary, who was wide
open in the corner of the end zone. When Sanson kicked the extra
point, Notre Dame was ahead for good, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   On Michigan's next possession, fullback Ray Jackson fumbled when
hit by Anthony Weaver, the first freshman to start on defense for
Notre Dame since 1983. Linebacker Grant Irons was there to gather
it in at Michigan's 35-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   This time it took Jackson only one play. He dropped straight
back and found Raki Nelson streaking down the sideline and put it
in his hands. Suddenly, 23-13, the Irish were on their way.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an embarrassing off season for Notre Dame, which
lost an age discrimination suit filed by a former coach that made
public details of player abuse and internal squabbling among the
coaching staff. The program also reported itself for violating
National Collegiate Athletic Association rules involving gifts
given to a dozen players by a woman who pleaded guilty to
embezzling $1 million from her employer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory Saturday was sure to lift spirits, but it started
slowly. In an odd first half filled with critical penalties, missed
kicks and tough goal-line defense, it looked like the Irish and the
Wolverines would settle for swapping a pair of field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines abandoned their Big Ten-style running game and
went to the air 28 times in the half. The junior quarterback Tom
Brady completed 18 passes for 193 yards _ 8 for 101 yards to Tai
Streets, who continually befuddled the Irish secondary. Three times
Michigan drove inside Notre Dame's 20-yard line, but it still only
had 6 points to show for it. The Wolverines held the ball for 20
minutes of the first half, gained more than 269 yards, and could
not cross the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   But with 2 minutes 59 seconds left in the half, Brady marched
Michigan once more, this time for 72 yards, and then carried the
ball over himself to take his team into the locker room leading
13-7. The touchdown came after A'Jani Sanders, a 5-foot-8-inch
safety, was called for pass interference against the Michigan tight
end Jerame Tuman. Suddenly, a third-and-goal stop was transformed
into four fresh downs from the 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish offense never fired under Jackson in the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
