<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-ATTENDANTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran, attendants reach accord
 &HT;    By Sophia Lezin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AirTran Airlines and its flight attendants reached a tentative
agreement Saturday afternoon, avoiding last-minute flight
cancellations at Atlanta's second-largest carrier during the busy
Labor Day weekend, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic,'' said William Green Jr., the Association of
Flight Attendants' local council president for AirTran, in a
statement. ``The flight attendants worked three years to get a
legally binding contract with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   If a settlement had not been reached, the union had threatened a
campaign called CHAOS _ Creating Havoc Around Our System _ in which
members would stage walkouts from selected flights.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to cause uncertainty among travelers, cost AirTran
business and prod management into a better offer, the union said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran has about 120 daily departures from Hartsfield
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, negotiators for the Association of Flight
Attendants _ to which 500 AirTran flight attendants belong _ and
the airline reached a four-year-agreement that includes pay raises
of 10 percent effective Oct. 31 and annual raises of 4 percent each
year of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the raises, the pact also gives flight attendants
vacation pay, sick pay, merger protection, strong grievance
procedures and other concessions they had requested.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA and AirTran, formerly ValuJet, have been in on-again,
off-again negotiations since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased to continue to build an airline without any
distraction,'' said AirTran President and CEO D. Joseph Corr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
