A1120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOMERUN60     09-05 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-HOMERUN60-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE BLASTS NO. 60 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ His swing was sweet. In one spectacular motion, Mark
McGwire gave a sellout crowd of 47,994 fans at Busch Stadium and
millions of fans watching on television something they had been
waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   There never was any doubt about McGwire's 60th home run, which
came in the first inning of Saturday's 7-0 St. Louis Cardinals
victory over Cincinnati. In the 142d game of the season, McGwire
got a 2-and-0 fastball from Cincinnati's Dennis Reyes and drove it
an estimated 381 feet into the lower deck in left field.
</P>
<P>
   With that, McGwire had caught up to another baseball ghost. On
Tuesday, he had hit his 56th and 57th homers to pass Hack Wilson's
National League record, a mark that had stood since 1930. Only Babe
Ruth and Roger Maris stood before him. Saturday, with his 60th,
McGwire matched Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' McGwire said over and over in his
postgame press conference. ``What's happening right now with
myself, Sammy Sosa, and (Ken) Griffey has brought baseball back on
the map. If you want to say it brought America together, it has. So
be it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had been shut out on Friday night, going 0 for 3 with a
walk in the Reds' 3-2 win. After the game, he was not available to
the media. Nor did he appear publicly before Saturday's contest. He
wasn't mad at anybody. He was refocusing himself. He apparently
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and one on in the first, McGwire stepped to the
plate to thunderous applause. True to their word, the Reds didn't
pitch around the slugger. But Reyes made the mistake of falling
behind with two pitches down and in. His third one was right down
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Pow!
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire rounded the bases, the fans at Busch Stadium went
crazy. They continued to cheer after McGwire had crossed the plate
and disappeared into the Cardinals dugout. The wanted a curtain
call, and got one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before if he's going to get me, it would be with my
best pitch,'' said Reyes. ``That's what I threw. When he hit the
ball, I knew it was gone. All I could do was think about getting
the next hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire made three more plate appearances in the game and was
retired each time, twice on strikeouts. One came in the seventh
inning with two men on base and first base open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about walking him,'' quipped Cincinnati manager
Jack McKeon, ``but I also thought about all those phone calls on my
voice mail calling me the Heel of America. I thought I could aid
the healing process and do something good for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he went about his job Saturday without thinking
about records. He kept to his usual pregame routine, although
neither club took batting practice. Once the game started, he was
patient at the plate, and it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the count was 2 and 0,'' said McGwire, ``I was just
telling myself to get a good pitch to hit and drive it. He threw a
fastball, middle in. I got it up in the air and out of the
ballpark. That's all there was to it. They came after me. In my
last three at-bats, I had been pitched very well.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he used the same bat he had used for his previous
four homers. He will continue to use it until it breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know,'' said McGwire, ``60 is a great number and I'm
going to do my best to do whatever I can in the time left before
me. There is pressure upon me every day I take the field.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire knew that Sosa was still on his tail, playing last night
with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there is a lot of focus on him because he is doing some
great things, too,'' said McGwire. ``He's having a magical year,
and I'm rooting for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
