</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HOPEFUL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCKY ROBERTO WINS THE HOPEFUL STAKES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ For 94 years at Saratoga, they have
called it the Hopeful because it was a career-building stakes for
2-year-olds whose owners were ``hopeful they had a colt of classic
capabilities.'' And it was won by special colts named Man o' War
and Secretariat and, last year, Favorite Trick, later voted Horse
of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The clear favorite Saturday to win this year's Hopeful was the
trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who had already won it three times in this
decade and who had entered two of his star juveniles, Time Bandit
and Tactical Cat. But his hopes were shot down by a 9-1 outsider
named Lucky Roberto, who ran fifth behind Tactical Cat in the
Sanford last month and second behind Time Bandit in the Tremont
four weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Lucky Roberto came from a stalking third place and
sprinted past Tactical Cat to take the lead in the homestretch. At
the finish, he had one length on Tactical Cat, who had three on
Time Bandit. He ran the seven furlongs in 1:23 4/5 and paid $20.20
for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Roberto, a New York-bred colt owned by J. Mack Robinson
and trained by Frank Alexander, will still have to face the No. 1
prodigy in the Lukas barn, Yes It's True, and they most likely will
meet in the Belmont Futurity on Sept. 20. But for now, at least,
Lucky Roberto has outrun two of the Lukas herd in one race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, there are no real excuses,'' Lukas said. ``The
winner ran well and gave a career best. Yes It's True is obviously
our strong one. We'll probably split these two up, but we have some
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Davis rode Lucky Roberto in place of Mike Smith, who won
the Travers on Coronado's Quest one week ago but fractured two
vertebrae in a spill two days later and is out for three or four
months. Davis dedicated his ride aboard Lucky Roberto to Smith, and
added: ``The minute I stepped on this colt, I knew it would be
tough to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the race before the Hopeful, they ran one of the rare rain
makeups at Saratoga: the Saranac Handicap, which was one of two
races canceled because of a violent thunderstorm Wednesday. Parade
Ground, the favorite to win his third straight on the turf after a
successful career on the dirt, was trapped on the rail and finished
second by four lengths to Crowd Pleaser, who certainly lived up to
his name when he paid $53.50 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sheppard was the trainer and Jean-Luc Samyn the rider,
but all of the running was done by Crowd Pleaser, a son of A.P.
Indy, who won his second straight at Saratoga and the fifth in 11
starts in his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-98 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
