A1130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-MANFREDY     09-05 2412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-MANFREDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS ARE FIGHTING WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;   &UR;  &LR; Angel Manfredy doesn't talk like one.
</P>
<P>
   The World Boxing Union super featherweight champion may be the
least-known dangerous fighter in all Christendom, a point he
intends to make to one John Brown Sept. 22 but would rather be
hammering home to people like Prince Naseem Hamed or World Boxing
Council 130-pound champion Genaro Hernandez, the latter generally
considered the most skilled boxer in the world today at that
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Manfredy would even gladly go up to 135 pounds and take on
International Boxing Federation champion Shane Mosley, who is
widely assumed to be the best lightweight around at the moment as
well.
</P>
<P>
   But a rematch with Arturo Gatti, whom he slapped half silly a
few months back in a stunningly proficient performance, holds no
interest to Manfredy despite the money it would bring, because this
Angel wants to be faced only with devilish matches when he goes to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I fight Gatti again?'' Manfredy said last week.
``I'm the one who beat him in his prime. Ivan Robinson (who
recently won a split decision from Gatti in a slugfest that is
likely to be 1998's fight of the year) just got the leftovers. He
didn't beat the real Gatti.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gatti I fought was sharp and strong. Everyone was ducking
him. He was everything he was supposed to be, and I destroyed him
and made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chased Gatti for two years and got 20 percent of what he
got, which is nothing. I wanted to take his soul, to show the world
these superstars ain't nothing. I did it, but it slowed down my
career. After that, everyone wanted big money to fight me, so I got
to go with the flow. I'm not going to fight once a year so people
forget about me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manfredy-Hernandez is the fight at 130 pounds because it looks
like the Prince is ducking everybody. The biggest money fight we
can make is me and the Prince, but HBO is protecting him. Not only
HBO, but his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to fight Kennedy McKinney, and now he's
fighting some Pocket Rocket (former bantamweight champion Wayne
McCullough on Oct. 31) who can't break an egg. Come on. If you
can't punch, what you going to do with the Prince? Catch him with
your little punches? Me and the Prince is the fight about who's
really the best out there.''
</P>
<P>
   These statements came immediately after the words, ``Good
morning,'' so if you get the idea that Angel likes to talk, you'd
be as accurate as his punches. But unlike many of his fellow
practioners of the Sweet Science, Manfredy also likes to fight. It
is something he's been doing in and out of the ring all his life,
and for a time that was a problem because what he was fighting
outside were drink, drugs, and the streets, three things more
lethal than a boxer's fists.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly killing himself in the last of about a dozen
car accidents, Manfredy found God. Or God found him. Although that
hasn't made an angel out of Angel, it has certainly helped him on
the nights when he is paid to box.
</P>
<P>
   That is why his record has improved to 24-2-1 after two early
losses attributable to his lifestyle more than his boxing style.
The memory of those losses has begun to fade, replaced by one
glorious night of destruction against Gatti. Now that he has both
that buffed record and an obscure portion of the 130-pound title,
all he wants is money _ which makes him no different from most
boxers today _ and the chance to fight the very best opponents _
which makes him different from nearly all boxers today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could fight all the champions out there, but they
don't want to fight,'' Manfredy said. ``I want to be in the Hall of
Fame. That's my goal. That's my dream. That's what I want, so I'll
keep on calling out the fighters I want, like the Prince.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a heavyweight in a lightweight's body. That's what I
bring. You see all these heavyweights paid big money and they ain't
doing nothing no more. It's the lightweights and the featherweights
who are making the noise. We're the ones who bring the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Few bring more than Manfredy, who will make his first appearance
in Madison Square Garden when he defends his title against Brown
(18-4, 9 KO's) in a fight that may not last long. Such a fight is
important only if Manfredy doesn't win it, a fact he well
understands. So while he cannot look past Brown, what this Angel
craves is a night in hell with someone like Hamed or Hernandez, a
night when people will say he cannot win the way they said it the
night he changed Arturo Gatti forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamed is making good money,'' Manfredy said of HBO's $12
million poster boy for lighter weights and sizzling entrances. ``I
take my hat off to him. The boxing world can't see what he's doing.
He's blinding the boxing world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the fighters, I don't think. It's the people who
handle the fighters. They don't want to let them go if they can
make a lot of money off of Joe Blow. But my whole life is boxing.
People don't understand how much I love boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't know how it feels. The glory, I love it. I am the
golden boy of the lightweights. I bring the show, the fight, the
blood, the knockouts. Not too many do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not enough do. In boxing, like in life, there just aren't enough
Angels to go around.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Mike Tyson  &LR; soap opera continued last week when his wife's
car was rear-ended outside Washington by a 53-year-old man whose
car was also rear-ended, knocking it into hers. Unfortunately for
all involved, Tyson was a passenger in his wife's car, and he
leaped out and allegedly punched one man in the lip and kicked the
other driver in the groin. What a surprise that his new
``advisor,''  &UR; Shelly Finkel &LR; , &UR;  &LR; within hours was claiming that Tyson
had been seeing a psychiatrist to work on ``anger management.''
Angry about what? Being a fool? Tyson's act gets older and more
boring every day. He is no longer an athlete; he is a sideshow.
He's the bearded lady at the circus, one of the midgets in a
wrestling ring. Most of all, he has become a sad joke. First his
new trainer,  &UR; Jesse Reid &LR; , &UR;  &LR; walked out on him last week, calling
him ``an angry man''; then he is charged with assault following a
fender-bender. That doesn't sound like a well-balanced guy, which
will be the portrayal he'll try to give at his Sept. 19 license
hearing in Las Vegas. But, then, maybe regaining his license is not
his plan. Tyson sounds like a desperate guy looking for a way out
of boxing _ a way out that he can later blame on someone else.
Sound familiar? By the way, isn't it funny how the closer Tyson
comes to actually boxing again, the more trouble he seems to get
into? ... The Manfredy fight is part of TNT's first foray into
televised professional boxing. On the same card will be Mosley
(28-0) defending his title against No. 1 contender  &UR; Eduardo Morales
 &LR; (26-0) and the return to New York of heavyweight  &UR; Shannon Briggs
 &LR; (30-2-1) for a bout against  &UR; Arthur Weathers  &LR; (23-11-1). The
well-traveled  &UR; Louis Monaco  &LR; brings his 7-14-2 record into the
Theatre at Madison Square Garden that night to test  &UR; Corey Sanders
 &LR; (16-6). Sanders is the kid who sliced up  &UR; Andrew Golota  &LR; in July
... Las Vegas police Lt.  &UR; Tom Monahan  &LR; had an interesting
description of the damage former heavyweight champion  &UR; Michael
Dokes  &LR; allegedly did to his fiancee Monday while beating and
sexually assaulting her. ``I've never seen anybody walk out of the
ring after fighting Michael Dokes that looked this bad,'' Monahan
said. Monahan said the woman's face was unrecogniz-able from her
driver's license ... Some have criticized referee  &UR; Mills Lane  &LR; for
breaking up  &UR; Bernard Hopkins  &LR; and  &UR; Robert Allen  &LR; so physically last
weekend that Hopkins fell out of the ring and hurt his ankle badly
enough that the fight was stopped and he will not be available for
a proposed October match on HBO. I didn't see it that way. Both
guys were holding on to each other from the first round like two
men buffeted by Hurricane Harry. They repeatedly refused to break
when ordered, and did so only reluctantly when Lane physically
intervened. When Lane saw Allen holding Hopkins in a headlock and
tried to break them, he shoved the fighters hard after the
challenger refused to unhand the champion. What resulted was both
fighters staggering back off balance, leading to Hopkins's foot
slipping off the ring apron. He tumbled backward out of the ring,
injuring himself. That was unfortunate, but the IBF middleweight
champion asked for what happened, and so did Allen. Meanwhile, poor
Lane now has been involved in more bizarre ring occurrences than
anyone should have to submit to, including Fan Man crashing into
the outdoor ring at Caesars Palace during a  &UR; Riddick Bowe &LR; - &UR; Evander
Holyfield &LR;  bout,  &UR; Oliver McCall  &LR; having a mental breakdown,
dissolving into tears, and refusing to fight back against  &UR; Lennox
Lewis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and Tyson's ear-biting attack on Holyfield. No wonder Lane
is dabbling in a TV career ... Speaking of Lewis, last week he
again implied that Holyfield was ducking him and Tyson was a hollow
shell of the fighter he used to be. ``Basically, he showed he
didn't want to fight me,'' Lewis said of Holyfield's insistence on
first $20 million and then $25 million after the $20 million was
finally delivered. ``If he was serious, we could have sorted out
the money. He's fearful because he knows he can be beat. His two
lackluster performances against Tyson proved nothing except that
Tyson is over the hill and plateaued out. That's what happens when
a man spends time in incarceration.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Talk that 140-pound champion  &UR; Vince Phillips  &LR; will be fighting
again soon may be overstatement. Word is he's presently weighing
170 and will be hard-pressed to be ready for a real fight before
the end of the year ... IBF welterweight champion  &UR; Felix Trinidad
 &LR; has been penciled in for a Dec. 12 date on HBO vs.  &UR; Pernell
Whitaker  &LR; if (a) Trinidad gets out of his promotional contract with
 &UR; Don King  &LR; and (b) Whitaker can stay straight ... There had been
talk of Robinson fighting Mosley or Manfredy, but Robinson has
already been offered a rematch with Gatti Nov. 14 that will pay him
a lot more money and offer less risk. Robinson received only
$75,000 for the first fight and will make considerably more for a
rematch that could spell the end of Gatti's days as a big-money
fighter if he loses for a third straight time. Despite those
losses, no one can argue Gatti's fan appeal even now. The
Gatti-Robinson fight beat both ``Saturday Night Live'' and the new
 &UR; Howard Stern  &LR; show in its time slot ... Here's an example of how
nuts things can get in boxing. When  &UR; Roy Jones  &LR; refused to defend
the WBC light heavyweight title against then-No. 1 contender
 &UR; Michael Nunn  &LR; early this year, the title was declared vacant and
Nunn fought  &UR; Gianfranco Rocchigiani  &LR; to fill it. When Rocchigiani
won, he was declared ``interim champion'' by the WBC and assumed
the interim meant until someone like Jones beat him. Then Jones
defeated former two-time world champion  &UR; Virgil Hill  &LR; in April and
the same WBC handed him back the title, declaring Rocchigiani
``champion in recess'' even though no one had taken him to school.
Now Jones is trying to negotiate a deal with Rocchigiani, who the
WBC now says is the mandatory challenger, but Rocchigiani's people
insist their guy should get close to a 50-50 split because he's the
real WBC champion. Jones, meanwhile, says everyone knows who the
light heavyweight champion is, and it's him. One negotiator for
Rocchigiani made a good argument against that, though. He didn't
try to use ratings sheets or TV rating sheets or anyone's opinion.
He produced cancelled checks made out to the WBC covering the
sanction fee for the ``title'' fight with Nunn and the fee the WBC
charged Rocchigiani for delivery of his world champion's belt. If
he's not a champion, how'd he get the belt? And why'd he have to
pay for it? Now it appears Jones may end up fighting  &UR; Otis
Grant &LR; , &UR;  &LR; possibly in Montreal, on a Nov. 14 card along with the
Gatti-Robinson rematch ... WBC super middleweight champion  &UR; Keith
Mullings  &LR; has been offered an HBO ``Boxing After Dark'' date vs.
 &UR; Bronko McKart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and Mullings is mulling the offer. If he
declines, BAD could go with  &UR; Vuyani Bungu  &LR; vs.  &UR; Danny Romero &LR; . If
the latter comes off, it would be another sign that Romero- &UR; Johnny
Tapia  &LR; is not about to happen because Romero would be fighting at
122 pounds while Tapia still reigns at 115 pounds ... Summer was a
busy time for heavyweight hopeful  &UR; Michael Grant &LR; . Grant was
married Aug. 7, with Holyfield and trainers  &UR; Don Turner  &LR; and  &UR; Tommy
Brooks  &LR; serving as ushers. Then he had to pull out of a Sept. 26
date with  &UR; Ahmad Abdin  &LR; because of a bout with food poisoning. The
fact he has an outside (but very unlikely) shot at Lewis before the
end of the year might have had something to do with that ``food
poisoning.'' ... Boxing has done a unique thing even by its own
sometimes questionable standards. It has scheduled back-to-back
mismatches, with  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya  &LR; fighting washed up  &UR; Julio Cesar
Chavez  &LR; on Sept. 18 and Holyfield defending the heavyweight title
vs. No. 1 pretender  &UR; Vaughn Bean  &LR; Sept. 19, which led New York
Daily News boxing maven  &UR; Michael Katz  &LR; to comment: ``Watch
Holyfield-Bean. The mismatch you haven't seen is always better than
the mismatch you've already seen.'' So who's fighting Sept. 20?
Lennox Lewis vs.  &UR; Joe Louis &LR; ? ...  &UR; Vernon Forrest  &LR; (25-0, 20 KOs)
won the North American Boxing Federation welterweight title
recently with an 11th-round stoppage of  &UR; Adrian Stone &LR;  ... Word is
 &UR; Andrei Pastriev  &LR; now will fight  &UR; Jose Luis Lopez  &LR; for the vacant
World Boxing Association welterweight title. Lopez twice dropped
 &UR; Ike Quartey  &LR; in a fight that was judged a draw. To lure Lewis to
the Mohegan Sun Sept. 26 to defend the WBC heavyweight title, the
Connecticut casino will erect a 5,000-seat tent to house the event.
Obviously, Lewis is the draw, but the best fight on the card may
well between  &UR; David Tua  &LR; (31-1, 26 KOs) and  &UR; Hasim Rahman &LR; . Rahman
holds both the US Boxing Association and IBF Intercontinental
heavyweight titles, and will risk both against Tua. Offcials at
Mohegan Sun are elated at landing the Lewis- &UR; Zeljko Mavrovic  &LR; bout
and believe as soon as they can build their proposed 10,000-seat
arena, they can become a player in boxing's casino big time.
</P>
</TEXT>
