<DOCNO> NYT19980905.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-DENVER-BOS &LR;      09-05 2246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-DENVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRY ELWAY READY TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVE VALLEY, Colo. _ John Elway walked off the practice field
just before noon. The sun was gloriously warm, a perfect late
summer's day on the Front Range of the Rockies, and the routine was
just about to begin. Elway would speak with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Elway is now at that age _ 38, to be precise _ and station in
his pro football life when he practices when he wishes and talks to
the media on his terms. Virtually no one-on-one interviews, just
this one session a week in which Elway answers questions for
perhaps five minutes, sometimes less.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are scattershot. Each reporter has his or her own
needs. Elway talks, jumping from this question to that, doing his
duty. One Denver TV station wants to know whom Elway likes in the
monstrous Colorado-Colorado State game that was played last night
at Mile High Stadium, another wants to know why the Denver Broncos
always beat the Patriots, a third asks about New England's
linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots are a good football team and we're going to have
to go out and play well; the past has nothing to do with it,''
Elways says. ``Opening Day is so important because you can really
get behind the 8-ball in a hurry. Especially when you've got
Opening Day at home and you've got to win it, I always feel more
pressure on Opening Day than almost any other game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coates or Shannon Sharpe? Each questioner is following that
story, and Elway cooperates: ``Shannon is a guy we can use on third
down. Both are great receivers. Ben is a little bit bigger but I
think Shannon is a little bit faster, but the bottom line for Drew
(Bledsoe) is that Ben is his go-to guy and Shannon's the same with
me. They're great guys to have because if you can't outsize them,
Shannon can outquick them and the same, vice versa, with Ben. The
fact that they try and come with a DB, but Ben's a lot stronger
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   A scattershot answer, too.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous athletes in America all can say many words
without saying anything _ it's a matter of practice, if not
survival _ but Elway seldom has been like that. His very rambling
answer to the Sharpe-Coates question suggested his mind was
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And then came The Question.
</P>
<P>
   ``John, how's Janet doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's doing better,'' came flying from Elway's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting out of the hospital today, or was it yesterday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, today.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was imagined, maybe not, but there seemed a slight
crack in Elway's voice.
</P>
<P>
   Changing times
</P>
<P>
   John Elway said he has already forgotten the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that stuff is behind us, and really the only time it gets
brought up is when you guys ask about it,'' said Elway. ``Other
than that, we don't really do much talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl may be a memory, but even with the season opening
Monday night against New England, football itself can seem distant
in comparison to Elway's personal worries.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it has been difficult to focus on football, Elway said,
``Yeah. It's always tough when you have things going on the other
fronts that are more important than ... this. It's tough to focus
on things that are less important.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to overstate what the Broncos mean to Denver,
especially now that Denver has won the Super Bowl, nor is there any
way to overstate John Elway's place in these Rocky Mountains _ he
is higher than any of them _ or that of his wife, Janet, who is
regularly referred to on Denver TV as ``the First Lady of Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   But a month ago, Elway brought his 37-year-old wife to the Mayo
Clinic in Rochester, Minn., where her colon was removed. After
returning home, Janet Elway was brought to a Denver hospital
because of complications from the surgery and remained there for at
least a week before going home last Thursday. Few details about the
surgery or the complications are known and John Elway,
understandably, is not pressed about them.
</P>
<P>
   Life seldom can be X'd-and-O'd on a blackboard. Just a few
months ago, John Elway had finally made up his mind that he would
not retire with his Super Bowl triumph but would return for one
more season. In football terms, it made sense because Terrell Davis
is such a force and opposing teams would first and foremost have to
stop Davis and the Denver running game, so Elway most likely would
not be battered and bloodied much.
</P>
<P>
   It is understood in Denver that Elway also returned as a favor
to Pat Bowlen, the Broncos' owner, who is trying to have the public
pay for much of the costs of a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will decide in November whether to extend the sales tax
that paid for the construction of Coors Field to cover 74 percent
of the costs of the new football stadium. If Elway were retired,
and if Bubby Brister were the Denver quarterback, and if the
Broncos were 4-4, voters just might be a bit more reluctant to foot
the bill. If Elway and the Broncos are again flying high in
November, passage might be more likely.
</P>
<P>
   So, until a month ago, all seemed fine. But events that occurred
within a few days of each other in early August made this a most
traumatic summer for Elway.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was his wife's operation, the effect of it on the
Elways' four children (three daughters and one son, ages 7 to 12),
and then Elway's trip to Sturgis, S.D., and an annual bikers'
reunion where he tried persuade his old pal, Gary Zimmerman, to
return to the Broncos and play left tackle again. The future Hall
of Famer seemingly was ready to return but then changed his mind
and decided to remain retired.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he might have decided to retire himself if he knew what
was going to happen, Elway said, ``Ahhh, no. I'm just ... you know
... the situation was always tough, but when it came along, it
allowed me the time to do both, to spend time with her and it being
in the preseason ... ahh ... who knows what would have happened if
it had been during the regular season? Ah, no, there's nothing
that's going to come up to question me playing again.''
</P>
<P>
   As sharp as ever
</P>
<P>
   ``They had talked in the offseason, John and Zim, sort of like
if John was coming back, so was Gary,'' said Brister, Elway's
backup. ``It was sort of like a package deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Elway announced that he was coming back, similar words
were not forthcoming from Zimmerman. So Elway headed off to Sturgis
after leaving his wife at the Mayo Clinic and spent time amid
thousands of bikers, Hell's Angels vrooming and zooming the entire
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Zim came back, it would not only help our line and give us
more depth,'' said Brister, ``but Zim was also John's pal. They had
been together so long, and they sort of had that little pact, if
one came back, they both came back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmerman did not come back to the Broncos. So Elway's heart
was heavy returning from the trip. Brister thought Elway had second
thoughts about his decision to play one more year.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's not really affected emotionally where people can see,''
said Brister, ``and he might keep it under wraps or whatever, but I
think he felt at the time that if he was coming back, Zim was
coming back. It was a given.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in Brister's mind, Elway ``was probably bothered by Zim's
decision, but it was cut-and-dried. It had to be. That's because
John was more worried about Janet.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoulders shrug when an outsider asks around the Broncos locker
room or among the media for a close friend of Elway's to talk to on
the team. ``Talk to the other QBs'' is a reply heard more than
once.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Elway has outlasted many of his friends on the
Broncos. He is still playing while many of his friends over the
years have retired and now are coaching or taking on other careers
far removed from football.
</P>
<P>
   But Brister _ one of ``the other QBs'' _ roomed with Elway at
camp in Greeley, Colo., and will room with Elway when Denver is on
the road and has been close enough to Elway to see how this
traumatic summer has affected the legend.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no doubts about Elway The Quarterback, Brister was quick to
offer. Just last Thursday, for instance, when Denver was putting in
its final touches for its game plan for Monday night's game,
Brister couldn't help but notice Elway's demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's still sharp as a tack,'' said Brister. ``We were
putting in some plays for the Patriots and we had some audibles and
I guess John went home and studied them (Thursday) night and came
to our meeting (Friday morning) and John talked to the coaches
about how there would be a better way to do this particular
audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they changed it and the coaches started evaluating the play
and they finally decided John was right. Whether it was his
intuition or whatever, John saw that he could do something better.
He's still as sharp as he ever was.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Elway's body, Brister said, ``I don't see a 38-year-old
body. He's been beat up a lot over the years, he's had a lot of
surgeries and his knees bother him some, but I still don't see a
38-year-old body.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Brister was into it, saying, ``I see a guy who comes out
here every day, has fun and he can still outthrow most everybody in
the league. Plus, he's probably smarter than anybody in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Brister told of how Elway would be gone two or three days at a
time at training camp to be with his wife ``and he'd come back and
he'd be 8 out of 11 in practice the next day. I know a quarterback
like myself, and most of the rest of the guys in the league, and
you take two or three days off and you'd be rusty as hell when you
came back. But not John. He hits 9 of 11.''
</P>
<P>
   The cliche is just as true in football as it is in basketball,
baseball, or hockey: The legs go first. But even here Brister
countered that Elway _ while clearly not as mobile as he was 10
years ago _ still has legs, ``because he tucked the ball under his
arm in that game we had here at Mile High just a couple of weeks
ago (against Green Bay), turned the corner and picked up 8 or 9
yards. I'd say John's legs are still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, said Brister, Elway has Davis. And Davis makes
Elway healthier and happier and prolongs his football life.
</P>
<P>
   ``John doesn't get beat up the way he used to several years ago
because of the way we run the ball,'' said Brister. ``I'm sure
that's why John feels as good as he does right now, because the
last couple of years he hasn't been beat up as much. And you know
what?''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of system we're in, with Terrell running, and the way
John keeps himself in condition, in the offseason lifting weights
and all, I see John playing until he's 40.''
</P>
<P>
   40?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh. 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure persists
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only my personal opinion,'' Brister said, and then added
again for emphasis, ``Now this is only opinion and it's not
something John said, but I was his roommate.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John had some doubts in his mind then whether he
should have come back or not,'' said Brister. ``I mean, during that
time when Janet was in the hospital and Zim wasn't coming back,
back at that time when all this was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all that was tough on him,'' said Brister. ``Having to
leave and stuff and worrying about Janet and then it sort of hit
home that Zim wasn't coming back. John was missing a lot of
practice then and I think he was having those doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   If he had not decided to return to football, Elway could have
been with his wife in her time of need. And with Zimmerman gone,
the Broncos' offensive line was flipped topsy-turvy, Tony Jones
moving from right tackle to left, and veteran Harry Swayne, a
backup at left tackle, moving to right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now that Janet's doing better, John's happy to be here
because he's such a competitor,'' Brister went on. ``Him not being
here this year when he can still run and throw and still be one of
the best quarterbacks in football would have hurt him and, of
course, would have hurt the team, because, John can still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It it estimated that Elway has made more than $100 million from
football, his car dealerships that were sold last season to Wayne
Huizenga, and other business interests. Some believe that Elway
will enter Colorado politics once his football career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no second thoughts (about coming back),'' Elway said.
``I'm really looking forward to playing this year and where we go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, football is no release from the worries at home, Elway
said, ``because of the stuff that we (quarterbacks) have to do, the
stuff mentally that we have to know. We're under a lot of pressure
mentally to do a lot of different things, so it's tough to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Elway was asked if he felt his age, if he felt like a
38-year-old playing a position that so few 38-year-olds have been
able to play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' replied Elway. ``You don't really feel a lot
different from 28 to 38 except there are things that you can and
can't do, especially physically. But mentally, I'm better off than
when I was 28.''
</P>
<P>
   Elways then added that he was saying to a few teammates just the
day before ``that it'd be nice if I can feel the way I feel right
now the rest of the season. But, ah, I know it's downhill from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``here'' _ mentally, at least _ is not as high as the Rocky
Mountains that could be seen over John Elway's shoulders.
</P>
</TEXT>
