</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-IAFRATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLY, HE'S A WILD THING OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Farewell, big Al. We hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   Some big names have been hanging up the skates this offseason,
most notably Mike Gartner and Kevin Lowe. Both had stellar careers
and were classy, intelligent ambassadors for the sport. But another
veteran whose career appears over will be missed in a far different
way. Defenseman Al Iafrate announced last week that his chronic
knee injuries will prevent him from honoring the contract he signed
in July with the Carolina Hurricanes. Back and knee operations have
plagued Iafrate's last few years; he's spent more time in
rehabilitation centers than the therapists who work there. The man
nicknamed ``Wild Thing'' is saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sad aspects of sports in the '90s _ with more written
about money, contract disputes, and legal troubles than the games
themselves _ is that there are very few characters anymore. The
Bruins of the 1970s were full of colorful personalities who
participated in some outrageous antics. Iafrate was a throwback to
the old days. He smoked, lighting his cigarettes with the blowtorch
players use to finish their sticks. He was a Harley Davidson
devotee and had a rock 'n' roll radio show when he played in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the ice, Iafrate was a ferocious presence with a slapper that
could reach 105 miles per hour. In his brief, troubled tenure with
the Bruins, Iafrate played 12 regular-season games and 13 playoff
games in 1993-94. His postseason performance against the Montreal
Canadiens was mammoth, giving the fans a taste of the Iafrate of
old. He didn't play the next two seasons because of injuries. In
the past two seasons with San Jose, Iafrate appeared to be playing
on borrowed time and was limited to a total of 59 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al is devastated,'' said Rick Curran, Iafrate's agent. ``You
can't even imagine how much time and effort he's put into his
rehabilitation over the last three to five years. He's leaving the
door open, and if there's anybody who can walk through that door,
it's Al.''
</P>
<P>
   At 32 and with his injury history, it seems highly unlikely that
Iafrate, who faces yet another knee surgery, can go through all the
necessary rehabilitation again with no guarantee he can resume his
career. It was painful to watch him go through it for two years in
Boston. As Cam Neely and other athletes with chronic injuries have
experienced, there is no lonelier place than the trainer's room
when everyone else is out on the ice. For a time, Iafrate was
bigger than life, a personality who put the ``free'' in ``free
spirit.'' The fans and the league are poorer for no longer having
him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother told me she didn't want me to play football,''
Iafrate told me not long ago. ``She was afraid I'd get hurt.
Ironic, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Ironic indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It was a big summer for former Bruin  &UR; Rick Tocchet &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
recently tied the knot in Scottsdale, Ariz. After some rough times
because of injuries, Tocchet was back to form with the Coyotes last
season, scoring 26 goals in 68 games. In the playoffs, Tocchet
scored a team-leading six goals and had eight points in six games.
He has been a leader on every team he's played for and has asserted
those skills this summer, calling for the underachieving Coyotes to
pick it up. ``I think everybody should be ticked off,'' said
Tocchet, referring to the team's first-round punchout in the
playoffs. ``For some reason, this organization thought it was OK to
mess around for three months, then make a push in the last two,
three months. It doesn't work that way. I believe this team really
has to have a good start in October. None of this .500-at-Christmas
stuff.'' Phoenix has the talent to go farther than it has, but the
real question mark revolves around the mess that is the  &UR; Keith
Tkachuk  &LR; contract situation. Tkachuk is a good kid, always has
been, but seems misguided in his demands this time. The backlash
when and if this situation is resolved has the potential to be
brutal. The proper thing for the team to do would be to give the
captaincy to another player, specifically Tocchet. It would take
some of the pressure off Tkachuk and would ensure the club's
leadership would be in good hands. In this writer's opinion, both
sides have handled the Tkachuk dispute dreadfully. Tkachuk should
either honor his contracts or stop signing them, and the team
shouldn't have opened this renegotiation Pandora's box unless it
was prepared to follow through. This nonsense serves no one well
... Is there any more baffling situation than that of  &UR; Pavel Bure
 &LR; in Vancouver? Bure has demanded out and GM  &UR; Brian Burke  &LR; said
he'll let Bure sit out the year in a suspension (the player is due
to make $8 million US this season) if he can't work a proper deal
for the Russian Rocket. Bure won't publicly discuss his reasons for
wanting to be traded after seven seasons with the Canucks. His
agent,  &UR; Mike Gillis &LR; , said if the reasons are made public, they
``are going to do nothing but create ill will toward a bunch of
different people. I don't think (an explanation) is advisable, good
business, or necessary. I don't know why people can't understand
that.'' With all due respect to Gillis, given the facts, why would
anyone understand it? Bure is the one who is creating all kinds of
ill will among the people who have paid his generous salary all
these years. Maybe his reasons are legitimate, but if he has a
problem and wants out, Bure should take responsibility for the
reasons he wants to leave and be honest about them. He is coming
across as yet another whiny, spoiled athlete, which the public has
been fed a steady diet of in other sports, and blames the media for
the friction he has created ... There's quite a row going on
between Florida and Toronto regarding the deal nearly struck
between the clubs. It appeared a lock that goalie  &UR; Felix Potvin
 &LR; and defensive prospect  &UR; Jeff Ware  &LR; would head to Florida for
forward  &UR; Rob Niedermayer  &LR; and defenseman  &UR; Rhett Warrener &LR; . However,
what hung up the deal was that the Leafs wanted Niedermayer, who
has a history of concussions, to undergo an exam to determine if he
was fit to play. Panthers general manager  &UR; Bryan Murray  &LR; believes
that Niedermayer, who doesn't want to leave South Florida, undercut
the deal by saying his post-concussion symptoms flared up over the
summer. Murray is outraged at leaks out of Toronto that alerted
Niedermayer to the trade. ``If they've had past injuries, all they
have to say is, `Yeah, doc, I get a bit of a headache once in a
while,' to try to scare off the other team,'' said Murray. ``(The
news leaks) gave the player a chance to react to it. It affected
getting things done. I'm frustrated by that. I was ready to do
something big with Toronto.''  &UR; Mike Smith &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Leafs' associate
GM, said he didn't leak any names. ``I've been accused by other GMs
of doing that, too, but that's not my style,'' said Smith. ``I
haven't done that and I won't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   It's Sept. 6 and the Bruins' five Group 2 free agents remain
unsigned. Time for somebody to blink, gentlemen ... The Lightning
spent the offseason rebuilding and have added some talent to what
was the worst team in hockey last year. However, one of their
returnees, forward  &UR; Alex Selivanov &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is expected to be out 8-12
weeks because of wrist surgery to repair torn cartilage. Selivanov
was injured during summer workouts ... Lightning forward  &UR; John
Cullen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is attempting to make a comeback after battling
cancer, is asking for a one-way contract, but owner  &UR; Art Williams
 &LR; is balking. ``I don't like the idea of him being guaranteed a big
income to go down and play in the minors if that's what ends up
happening,'' said Williams. ``We're trying to be sensitive here,
but I don't want anybody having a feeling of security. To me,
there's no room for negotiation.'' Cullen reportedly is asking for
a one-year, one-way deal for $350,000 _ whether the ex-Boston
University star makes the team or not. The Lightning have offered a
$500,000 salary for making the NHL team and $100,000 for playing in
the minors. Both sides have proposed bonus clauses that if reached
could bring Cullen $1 million ... Dallas's assistant GM,  &UR; Les
Jackson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has left the Stars to take the same position with the
Atlanta Thrashers. Jackson had been a candidate for the Thrashers'
GM role, which went to  &UR; Don Waddell &LR; . ``Don and I go way back,''
said Jackson, 45. ``When I went there (to interview), I found it to
be such a neat setup. I felt it was such a good opportunity that I
wanted to jump in right now.'' Atlanta is due to come into the
league at the start of the 1999-2000 season. Jackson will have more
responsibility in his new role _ he will be in charge of scouting,
player development, and contract negotiations ... Former Canadiens
forward  &UR; Marc Bureau &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who signed with the Flyers as an
unrestricted free agent, said he thinks the Habs let him go because
he was too outspoken. ``I've been criticized for being too
upfront,'' said the 32-year-old, who agreed on a three-year pact in
Philly. ``But if that's all it was, that's not much. What counts is
that when the time came to do the job on the ice, I got it done.
And, anyway, the things I said never caused any problems. I still
don't understand why the Canadiens let me go, but I'm not alone
there. Unlike here (in Montreal), I feel wanted by the Flyers. The
day after I signed with Philadelphia, there was a message on my
answering machine from  &UR; Eric Lindros &LR; . I thought that was not
bad.'' ... Detroit coach  &UR; Scotty Bowman  &LR; continues his recovery
from heart surgery and a knee replacement operation. Bowman,
rehabilitating at his Buffalo home, is said to need 6-10 more weeks
of recovery. Red Wings associate coaches  &UR; Dave Lewis  &LR; and  &UR; Barry
Smith  &LR; will split the coaching duties in Bowman's absence, with
Lewis handling the defensemen and Smith guiding the forwards ... It
appears the career of 36-year-old center  &UR; Joel Otto  &LR; is over. The
Flyers declined to pick up an option on Otto's contract, and Otto
has moved his family back to Calgary. ``I'm going out in the
sunset,'' said Otto. ``I'm just kind of fading away. I've had
enough ... and the feeling is probably mutual. I haven't put out
any feelers. I just decided it's time to settle my family down and
spend some time with them. I'm sure, with September here, it'll be
different, but I'm ready to leave the game and move on. Things can
change, but for the time being, Calgary's where we want to be.''
... Former Bruin  &UR; Steve Leach  &LR; has changed teams. After he played
45 games for Carolina last year, getting four goals and nine
points, the Hurricanes bought out Leach's deal and the 32-year-old
right wing agreed to terms with the Ottawa Senators, who are
looking to add grit and leadership to their lineup ... Attorney
 &UR; Brian Cook  &LR; reports that forward  &UR; Eric Healey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who was a Hobey
Baker candidate and finished second in the ECAC in scoring with 21
goals and 48 points in 35 games with RPI, signed a one-year,
two-way contract with the Calgary Flames. Healey is a native of
Hull and his father,  &UR; Tom &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is a Quincy police detective ... 34
days to opening night.
</P>
</TEXT>
