<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES TURN UP HEAT FROM THE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Boston College didn't get much respect from the
Southern folks. A story in Friday's Atlanta Journal Constitution
kidded that ``BC'' stood for the last time Boston College had a
good football team. There were other remarks about this being a
Georgia Tech warmup game for North Carolina, and stuff about a
second-rate team from a second-rate conference. Last year's 42-14
Tech victory at Chestnut Hill no doubt contributed to the
overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above sweetened Saturday's 41-31 BC victory over
Georgia Tech. On a brutally hot Georgia day, BC's Mike Cloud ran
for a cumulus 203 yards and Scott Mutryn completed 16 of 26 passes
for 220 yards and one touchdown (plus two TDs on the ground) as the
Eagles opened their season with an upset win in the heart of the
South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they gave us any respect,'' said second-year BC
coach Tom O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a few comments about this being a warmup for North
Carolina,'' said Cloud. ``That added a little spark underneath
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior offensive lineman Doug Brzezinski said, ``We wanted to
prove we were an opponent worth playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mutryn added, ``Did they overlook us? Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks take football seriously in these parts, which might
explain why BC was so easy to disrespect. Tech has some tradition
to go along with four national championships since 1917. The Yellow
Jackets play at Bobby Dodd Stadium/-Grant Field, which was built in
1913 (one year after Fenway Park) and is the granddaddy of all
Division 1-A football sites. John Heisman himself coached here.
Only Penn and Harvard play in older stadiums, and the Ivies no
longer play with the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's home field sits in the heart of the campus, which served
as site of the 1996 Olympic Village. The campus swimming pool is
where Ireland's Michelle Smith won three gold medals, laughin' and
lyin' her way through those post-swim drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone could have used a dunk in the pool Saturday. It was 93
degrees at game time with typical tropical humidity. The 3:30
starting time only exaggerated the stifling conditions.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sun-bleached 38,229 seemed to mind. Heavyweight
champ Evander Holyfield, an Atlanta resident, didn't even break a
sweat as he watched from press level. But O'Brien was mindful of
the heat and rotated his players (including Tim Hasselbeck for
Mutryn for one series) throughout the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were tough conditions,'' said O'Brien. ``You can't get
this kind of heat in Boston. It was hot out there and these kids
were sucking air. But we hung in and outscored 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles looked a little too much like Harvard in their snappy
new red pants, but they played like some of BC's recent bowl teams.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been a good omen when Tech's first attempt to
score _ a 34-yard field goal try _ clanged off the right upright.
Proving they were not as slow as O'Brien feared, the Eagles clawed
to a 10-0 lead before Tech made it 10-7 midway through the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   With just over a minute left in the first half, BC's Brian Maye
intercepted a pass, and four plays later Rob Tardio caught a
15-yard TD pass from Mutryn to give BC a 17-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a touchdown of infinite redemption. Along with long
snapper Kyle Geiselman, Maye and Tardio are the only BC players
involved in the 1996 gambling scandal who play for the Eagles. Maye
is in his sixth year at the Heights, which makes him BC's version
of Dennis Eckersley. His appearance Saturday was his first since
October 1996, also his first since the scandal broke. He is
cocaptain of the 1998 Eagles. Maye finished with four tackles.
Tardio had a career-best six catches for 52 yards.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien smothered his enthusiasm:
</P>
<P>
   ``I told 'em a story. In 1986 (when O'Brien was coaching
Virginia), we beat South Carolina and everybody had us going to a
bowl. We finished 3-8 because the team was satisfied after that
first win. Now there's going to be a lot of poison by you (media)
and kids on campus telling them how good they are, and if they
drink it, they're gonna die. You can't be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' home opener is next week against Rutgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
