<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     09-05 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFTED IVANISEVIC TAKES IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are tasteful birthday presents, and then ... it
depends on your taste, of course. It seems safe to say that a pair
of handcuffs isn't your everyday present, unless you're a US
marshal.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Ivanisevic, who is not a US marshal, stared at the box
curiously Saturday, and couldn't stand the suspense. He had to see
what was inside, even though the card instructed: ``Don't open
until your birthday.'' That will not occur until next Sunday when
Goran, the quixotic tennis player from Croatia, hopes he will at
last bust his reputation as a bust in the majors by winning the US
Open.
</P>
<P>
   Suspense hadn't entered into his third-round victory as he
cuffed Paul Haarhuis around with 21 aces, 7-6 (7-5), 6-3, 6-4. That
slots him against the champ, Patrick Rafter, Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But how could he resist a package that the postman delivered to
Flushing Meadow? Ivanisevic's colleagues in the locker room were
very pleased that he couldn't because, in Rafter's words: ``He got
some funny things in the mail today. Handcuffs. We're all having a
good laugh about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First time in my life I see handcuffs,'' rumbles Ivanisevic in
that distinctive bass voice, deeper than his sorrow at blowing the
Wimbledon final to Pete Sampras. ``I want to kill myself,'' was his
most cheery statement at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I never seen them.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he been appointed sheriff of Flushing? Or was the gift a
suggestion that he cuff himself to a tree in the Petrified Forest
as penance for losing here in the first round three of the last
four years?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' he smiles rakishly. ``Is from a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, a sort of romantic message? This brings to mind Patti Paige
warbling ``Love Letters Straight From the Heart'' or Joe Cocker
with ``I Sent My Baby a Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the cuffs represent the dreaded double-bagel, or an
instrument he wishes he could have used on Sampras, Ivanisevic
seems recovered from his post-Wimbledon depression.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter says Ivanisevic, who fell to No. 14 after six years in
the top 10, is ``the best player of this day never to win a major.
There's more to him than just the big serve.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Goran's 36th major try since falling in his first, the
Wimbledon first round of 1988, and he's never come closer here than
a semifinal defeat by Sampras two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good mate of mine. Why? Because Goran's crazy,'' Rafter
laughs. ``We really get along. But there's no love lost when we
play.''
</P>
<P>
   During a frustrating moment of his difficult four-set victory
over Todd Martin Thursday night, Ivanisevic knelt on the court and
pounded his head against the asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he recalls. ``I started to play better.
Probably something, sometimes I have a little bit messed up in
there. I have to bang _ then everything comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   If Goran continues banging his serve and his head productively
against the mean green slabs, the quick hard courts of Flushing, he
may slip the cuffs off his terrible record in the majors and give
himself the best birthday present of all a week from Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
