<HEADLINE>
SUPPLEMENT USER STRIKING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What drug did Randy Barnes, the Olympic shot put champion, take
to get him booted from his sport for life? The same stuff that's
helping Mark McGwire chase Roger Maris from baseball's record book.
Androstenedione may be shrugged off as a harmless nutritional
supplement by major league baseball, but the International Olympic
Committee considers it a steroid and has banned it. Barnes, who
claims he didn't know andro was a no-no when he tested positive
last spring, is appealing, but odds are he's finished.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IOC, conceding that it's been losing the doping
war for years, has called a special global summit for February to
decide what should and shouldn't be banned and how to police it.
While athletes have been bulking up on epitestosterone and human
growth hormone and going undetected, the Lords of the Rings have
been chasing Sudafed users and marijuana smokers and trying to do
it all for a paltry $20 million on drug tests. As it is, roughly
half of American athletes picked for random tests by the US Olympic
Committee get off because it costs too much to find them.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Why did those five East German coaches and doctors get off with
fines after a Berlin court convicted them of feeding steroids to
unsuspecting young swimmers for more than a decade? Because they'd
already confessed and apologized to the athletes after claiming
they didn't know the drugs were harmful. Meanwhile, one of the
swimmers is sterile and the others have suffered from side effects
... The Russian economy may be melting down, but Saturday's Grand
Prix track and field final went on as scheduled in Moscow. Though
50 athletes, led by US sprinter  &UR; Jon Drummond &LR; , &UR;  &LR; petitioned to have
the IAAF move the meet because of the chaos in the Motherland, the
federation assured everybody that they would be secure and well
paid ($3.7 million in hard currency, not rubles). Meanwhile, there
are modest expectations for the United States at this week's
quadrennial World Cup meet in Johannesburg. The Yanks, who compete
for the Americas team under the continental format, were sixth
(men) and eighth (women) last time. Top names include
sprinter-jumper  &UR; Marion Jones &LR; , &UR;  &LR; shot putter-discus thrower  &UR; John
Godina &LR; , &UR;  &LR; 400-meter runner  &UR; Jerome Young &LR; , &UR;  &LR; hurdlers  &UR; Bryan
Bronson &LR; , &UR; Reggie Torian &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Kim Batten &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and distance runner
 &UR; Regina Jacobs &LR; . Africa (men) and Europe (women) are defending
champions ... Odds are you won't see anyone try to match the
200/400 double that  &UR; Michael Johnson  &LR; and  &UR; Marie-Jose Perec  &LR; pulled
off last time at next year's world championships in Seville, Spain.
Both events have rounds on the same day. And Jones, who's trying to
pull off a  &UR; Carl Lewis  &LR; multiple, has qualifying for the 100 and
long jump 15 minutes apart ... Barely two months after it regained
the world title, the US women's basketball team has already begun
choosing up folks for the 2000 Olympics.  &UR; Lisa Leslie &LR; , &UR; Nikki
McCray &LR; , &UR; Dawn Staley &LR; , &UR; Jennifer Azzi &LR; , &UR; Ruthie
Bolton-Holifield &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Katie Smith &LR; , &UR;  &LR; all members of the world
team, have been named to the national team that will compose the
bulk of the Sydney roster. All but Smith also won gold medals in
Atlanta two years ago. Four of them (Staley and Bolton-Holifield
are coming off knee surgery) will play for the squad that's Down
Under this week for five games against the Australians ... Who says
the Yugoslavs are men's world basketball champs? Not the Harlem
Globetrotters, who've challenged them to a friendly game for
planetary bragging rights. The Washington Generals get losers.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Tough act to follow for the US rowers at this week's world
regatta in Cologne after last year's six &UR;  &LR; medals, three of them
gold. Four of the champion men's eight return, as does sculler
 &UR; Jamie Koven &LR; .  &UR; Sarah Garner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the women's lightweight
single, is in the double this time. Local rowers include East
Bridgewater's  &UR; Wendy Wilbur  &LR; (women's eight), Boston RC's  &UR; Adam
Holland  &LR; and Newburyport's  &UR; Cy Beasley  &LR; (men's pair), Charles River
RC's  &UR; Greg Ruckman  &LR; and  &UR; Steve Tucker  &LR; (men's lightweight double),
Manchester's  &UR; Josh Crosby  &LR; (men's lightweight pair), Norwood's
 &UR; Carol Skricki  &LR; (women's double), Cambridge's  &UR; Terry Paige
 &LR; (women's lightweight quad), and  &UR; Wolf Moser  &LR; of Center Harbor,
N.H. (men's coxed four). The host Germans, who won 11 medals last
year, are favored to top the table. The Cologne regatta is the
first to have its own theme song, written and performed by six
German oarsmen who've cut a CD that includes party mix, gala mix,
and electro mix versions of the theme ... Gutsy performance by
 &UR; Blaine Wilson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who shrugged off a torn rotator cuff to win his
third straight US men's gymnastics title, the first three-peat
since  &UR; Kurt Thomas  &LR; in 1978. Nice comeback by 22-year-old  &UR; Kim
Zmeskal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former world champ who placed 11th (and made the
women's senior national team) six years after her last major
international meet.  &UR; Kristen Maloney &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who's been the top woman
all year, knocked off defending champ  &UR; Vanessa Atler  &LR; for the
title, with  &UR; Dominique Moceanu  &LR; third ... Russian Greco-Roman
wrestler  &UR; Alexander Karelin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; arguably the most dominant athlete
in his sport in the world, kept his amazing lifetime unbeaten
streak going at the recent world championships in Sweden by pinning
US superheavy  &UR; Matt Ghaffari  &LR; in a rematch of their 1996 Olympic
duel. Karelin, who has won 11 consecutive Olympic or world titles,
has never lost an international match. The Russians, as expected,
easily won the team title while taking four of the eight golds.
Ghaffari, competing internationally for the first time since
Atlanta, won the only medal for the Americans, who ended up 11th.
The US freestylers, who won only two medals last year and placed
sixth amid post-Olympic rebuilding, figure to fare better at this
week's meet in Tehran ... The incredible shrinking US men's Alpine
A team is temporarily down to zero now that  &UR; Daron Rahlves  &LR; is out
of action with his second dislocated hip in two years. Rahlves, who
got a ski stuck while training recently on a Norwegian glacier,
hopes to be back on the slopes by November. With  &UR; Tommy Moe &LR; , &UR; AJ
Kitt &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Matt Grosjean  &LR; all retired and  &UR; Kyle Rasmussen  &LR; still
up in the air, Rahlves is literally The Man ... Back together again
are skating coach  &UR; Richard Callaghan  &LR; and wayward former pupil
 &UR; Nicole Bobek &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is now on her 12th mentor in the past decade,
several of them twice. Callaghan coached Bobek to her US title and
world bronze medal three years ago and she went into a tailspin
after they parted company, made worse by the untimely death of
coach  &UR; Carlo Fassi  &LR; at the 1997 world championships. Bobek will
split her time between Richmond, where she now lives, and Detroit,
where Callaghan coaches ... Aching limbs and no medals for the
Yanks at the recent world triathlon championships in hilly
Lausanne, Switzerland. Top finishers in the new Olympic sport were
 &UR; Barb Lindquist  &LR; (seventh) and  &UR; Wes Hobson  &LR; (23d). Great Britain's
 &UR; Simon Lessing  &LR; and Australia's  &UR; Joanne King  &LR; were the victors ...
Unless synchronized swimmer  &UR; Bill May  &LR; has a sex-change operation
or can persuade the international federation to alter its rules,
he's essentially limited to domestic waters. Though May and partner
 &UR; Kristina Lum  &LR; are US champions in duet, they can't compete in next
summer's Pan-American Games because the event follows FINA rules,
which ban males from the Olympics, world championships, and World
Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
