<HEADLINE>
DALY STRUGGLES, ONE DAY AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The saga of John Daly continues. The latest chapter was
written in the first round of the Greater Vancouver Open a week ago
Thursday, when he became overcome by shakes and a chill and began
crying on the 15th hole. He was trembling, bundled up in two
jackets on an 80-degree day.
</P>
<P>
   Daly says he has been sober since Easter weekend of 1997, when
he went out of control in a Jacksonville beach club and tore up a
room in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. This led to a separation with his
third wife, Paulette, but they were back together in July during
the British Open at Royal Birkdale, where he missed the cut. Daly
has missed four cuts in his last six tournaments, has withdrawn
from the fifth, and was disqualified in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   His history has been well documented. When Daly returned to the
PGA Tour a year ago at the Memorial after a stint at the Betty Ford
Clinic, he gave a lengthy press conference at Muirfield Village.
``I surrounded myself with people that love me for the problem that
I have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daly played in the US Open at Congressional and walked off the
course after nine holes of the second round without telling anyone,
not even his caddie. He returned to the fairways at the Greater
Hartford Open, and talked about his problems with the shakes,
caused, he said, by the excessive amount of Diet Coke he was
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   He got off to a superb start this season, seemed content at The
Players Championship at Ponte Vedra Beach, but 17 of his last 48
rounds have been 75 or higher. There have been no reports that he
has been back on alcohol, but perhaps, as John Garrity wrote in
Sports Illustrated, there is a depression problem that should be
examined.
</P>
<P>
   Daly is too big a force on the PGA Tour to let it get away from
him.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There was good reason to celebrate when  &UR; Mike Baker &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a native
of Bangor, Maine, who serves as assistant pro at Bangor Municipal
GC, won the 78th New England PGA Championship Thursday at Agawam
Hunt Club. He won an enthralling duel with  &UR; Frank Dully &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a Holy
Cross graduate in his first year as head professional at Kernwood
CC.
</P>
<P>
   Baker dedicated the victory to his father, who died last
November. ``He worked with me on the mental part of the game,''
said the 36-year-old, who finished third in the Maine Open this
year and was the only member of the NEPGA to make the cut in the
National Club Pro Championship at Pinehurst, N.C. ``He was very
calm. He'd say, `Think before you speak.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me into a good frame of mind as far as putting. He'd
say to use the same routine and the same amount of time over the
ball. He wasn't a real student of the game, but if you talk to any
of the pros, that's a good thing to do. I like to look at it from a
few different angles, but I don't want to take all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether Baker will give the PGA Tour
Qualifying School a second look _ he tried a decade ago _ now that
his NEPGA win has given him an exemption into the second round.
``It's definitely not as time-consuming now,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't have to be away from my son as much. I have until Sept. 18
(to decide).''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There are two exciting golfing projects in the works in Vermont.
 &UR; Jim Remy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the immediate past president of the NEPGA, left his
job at Killington to take over as general manager and director of
golf at Okemo Valley in Ludlow, where he will build a course for
owners  &UR; Tim  &LR; and  &UR; Dianne Mueller &LR; . ``We're also going to build a
golf learning center with a full academy,'' he said at the NEPGA
Championship. ``It's under construction now and will open sometime
in the late summer next year. It's a par 71, about 6,700 yards.''
The architect is  &UR; Steve Durkee &LR; . More details from Remy: ``We're
also building a 22,000-square-foot clubhouse, and we'll get it
under construction in about a week. We're going to have membership,
resort, and public golf. The learning center will have a 350-yard
driving range, a chipping and putting green. We're going to have an
indoor learning center where we can take people in inclement
weather and in the winter. There's going to be 4,200 square feet of
indoor hitting area, a computer simulator, a 600-square-foot indoor
putting area, a golf classroom area, and a video review station.''
The first nine holes of the course, located about 25 miles
southeast of Rutland, should be open by next July, along with the
academy. The second nine holes are expected to open in the fall ...
 &UR; Larry Startzel &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the NEPGA Championship in 1979 at
Ferncroft while he was head pro at Stowe CC in Northern Vermont,
returns to the region after a varied tour of duties that took him
from the CC of Lansing (1981-87) in Michigan to Paradise Valley CC
in Phoenix (1988-91) to a stint as director of the Jordan Tour
(1992) to Yahnundasis GC outside Utica, N.Y. (1993-97). He has
signed on to become general manager and director of golf at the new
Country Club of Vermont just outside Stowe. He was lured by a group
of developers to the exclusive course, which will eventually be
restricted. ``I started working last fall,'' said Startzel, who
finished at 76-75-82_233 in the NEPGA Championship. ``It's a very
upscale, private-equity club. It's just pure golf. It's 450 acres
and nothing but golf. There's no housing.'' There are 17 holes
already open on the course designed by  &UR; Grahame Cooke  &LR; of Montreal.
The 18th will be opened next month. ``I was doing consulting work
for them for about a year and a half,'' said Startzel. ``I went up
to look at the property, and they offered me a position. It's just
a phenomenal golf course with tremendous vistas. Every par 4 and
par 5 is an elevated tee shot. I had a huge job, but I'd never
opened a golf course before and I've never been a general manager.
It's sort of where in this industry things are going. I like the
people, and this course is being built for golfers to walk and not
to ride.'' There is some outside play now, but when the membership
is filled out at 260 _ likely within two years _ it will be made
private. There are 127 members presently.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   They were bracing for a few weeks at the old course at
Ballybunion in the west of Ireland's County Kerry for Saturday's
visit from  &UR; President Clinton  &LR; during his trip to Ireland. It was
originally thought that  &UR; Tom Watson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who performed some
architectural modifications to the course, might join Ireland's
 &UR; Christy O'Connor Jr. &LR;  and club captain  &UR; Brian McCarthy  &LR; in the
presidential foursome. Watson, who began stopping off to play a few
rounds en route to the British Open in the early 1980s and started
a flurry of stopovers that included  &UR; Tiger Woods &LR; , &UR; Mark
O'Meara &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ernie Els  &LR; this year before the championship at
Royal Birkdale, was approached to make the refinements three years
ago to strengthen the great links course on the cliffs overlooking
the Atlantic Ocean. Clinton was scheduled to play Ballybunion a few
years ago but had to cancel. He promised to return. There are few
tee times available on the old course, but exceptions can be made.
``Right now,'' said club secretary/-manager  &UR; Jim McKenna &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``the
first tee for visitors is booked up almost to 1999. I spend most of
my working day turning down golfers who want to play here.'' ...
The Europeans named  &UR; Mark James  &LR; as Ryder Cup captain for the
matches next year at The Country Club, and it's something of an
irony. The first time the Europeans were included in the mix with
the Great Britain/-Irish makeup was 19 years ago at the Greenbrier,
and James was one of two ``bad boys,'' according to the Irish
Independent. James was fined a record 1,500 pounds by the European
PGA Tour and  &UR; Ken Brown  &LR; was banned from team matches for a year.
Now James is Europe's leader, but ironically again has stirred the
embers by refusing to show up for a scheduled media day involving
US captain  &UR; Ben Crenshaw  &LR; at The Country Club on Sept. 22. The PGA
of America subsequently canceled the event. Why the presence of
James, who said he had a commitment to play in the German Masters
in Cologne, was so essential is a mystery. Who in the world is Mark
James? ... A golfing gala was held Monday to celebrate the
centennial of Wannamoisett CC in Rumford, R.I., where the
prestigious Northeast Amateur has been held for the past 37 years.
 &UR; Brad Faxon &LR; , &UR; Billy Andrade &LR; , &UR; John Cook &LR; , &UR; Dana Quigley &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and the
Senior Tour's  &UR; Jay Sigel  &LR; along with host pro  &UR; Steve Napoli  &LR; played
in an exhibition match. Cook won the Northeast twice (1978, 1979)
and set a course record (8 under par) in 1979 that still stands.
Cook, who flew in after finishing fourth in the World Series of
Golf, hadn't been to the club since his last appearance in the
Northeast Amateur ...  &UR; Harry McCracken &LR; , &UR;  &LR; virtually a lifetime
member at Charles River CC, has organized a new event, the New
England Golf Association's Senior Championship, which will be
played Sept. 21-22 at Metacomet CC. The field includes former
Massachusetts Amateur champions  &UR; Bill Foley  &LR; of Wollaston and  &UR; Ed
Fletcher  &LR; of Bay Pointe and former New England Amateur champion
 &UR; Fred Kask  &LR; of Wethersfield, Conn. The second McCracken Cup will be
played at Charles River the following weekend, making this a hearty
month for the veteran amateur golf official and organizer ...
 &UR; Ronnie Quinn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; one of Rhode Island's noted players, winning the
State Amateur five times, died Aug. 22. He also won the Northeast
Amateur twice in the late 1960s, the New England Amateur, the
Porter Cup, the Rhode Island Open twice, and qualified for the US
Open in 1967 at Baltusrol. He was a Providence attorney who played
out of West Warwick CC, and though he competed only sparingly, he
compiled a noted record. He also was known for playing occasionally
with  &UR; President Eisenhower  &LR; when the summer White House was in
Newport. The president invited him on one occasion to play Augusta
National GC, and Quinn responded by shooting a 68 ... The upcoming
schedule shows qualifying for the USGA Mid-Amateur Championship
Tuesday at Brae Burn, where 123 will vie for seven spots in the
tournament proper (Oct. 3-8) over the South Course at NCR CC in
Dayton, Ohio ... The qualifying for the 16 spots in the NEPGA
individual match play championship was played within the NEPGA
Championship, and Baker will meet No. 16  &UR; Scott Hickey  &LR; of Norton
CC to open play Sept. 30 at Prouts Neck CC.
</P>
</TEXT>
