<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-GRUDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICALLY, GRUDEN THE BEST COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The first head coach of the 21st century starts work two years
ahead of time tonight.
</P>
<P>
   When the Oakland Raiders trot out to meet the Kansas City Chiefs
in the season's first Sunday night game, they will be led by the
youngest coach in pro football, which, historically speaking, bodes
well for them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, a 33-year-old guy named Al Davis took over the Raiders
and transformed them from a 1-13 loser to a 10-4 winner in one
season. Six years later, Davis, by then the team's managing general
partner, elevated a little-known 32-year-old assistant named John
Madden to head coach and was vilified for it. Madden went on to
lead the Raiders to seven AFL or AFC title games and a victory in
Super Bowl XI.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, 34-year-old Jon Gruden will follow in that tradition,
taking over a team that gave the word underachiever new meaning
last season by parlaying a 1,200-yard rusher, a 1,400-yard
receiver, and a 3,900-yard passer into a 4-12 record, losing eight
of their last nine games, and prompting one longtime front office
employee to say this summer, ``It was the first time I ever went to
the stadium knowing we didn't have a chance to win. It was a bad
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Such feelings could lead to only one thing, hence the arrival of
a new coach whom Green Bay's Mike Holmgren calls ``the Whiz Kid.''
Although his youthful face might make you wonder how much he can
possibly know about pro football, few coaches are believed to have
more of a grasp on the nuances of the West Coast offense than
Gruden, who is said to have every play ever run by it diagrammed
and stored on floppy disks that he keeps in a shoebox.
</P>
<P>
   Those disks also include the philosophies of Bill Walsh, the
great speeches of George Seifert, and the thinking of every
football mind Gruden has ever encountered, including the ones in
Philadelphia that he was supposed to leave behind when he joined
the Raiders in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   This process began in 1990 after Gruden had been hired to assist
Holmgren, who was then the San Francisco 49ers' offensive
coordinator. Before he got too settled, Gruden was given 30 days to
computerize the West Coast offense Holmgren had inherited from
Walsh and improved upon.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gruden was 26 and knew two things about computers.
He knew the plug goes into the wall and he knew he'd better find a
techie to teach him more than that.
</P>
<P>
   After hiring such a person, he learned the basics and then went
to work day and night, with the emphasis on night. By the time
Holmgren returned, everything he'd ever done with his offense was
on floppy disks and Gruden's legend was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I'm just a coach,'' the Raiders' newest boss insists
when asked if he should be considered the Bill Gates of coaching.
``So what that I know something about computers? It's not like I
went to Cal Poly.''
</P>
<P>
   No, as a matter of fact, he didn't. He went to the University of
Dayton, where he was a quarterback who had already chosen his
life's work before he got there. Gruden had spent hours sitting in
on coaches meetings of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, where his father
was an assistant under John McKay before moving into scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up a coach's son,'' Gruden said. ``I sat in running
back meetings with my Dad. I knew what I wanted to do since I was
9. I learned then that if you're an expert at something, you can
usually get a job. I wanted to be a quarterback coach even then.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he would become receivers coach for Holmgren in Green
Bay before Eagles head coach Ray Rhodes made him the youngest
offensive coordinator in football in 1995 at the age of 31. If you
see a trend with this age thing, consider that it's a family trait.
Gruden's brother, Jay, is currently the youngest head coach in the
Arena Football League, although it is unknown whether he too needs
specially made anti-glare glasses like the ones the Raiders had
made for his brother so he wouldn't go half-blind staring at his
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer can do so many things,'' Gruden says. ``It's a
great tool. Everyone in football should use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone does, but not everyone is its master. The Raiders have
two full-time computer operators who input information, but Gruden
does his own computer searches and studies, work that often begins
long before the sun rises.
</P>
<P>
   Nocturnal by nature, Gruden is generally working before any of
his colleagues, which is probably why in Philadelphia he helped
produce two playoff teams and a club last year that was second in
passing, fifth in rushing, and third in total offense in the NFC
despite spending much of the season without a true starting
quarterback until the eventual elevation of Bobby Hoying.
</P>
<P>
   But when he arrived there, Gruden's youth had many questioning
whether he was ready to run an NFL offense, just as some are now
questioning whether he's ready to run an NFL team. When the Eagles
lost their first game with him badly, he was no longer the Whiz
Kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost like 21-6 at the Vet and I went from Boy Wonder to Boy
Blunder in three hours,'' Gruden recalls. ``I remember thinking,
`Maybe I bit off more than I could chew.' But I had a lot of
confidence in myself. I developed a thick skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he would need it because Gruden learned about more
than computers and combatting NFL defenses in Philadelphia. He also
learned about head cases, which considering the Raiders' sorry
rec-ord last year may be knowledge he will put to good use.
</P>
<P>
   His problem in Philadelphia was mercurial running back Ricky
Watters. A great runner and receiver yet often a coach's nightmare,
Watters used to have signals he would direct to Gruden in the press
box if he didn't think he was getting the ball often enough.
</P>
<P>
   Watters would make a fist and beat his chest while staring up at
the coaches' box. Word is Gruden had a one-fingered signal he used
to send back most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have our moments,'' says Gruden, a sly laugh following
his words.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden is free of Watters now but some would say he is tethered
to an even more difficult person in Davis. The Raiders' managing
general partner has been a successful coach and front office
operative and has his own philosophy of what the Raider Way should
be, one that has been proven out with three Super Bowl
championships. But it is not, in many ways, the Gruden Way and so
some speculate this may not be a marriage made in football heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Davis insisted that Gruden was the young mind he wanted most
last winter and Gruden says he sees no reason he cannot adapt the
legendary Raider deep passing game to the West Coast style while
benefitting greatly from Davis's counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But before he can do any of that, Gruden must resurrect a
battered legend. Once the most feared team in football, the Raiders
have been anything but the past dozen years. They've missed the
playoffs nine times and have not reached the postseason in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gruden has many of the building blocks his offensive mind
wants. He has a strong-armed quarterback in Jeff George, a great
speed receiver in Tim Brown, and a 1,000-yard rusher in Napoleon
Kaufman. He has a new defensive coordinator who is bringing a more
attacking, zone-blitz style that should force turnovers. And he has
two brand new cornerbacks with impressive hardware, veteran Pro
Bowler Eric Allen and rookie Heisman Trophy winner Charles Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, with the millennium on the horizon, the
Raiders have a coach for the 21st century. All he has to do is win
enough games the next two years to be here for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can coach,'' Gruden says. ``Now I have the
opportunity to prove it. In Philadelphia, I never felt we weren't
going to win on Sunday. Maybe it's because I'm young but I feel the
same way here. I'm not going to the stadium conceding anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jon Gruden is going to the stadium the same way coaches
from the turn of the century to the 21st century have gone. He's
going there to win.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Thursday, the NFL's Executive Committee reviewed
the bids of the four remaining suitors for the Cleveland franchise
and a couple of things became clear. The first is that the price
tag, which will be announced Tuesday when the 30 owners fly to
Chicago to vote on the new owner, will be in excess of the $500
million that has been predicted, according to several sources, and
that will be divided among only 28 of the league's 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams and Baltimore Ravens surrendered their rights
to the expansion fee when they relocated into what the league
considered expansion cities. When they took those cities for
themselves, no such fee could be assessed on those two prime pieces
of NFL real estate, so they were cut out of the upcoming expansion
fee.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one can say for sure who will eventually get the 23
votes needed to win the bidding, the two finalists will be the  &UR; Al
Lerner &LR; - &UR; Carmen Policy  &LR; entry and the one submitted by  &UR; Chuck  &LR; and
 &UR; Larry Dolan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; with the former still holding the inside track.
</P>
<P>
   Many owners were angered by the actions of Ravens owner  &UR; Art
Modell  &LR; when he stood up and spoke against Lerner, his former
minority partner in the Browns. Modell urged the owners to support
the Dolan brothers' bid, but other owners felt the mess that
existed in Cleveland was of Modell's making and to try to influence
the solution now was the height of hubris.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lerner flew Modell to Baltimore on his private jet to
close his deal for the move to Maryland, he later backed away from
his longtime connection to Modell. Lerner held a 50 percent
interest in the stadium and a 9 percent interest in the Browns but
sold both and began form-ulating a plan to bring the NFL back to
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Executive Committee was shocked to learn that when  &UR; Howard
Milstein's  &LR; application was finally submitted, it did not include
the names of former Browns  &UR; Calvin Hill  &LR; and  &UR; Paul Warfield &LR; , &UR;  &LR; as
advertised. That alone may have pushed Milstein out of Tuesday's
final discussion, leaving Lerner and the Dolans to slug it out.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against Lerner, especially if Modell gets up and rips
him one more time on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   49ers wide receiver  &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; acknowledged that he was
nervous about Sunday's game with the New York Jets because he
hadn't tested his twice-repaired knee in game conditions this
summer. Rice was injured in the first game of last season but came
back in December, only to crack his patella while scoring his first
touchdown minutes into the game. He was held out of this summer's
exhibition games but is said to be at full speed. Rice conceded
this challenge will be more mental than physical. ``I think the
main concern right now is being able to take the blows, jump up,
and go back in the huddle and just do what I've been doing over the
years,'' Rice said Wednesday. ``I'll be a little nervous out there
but I'm sure when it's time to play I'll come to play and I'll try
to make those plays I've been making over the years. I'm 100
percent but I have one more test. That test is being hit and being
able to jump and being able to continue in the ballgame. Right now
that's almost a battle from within.'' Rice said he has no regrets
about returning last December for the Monday night game at 3Com
Park. ``I still had the explosion, the cutting, and the burst off
the ball,'' he said. ``I felt like it was the right time to come
back. It was the highlight of my career _ just to be able to run on
that field on that Monday night with  &UR; Joe  &LR; ( &UR; Montana's &LR; ) jersey
being retired, the atmosphere was unbelievable.'' Sunday, on that
same field, the atmosphere will be apprehensive until the game's
greatest receiver takes the hits and reacts the way he has
throughout most of his career. By ignoring them ... Rice was not
surprised when he was made the game's highest-paid receiver last
week. Despite his age (35) and recent injuries, his new contract
extension and raise reflect what he has been doing thoroughout his
career. ``I think what I've done is set the standard for the other
receivers,'' Rice said of his new contract. ``They are trying to
make what I'm making.'' ... Although he changed the 49er offense
considerably last season by running the ball nearly 100 times more
than he threw it, head coach  &UR; Steve Mariucci  &LR; says no one should
think  &UR; Steve Young  &LR; won't be throwing to Rice this afternoon.
``Steve is healthy this year,'' Mariucci said. ``He feels great.
Last year we lost Jerry the first week and Steve got rocked
(suffering several concussions). Last year we didn't even have a
quarterback sneak in the game plan until the 13th week. When I went
to use it against Minnesota, Steve got rocked! This year our team
is different. Steve is healthy and Jerry is back. Plus we lost
(fullback)  &UR; William Floyd &LR; . We still want to be balanced but Steve
wants to get back into it and he will.'' ... Here's how much
respect his teammates have for Rice. Because Rice is in the
starting lineup, one of the 1997 starters who was very productive
must sit. To avoid a controversy,  &UR; Terrell Owens  &LR; went to Mariucci
and told him he did not have to start. ``He made that comment to me
and I was taken aback,'' Mariucci recalled. ``It was a concern of
mine how these three men would react to sharing the load. I thought
it was a first-class gesture.'' Owens made his suggestion after
scoring three touchdowns and producing 142 receiving yards against
Miami Aug. 23. Mariucci has chosen to have all three announced to
the opening day crowd, even though only two will be in the huddle
on the first play.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs continue to search for a veteran running back. Last
week they had in former New York Giant  &UR; Rodney Hampton &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but they
were concerned that he was heavy and out of shape, tipping the
scales at 240 pounds. What did they expect? He hasn't been in a
training camp all summer. They also worked out ex-Jet  &UR; Ron Moore
 &LR; ... Football super agent  &UR; Leigh Steinberg  &LR; knows business, and not
just the football business. He will be in Boston Wednesday to sign
copies of his new book, ``Winning with Integrity,'' as part of a
15-city tour. Alongside him at the South Shore Mall will be  &UR; Drew
Bledsoe &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who should help attract a crowd. Steinberg will have one
of his top clients at 12 of the stops, including  &UR; Kordell Stewart
 &LR; in Pittsburgh,  &UR; Warren Moon  &LR; in Seattle, Young in San Francisco,
 &UR; Troy Aikman  &LR; in Dallas,  &UR; Derrick Thomas  &LR; in Kansas City,  &UR; Ryan
Leaf  &LR; in San Diego,  &UR; Warrick Dunn  &LR; in Tampa,  &UR; Derrick Rogers  &LR; in
Miami, and  &UR; Jake Plummer  &LR; in Phoenix ... Buffalo running back
 &UR; Thurman Thomas  &LR; may be more upset than he has let on about backing
up budding star  &UR; Antowain Smith &LR; . Thomas went after several Buffalo
reporters this week and gave them personal tongue lashings for
suggesting he might be finished ... To say the Colts are starting
over is an understatement. Six of their nine offensive linemen have
two years' experience or less, and tight end  &UR; Ken Dilger  &LR; is their
oldest skill-position player and he's only 27. Although you may
think he's 105, running back  &UR; Marshall Faulk  &LR; is only 25 ... For
the first time in the 25-year history of the local TV blackout
rule, no NFL game will be blacked out this weekend. To accomplish
that, the Cincinnati Bengals had to be granted a 24-hour extension,
until 1 p.m. Friday, but they did sell out. The league is expecting
a record weekend attendance to exceed 1 million. The previous high
was 999,770 on the weekend of Nov. 23-24 last year ... Denver's
 &UR; Justin Armour  &LR; says he's learned from the mistakes of so many of
his contemporaries. The 25-year-old wide receiver recently
announced he was a virgin, saying his abstinence is rooted in his
Christian faith but adding that another benefit is ``it keeps you
out of trouble. I've never broken any hearts because I haven't
taken anything from anyone.'' ... Although there has been much talk
in New England about the effects of playing at altitude Monday
night in Denver, head coach  &UR; Pete Carroll  &LR; would have none of it.
``You can feel it walking upstairs in Mexico City, which is nearly
3,000 feet higher, but you're not going to die,'' Carroll said.
``There's plenty of air.'' ... Miami head coach  &UR; Jimmy Johnson
 &LR; said he's not sure that his Dolphins have solved their running
game problems but he was adamant that there is no turning back.
``The easy thing for us is to fall back and start throwing it once
the season starts if we find we're having problems, but we're not
going to do that,'' Johnson said. ``We know we're on the right
track. For me, I just look at past history. When we were most
successful in Dallas was when we ran it. We'll be better.'' Johnson
believes that taking audibles away from  &UR; Dan Marino  &LR; will make his
offensive line more aggressive because from huddle to play
completion there will be no hesitation in their minds. To reinforce
that, Johnson has changed the blocking to a more aggressive zone
style in which his players will come off the ball and attack ...
How important is Opening Day in the NFL? Well, since the advent of
the 16-game schedule in 1978, of the 269 teams who lost the first
game of the season, 209 (77.7 percent) failed to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jamal Anderson  &LR; is trying to become the third Falcon back since
1981 to rush for 1,000 yards in three straight seasons.  &UR; William
Andrews  &LR; did it from 1979-81,  &UR; Gerald Riggs  &LR; from 1984-86 ...
Saints president  &UR; Bill Kuharich  &LR; has seen an alarming thing since
the advent of free agency in 1993. ``There's been only two players
we gave a lot of money to whose performance has increased,''
Kuharich said. ``That was  &UR; Wayne Martin  &LR; and  &UR; William Roaf &LR; .
Everyone else _  &UR; Pat Swilling &LR; , &UR; Renaldo Turnbull &LR; , &UR; Eric
Allen &LR; , &UR; Michael Haynes &LR;  _ slipped. There's a message there if we
all want to hear it.'' ... Here's an unexpected point of view on
guaranteed contracts from  &UR; Dave Wohl &LR; - &UR; abaugh's  &LR; agent,  &UR; Allan
Herman &LR; : ``I believe big signing bonuses are obviously a form of
guarantee that's good for the players. But NFL teams can still pull
the plug, and because they can, it keeps the players pure. They
know they still have to perform to stay on the team. It's the edge
football has over other sports. From my side, you'd like to see
guaranteed contracts but the fact is the owners have resisted it
because they've seen what's gone on in baseball and basketball.
Guarantees have got to interfere in the quality of the product.
It's the nature of human beings. As an ordinary citizen it's
disturbing to see a ( &UR; Latrell &LR; ) &UR; Sprewell  &LR; situation. Sure there are
coaches who can agitate you, but guaranteed contracts create some
of these problems. That situation would not exist in football.''
... Teams from coast to coast seem to be talking about nothing but
running the football this year. In Dallas, new head coach  &UR; Chan
Gailey  &LR; says, ``This is a tough game for tough people. You win by
running the football. We will run the football.'' Probably, but
will  &UR; Emmitt Smith  &LR; be the one doing the running? ... Dallas
quarterback  &UR; Troy Aikman  &LR; says he knows what's at stake this season
for the Cowboys, who are coming off a 6-10 year and an 0-5
preseason. ``I think this year we get exposed,'' Aikman said. ``I
think this year is going to tell us how good or how bad we are. At
the end of the season, we're going to know exactly what areas we
need to improve on and where we need some help and what exactly
happened in the draft over the last three or four years. I'm tired
of hearing why we went 6-10. It's time to go play and see if all
those reasons were valid or are we as good as we think we are?''
... When Plummer starts at quarterback this afternoon for Arizona,
it will mark only the second time since 1988 that the Cardinals
have had the same opening day quarterback two years in a row.
 &UR; Steve Beuerlein  &LR; started in 1993-94 ... Here's an interesting stat
from the maven of figures,  &UR; Bud Goode &LR; . According to Goode, if
you're intent on living and dying with the pass, one key statistic
has to be touchdowns-to-interceptions ratio. ``Champions have a 3-1
ratio,'' said Goode. ``New England does not.'' Goode predicts
another tough night for the Patriots in Denver, because
statistically speaking the Patriots are weakest where Denver is
strong. New England has averaged 24.8 rushing plays, which is 12
behind the league's leaders of a year ago and far too few to
control the clock.
</P>
