<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CLAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAY LOOKS TO MOLD DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Willie Clay is the prophet of the football sandlot.
</P>
<P>
   He's the one who stood boldly before reporters in Smithfield,
R.I., last year and said that defense would be the best part of the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   He backed it up. The defense came together, went through a few
downturns at midseason, but finished strong, allowing only one
touchdown in a 7-6 playoff loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers that
ended the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now the New England defense is applauded from Maine to Montana.
When the national analysts look at the Patriots, it's the defense
that stands out. And now it's become a classic scenario: The
defense will keep the Patriots in games and whatever the offense
can produce will be a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   How did it come to be that an offense with weapons such as Drew
Bledsoe and Terry Glenn and Ben Coates is the unit striving for
recognition?
</P>
<P>
   And, with the season opener on tap Monday night in Denver, does
the defense have to guard against being overconfident?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we have to guard against having a big
head,'' said Clay, ``but I think you have to be careful about the
fact when we haven't done anything yet when it counts. Sure, we had
a good preseason, but I'm pretty sure a lot of teams looked good in
the preseason, and we have to go out and prove that we can do it
when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you have to do it every week _ week in and week out.
Denver is a tough challenge but you have to play well against an
offense like that to prove how good you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Clay's prediction has come true, he's not about to let
his fellow defensive players rest on their laurels. Veterans like
Clay and Chris Slade and Ted Johnson stay on their younger
teammates to get points across. The coaching staff is also taking
nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you swallow up the hype, it could lead you down a bad
road,'' said head coach Pete Carroll. ``We have done what we set
out to do in the preseason. We got off to a fast start. It all
builds up to this. What we have said and done in the past means
absolutely nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed that's true because Terrell Davis and John Elway could
make it a long night for the defense. Certainly they have the last
three times they've played against the Patriots, who have lost by a
combined score of 105-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense is better now than it was last year, I can say
that,'' said Carroll. ``That sounds great, so now let's go and play
Denver and see what happens. Hey, they're better, too. But we have
a broader package of what we can do now because of our
experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay says, for one thing, the Patriots are much more comfortable
in their base defense, after resorting to some gimmickry at the end
of last season to be completely effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've spent time in a system that we now understand,''
said Clay. ``We've done a lot of things and now we understand what
we're trying to get done. We've played together now for three
years. It's been good. It's been a good growing experience. But we
have to do well in our base defense all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denver game traditionally is the ultimate test for this
defense. The great runner (Davis), the great offensive line, the
great quarterback (Elway), and the big receivers combine for every
problem imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play 60 minutes,'' said Clay. ``Sometimes we play
well and sometimes we don't hold it together. We have the talent.
We have as much talent as they do. We have enough tools offensively
that are comparable to their offense. They might have a better
running back, but we have other things, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``On defense, we feel we're better than them. It's not a thing
that they're a better team. What they have over us is that they
have more experience and they know how to win big games.''
</P>
<P>
   There is talk that the Denver offensive line is weaker because
of the retirement of Gary Zimmerman. But the Patriots have gone
through reel after reel of film and haven't seen much of a
drop-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as 30 (Davis) is back there, they'll be tough,'' said
Clay. ``You've got to get penetration in the backfield before he
gets going.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping the run is where Clay feels the Patriots are a very
good team. Davis ran for 172 yards against them last year, but Clay
believes the Patriots are now better built to stop the run,
pointing not only to Johnson being a year older and wiser, but also
to the contributions of Ferric Collons and Chad Eaton on the
defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad and Ferric don't get a lot of limelight, but when it
comes to run defense, those two guys are around the ball all the
time,'' said Clay. ``What's also good is that we have a rotation on
the defensive line where we can keep eight people pretty fresh
throughout the game. I think that has to wear out the opposition
after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Broncos' receivers having a huge height advantage _ Ed
McCaffrey is 6 feet 5 inches, Rod Smith 6-1, and Willie Green 6-4 _
Clay and strong safety Lawyer Milloy will have to give a lot of
help to Chris Canty, who at 5-9 is the smallest Patriots
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, like many, thinks Canty has come far and earned the right
to be the starter. Can he be better than Jimmy Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially he can, but that's hard to tell,'' said Clay, who
led the Patriots with six interceptions a year ago. ``Jimmy didn't
get a chance to show everything he could do. As good as Hitchcock?
I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots would love to have Tebucky Jones further along,
especially because of the height issue. Jones, at 6-2, 216 pounds,
would have matched up well against a McCaffrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tebucky's play is going to be limited,'' said Carroll. ``He's
not quite ready. He needs more time to gain the experience before
he can get out there and play a lot. I think in time he'll be very
effective against the Keyshawn Johnsons and the bigger receivers in
our league.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have hampered Jones's progress, and the Patriots are a
little thinner than they'd like to be at the corner spot,
especially considering that Steve Israel has yet to step on the
field. That creates more pressure on the safeties, and Milloy is
going to have his hands full against Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots can't afford to be sloppy with the ball at the
start of the game. Turnovers have been the biggest killer in the
last two meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play a flawless game,'' said Clay. ``We have to
keep it close.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been on the field a lot against Denver; last
year's total was nearly 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has to do with having a running game,'' said Clay.
``That affects the defense completely. Everybody understands that.
We're more committed to the running game this year, so they say.
We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay offers no bold statements or predictions for Monday or the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just play the game and let our talents take over,'' he said.
``If we do that, it'll be fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
