<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-05 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUGGER TIES ONE ON WITH THE BABE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When Babe Ruth hit No. 60 on Sept. 30, 1927, he is
alleged to have said, ``60! Let's see some (expletive) top that!''
</P>
<P>
   As we know, Roger Maris hit 61 in 1961. Now the 60 Club has a
third member, and along with that number there is another chilling
numeral _ 141.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many games the St. Louis Cardinals have played. Mark
McGwire has 60 home runs before Labor Day. Let's see some
(expletive) top that.
</P>
<P>
   So tell me, do you think McGwire, who is hitting a home run
every 7.4 times up this year (and one every 8.2 times up since the
beginning of the 1995 season), might be able to hit two home runs
in the final 21 games of the season?
</P>
<P>
   More to the point: Is 70 worth discussing?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a nice number,'' McGwire said at the tail end of a
free-wheeling postgame press conference Saturday. ``But it's a long
way away.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit No. 60 in his first time up Saturday. John Mabry was on
first. A Fernando Valenzuela knockoff by the name of Dennis Reyes
was on the mound. The count was 2 and 0.
</P>
<P>
   At that point in the series, McGwire had seen 18 pitches from
three Cincinnati pitchers. He had swung at eight and had put only
one in play, an altitudinous first-inning fly ball to right on
Friday night. It was clear that the Reds were going to play fair.
Yes, Pete Harnisch had issued McGwire his 146th walk the night
before, but McGwire could have swung at two of the balls, minimum.
Let's just say they were pitches Sammy Sosa would never have turned
down.
</P>
<P>
   So now it was 2 and 0 and young Mr. Reyes _ neither as savvy nor
as generally accomplished as Harnisch, that's for sure _ had to
come in with a fastball, and McGwire put some decent wood on it. In
contrast to his patented moon shots, this was a plain, ordinary
381-foot fly ball, some 12 to 15 feet fair. It landed perhaps a
dozen rows up in the lower deck (which, however, does have
substantial elevation). It was hardly a Ruthian shot. It was,
frankly, more along the lines of a typical Roger Maris home run.
</P>
<P>
   These historical names are the only proper references for Mark
McGwire and his home runs. No offense to Sosa, but he really is the
Other Guy in this scenario. Sammy is going to hit 60-whatever, and
McGwire will be the story, because the No. 1 angle is Mark McGwire
vs. two baseball ghosts named Ruth and Maris.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant story behind the story here is that the Reds are
giving McGwire a chance to hit. He followed his home run Saturday
with three swinging strikeouts, the third of which, in the seventh
inning, came with men on second and third and, therefore, first
base open. Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon brought in righthander
John Hudek in place of lefthander Mike Remlinger, and Hudek didn't
mess around, fanning McGwire on a full count.
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the story behind the story is that the
cigar-chomping McKeon has a sense of humor. Consider, for example,
his response to the question as to why he pitched to McGwire in the
spot when he had refused to pitch to him in similar situations
earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about walking him,'' McKeon said, ``but I also
thought about all those phone calls on my voice mail calling me the
Heel of America. I thought I could aid the healing process and do
something good for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be nice if that's all it took?'' smiled McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   More bookkeeping: McGwire has now hit 30 home runs at home and
30 on the road. He has now hit 11 on Saturdays. He has now hit nine
in the first inning. He has now hit 24 with one man on. He has now
hit 19 with one out, as opposed to 20 with two out and 21 with none
out. He has now hit 15 in the day and 45 at night. He has now hit
12 off lefthanders and 48 off righties.
</P>
<P>
   He has done all this and we've still got three weeks to go.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire knows he is now tethered to something bigger than
himself, and he is grappling with ways to cope. The Ruth queries
and the Maris queries keep coming, just as the Lou Gehrig questions
kept coming for Cal Ripken three years ago. It forces a man to look
outside himself. It is easy to see how it could become
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable; what can you say?'' said McGwire, when
asked if he now had any sense what it might have been like to be
Babe Ruth in 1927. ``I play this game because I love it, and it
just happens to be America's pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is no longer true. But we have arrived at the
beginning of a football season with more attention being focused on
baseball than at any time in the past three decades, and it's all
because of Messrs. McGwire and Sosa. Mark McGwire is very much in
tune with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe that what we are doing is helping to bring
baseball back,'' he maintained. ``The reception I'm getting all
across the country is unbelievable. I've run into fans on the
street who said that they had turned on baseball after the strike
because of what we did to it, but that now they're excited about
baseball again. All I can say is thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   With a staggering 209 home runs in the past four seasons,
McGwire is, on the field, truly the Babe Ruth of our time. But
that's where it ends. The times are different. The challenges are
different. The only thing that hasn't changed is the sense of
accomplishment, and that's where McGwire sees the links between the
two great Yankee sluggers of the past.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire on Maris: ``I can only imagine what he went through in
New York City. I truly believe he's up there watching.'
</P>
<P>
   McGwire on the Bambino: ``You are almost speechless when people
put your name beside his. ... Hopefully, some day when I pass away,
I get to meet him and then I can really, truly find out what he was
really like.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Mark, here's what will happen. The Babe will say, ``I never
thought any SOB would ever outslug me.'' And then he'll say, ``Put
yer money away, kid. I'm buyin' tonight!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
