<SLUG> BC-BBN-FAN-MCGWIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN SWINGS A DEAL FOR BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ His name is Deni Allen, and nobody should be
surprised if the St. Louis Rams give the 22-year-old member of
their marketing staff a day off sometime soon, even though the NFL
season begins Sunday. Allen will be spending that day at Busch
Stadium, not the Trans World Dome, taking batting practice with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Allen earned such a privilege Saturday by capturing the ball
that Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire hit into the left-field
bleachers for his 60th home run, tying him with Babe Ruth and
putting him within one homer of Roger Maris's record.
</P>
<P>
   The ball, which Allen grabbed after it had bounced around among
the fans in the first inning of St. Louis's 7-0 win over the
Cincinnati Reds, may be worth serious money to sports memorabilia
collectors, but Allen has other plans for it. He is going to give
it to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   What does he want in return?
</P>
<P>
   ``A few season tickets for my family,'' said Allen, ``and a
chance to have batting practice with the Cardinals.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Cardinals agreed to give Allen two season
tickets for 1999, some bats, hats, and autographed balls _ plus a
round of batting practice before a game at Busch Stadium later in
the season. All for the ball McGwire hit for No. 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's his ball,'' said Allen, who was raised in
nearby Ozark, Mo. ``It's the only thing to do for baseball right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit five home runs over the past week, and in each case
he has gotten the ball back from a fan, without having to pay a
huge price. All have offered the ball back for merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the same thing happens with 61,'' said McGwire. ``Ball
No. 62 belongs in Cooperstown.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's home run traveled 381 feet to the upper deck down the
left-field line. Allen had come to the game with his grandparents
and had seats farther over in left-center. But with McGwire due to
bat, Allen said, he began to drift toward what he considered a
better position down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drift'' isn't the right word. Stadium security was stationed
in left to keep wanderers from entering the ``Promised Land,''
which the area in the left-field stands at Busch Stadium is
sometimes called. Guards stopped Allen once. But he was persistent
and made it through on his second attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (John) Mabry got his hit,'' said Allen, referring to the
batter preceding McGwire in the lineup, ``I decided I had to run
and find a place. I jumped over two seats. I walked down and
around. Some guy ran me out. He was just trying to do his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball was hit, and I don't remember much after that. I went
for it, I got a few punches and some kicks. But I got the ball and
just tucked it away in my pocket. I got it off the bounce. In every
home run highlight, the first guy never catches it. I knew that. I
waited for the bounce and I somehow came up with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Allen be in the bleachers Sunday looking for No. 62?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' he said. ``I have to work the Rams game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
