<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves let lead, win slip away in eighth
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Midway through a lost Labor Day weekend, the Braves
have done nothing to help themselves extend the league's best
record or hurt the Mets' postseason hopes. This, Chipper Jones
knows, is not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned,'' Jones said after Atlanta's disturbing 5-4
loss Saturday. Tony Phillips' second homer of the year, a two-out,
two-run shot off Rudy Seanez in the eighth, sent the Braves to
their third straight defeat and fifth in six games. ``This isn't
the way you should be playing in September. ... We're going to be
sitting at home on October 4th or 5th.''
</P>
<P>
   That would mean a first-round exit in the National League
playoffs. But then, the Braves have done little lately to suggest
they'll still be playing deep into October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're helping the Mets stay in it,'' Jones said of the NL
wild-card race. ``It's the same old thing every day, not doing the
little things. We had one opportunity to turn a double play and
didn't. Had second and third, one out, didn't score. Those two
things cost us two runs, at least two runs. Cost us a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones hit his 26th homer in the fifth inning but Braves
starter Kevin Millwood gave up a two-out infield single to Edgardo
Alfonzo in the bottom half, then a two-run homer to John Olerud.
``Right down the middle,'' Millwood said. ``You can't do that to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   When Javy Lopez singled off Bobby Jones to tie it in the sixth,
and Greg Colbrunn hit a two-run double, Atlanta had a 4-2 lead and
men at second and third with one out. But Tony Graffanino (now
hitless in his last 12 at-bats) struck out for the second of three
times Saturday, and Millwood took a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   With Mets on first and third in the seventh and one out, Mike
Piazza was forced at second but came in with both hands raised.
When Ozzie Guillen's throw hit Piazza's hand, the relay was in the
dirt, allowing Olerud to score.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bobby Cox said, ``We played very well all day long. Then
to lose it like that. But that's what happens when you walk a guy
with two out. You're always going to get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
