<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons assured as debut arrives
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE _ Free safety Eugene Robinson is old by NFL standards
and slower than a few years ago. But when the Atlanta Falcons
signed Robinson during the offseason, they were counting on him
bringing experience and a new attitude from the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson, 35, begins talking about Atlanta's season opener
today at Carolina, he sounds as if his team is playing for a high
school championship instead of NFC West rivals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mindset Falcons officials hope is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want to call it, you've got to be so confident
when you step out on the field,'' Robinson said. ``That's the
difference between making a play and not making a play. There's a
domino effect; everybody is trying to make a play and get their
name in the paper. I see that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta rebounded from a 1-7 start under new coach Dan Reeves
last year to win six of its final eight. The question: Was it a
fluke?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see if the 6-2 was for real or fake,'' Robinson
said. ``From all indications, it's for real. These guys are playing
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's game should provide a nice barometer.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are 0-3 in Ericsson Stadium, lost twice last year to
the Panthers and have lost 11 road openers in a row.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of attention will be paid to right tackle Ephraim Salaam,
the only rookie in Atlanta's starting lineup. Salaam will try to
protect quarterback Chris Chandler, who signed a new contract on
Saturday. The Falcons have to slow Carolina tight end Wesley Walls
and the Panthers' new West Coast passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   But where there was doubt, even confusion, before last year's
opener, players and coaches say there is confidence and
understanding this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys expect to win, and that's a big difference from hoping
you win,'' Reeves said. ``(Players are) looking to make plays to
win games rather than worrying about making plays to cost you a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we beat New Orleans and St. Louis, but if we're
going to compete in this division ... we've got to beat teams
people expect to be above us, and this is one of those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
