A1332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN06-CO     09-05 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The guy's always open
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Atlanta Falcons never saw Wesley Walls again, it would be
fine with them. Unfortunately, they're likely to see plenty of
Carolina's tight end this afternoon, because whenever the team he's
on plays Atlanta, Walls tends to do real damage to the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's home opener, John Kasay kicked three
fourth-quarter field goals _ including a 39-yarder as time expired
_ to drive a stake through Atlanta's heart, 9-6. But Walls first
lined up the stake and pounded on it repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 250-pounder had a career-high seven catches for a
career-high 147 yards that afternoon, and when it looked as if
Falcons strong safety William White was going to intercept a pass
with just 1:38 left, only to tip the ball instead, Walls caught it
for a 14-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   Walls caught five passes in the fourth quarter for 105 yards; it
was no surprise. He had 58 receptions last year for 746 yards and
six touchdowns and was the Pro Bowl starter for the second year in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play Carolina, you have to be cognizant of Wesley
Walls,'' said Rich Brooks, Atlanta assistant head coach and
defensive coordinator. ``He's an outstanding receiver; he makes
plays on everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine-year veteran had punished the Falcons before. In his
first game with Carolina, the 1996 season opener in Charlotte, he
caught four passes for 32 yards and a TD in a 29-6 win over
Atlanta. When he was with the Saints, he caught six passes for 61
yards and a TD, and Atlanta needed overtime to beat New Orleans
early in 1995. In '94, his first year with the Saints after
spending five seasons with San Francisco, Walls made a diving
21-yard TD catch in a 29-20 New Orleans win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's their go-to guy. Even if he's covered, they're going to
look for him,'' said the Falcons' White (5-10, 205), who often will
try to cover the bigger Walls. ``He's their Jerry Rice. He's very
smart, and a lot of times he has an option (to break his route) if
he sees something in the defense. People talk about how slippery he
is, but he's got great hands. And he can gain ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls has kind of come out of nowhere several times.
</P>
<P>
   He was a quarterback for three years and then a fullback in high
school. At the University of Mississippi, he was a defensive end
for three years and then played two ways as a senior, at outside
linebacker and tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers made him a second-round draft choice in 1989, but he
had just 11 catches for 67 yards and a TD in three years, playing
more as a deep snapper. He spent '92 and '93 on injured reserve
before becoming a free agent and signing with New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   His first year with the Saints, he caught 38 passes for 406
yards in '94. Then in '95, he caught 57 passes for 694 yards and
four TDs, and in two seasons in Carolina, he has caught 119 passes
for 1,459 yards and 16 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great feel and knowledge,'' Brooks said, ``and he
just kind of wiggles his way into an open seam and catches
everything thrown to him. He's really hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
