A1333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HOMERS06-COX     09-05 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOMERS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One down, two to go!
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ On a hot, marvelous afternoon here for baseball,
Mark McGwire put himself one big swing away from Roger Maris and
right along side baseball's greatest legend.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, like almost everyone else who has ever picked up a bat
and ball, holds a special place for Babe Ruth. He hit his 60th home
run of the season Saturday to tie the Bambino on a 2-0 pitch in the
first inning, belting a fastball from Cincinnati's Dennis Reyes
into the left-field seats. A mad scramble for the ball ensued,
Busch Stadium exploded and McGwire made another of his now familiar
curtain calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could go back in time and meet him,'' McGwire said of
Ruth. ``When I pass away, I want to meet him and find out what he
was really like.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, McGwire needs just one more homer to tie Maris
and two to break what has been a record for 37 years. He had three
chances after his homer Saturday in the Cardinals' 7-0 win over the
Reds, striking out all three times. But in no way did thatdampen
McGwire's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, he held a 45-minute press conference under the
stands in right field. Some of the 47,994 on hand for the game
stuck around to listen, as his face and words were put on the big
overhead screen in center field. McGwire was unaware of that until
he heard the roar after one of his comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There still here,'' he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not going anywhere, nor is the rest of the country
until McGwire hits No. 62. With the Chicago Cubs in Pittsburgh
Saturday night and Sammy Sosa going into the game with 57 homers,
the chase picks up again this afternoon for McGwire, as the Fox
network has decided to televise the game nationally and has changed
the game time to 4:10 p.m., allowing the network to get to 80
percent of the country's television markets.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire now has five home runs in September, and his homer
Saturday was his first against the Reds this season. He now has hit
homers against every team in the league. Except for the first
at-bat Saturday, the Reds have done an excellent job against him
these last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Their only fault was Reyes falling behind McGwire two balls in
the count. Reyes then came back with a fastball in, and McGwire hit
it 380 feet, just the 17th of his 60 homers to travel less than 400
feet. The homer came in the Cardinals' 142nd game. Ruth hit No. 60
on the final day of the 154-game season in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a bad pitch,'' Reyes said. ``I was down 2-0 in the
count and had to throw a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked where he thought the pitch should have been thrown,
Reds manager Jack McKeon said, ``Out of the strikezone.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's second at-bat came in the second, and he had trouble
with three straight curveballs from Reyes, swinging at only the
third one. He then faced reliever Mike Remlinger in the fifth,
taking a strike and was unable to catch up with the last two
fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a surprise in the seventh. The Cardinals had runners
at second and third and one out, and this seemed to be a perfect
situation to walk McGwire, with the Reds down 5-0. But McKeon, who
would have probably had to have an army escort him back to the
hotel if he walked McGwire, brought in right-hander John Hudek to
pitch to McGwire. ``I knew Hudek would challenge him,'' McKeon
said. Hudek worked the count full. McGwire fouled off a fastball.
Hudek came back with another fastball and McGwire went down
swinging, saying later, ``On my last three at-bats I was pitched
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McGwire will be facing Cincinnati's most talented
pitcher today in right-hander Brett Tomko. McGwire has faced Tomko
six times this season, going 2-for-5 with a walk and no homers.
Tomko, however, has said recently that he wouldn't mind giving up
the homer that either ties or breaks the record.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is just one homer away from tying the record,
McGwire said he isn't about to change anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it and you try to put it out of your mind,''
McGwire said. ``I'm trying to simplify it, the only thing I can do
is swing the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   And make history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
