<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-05 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-RAIL06-COX     09-05 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-RAIL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC Notebook
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turning (on) Gray
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis general manager Bill Polian has started rebuilding
the Colts in his image, and the latest victim is cornerback Carlton
Gray. The five-year pro was demoted to a backup role Wednesday and
then cut Thursday when he took his complaints public. Early in the
free-agency period, Polian signed cornerback Jeff Burris, whom he
had scouted while in Buffalo. In July, he traded for corner Tyrone
Poole, a player he selected in the first round of Carolina's
inaugural draft. Secondary coach George Catavolos tried to placate
Gray by pointing out that he'd still log 60 percent to 70 percent
playing time in the ``nickel'' package, but the veteran wasn't
buying it. ``It was obvious this was going to happen, because they
want their own guys in there,'' said Gray, who averaged 14 starts
the last four seasons. The Giants, who lost corner Jason Sehorn for
the year, already have called agent Marvin Demoff about Gray.
Minnesota, New England and Philadelphia also are interested.
</P>
<P>
   Myles to go
</P>
<P>
   There were 11 linebackers taken before former Nevada star
DeShone Myles, but Seattle might have gotten a bargain in the
fourth-rounder. Of the six inside linebackers selected ahead of
him, only Takeo Spikes of Cincinnati will start today. But Myles
could move into a starting spot before any of the others _ Sam
Cowart (Buffalo), Brian Simmons (Cincinnati), Jermiah Trotter
(Philadelphia), Jamie Duncan (Tampa Bay) and Anthony Simmons
(Seattle). ``He just has a great feel for the ball,'' Seahawks
coordinator Greg McMakin said. So great, in fact, that McMakin last
week moved Anthony Simmons to an outside spot and could soon
replace starter Dean Wells with Myles.
</P>
<P>
   Good Will Wolford
</P>
<P>
   When Steelers coach Bill Cowher shuffled his offensive line last
week and moved left guard Will Wolford to left tackle, the 13-year
veteran could have balked and asked for more money. Wolford's
contract stipulated he can earn as much as $400,000 in incentives
if moved back to tackle, where he earned three Pro Bowl berths in
Buffalo (1990 and '92) and Indianapolis ('95). But he and agent
Ralph Cindrich agreed to waive the clause for this season, in part
to help the Steelers with salary cap problems. Look for Pittsburgh,
which is trying to negotiate extensions with tight end Mark
Bruener, corner Carnell Lake and free safety Darren Perry, to
reward Wolford at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles lure
</P>
<P>
   After the league awards the Cleveland expansion franchise
Tuesday, attention will turn to adding a 32nd team. The focus is on
Los Angeles and Houston. But because the NFL might not be able to
get a publicly financed stadium in L.A., Houston could have an
edge. There remain rumblings that Al Davis wants to move the
Raiders back to the potentially lucrative Los Angeles market. ``But
they hate him as much (in Los Angeles) as the fans do in Oakland,''
league attorney Frank Rothman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ragged Raiders
</P>
<P>
   An Oakland defense that finished last in 1997 still is
scrambling to find help at end and outside linebacker. Terry
Wooden, signed Wednesday, immediately was installed as the starting
strong-side linebacker. Richard Harvey, acquired Monday, is a good
bet to unseat James Folston on the weak side.
</P>
<P>
   The grapevine
</P>
<P>
   If the Al Lerner-Carmen Policy group is awarded the Cleveland
expansion franchise, look for San Francisco personnel director
Vinny Cerrato to get the same title with the Browns. ... Kansas
City defensive tackle Dan Williams, the only veteran holdout left
in the league, has vowed he won't return to the Chiefs. ...
Linebacker Eddie Robinson, signed by the Oilers after being cut by
Jacksonville, has bumped leading tackler Barron Wortham from the
starting lineup. ... Because he wants a more physical runner,
Baltimore coach Ted Marchibroda will start Errict Rhett at tailback
over Jay Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
