<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Week 1: Falcons vs. Carolina
 &HT;    BY Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Falcons (0-0) vs.Carolina (0-0)
</P>
<P>
   1:01 p.m., Ericsson Stadium, Charlotte;
</P>
<P>
   Fox/Channel 5 and 640-AM, 105.7 FM, 96.1 FM
</P>
<P>
   Falcons coach Dan Reeves was harping on turnovers in the
preseason, and it's easy to see why. Atlanta finished 3-13 in 1996,
when its turnover differential was minus-18. But last year, the
Falcons were plus-4 in turnover differential and finished 7-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons did not get a turnover during the preseason until
the final game, when safety Eugene Robinson had an interception and
recovered a fumble against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina, meanwhile, had a minus-17 turnover differential last
year, while compiling a 7-9 record. In the franchise's three-year
history, it has a 25-6 regular-season record when the team is even
or better in turnover differential and a 1-16 record with a
negative turnover differential.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Panthers were minus-1 in the preseason, it's worth
noting that quarterback Kerry Collins did not throw an
interception. He completed 32 of 55 passes (58.2 percent) for 337
yards and two touchdowns in the Panthers' new West Coast offense.
Backup Steve Beuerlein completed 42 of 68 passes (61.8) for 583
yards, four TDs and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   When the Panthers made it to the NFC Championship game after the
1996 season, a stout run defense had a lot to do with it. But in
dropping from 12-4 in 1996 to 7-9 last year, Carolina's 22nd-ranked
run defense _ or lack thereof _ took a lot of the blame. The
Panthers gave up yardage totals of 198, 219, 158, 160, 218 and 147
in games last season.
</P>
<P>
   But that porous run defense didn't apply against the Falcons in
the two meetings between the NFC West teams. Atlanta managed 48 and
68 yards _ a 2.3-yard average _ in two losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the real keys in the ballgame is going to be
who can run the football,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``Both
teams have struggled stopping the run in the preseason. And we've
had more success running the ball in the preseason than Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina has given up 143 yards per game in the preseason. The
Falcons are averaging 126.3 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina tried to address its run defense by acquiring defensive
tackle Sean Gilbert and drafting defenders Jason Peter, Chuck Wiley
and Mitch Marrow. Wiley and Marrow, however, are out for the season
after being placed on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
