<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A big bid by `Little Man'
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jacksonville tailback James Stewart should have spent the first
three years of his career with cotton balls stuffed in his ears and
a rear-view mirror glued to his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   He was battered constantly by the verbal barbs of coach Tom
Coughlin, and he challenged the Jaguars' penchant for annually
acquiring players to compete for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a former Tennessee star nicknamed ``Little Man,'' was
one of the Jaguars' first-round picks in their inaugural 1995
draft, and unwittingly became the symbol for a running game that
has grown progressively worse _ 16th in 1995, 17th in '96 and 18th
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In this fourth season, however, ``Little Man'' has become ``The
Man'' for a Jaguars team with Super Bowl dreams. During preseason,
when he gained 197 yards on 38 carries, Stewart matured into the
kind of back who finally can provide balance to an offense that too
often has relied on the arm of Mark Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think James realized he was at a crossroads in his career,''
agent Pat Dye Jr. said. ``It wasn't as if the organization didn't
like him, but they kept bringing in backs every year. No matter
what they were saying, there was always a feeling they weren't
completely sold on James. After a while, the hints aren't so subtle
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, club officials were about as understated as a
sledgehammer this spring when they warned Stewart and Dye that
Coughlin planned to select a tailback in the first round. After
failing in attempts to move up and take Penn State's Curtis Enis,
the Jags took Florida standout Fred Taylor with the ninth overall
choice, then grabbed Iowa speedster Tavian Banks in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   For the soft-spoken Stewart, it was nothing new. His lofty draft
status aside, Jaguars officials never regarded him in previous
seasons as the answer to their tailback questions and brought in an
annual challenger: Vaughn Dunbar in 1995, Natrone Means in 1996 and
'97 and now Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Despite being the Jaguars' career leader in rushing
yards and touchdowns, Stewart has averaged only 154.3 carries per
season. That should change this year, when he figures to get about
300 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with minicamps, when his toughness and resolve were
obvious, Stewart did more than just fend off his latest
challengers. ``He blew them away,'' Brunell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they brought in (Taylor) and all the talk started
focusing on him,'' Stewart said, ``it was nothing new to me. (It's)
happened every year. People say I responded different this time,
but I didn't think so. I've always just tried to control the things
I had some say-so on. The other stuff, I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 26, conceded he might have been victimized early in his
career by the pressure of being a first-rounder and an immediate
high-profile personality in a city with just one professional
sports franchise. A subpar offensive line and Coughlin's frequent
criticism of his play also contributed to Stewart's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a kid from a small town (Morristown, Tenn.) suddenly
thrust into the limelight with a demanding coach,'' Dye said. ``He
took things personally. He lost some confidence and went into a
shell there for a while. The upside is it made him tougher
mentally, and he's so confident now of his standing with his team
and the respect of his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   A contract extension that doubled his 1998 compensation _ it
will pay Stewart nearly $2 million next year _ offers tangible
evidence of management's newfound respect for the fourth-year
veteran. Stewart plans to provide instant dividends on the
investment, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any more doubters,'' he said, ``we're going to
take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
