</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Geoff Bodine may be moving
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Winston Cup ``silly season,'' where the rumor mill heats up,
is under way. Jim Mattei, owner of Mattei Motorsports, said driver
Geoff Bodine will finish the current season with the team and might
remain in the future. But he also is considering other options.
``During the past month, we have made great strides as a team,
which has allowed us to learn a great deal about our operation,''
Mattei said. ``I anticipate being able to announce our plans for
the next year within the next 30 days.'' Bodine ranks 32nd in the
Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   First and third
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon might be first in the Winston Cup points standings,
but he's only third in the World Driver Rankings. He moved ahead of
Formula One's Mika Hakkinen, who spun out of last week's Belgian
Grand Prix. F1's Michael Schumacher and CART's Alex Zanardi are
ranked 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Wallace has made it official. He will leave the No. 81
Square D team of owner Filbert Martocci after the season and move
to Andy Petree Racing, joining Ken Schrader to form a two-car team.
.. Steve Hmiel was released earlier this week as general manager of
Jack Roush's two-team operation in Liberty, N.C. Hmiel managed the
facility that prepares the cars forKevin Lepage and Johnny Benson.
He has been replaced by Harry McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH
</P>
<P>
   Sadler opts out
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Sadler had been pointing to Saturday's Busch Dura-Lube
200, hoping to equal or better his fifth place in March. But he
couldn't get back fast enough to run with the Winston Cup teams.
``The Southern 500 is a premier race, and Winston Cup is a
different world out there. And that's why we've chosen to run it,''
Sadler said. ``I'm not taking anything away from the Busch series;
it's No. 1.Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr. and Matt Kenseth easily are the series
statistical leaders. Earnhardt is first in points (3,269) and
Kenseth second (3,1274); Earnhardt leads in money, $598,160 to
Kenseth's $533,220. ... Stat of the Week: Randy LaJoie's victory in
last year's Dura-Lube was the only one by a Busch Series regular
ever in the fall Darlington event. CRAFTSMAN TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Bliss moving on
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bliss won't be back in 1999, ending a four-year
relationship with ASE Racing.``The team and I came to an agreement
that things weren't working out the way we had hoped. The chemistry
just isn't there,'' Bliss said. ``It's time to move on with my
career.'' The season has been up and down for Bliss. He's won three
poles, has 10 top-five finishes and 15 top-10s. ``I hope we can get
a few more wins together before the season is over,'' said Bliss,
who finished second last week at Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling along
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the year candidate Greg Biffle has been on a
roller-coaster ride this year. He started the season with a fifth
at Disney, then was fourth at Homestead before finishing 36th in
Phoenix. While he has had five top-fives and eight top-10s in 19
races, he also has finished 17th or worse 11 times. It's not all
bad, however. He leads Andy Houston by 12 points in the race for
rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   At the Kroger 225 in Louisville, Tony Raines became the seventh
different winner. That's one short of the season record set in
1997...Fords finished 1-2 in Louisville after failing to win at the
.438-mile oval in three previous attempts.
</P>
