<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tough track to love
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darlington, S.C. -- IIt's called the track ``Too Tough to
Tame'', ``The Lady in Black.'' The men who have raced here have
called it much worse, cursed it and lost sleep over it.
</P>
<P>
   It's Darlington Raceway, the track they love to hate. It's 1.366
miles of egg-shaped asphalt, which this time of year tests the best
NASCAR can offer in the Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, drivers like Fireball Roberts, Joe Weatherly,
David Pearson and Cale Yarborough made reputations for mastering
the track, whose tire-eating surface and different-shaped corners
made it a run like no other.
</P>
<P>
   And today it will be up to its usual tricks and treats in the
Pepsi Southern 500.
</P>
<P>
   For pole winner Dale Jarrett it's a trip down memory lane. He's
been coming here for over 30 years, tracing the tire tracks of his
father, and putting down a few of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly that day in 1965 when dad was able to win the
Southern 500, I'm not even asking to win it by 14 laps,'' Jarrett
said. ``I'll let most people stay on the lead lap if I can win it.
It was just a special day.
</P>
<P>
   Also, knowing how well David Pearson got around here, watching
his style, and how he went about winning races here. I think all of
that has helped me. Plus, the history and prestige of this race
means a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's where Bill Elliott won the first Winston Million in 1985,
holding off Cale Yarborough by .06 seconds. It's where Pearson most
shined, holding the record for most victories with 10.
</P>
<P>
   And it's where the entire field will be tested today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is real history here,'' Jeremy Mayfield said. ``With a
shape like it has, you have to compromise your setup. Your are
either really good in turns one and two or three and four. There's
no way you can be good at both ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darlington is the one place I can remember older drivers
talking like it was alive. You hear them talk about other tracks
and saying, 'That place' or 'that track'. With Darlington, you hear
them talk about 'she and her,' those kinds of terms. That's what
sets it apart from all the others.''
</P>
<P>
   What it isn't is a fun track. The racing groove is narrow and
the corners are different than most tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fine line between racing against the competition and
the track,'' said Derrike Cope. ``You have to separate the two. You
obviously have to play strategy and watch where the leaders are,
and what they're doing and be concerned. But, at the same time, you
really have to watch the track and drive within your means.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your car isn't good enough, it can be a short day. And if
you get down laps, it can be a shorter day yet. That's just the way
Darlington is, and what makes it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
