u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER06-COX     09-05 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No place like home
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a bad night. The house was dark and lonely. Most of the
windows lacked draperies _ and, yes, even heavyweight champions
with 200 gated acres and elaborate security systems get paranoid
that somebody is peeking inside.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, there was nothing to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``First I was kind of nervous, being in that big ol' house by my
doggone self,'' Evander Holyfield said of the new
54,000-square-foot mansion on his estate in Fayette County. ``Then
I walk into the kitchen and there's no food. There I am, standing
in front of these two big empty refrigerators, thinking, `How come
you got all this money and you ain't got no food in your
refrigerator?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is a guest in his own hometown. In his own house. He
opted to move his training camp for the Sept. 19 title defense at
the Georgia Dome against Vaughn Bean from Houston to Atlanta. But
while his family resides in an older, relatively modest home on the
property, Holyfield spends nap times and evenings at the
not-quite-complete, mostly unfurnished, $18 million (so far) palace
next door.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield built a full boxing gym and weight room on the grounds
a few years back with the idea of holding prefight camps at home.
But phone calls, children tugging on his shirt and unforeseen
obligations convinced him to continue his preparations in Houston,
where he owns a home and has trained for most of his professional
career.
</P>
<P>
   Because Holyfield shares in promotional responsibilities on the
Bean fight and a significant portion of the champion's purse is
tied to attendance, he felt compelled to train at home for the last
four weeks. The move will allow him to conduct public workouts, the
first of which is scheduled for noon Wednesday at CNN Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm older now and more mature, so I can handle the
distractions better,'' he said. ``If I need my rest, I can get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is made easier by Holyfield's sleeping arrangements. He and
longtime fitness trainer Tim Hallmark snooze in guest rooms, which
are furnished while most others, including the master bedroom,
remain unequipped. The Holyfields had hoped to move in a year ago,
but have been delayed by construction problems. Most of the
unfinished work relates to either landscaping or electrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lake looks low. Must have a leak,'' Holyfield said from
his view on a balcony.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems the entire structure had to be rewired after the
original electricians, Holyfield said, used wiring more conducive
to a 3,000-square foot home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some (new) professional electricians in and they said,
`Your house is going to catch on fire,' '' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   That little mistake cost Holyfield between $300,000 and
$400,000. The current $18 million tab does not include furniture,
balls for the bowling alley, movies for the home theater or the
$250,000 in new Cybex equipment Holyfield purchased for a second
weight room _ just to save him a walk to his gym 200 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all this equipment, my kids will have no reason not to
exercise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, mostly what Holyfield wants from the three of his seven
children living on the property _ a fourth is on the way any day
now _ is quiet. He spends little time at the other house, other
than for meals.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has the phone number at the new home, and Janice
Holyfield reaches her husband by intercom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rings all the time (at the old home),'' Holyfield
said. ``I can't tell people not to call. People call for Janice or
the business. I go upstairs and I can still hear the phone, even
when it's turned off in my room. When I'm in the new house, it's
just peaceful. I mean, I don't hear nothing. I don't hear any more
than I want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield did answer one call the other day. While giving a tour
to two visitors, the phone rang in the mansion's elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello?'' Holyfield said. After a pause, he told the caller,
``You dialed the wrong number.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's first night there two weeks ago was more
intimidating than he expected. He later asked Hallmark to stay down
the hall, though in different wings, to provide some company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lost the first morning,'' Hallmark said. ``I made a
wrong turn and didn't know where I was. I'm a little more used to
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Brooks, one of his boxing trainers, said, ``When you think
about it, it's kind of funny, just him and Tim in that big house.
Tim told me he felt like he had to take a shower before going to
bed because everything was so new. He didn't want to ruffle the
sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's daily routine here has not changed much. He rises
for a 5:30 a.m. boxing workout, has breakfast, takes a nap, hits
the weight room in the afternoon, rests, then sometimes runs in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The three mansion kitchens remain unstocked, but Holyfield has
smuggled in some juice and potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   He has no plans to move in until the house is completed and
furnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my house to be like a train station, people going
in and out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's more like a ghost town with all the extras.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
