u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MANNING06-COX     09-05 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MANNING06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Manning at ease in spotlight
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Like a pair of giant doormen, the
larger-than-life billboards of tailback Marshall Faulk and free
safety Jason Belser will silently greet a sellout crowd as it files
into the RCA Dome for today's regular-season opener against the
Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   But even the two Indianapolis veterans, both surprised that
their likenesses were selected for the posters that hang above the
Capitol Avenue entrance, acknowledged they can't take credit for
the Colts' first opening-day full house since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we all know who they're coming to see,'' Faulk said,
without a hint of envy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, civic leaders staged a parade early this morning to
honor the Colts _ the kind usually reserved here for Indianapolis
500 drivers _ and a large crowd was expected to herald the arrival
of Peyton Manning, the man anointed the city's latest football
savior.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night at St. Elmo Steak House, an entire table of
patrons wore Colts jerseys with Manning's new No. 18 on the front.
A few feet away, fans from Knoxville, here for the NFL debut of the
Tennessee Volunteers' greatest all-time player, preferred orange
mesh shirts with the more familiar No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the Peyton Manning era begins. And while Manning mania
isn't quite epidemic yet, it has provided a pulse in an area that
favors point guards over pinpoint passers.
</P>
<P>
   The moribund franchise, rumored as recently as a year ago to be
primed for relocation to Cleveland, sold 3,500 more season tickets
than in 1997. Marketing and advertising revenues have in- creased
dramatically. Owner Jim Irsay, whose struggling team had the NFL's
lowest stadium-generated revenue, gained concessions and a more
favorable lease agreement from the city. The owner of a downtown
sporting-goods store estimated sales of Colts apparel had more than
doubled over last year.
</P>
<P>
   All of that even before Manning, a $42.6 million investment, has
appeared in his first commercial.
</P>
<P>
   That comes next month, when Hoosiers will see grainy celluloid
of a gangly, 7-year-old Manning tossing a football with his
brothers. The commercial is part of his first local endorsement
deal, with St. Vincent's Hospital, and will help pitch ``Peyton's
Playbook,'' a collection of health advice and success tips for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   But the intentionally low profile, which is equal parts respect
for his older teammates and the realization that he has yet to
complete his first regular-season pass, hasn't kept the spotlight
from focusing on Manning. This city's nickname may be Nap Town, but
it has awakened to the reality that, for the first time since
tailback Eric Dickerson abandoned it in 1991, there is an
honest-to-goodness NFL celebrity in its midst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think everything was fair game except church and
your doctor's office,'' Manning said.``But then I got elbowed
during a prayer in church by some guy with a shirt (he wanted
autographed). At the hospital, the nurses had me (autograph) my
X-rays. .. I guess anything goes now. For me, hey, I just want to
be one of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of his 22 years, however, Manning has known that his
name, pedigree and talent for throwing a football would preclude
anonymity. Even while still a prep star at Isidore Newman High
School in New Orleans, his accomplishments fell somewhere between
legendary and mythical.
</P>
<P>
   The unpretentious Manning has handled celebrity with aplomb and
civility. A few weeks ago, San Diego quarterback Ryan Leaf, the No.
2 pick in last year's draft, referred to Manning as ``Perfect
Peyton'' and ``the Golden Boy.'' During a lengthy interview Friday,
Manning refused to be drawn into a verbal battle with Leaf. But it
was obvious that he simmered over the comments and that he's proud
of a reputation that, except for a ballyhooed mooning incident in
college, is clean.
</P>
<P>
   His father, who lost more games as a starter than any other NFL
quarterback, remains one of the game's true gentlemen. Peyton
witnessed ``unbelievable patience'' during Archie Manning's
star-crossed 15-year career. His mother, Olivia, is a
pageant-lovely belle. The great-uncle for whom he is named was a
cotton farmer whose charitable legacy still benefits parts of rural
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is fiercely loyal to the legacy, and it will play well
in this city, a Mason-Dixon straddler that possesses plenty of
Southern wannabe. Whereas Leaf noted that he hopes to follow his
inaugural game with a celebratory trip to Tijuana tonight, Manning
has dinner reservations for his mother, father, girlfriend and
agent at a small restaurant in moderately upscale Broad Ripple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made plenty of mistakes, but at least I've always tried
to do the right thing,'' Manning said quietly. ``I don't know what
a so-called `golden boy' is. I know I've always been under a
microscope since I was a kid, because I'm Archie Manning's son.
Having all that pressure, though, made me a better person. People
always knew who I was, and so they were looking for me to mess up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes that's the best way you learn on the field, to screw
up once. But in life it's tough. Being (Archie's) son, you just got
used to it. And being a quarterback, it was an advantage, because I
had my hero and my mentor right there in my own house.''
</P>
<P>
   Every father dreams of raising a son who is too good to be true,
and Archie Manning said he's been blessed in that regard. Every
team covets a superstar around whom it can market itself, and Irsay
believes Manning should be the centerpiece of a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a Manning dissenter in Indianapolis could prove
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been groomed for greatness,'' wide receiver Marvin
Harrison said. ``He may be Archie's son, but he's our moon, our
stars, our universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackle and former University of Georgia star Adam
Meadows said: ``From the first day, it was his huddle and his
offense. It might be cliche, but he acted like a 10-year veteran
and had everyone's eyes (on him). Maybe someone else is going to
begrudge him the money's he's making or the attention he gets. As
far as I'm concerned, Peyton is the meal-ticket. Anyone who works
as hard as him gets respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He is ``a sponge,'' says quarterbacks coach Bruce Arians, who
has at times been caught off-guard by Manning's insightful
questions about game plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mind is like a projector,'' Arians said. ``One time _
that's all it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning and his coaches are not naive enough to believe that an
exemplary work ethic will translate into immediate success.
Ironically, the last No. 1 quarterback to start and finish a
victory in his NFL debut was Archie Manning in 1971. It is a league
that chews up rookie quarterbacks and spits them out, and Manning
is the leader of a very young offense.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Miami defense probably will throw everything at
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that, because I'd do the same thing,'' Colts coach
Jim Mora said. ``But you know, for some reason, I don't stand on
the field this week and think, `Man, we have a rookie quarterback.'
He doesn't act like a rookie quarterback. Now maybe he will
(today), I don't know. But I'm not lying awake at night worrying
about it. I've accepted the fact we're going to have some tough
times. But Peyton is the best we have, and he's only going to keep
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
