A1341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-RAIL06-COX     09-05 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-RAIL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC Rail
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rice's comeback
</P>
<P>
   He played only 47 snaps last year, didn't get on the field for a
preseason game and, at age 35, is trying to come back from a pair
of major knee surgeries. Little wonder San Francisco wide receiver
Jerry Rice admits to some apprehension about his return today
against the New York Jets. ``I can deal with being rusty,'' Rice
said last week. ``A bigger concern is whether I'll be able to take
a blow on the knee, jump up and run back to the huddle. It's almost
a battle from within. The media has made such a big thing of it
that it starts to get inside your head.'' Rice said the emergence
of Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes, and the increased use of a
three-wideout alignment, could mean his receptions decline and his
yards-per-catch increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Ironhead tour
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Craig Heyward, released last week by St. Louis, most
likely will wind up in Jacksonville, San Diego or Oakland. Jags
coach Tom Coughlin wants to upgrade from second-year veteran Daimon
Shelton and met with Heyward on Friday. In San Diego, he has
supporters in June Jones and former Falcons running backs coach
Ollie Wilson. In Oakland, former Atlanta personnel man Ken Herock
is making a pitch. ``Hopefully we'll know something by early in the
week,'' agent Jack Mills said. Heyward, who spent some time in the
Duke University weight-management program, is telling teams he is
down to 258 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth agrees
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't help the Arizona Cardinals much in today's
opener against the Dallas Cowboys, but the club finally reached
agreement Saturday afternoon with first-round draft choice Andre
Wadsworth. The former Florida State standout signed a complicated
six-year deal that could pay him as much as $42 million. The
signing bonus is $10.491 million and the Cardinals have, after
three seasons, annual options on each of the final three years of
the deal. The last draft pick to reach terms, Wadsworth could
actually play a few snaps today in pass-rush situations. Arizona
coach Vince Tobin still was considering that possibility. Wadsworth
will join end Simeon Rice and tackles Eric Swann and Mark Smith to
give the Cardinals one of the NFL's best young front fours.
</P>
<P>
   Purple hazing
</P>
<P>
   Former New Orleans linebacker Andre Royal, now playing for
Indianapolis, will not discuss his role in the ugly hazing incident
that occurred the final night of Saints training camp. Royal's only
statement was that, while he was involved, he is not the player who
wielded a bag of coins against rookie tight end Cam Cleeland. NFL
security officials continue their investigation. Word is that
Saints coach Mike Ditka, who traded Royal to Indy for tight end
Scott Slutzker, waived another culprit. At least one major
perpetrator remains on the New Orleans roster.
</P>
<P>
   Courting Haley?
</P>
<P>
   For at least 24 hours last week, the 49ers and Dallas Cowboys
toyed with the idea of bringing defensive end Charles Haley out of
retirement. Something still could happen with Dallas, but the
Niners have backed off the one-time pass-rush threat. Director of
football operations Dwight Clark broached to quarterback Steve
Young the possibility of Haley's return, and it apparently didn't
go over too well. In his book ``All the Rage,'' Haley noted that
Young was hardly the equal of Joe Montana. The Cowboys, who last
week did the annual restructuring of Troy Aikman's contract to
create salary-cap room, want to add a defensive front-seven player.
</P>
<P>
   The grapevine
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Penson, the New York real estate financier who is
offering $450 million for the Redskins, is said not to be a fan of
coach Norv Turner. ... Chicago coach Dave Wannstedt, who continues
to shuffle his linebackers, probably will take a look at deposed
Colts linebacker Quentin Coryatt, but not until next week. ... The
new, three-year deal the Giants gave quarterback Danny Kanell on
Thursday includes a signing bonus of $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
