<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-     09-05 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX BEAT YANKEES, 9-5  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Baseball and Jim Abbott parted ways two years ago,
Abbott confused and hurt by his rapid demise. He had been an
18-game winner and threw a no-hitter for the Yankees in 1993, and
suddenly his ability abandoned him at age 28.
</P>
<P>
   But Abbott reconciled with baseball this summer, and Saturday,
in his first major league appearance in almost two years, he
pitched six and one-third innings and was the winning pitcher as
the Chicago White Sox stalled the Yankees, 9-5. Andy Pettitte
(15-9) lasted only two innings for the Yankees, surrendering five
runs and departing shortly after his manager went to the mound to
see if he might be hurt. The Yankees are 100-39, their magic number
for clinching the American League East down to four.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, who turns 31 later this month, did not overwhelm the
Yankees, allowing eight hits, three walks and four runs and
benefitting from four double-plays. When he left the game in 1996,
his fastball was diminished, down to 83 to 84 miles an hour, and
that was about how hard he threw against the Yankees. On another
night, with another look at Abbott, the Yankees might have done a
lot more damage.
</P>
<P>
   But he was good enough to win, fortunate enough to win, aided by
inning-ending double-plays in the first, second, third and sixth
innings. The Yankees had a runner at first base and one out in the
sixth, for example, when Chili Davis smashed a grounder down the
third-base line, a would-be double _ until Robin Ventura, Chicago's
slick-fielding third baseman, intercepted the ball with a flash of
his glove, turned and fired to second to start the double-play.
Abbott, born without a right hand, pumped his left as he walked off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott walked Scott Brosius with one out in the seventh,
prompting Chicago Manager Jerry Manuel to call for a reliever. The
White Sox led by 8-3 at the time and Abbott was in position to get
his first victory since Sept. 8, 1996. Abbott stood on the mound
momentarily as the infielders congratulated him.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott had been released in the spring of 1997 and sat out the
season. But in May, he reached an agreement on a minor-league
contract with the White Sox and slowly worked his way back,
starting with Class A Hickory on May 31 and moving up through all
levels of the White Sox farm system.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was well aware of Abbott's history as he walked off
the mound Saturday night, and most stood and clapped for him.
Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third base coach, leaned forward and
said something to Abbott while the pitcher returned to the dugout,
and Abbott nodded in response.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had allowed 26 hits and 15 runs in 22 innings in
winning just one of three starts before Saturday night's game,
competing voraciously, as he always does, in spite of mediocre
stuff. During his last start, against Seattle last Sunday, Mariners
Manager Lou Piniella pulled the left-hander Paul Spoljaric aside
and told him to watch Pettitte. This guy does not have anything,
Pettitte told Spoljaric, and see how he's battling.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the White Sox Saturday night, however, Pettitte did not
even have enough stuff to battle with, throwing just about
everything over the middle of the plate, and the White Sox battered
him before he was replaced after two innings. The Yankees announced
that Pettitte was fine and that his departure was not
injury-related, despite some evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had very poor control: Only half of the 42 pitches he
threw were for strikes, one possible symptom of injury. One pitch
into Craig Wilson's at-bat in the second inning, Torre and the
Yankees' pitching coach, Mel Stottlemyre, and catcher Joe Girardi
all hustled to the mound, asking the umpires for time so they could
ask Pettitte if he was hurt. Torre asked Pettitte if he was OK, and
Pettitte assured his manager he was. Then Torre and Stottlemyre
waited for Pettitte to throw two warm-up pitches before allowing
him to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson smacked a double and Frank Thomas slapped a run-scoring
single and then was caught in a run-down that ended the inning.
Backing up home plate on the play, Pettitte rushed off the field
and disappeared into the runway, never to be seen again in this
game.
</P>
<P>
   Back trouble hampered Pettitte at the end of last season, when
he was pounded in two post-season starts. Earlier this season in
Montreal, in June, Torre suspected Pettitte was bothered by a
buttocks strain and removed him against his wishes. Pettitte
skipped a start in August after slightly injuring a muscle behind
his left shoulder. The Yankees maintain Pettitte is healthy, and
that may well be the case; virtually all major league teams at one
time or another mask or minimize injuries. Time will tell whether
Pettitte is healthy, if he can regain his effectiveness. He has
approximately four more starts to prepare for the American League
playoffs that begin Sept. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
