A1349 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RDP-3RDLD-WRITE     09-05 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH INQUIRY FINDS A SILENCE FROM THE CREW  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to expand)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ The crew of the Swissair jet that crashed
near here on Wednesday night had stopped responding to air traffic
controllers about six minutes before the plane, an MD-11 with 229
people on board, hit the water, investigators said Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators also said that on Friday they detected the
homing device from one of the plane's ``black boxes,'' either the
cockpit voice recorder or the flight data recorder. Divers spent
this morning trying to find the recorder, they said, but had to be
called back because of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigator, Vic Gerden, said that shortly after the
plane's last radio transmission, in which a crew member told a
controller at the Moncton Area Control Center, ``We have to land
immediately,'' the plane's transponder also stopped working. That
piece of equipment transmits the plane's identity and altitude to
controllers, and when its signal stopped, radar data from the plane
became much less reliable, Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, with 215 passengers and a crew of 14, plunged into
the sea at 10:30 local time on Wednesday night, about 40 miles from
Halifax Airport, killing everyone aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The brief excerpts of the conversations between a controller in
Moncton and the crew _ released here Saturday night _ show flashes
of drama and tension. Someone on the plane, either the captain or
the first officer, tells the controller, ``We are declaring an
emergency at time zero one two four ... We are starting vent now.
We have to land immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerden, of Canada's Transportation Safety Board, said he was
consulting with Swissair pilots and MD-11 experts about what
``starting vent'' meant. It could have meant depressurizing the
airplane to allow the cockpit windows to be opened, or dumping
fuel, which the crew had said it would have to do, Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not characterize the tone of the exchanges in the 10
minutes that followed the crew's first announcement of a problem,
or say what had been going on in the cockpit in the final six
minutes after communication stopped. Gerden said it was impossible
to know now whether the pilots' silence meant that they had been
incapacitated by the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the transponder stopped working, he said that the
failure might be ``indicating some electrical issue, potentially.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about the tone of the crew members'
voices, Gerden said that it had changed in the course of the 10
minutes, probably indicating that they had put on oxygen masks. ``I
really don't have enough information to determine their condition
inside the cockpit, I'm afraid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cites smoke, but we really don't know what density of
smoke, what amount,'' Gerden said.
</P>
<P>
   In a briefing that lasted more than an hour, Gerden gave a
limited chronology of the last few minutes of the flight, beginning
at a point about 70 nautical miles from here.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, under the control of the Moncton Center, radioed in:
``Swissair 111 heavy is declaring pan-pan-pan. We have smoke in the
cockpit, request deviate immediate right turn to a convenient
place. I guess Boston.'' (``Heavy'' refers to a large aircraft.)
</P>
<P>
   Advised that the plane was 300 nautical miles from Boston, the
crew readily agreed to go to Halifax, but when told that the
airport was just 30 miles away, the pilot said: ``We need more than
30 miles.'' The controller told the plane to turn left to lose
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Gerden said he would have experts analyze whether it was
possible to drop from the 33,000-foot cruising altitude to the
runway, which is not far above sea level, in the 30 miles
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem, he said, was weight. ``The aircraft at that
point, about that time, had a weight of about 230 metric tons,'' he
said. But it cannot land weighing more than 200 metric tons, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have taken probably in the vicinity of 12 minutes of
flying to dump that amount of fuel,'' he said. ``If one attempts to
land an aircraft at a weight that is greater than the maximum
landing weight, depending on many conditions _ length of runway,
surface condition of runway, is it wet, many other factors _ there
is a risk having landed the aircraft, it would go off the other end
of the runway at some unknown rate of speed and cause damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether, in hindsight, the crew might have done better
risking a landing, he said: ``The crew had a difficult situation to
contend with, starting with a high altitude and having to descend
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles, he said, was very short for the crew to ``descend
into an airport that you weren't expecting to descend into.'' The
crew would have had to decide quickly, he said, about risking a
landing above the maximum landing weight ``and at the same time,
contending with some problem, unknown at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are counting on the flight data recorder and the
cockpit voice recorder to answer many more questions and, they
hope, explain the source of the smoke. Even if an electrical
problem cut the power to those devices, Gerden said Saturday night,
knowing when they stopped working would be useful.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-11 is a computerized airplane and its flight data
recorder tracks about 100 ``parameters,'' he said. A parameter
could be the functioning of one of the plane's three engines, the
position of an aileron, the plane's speed, its heading, altitude,
acceleration or deceleration.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``black boxes'' are equipped with battery-powered
``pingers.'' These are activated by contact with water and are
supposed to work for 30 days. Since the boxes send out a signal at
the same frequency, 37.5 kilohertz, investigators do not know which
one they have heard.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Coast Guard and Navy officials said they had about 40
vessels in the search area, from Zodiacs and Boston Whalers to a
submarine, the HMCS Okanagan. They have found one cylindrical
object, about 30 feet long, but have not sent divers down to
determine if it is part of the plane; they are concentrating
instead on finding the black boxes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the chief medical examiner of Nova Scotia, Dr. John
Butt, reported that a French woman on the plane had been positively
identified by her family, the first such identification. He said he
did not expect many more identifications soon, although six teams
of pathologists are now working around the clock in a temporary
morgue at the military base at Shearwater, across Halifax harbor
from the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Medical technicians have begun taking blood samples from
relatives gathered here, to aid in DNA analysis of the remains
being gathered off the water and the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Butt said that damage to bodies was consistent with an impact,
not damage from a blast.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate hangar at Shearwater, a different team is rinsing
down parts of the airplane, and explosives experts are examining
them ``as a precaution,'' said Chief Superintendent Steve Duncan of
the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   The search coordinators have established a Web site
(www.marlant.hlfx.dnd.ca/marlant/swissair), to describe their
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Saturday, search boats placed wreaths on the water at
the request of families, and collected water samples for the
families to take home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
