<HEADER>
A1352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      09-05 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS BEAT PIRATES, 8-4, AS SOSA GETS NO. 58  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ It's called a home run race, but the contestants
are rooting for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck to you, Sammy, tonight in Pittsburgh,'' Mark McGwire
said after hitting his 60th home run in an afternoon game in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to clap for Mark,'' Sammy Sosa said, before
responding with his 58th homer Saturday night in Pittsburgh. ``I
want him to break the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Good cheer does not mean either player is conceding the race.
Sosa remained two behind McGwire in the competition to best Roger
Maris' record of 61 home runs. In te past 10 games, each player
has hit seven home runs.
</P>
<P>
   What a week it was, as at least one of the two homered for six
game days in a row. On Sunday came No. 55 for McGwire and 54 for
Sosa. On Monday, Sosa tied with his 55th. As September began on
Tuesday, McGwire pulled two ahead with 56 and 57. On Wednesday,
McGwire stretched the lead to three with 58 and 59, while Sosa his
his 56th. After Thursday's off day, Friday brought Sosa's 57th.
Then came Saturday's performances.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Three Rivers Stadium Saturday afternoon, Sosa walked
past the statue of Roberto Clemente, the first Latin player in the
Baseball Hall of Fame. Sosa, who was born in 1968 in the Dominican
Republic, keeps a figurine of Clemente in his locker. ``He is a
hero to me,'' Sosa said. Now Sosa holds the record for the most
home runs in a season by a Latin player and is the Cubs' nominee
for baseball's Roberto Clemente award, which honors charitable
work.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Sosa first faced a rookie pitcher, Sean
Lawrence, who entered the game with only eight innings of big
league experience. As Sosa came to the plate for his first at-bat,
the scoreboard monitor showed a replay of McGwire hitting his 60th
home run. On the first pitch from Lawrence, Sosa hit a long foul
ball of home run distance to right field. As the next two pitches
missed the strike zone, the crowd of 37,711, eager for a home run,
booed. Sosa slapped a 3-2 pitch into center field for a single. He
moved to second on a single by Glenallen Hill. Both runners scored
on a double by Gary Gaetti, giving the Cubs an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Sosa reached base again on a fielder's
choice.
</P>
<P>
   As Sosa led off the sixth inning, he was seeing Lawrence for the
third time, which was enough. He drove the ball an estimated 417
feet to the first row of the right-center-field crowd. Misplayed by
a fan, the ball dropped into the area between the outfield and the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Sosa looked bad, swinging late on an outside
pitch by reliever Jeff Tabaka, a left-hander. Sosa leads the league
in strikeouts with 141, or one every four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, he hit a longer homer-length foul into the upper
deck off of Ricardo Rincon, driving the crowd into a frenzy. When
the home plate umpire, Angel Hernandez, called an outside pitch for
the third strike, fans booed, then streamed for the exit. Sosa
finished the night 2 for 5, raising his batting average to .314.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' 8-4 victory was their sixth straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have hit home runs in 17 consecutive games, a club
record.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, just two players, Sosa and McGwire, have hit 21
during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa said he appreciated the warm reaction from the Pirates
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like me everywhere,'' Sosa said, beginning to grin. ``And
I would like to tell them that I love them, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
