</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS SIGN WADSWORTH TO SIX-YEAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Who needs practice?
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals first-round draft pick Andre Wadsworth apparently
doesn't need training camp or drills after ending his 44-day
holdout Saturday by signing a six-year deal that could be worth as
much as $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, who received a team-record signing bonus of $10.491
million, not only will dress for today's season opener against the
Dallas Cowboys but also is expected to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We presume he's in good physical condition, knowing the type
of person Andre is,'' said Coach Vince Tobin, who released rookie
defensive end Mike Moten to make room for Wadsworth on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he'll get some snaps in the nickel as a pass rusher.
When you're the left end, you've got four guys rushing, all you
need to know is you rush up the field and try to sack the
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth's agent, Roosevelt Barnes, said Wadsworth is ready to
play. ``He's like a caged animal,'' Barnes said. ``If they would
let him start, he'd start.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth said he is in ``the best physical shape he could
possibly be in but not football shape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to train for constant repetitions of seven or eight
seconds of total explosion,'' said Wadsworth, who added that he's
not concerned of the health risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make sure I stretch real well and make sure I watch what
I eat in the pregame meal because I know I'll have the butterflies.
Hopefully, I can dance around and (play) a little nickel, take some
little baby steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Until late Friday night, a deal between the Cardinals and
Wadsworth's agents, Eugene Parker and Barnes, didn't appear
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals maintained Wadsworth, the Florida state defensive
end who was the third pick overall, wanted to be paid as much as
San Diego Chargers rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf, the second pick
overall who received a five-year, $31 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth didn't get as much as Leaf, but the Cardinals can opt
out of the deal after three years. If they decide to end the
contract after five years, Wadsworth's total deal would be worth
$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bidwill, team vice president who had been in France
until Friday, said both sides made concessions.
</P>
<P>
   A concession the Cardinals made was to allow the contract to
include escalators, pay-for-performance clauses.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the escalators were likely to be earned, Barnes said
they were if Wadsworth is  &UR; ...  &UR; (MISSINGTYPE)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no gimmes, but he should be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A concession Wadsworth's agents made a week ago was to abandon
their demand that the contract include voidable years. On Friday,
they dropped the amount of total package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to play football,'' Michael Bidwill said. ``Andre
wanted to play football. We wanted him to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Wadsworth got involved in the negotiations and that
he started dealing directly with Michael Bidwill and his brother,
Bill Jr., who oversees contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two days, B.J. (Bidwill Jr.) and Michael got
personally involved,'' Barnes said. ``It was a lot smoother dealing
directly with them. They called me late (Friday) night and put a
proposal on the table. We put a proposal on the table. We were
within striking distance and then Michael and B.J. got aggressive
when they saw we could make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The final contract wasn't much different than the deal the two
sides almost reached a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth said he wasn't upset that the negotiations took so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew eventually I was going to come (to terms),'' Wadsworth
said. ``I didn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the Cardinals for showing confidence in me and
investing in me. I think this was perfect timing. Like a fine wine
or fine cheese, it takes time to come out and taste good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals didn't know that the impasse had ended until 12:45
p.m. Saturday when team owner Bill Bidwill grabbed the microphone
on the team's charter plane and told the team that Wadsworth had
agreed to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, meanwhile, then boarded a plane in Tallahassee, Fla.,
for Dallas. He has been living there and taking a graduate class in
business administration during his holdout.
</P>
<P>
   The bonus the Cardinals paid Wadsworth _ part of it will be
deferred _ is the third largest given to an NFL rookie.
Indianapolis quarterback Peyton Manning, the first pick overall,
received an $11.6 million bonus. Leaf was paid a bonus of $11.25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth will earn the minium base salary of $144,000 for a
rookie this year. His annual salaries will then increase 25 percent
each year.
</P>
<P>
   His salary-cap figure for this season will be $1.89 million, the
remaining available under the team's rookie pool.
</P>
<P>
   With Wadsworth signing, the Cardinals now are about $2 million
under the $54.3 million salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a credit to the organization it stepped up to the plate
and got the contract signed,'' Tobin said. ``Hopefully, this is a
turning point in this organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
